?def: Myotonia that occurs after a period of rest and decreases with continuing exercise.
Underdevelopment of the thenar eminence with reduced palmar soft tissue mass surrounding the base of the thumb.
Width of the forehead or distance between the frontotemporales is more than two standard deviations below the mean (objective); or apparently narrow intertemporal region (subjective).
Encephalomalacia is the softening or loss of brain tissue after cerebral infarction, cerebral ischemia, infection, craniocerebral trauma, or other injury.

An arteriovenous malformation is a disruption of the normal vascular pattern in which arteries or arterioles connect directly to the venous collection system, bypassing any capillary bed. This term refers to an arteriovenous malformation located in the optic nerve.
Any structural anomaly of a myeloid mononuclear recirculating leukocyte that can act as a precursor of tissue macrophages, osteoclasts and some populations of tissue dendritic cells.

Abnormal location of the insertion of the anterolateral papillary muscle near to the apex of the left ventricle. This feature may be appreciated by noting that this muscle is usually not seen in the apical level of the parasternal short-axis echocardiographic view,
A posterolateral defect in the diaphragm, commonly referred to as a Bochdalek hernia, which is often accompanied by herniation of the stomach, intestines, liver, and/or spleen into the chest cavity.
Abnormality of the dens of the axis, which is also known as the odontoid process.
Abnormally pale skin.
Atrophy of the frontal cortex.

Mycobacterium abscessus complex comprises a group of rapidly growing, multidrug-resistant, nontuberculous mycobacteria that are responsible for a wide spectrum of skin and soft tissue diseases, central nervous system infections, bacteremia, and ocular and other infections.
Reduced pigmentation of hair in patches.
An abnormality in the reflexive contraction of the middle-ear muscles in response to sound stimulation.
Separation of the inner layers of the retina (neural retina) from the pigment epithelium occuring near the outer limit (periphery) of the retina.
Difficulty initiating sleep, that is, increased sleep onset latency.
An abnormal accentuation of the inward curvature of the spine in the lumbar region.

Increased length of the arm span (length from one end of an individual's arms measured at the fingertips to the other when raised parallel to the ground at shoulder height at a one-hundred eighty degree angle).
Criss-cross atrioventricular valves with a rare cardiac malformation characterized by the two ventricles lying one above the other instead of side by side.
Recurrent episodes of decreased concentration of glucose in the blood occurring during the infantile period.
Astrocytoma is a neoplasm of the central nervous system derived from astrocytes. Astrocytes are a type of glial cell, and thus astrocytoma is a subtype of glioma.
An abnormally elevated amount of alpha1-antitrypsin in the feces.
Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the proximal phalanx of the third finger.
Partial or complete wasting (loss) of brain tissue that was once present.
Amelia of one or both legs.
A type of autosomal dominant inheritance involving a gene that is imprinted with maternal silencing.
A type of blepharitis that affects the eyelid skin, base of the eyelashes, and the eyelash follicles.
A type of glaucoma defined by an open, normal appearing anterior chamber angle and raised intraocular pressure,

This finding is composed of a ring-shaped opacity representing a dilated bronchus in cross section and a smaller adjacent opacity representing its pulmonary artery, with the combination resembling a signet (or pearl) ring. It is the basic sign of bronchiectasis in pulmonary computed tomography imaging.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exertion or physical exercise.
A cutaneous cyst that is small (one or two millimeters in diameter) and painless, presenting as a follicular papule that usually is skin colored but may have a reddish or brownish tinge.
An increase in the number of chromosome sets per cell in bone marrow cells.
A type of cataract affecting the posterior pole of lens immediately adjacent to ('beneath') the Lens capsule.
A deviation from the normal count of CD4-positive, CD25-positive, alpha-beta regulatory T cells.
Inability to perceive painful stimuli.
Absence of the radial spokes of the axoneme of the respiratory cilium.
Absence of the pectoralis major muscle.
A congenital defect characterized by the lack of ganglion cells in the entire intestine, i.e., the aganglionic segment comprises the entire large and small bowel.
An abnormality of the partial pressure of oxygen or carbon dioxide in the arterial blood.
An abnormality of a dorsal nasal artery.
Developmental hypoplasia of the eyelid.
Absence of the usual parallel position of philtral ridges.
Reduced movement of the superior rectus muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.
A non-progressive finding characterized by multiple joint contractures found throughout the body at birth.
The presense of molluscum contagiosum lesions across multiple areas of the body.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the centrotemporal region of the brain (also known as the central sulcus), i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.
A subtle unilateral cleft of the upper lip, which may appear as a small indentation.
On pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography, reticular pattern is characterised by innumerable interlacing shadows suggesting a mesh.
Well-demarcated area(s) of partial or complete depigmentation in the macula, reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss.
A episode of severe pain that breaks through (i.e., temporarily exacerbates) a period of persistent pain.
Insertion of thumb at a more distal location than normal.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the groin region.

A deviation from normal in the expression of valosin-containing protein in muscle tissue. Valosin-containing protein an ubiquitously expressed multifunctional 100-kD protein that is a member of the AAA+ (ATPase associated with various activities) protein family.
Anomalous insertion of the chordae tendinae or papillary muscles into the contralateral ventricle in the presence of a ventricular septum defect.
Increased size of cerebral gyri, often associated with a moderate reduction in the number of sulci of the cerebrum.
An abnormally increased sodium concentration in the cytosol.
An abnormality of the Internal acoustic meatus, i.e., of the canal in the petrous part of the temporal bone through which the cranial nerve VII and cranial nerve VIII traverse.
An anomaly of the ilium ala. This is the large expanded portion of the ilum which bounds the greater pelvis laterally.
A deviation from the normal concentration of a polysaccharide in the blood circulation.
A loss of the ability to move the vocal folds.
An abnormality of morphology of premolar tooth.
Fusion of the C5 and C6 cervical vertebrae.
The presence of a supernumerary tooth in the midline between the maxillary central incisors.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:8666004 UMLS:C0040457 SNOMEDCT_US:266414008 UMLS:C4280340 SNOMEDCT_US:17802000 MSH:D014096 UMLS:C0266030 SNOMEDCT_US:367534004

?def: Reduced side to side width of the pelvis.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one and two.
A reduced number of large myelinated nerve fibers.

Seesaw nystagmus is a type of pendular nystagmus where a half cycle consists of the elevation and intorsion of one eye, concurrently with the depression and extortion of the fellow eye. In the other half cycle, there is an inversion of the ocular movements.

Any deviation from the normal concentration of iInhibins, which are heterodimeric protein hormones secreted by granulosa cells of the ovary in females and Sertoli cells of the testis in males. Inhibins suppress the secretion of pituitary follicle-stimulating hormone.
EEG frequency is abnormally increased.
Decreased activity of von Willebrand factor. Von Willebrand factor mediates the adhesion of platelets to the collagen exposed on endothelial cell surfaces.
Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as Phenobarbital in urine.
Chronic loss of joint motion of the distal interphalangeal joint of the 3rd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen, due to a hypothalamic or pituitary abnormality diagnosed with hypo-gonadotropic-hypogonadism. The diagnosis is made on the basis of low LH and FSH levels and low or normal testosterone levels.
Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter that surrounds the cerebral ventricles.

Aortic arch crosses the left mainstem bronchus. The first branch is the right carotid artery, the second branch is the left carotid artery, the third branch is the subclavian artery, the fourth branch is the right subclavian artery arising from the posteromedial aspect of the distal aortic arch and continuing posterior to the esophagus to the right hand side of the body.
A maladaptive personality trait characterized by moderate or greater impairment in personality (self /interpersonal) functioning.
Any abnormality of the vertebral column.
Having a high degree of severity. For quantitative traits, a deviation of between four and five standard deviations from the appropriate population mean.
Any deviation from the normal circulating concentration of chylomicrons.
A gap in the upper lip. This is a congenital defect resulting from nonfusion of tissues of the lip during embryonal development.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 4th finger.
An increase in width in one or more phalanges of the big toe.
An anomaly of the electrical conduction physiology of the heart.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a phospholipid in the blood circulation.
Wedge-shaped, or triangular head, with the apex of the triangle at the midline of the forehead and the base of the triangle at the occiput.
Urticaria caused by physical agents, such as heat, cold, light, friction.
The left common carotid artery normally originates from the aortic arch. This term refers to an origin of this artery from the brachiocephalic artery.
An elevated concentration of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
A developmental anomaly characterized by a reduced number of teeth, whereby more than 6 teeth are missing.
Fingernail that appears thin when viewed on end.
A goiter that is not associated with functional thyroid abnormalities.
Abnormal enlargement of the urinary bladder.
Myoclonus that occurs during the initial phases of sleep.
Any abnormality of cartilage.
Trapping and compression of the rotator cuff tendons during shoulder movements.
Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disc is 0.7 (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).

Deficiency of secretory IgA (polymers of 2-4 IgA monomers are linked by two additional chains) and is the primary antibody response at the mucosal level, where it forms immune complexes with pathogens and allergens.

A disruption of the structure of the sarcomeres of cardiomyocytes. The sarcomere is the repeating unit between two Z lines comprised largely of myosin and action that mediates contractility, and normally sarcomeres are aligned with the long axis of cells, with the Z bands being in register throughout the length of the cardiac myocytes.
An increase in the level of xylitol in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Bleeding into the ventricles of the brain.
In type E brachydactyly, shortening of the fingers is mainly in the metacarpals and metatarsals.
Aplasia of the vagina.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:248871003 UMLS:C1321884 SNOMEDCT_US:87380008 UMLS:C0220763 MSH:C536523 UMLS:C1841990

?def: Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the little finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
Abnormality of the first branch of the internal carotid artery.
A situation in which phenotypic abnormalities become evident with age.
Any functional abnormality of the eyelid.
An increased concentration of urocanic acid in the urine.
An exostosis is a benign growth the projects outward from the bone surface. It is capped by cartilage, and arises from a bone that develops from cartilage.
Reduced uptake of [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) in the prefrontal cortex as measured by positron emission tomography (PET) brain scan.
An abnormality of alkaline phosphatase activity.

A vestibular Schwannoma (also known as acoustic neuroma, acoustic neurinoma, or acoustic neurilemoma) is a benign, usually slow-growing tumor that develops from the VIIIth cranial nerve supplying the inner ear.
A narrowing of the vagina owing to scar formation.
An abnormality of dermatoglyphs (fingerprints), which are present on fingers, palms, toes, and soles.
An anomaly of the joint between the trochlear notch of ulna and the trochlea of humerus, which is part of the elbow joint.
Underdevelopment of the spleen.
An abnormality of an erythrocyte cell surface molecule.
A generalized disorder of peripheral nerves.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:42658009 UMLS:C0031117 SNOMEDCT_US:302226006 MSH:D010523 MSH:D011115 SNOMEDCT_US:42345000 UMLS:C0152025

?def: A parasitic infection whereby the parasite invades (migrates through) tissues of the infected host.
Difficulty in recognizing objects by visual input in absence of sensorial visual impairment.
An cystic ovarian teratoma composed of dermal and epidermal elements and containing tissue components including hair, teeth, bone, thyroid, and others.
Developmental hypoplasia of the vagina.
Any structural abnormality of the right atrium.

A type of holoprosencephaly in which most of the right and left cerebral hemispheres and lateral ventricles are separated but the most rostral aspect of the telencephalon, the frontal lobes, are fused, especially ventrally.
Non-continuity of the aortic arch with an atretic point or absent segment at the level of the isthmus.
Partial or complete duplication of phalanx of third toe.
Anomalous origin of one pulmonary artery from the ascending aorta with the contralateral pulmonary artery arising from the right ventricle.
An anomalous concentration of testosterone in the blood.
Absence or underdevelopment of the abdominal musculature.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against alpha-gal.
An increased concentration of homocystine in the urine.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one to three.

A myocardial disorder in which the heart muscle is structurally and functionally abnormal, in the absence of coronary artery disease, hypertension, valvular disease and congenital heart disease sufficient to cause the observed myocardial abnormality.
A facial appearance characterized by a permanently or nearly permanently opened mouth, in which the upper lip is tented in a way that the opened mouth has the appearance of a triangle.
Difficulty in performing the correct execution of limbs movements in absence of motor impairment.
An increased rate of urine production.
Reduced level of CD59 on the granulocyte surface as assessed by flow cytometry.
Congenital absence (aplasia) of one or more limbs.
An abnormal narrowing of the external auditory canal.

An abnormal change (metaplasia) in the cells of the inferior portion of the esophagus. The normal squamous epithelium lining of the esophagus is replaced by metaplastic columnar epithelium. Columnar epithelium refers to a cell type that is typically found in more distal parts of the gastrointestinal system.
Glaucoma refers loss of retinal ganglion cells in a characteristic pattern of optic neuropathy usually associated with increased intraocular pressure.
Lack of stability of a joint.

A reduced amount of the enzyme acrosin in the sperm head acrosome. The acrosome is an organelle in the anterior half of the head of spermatozoa, and acrosin is a protease that contributes to the digestation of the zona pellucida in the fertilization process.
A tooth abscess that occurs at the tip of the root (apex) of a tooth.
A deviation from normal concentration of estriol in the circulation.
An air-filled cystic space within a lung.
The presence of micro-megakaryocytes, hypo-lobed, or non-lobed nuclei in megakaryocytes of all sizes and multiple, widely-separated nuclei.
A continuous form of lactic acidemia.
An anomaly in the placement or shape of the hairline (trichion) on the back of the head (neck), that is, the border between skin on the back of the head that has head hair and that does not.
Increased width of the middle phalanx of the 4th finger.
Any structural abnormality of a cardiac valve.
A functional anomaly of the adjacent structures (i.e., adnexa) of the eye, defined as the lacrimal apparatus, the extraocular muscles and the eyelids, eyelashes, eyebrows and the conjunctiva.
Difficulty releasing one's grip associated with prolonged first handgrip relaxation times.
Trophic changes occurring in a limb.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the external carotid artery wall.
Inability to move the muscles of respiration.
The presence of a gonadoblastoma of the ovary.
Deposition of large, diffuse cotton wool amyloid plaques (CWPs) lacking a dense core and associated neuritic changes.
Circulating antipituitary antibodies (APA) are markers of autoimmune hypophysitis, which may cause deficient pituitary function.
Bending or curvature of a finger toward the ulnar side (i.e., away from the thumb). The deviation is at the metacarpal-phalangeal joint, and this finding is distinct from clinodactyly.
Complete absence of all von Willebrand factor multimers.

Retinitis pigmentosa inversa is form of retinal degeneration characterized by areas of retinal/chorioretinal degeneration with pigment migration in the macular area (in contrast to retinitis pigmentosa which, at early disease stages, predominantly affects the retinal periphery).
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger.
Enlargement of the thyroid gland related to a singular nodule in the thyroid gland.
Abnormal sensations such as tingling, pricking, or numbness of the skin with no apparent physical cause.
Absence or underdevelopment of the corpus callosum.
Loss of all hair on the entire body.
An increased amount of subcutaneous fat tissue in the face.
Abnormally increased levels of citrulline in cerebrospinal fluid.
A deviation from the normal concentration of a fatty acid in the blood circulation.
An abnormality of the femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft).
An anomaly of cells involved in the formation of a granulocytes, that is, of the granulocytopoietic cell.

Proximal interphalangeal (PIP) flexion deformity of the little finger. That is, the PIP joint of a little finger is bent (flexed) and cannot be straightened actively or passively. It is thus a chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement.
An elevation in bone density in the middle phalanx of the third toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
Asthma is characterized by increased responsiveness of the tracheobronchial tree to multiple stimuli, leading to narrowing of the air passages with resultant dyspnea, cough, and wheezing.
Nystagmus due to disturbance of the vestibular system; eye movements are rhythmic, with slow and fast components.
A structural anomaly of a male reproductive cell.
Loss-of-function thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR) defect.
A first-trimester prenatal ultrasound finding of abnormal blood flow in the ductus venosus.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a long-chain fatty acid in the blood circulation.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the ear.
A deviation from the normal straight shape of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger.
Calcium deposition in the myocardium.
Presence of the Duffy Fya antigen.
Presence of reduced amount of a membrane protein on the cell membrane of platelets. This feature is typically measured by flow cytometry.

Complete or partial duplication of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx), a partially fused appearance of the two bones, or two separate bones appearing side to side. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the extracranial portion of the internal carotid artery wall.
A herniation of meninges through a congenital bone defect in the skull at the junction of the frontal and ethmoidal bones.

A type of proximal renal tubulopathy characterized by resorption defects leading to glycosuria, aminoaciduria, tubular proteinuria, renal hypophosphatemia, and urate tubular hyporeabsorption without bicarbonate loss.
Aplasia of the hallux, that is, a development defect such that the big toe does not develop.
Any structural anomaly of the papillary muscles of the left ventricle.
Congenital onset of a marked decrease in the number of granulocytes.
Any functional abnormality of a cardiac valve.
A deviation from the normal straight shape of the distal phalanx of the thumb.
An abnormal elevation above the normal number of red blood cells per volume in the circulation.
The presence of a carcinoma of the thyroid gland.
Vestibular areflexia can be measured as the absence of the caloric nystagmus response in electronystagmography.
An inflammation of the tonsils.

An abnormality of the inferior crus of the antihelix is the lower cartilaginous ridge arising at the bifurcation of the antihelix that ends beneath the fold of the ascending helix, and separates the concha from the triangular fossa.
A severe form of B lymphocytopenia in which the count of B cells is very low or absent.
Hypoplasia of the pancreas.
Absence of the tongue owing to a developmental abnormality.

Deviation from normal in the amount of alpha sarcoglycan in muscle. The alpha, beta, gamma, and delta sarcoglycans are components of the dystrophin-complex. They are all N-glycosylated transmembrane proteins with a short intra-cellular domain, a single transmembrane region and a large extra-cellular domain containing a cluster of conserved cysteines.
The presence of inflammation of the gastric mucous membrane.

A condition characterized by patchy atheromas or atherosclerotic plaques which develop in the walls of medium-sized and large arteries and can lead to arterial stenosis with reduced or blocked blood flow.
A type of monoclonal elevation of IgG in which the involved immunoglobulin has an abnormal structure with a heavy chain but not a light chain.
Increase in bone denisty in the diaphyseal (shaft) region of a metacarpal bone.
An abnormality of the morphology of the toes, such that the tips of the toes are prominent and bulbous.
Absence of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger.
A partial or complete duplication of one or more distal phalanx of toe.
Right-sided heart failure resulting from chronic hypertension in the pulmonary arteries and right ventricle.
Borderline intellectual disability is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 70-85.
Inflammation or infection of the middle ear.
A deviation from the normal straight form of the distal phalanx of the third toe.
An anomaly of the pharynx, i.e., of the tubular structure extending from the base of the skull superiorly to the esophageal inlet inferiorly.
An abnormality of the anterior fontanelle, i.e., the cranial fontanelle that is located at the intersection of the coronal and sagittal sutures.
Cysts of the cortex of the kidney.

Chronic loss of joint motion of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 4th finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. That is, the PIP joint of a fourth finger is bent (flexed) and cannot be straightened actively or passively. It is thus a chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement.
A neoplasm containing histiocytes.

A dermatosis characterized by generalized shiny, enamel-like, hyperpigmented scales in an irregular pattern. The scales may peel or desquamate, rather like old, sun-baked blistered paint, often with areas of underlying hypopigmentation. This has led to the terms peeling paint or flaky paint dermatosis (See the Figure in PMID:24285001).
Hoarseness refers to a change in the pitch or quality of the voice, with the voice sounding weak, very breathy, scratchy, or husky.
An increase in the level of N-acetylneuraminic acid in cultured fibroblasts.
A circumscribed, solid elevation of skin with no visible fluid, varying in size from a pinhead to less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point.
Formation of calcified tissue in the soft tissues surrounding the shoulder.
Supernumerary digits located at the ulnar side of the hand (that is, on the side with the fifth finger).
An abnormal concentration of sodium.
Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of an artery.
A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the basal ganglia.
An anomaly of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.

A displacement of the external urethral orifice from its normal position (in males normally placed at the tip of glans penis, in females normally placed about 2.5 cm behind the glans clitoridis and immediately in front of that of the vagina).

A deviation in the normal proportion of naive B cells (CD19+/CD27-/IgD+/IgM+) relative to the total number of B cells. Naive B cells represent one of the subtypes of B cells in the peripheral blood, and are B cells that have not been exposed to antigen.
A lack of ossification of the vertebral bodies.
An abnormally low value of the serum anion gap (the sum of serum chloride and bicarbonate concentrations subtracted from the serum sodium concentration).
Increased time for the complex comprised of the Q wave, R wave, and S wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).. In adults, normal values are 0.06 - 0.10 sec.

Hepatic failure refers to the inability of the liver to perform its normal synthetic and metabolic functions, which can result in coagulopathy and alteration in the mental status of a previously healthy individual. Hepatic failure is defined as acute if there is onset of encephalopathy within 8 weeks of the onset of symptoms in a patient with a previously healthy liver.
A dissemination viral infection caused by a live attenuated vaccine virus.
An increased concentration of methionine in the blood.
Agenesis of canine tooth.

A complete duplication affecting one or more of the middle phalanges of the hand. As opposed to a partial duplication were there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones, a complete duplication leads to two separate bones appearing side to side (radio-ulnar axis) as seen on x-rays. A duplication leading to an accessory bone appearing in the proximo-distal axis on x-rays, this is actually a different entity called a pseudoepiphysis (see corresponding terms) sometimes also referred to as hyperphalangism.
Aplasia or Hypoplasia affecting the 2nd metacarpal.
Slowing in occipital areas of the scalp EEG.
Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as Phenobarbital in blood.
Left main coronary artery begins (branches off from) the pulmonary artery rather than as normal from the root of the aorta, above the left cusp of the aortic valve.

Deterioration of enteric neurons with impairment of enteric neuronal structure. Typical neuropathological findings include qualitative (e.g., neuronal swelling, intranuclear inclusions, axonal degeneration) and quantitative (e.g., reduction in the number of neurons) abnormalities of the enteric neurons.
A hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, located in the intestines, which includes the bowel.
Abnormally big lacrimal glands.
Any anomaly of the structure of the femur.
Increased width of the femoral head.
Fusion of a middle phalanx of a finger with another bone.
An abnormal bulge or lump in a testis. A testicular mass has a long differential diagnosis including testicular torsion, epididymitis, acute orchitis, strangulated hernia and testicular cancer.
Immunohistochemistry shows complete lack of dysferlin protein in the muscle biopsy.
Focal clonic seizures affecting one side of the face.
Growth arrest lines are alternating transverse rings of sclerosis at the metaphysis of a long bone.
Underdevelopment of the ventral portion of the pons.
A medical history of exposure during the fetal period to hyperphenylalaninemia because the mother had phenylketonuria with inadequate control during pregnancy.
Presence of erythrocyte casts (cylindrical structures produced by the kidney in certain disease states) in the urine.
A rare form of anaphylaxis for which triggers cannot be identified despite a detailed history and careful diagnostic assessment.
An increased concentration of insulin in the blood in the fasting state, i.e., not as the response to food intake.
Increased distance between the maxillary central permanent incisor tooth.
The presence of any abnormality affecting the abdominal wall.
Amyotrophy (muscular atrophy) affecting the proximal musculature.
An abnormally increased diphosphate(4-) concentration in the blood. Diphosphate(4-), as ester with two phosphate groups, is also known as pyrophosphate.
Fasciculations or fibrillation affecting the tongue muscle.
A state of unease characterized by diffuse motor activity or motion subject to limited control, nonproductive or disorganized behavior, and subjective distress.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the retina.
An anomaly in the communication from a neuron to a target across a synapse in the peripheral nervous system.
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against nuclei or nuclear components.
Reduced strength of the axial musculature (i.e., of the muscles of the head and neck, spine, and ribs).

Disseminated intravascular coagulation is characterized by the widespread activation of coagulation, which results in the intravascular formation of fibrin and ultimately thrombotic occlusion of small and midsize vessels.

A bent (flexed) finger or toe joint that cannot be straightened actively or passively. It is thus a chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement of joints.

Absence of the right superior vena cava (RSVC). An absent RSVC is always associated with a persistent left superior vena cava (PLSVC). During normal fetal development, the left-sided anterior venous cardinal system regresses, leaving the coronary sinus (CS) and the ligament of Marshall. Failure of the closure of the left anterior cardinal vein results in PLSVC. In general, PLSVC is associated with the right superior vena cava (RSVC) and drains into the RA via a dilated CS. When developmental arrest occurs at an earlier stage, the CS is absent and the PLSVC drains into the left atrium.
Underdevelopment of the helix that either affects the entire helix, or is localized.

Absent or undetectable level of isohemagglutinin. An isohemagglutinin refers to the naturally occurring antibodies in the ABO blood group system (i.e., anti-A in a group B person, anti-B in a group A person, and anti-A, anti-B, and anti-A,B in a group O person).
An abnormally increased level of immunoglobulin A in blood.

A type of focal-onset seizure in which awareness is preserved. Awareness during a seizure is defined as the patient being fully aware of themself and their environment throughout the seizure, even if immobile.
Co-occurrence of reticular and micronodular patterns on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography.
Deterioration of cardiomyocyte charyacterized by abnormal features sich as loss of myotilaments, occurrence of cellular sequestration, decreased mitochondrial sizes and cellular debris.
The presence of an abnormal decrease or increase of one or more amino acids in the blood circulation.
Skin characterized by the lack of natural or normal moisture.
Underdevelopment of the vestibule of the inner ear.
