?def: Permanent indentation on the posteromedial aspect of the helix that may be sharply or indistinctly delineated.
The nostrils (the paired channels of the nose) are not present.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger.
Blockage of blood flow in the central retinal artery.
Increased width of the inferred cross-section of the inferior crus.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the phalanges of the 5th finger.
Flesh-colored papule in or around the nail bed. Ungual fibromas may be periungual (arising under the proximal nail fold ) or subungual (originating under the nail plate).

A complete duplication affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 2nd finger. As opposed to a partial duplication were there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones, a complete duplication leads to two separate bones appearing side to side (radio-ulnar axis) as seen on x-rays. A duplication leading to an accesory bone appearing in the proximo-distal axis on x-rays, is a different entity called a Pseudoepiphyses (see according terms) sometimes also referred to as Hyperphalangism.
Subcutaneous nodules that are located in the vicinity of joints.
Varicosity of veins in the vulval region.
Absence of the abdominal musculature.

Laxity of the tendon stabilising the lateral aspect of the tarsal plate to the zygomatic bone. This can result in rounded appearence of the lateral canthus. Also, when the eyelid is pulled medially, more than 2 mm movement of the canthal angle may be observed.
A type of astigmatism in which the principle meridians are not 90 degrees apart and which is associated with loss of vision.

An abnormal anatomical location of the posterior lobe of the hypophysis, also known as the neurohypophysis. The posterior pituitary is normally present in the dorsal portion of the sella turcica, but when ectopic is usually near the median eminence. This defect is likely to be due to abnormal migration during embryogenesis.
Pungent body odor.
An abnormality of the urinary bladder.

Uncontrolled contractions of muscles fibers in the left ventricle not producing contraction of the left ventricle. Ventricular fibrillation usually begins with a ventricular premature contraction and a short run of rapid ventricular tachycardia degenerating into uncoordinating ventricular fibrillations.
Areas of low density corresponding to parenchymal destruction and reduced perfusion, and attenuation of the pulmonary vasculature, as visualized on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography.
A scotoma (area of diminished vision within the visual field) that surrounds the central fixation point.

A type of bicuspid aortic valvue (BAV) characterized by the presence of a single raphe that extends from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps, resulting in two leaflets of unequal size.
A benign cartilaginous tumors of the lung.
A decreased concentration of leptin in the blood.
An increased denisty (number and tightness) of the muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the left ventricles of the heart (cardiac trabeculae, trabeculae carneae).
A morphological anomaly of the lateral ventricle.
A structural anomaly of the ciliary body.

Mottling (spots or blotches with different shades) of the retinal pigment epithelium, i.e., localized or generalized fundal pigment granularity associated with processes at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium.
Cellular infiltration of the liver parenchyma with a preponderance of eosinophils.
A structural anomaly of the nervous system.
An elevated circulating testosterone level in the blood.

An finding upon obstetric ultrasound examination performed at around 16 to 20 weeks of gestation that is abnormal but not clearly identifiable as a fetal anatomic malformation or growth restriction. Such findings are known as soft markers since they are associated with increased risk for fetal aneuploidy or other disorders.
Formation of bone tissue of trapezoid is less than expected for age.
The presence of immunoglobulin A deposits in the glomerulus.
An abnormal gait pattern in which persons stand and walk with their feet spaced widely apart. This is often a component of cerebellar ataxia.
Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the 4th (ring) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
Any structural anomaly of the muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the right ventricle of the heart (cardiac trabeculae, trabeculae carneae).
Decreased length of the eyelashes (subjective).
Abnormality of the temporal bone of the skull, which is situated at the sides and base of the skull roughly underlying the region of the face known as the temple.
A malignant olfactory neuroblastoma arising from the olfactory epithelium of the superior nasal cavity and cribriform plate.

Mutliple lesions of the oral mucosa resembling those characteristic of the disease lichen planus. These are symmetric reticular lesions that resemble a white, lacelike network, as well as by papules, plaques, erythematous lesions, and erosions.
A diminution of the volumetric fraction of blood pumped out of the ventricle with each cardiac cycle.
Direction of the U wave opposite to the T wave (i.e., below baseline) in leads with upright T waves.

An electrocardiographic anomaly of the ST segment, which is the segment that connects the QRS complex and the T wave. The ST segment normally has a duration of 80 to 120 ms, is flat and at the same level (isoelectric) as the PR and TP segment.
Extreme rapidity of speech.
An outward turning (eversion) or rotation of the eyelid margin (i.e., ectropion) caused by shortening or contraction of the anterior or middle lamellae related to scarring.
Absence or underdevelopment of the mandible.
A type of papillary renal cell carcinoma in which the papillae are covered by large eosinophilic cells with pleomorphic nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and nuclear pseudostratification.
Underdevelopment of the nasal septum.
The presence of a nephroblastoma, which is a neoplasm of the kidney that primarily affects children.
A reduction in the level of carnitine in muscle tissue.
Marked rugae formation of the skin of the labia majora.
An abnormality of the adenohypophysis, which is also known as the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland.
Dysplasia affecting the vasculature of the gastrointestinal tract.
Any structural anomaly of the principal vein draining blood from the lower portion of the body.
A comedo in which the part of the pore at the surface of the skin is stretched and open, exposing the contents of the comedo, which appear black.
A pregnancy that extends to 42 weeks of gestation or beyond.
A fibrous cardiac diverticulum refers to an aneurysm and usually appears as an isolated congenital anomaly.
Periodic (episodic or recurrent) bouts of fever.
The presence of punctiform calcification of the bone of the vertebral bodies.
Absence or extremely low level of IgA, IgM, and IgM in the circulation.

An abnormal concentration of globulins in the blood. Albumin makes up more than half of the total protein present in serum. The remaining blood proteins except albumin and fibrinogen (which is not in serum) are referred to as globulins. The globulin fraction includes hundreds of serum proteins including carrier proteins, enzymes, complement, and immunoglobulins. Most of these are synthesized in the liver, although the immunoglobulins are synthesized by plasma cells. Globulins are divided into four groups by electrophoresis. The four fractions are alpha1, alpha2, beta and gamma, depending on their migratory pattern between the anode and the cathode.
Inflammation of the optic nerve.
Mechanical percussion (i.e., striking a muscle with a reflex hammer) leads to spreading waves of muscle contractions that begin proximally and spread laterally across the muscle.
Any anomaly of the cerumen (ear wax), the yellowish waxy substance secreted in the ear canal.

A type of cancer that originates in the peritoneam. It is to be distinguished from metastatic cancer of the peritoneum. Peritoneal cancer can occur anywhere in the abdominal space, and affects the surface of organs contained inside the peritoneum.
Positioning of the antitragus at an angle perpendicular to the plane of the ear (oriented away from the plane of the ear).
An abnormally reduced count of basophils per volume in the blood circulation.
A headache disorder that occurs exclusively at night, waking the affected individual from sleep.
Conduction block in the posterior division of the left bundle branch of the bundle of His.
An excessive concavity of the anterior surface of one or more vertebral bodies.
Precocious (accelerated) maturation and calcification of any of the tarsal bones, seven bones of the foot comprising the calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, and the cuneiform bones.
Compression of the heart caused by rigid, thickened, or fused pericardial membranes.
An abnormal conical morphology of the incisor tooth.
An abnormal conical morphology of either maxillary primary incisor tooth or maxillary permanent incisor tooth or both.
A type of ventricular tachycardia characterized by polymorphioc QRS complexes that change in amplitue and cycle length, and thus have the appearance of oscillating around the baseline in the EKG.
An abnormality in which the eyes are held permanently wide open.
Any structural anomaly of the blood vessels of the macula.

Ebstein's anomaly refers to an abnormally placed and deformed tricuspid valve characterized by apical displacement of the septal and posterior tricuspid valve leaflets, leading to atrialization of the right ventricle with a variable degree of malformation and displacement of the anterior leaflet.
A developmental defect characterized by the absence of the Third ventricle.

A scoliosis which is the results of a difference in leg length (which might be due to hemihypertrophy or hemihypotrophy of a leg) and the resulting tilting of the pelvis. If untreated this will lead to the development of scoliosis over time.
Absence of wakefulness and conscience, but (in contrast to coma) with involuntary opening of the eyes and movements (such as teeth grinding, yawning, or thrashing of the extremities).
Abnormal flatness (decreased height) of epiphyses.
Presence of viable bacteria in the blood.

A facial cleft extending from the zygomatic arch to the eye. This zygomaticomaxillary cleft is similar to that typically found in Treacher Collins syndrome. The overlying tissue shows a vertical sclerodermic furrow radiating from the labial commissure or the angle of the mandible across the cheek to a coloboma of the lower eyelid between the middle and lateral one-third. Microphthalmia is not observed. The skeletal cleft is between the maxilla and zygoma; it passes through the inferolateral orbital rim to enter the inferior orbital fissure. No alveolar cleft is present. The zygomatic arch is intact. The soft tissue furrow, which is more apparent on the right, radiates from the oral commissure toward the lateral two-thirds of the lower eyelid. The antimongoloid obliquity of the palpebral fissures is associated with laterally placed lower eyelid clefts and some ectropion. A left-sided anophthalmia is accompanied by adjacent soft tissue hypoplasia and is reflected in a short palpebral fissure, enophthalmos, and minor ptosis of the eyebrow. No abnormality is present in the alveolar arch except for some tilting of the occlusal plane secondary to hypoplasia of the left side of the maxilla. There is a vertical bony groove in the region of the zygomaticomaxillary suture that ends in the inferolateral portion of a small bony orbit. More laterally, the remainder of the zygomatic body and arch is normal in both shape and dimension. The lateral orbital floor is downslanting but intact, and it lacks direct communication with the temporal or infratemporal fossae. The hypoplasia of the left side of the maxilla and orbit is associated with a reduction in the transverse and anteroposterior dimensions of the anterior cranial fossa; mild asymmetry of the middle cranial fossa and calvarium is present. No significant asymmetry of size, shape, or position is present in the sphenoid.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes two to four.
An infection of bone of the foot.
Underdevelopment of the ulna.
An increased amount of taurine in the blood.
Extreme thickening of the cortex of long bones.
A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs that is lethal at birth.
A type of dyssynergy characterized by the lack of the ability to smoothly perform the elements of a voluntary movement in the appropriate order and speed.
Acute renal failure with resolution of manifestations.
Agenesis of mandibular premolar.
Decreased width of the nasal ridge.
A functional abnormality of the pupil.

A developmental structural anomaly of the stalk-like part of the brain that comprises the midbrain (aka mesencephalon), the pons (aka pons Varolii), and the medulla oblongata, and connects the cerebral hemispheres with the cervical spinal cord.
A severe form of respiratory insufficiency characterized by inadequate gas exchange such that the levels of oxygen or carbon dioxide cannot be maintained within normal limits.
An elevation in bone density in one or more proximal phalanges of the fingers. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the third toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
A feeling of uneasiness and restlessness in the legs after going to bed (sometimes causing insomnia).

Bronchiolitis obliterans organizing pneumonia (BOOP) is and interstitial lung abnormalitiy characterized histopathologically by plugs of granulation tissue lying within small airways, alveolar ducts, and alveoli and by chronic inflammatory cell infiltration in alveolar walls. Patients with BOOP generally present with subacute illness, including shortness of breath, fever, malaise, and weight loss.
An endocrine tumor of the pancreas that secretes excessive amounts of glucagon.
A functional anomaly of the muscles of the eye.
Hyperapobetalipoproteinemia is defined as the combination of a normal low density lipoprotein (LDL) cholesterol in the face of an increased LDL apolipoprotein B (apoB) protein.
A malignant soft tissue neoplasm that arises from the heart.
A form of heterotopia were the mislocalized gray matter is located deep within the white matter.
Absence or underdevelopment of the distal phalanges.
Double outlet right ventricle (DORV) is a type of ventriculoarterial connection in which both great vessels arise entirely or predominantly from the right ventricle.
For children from birth to 16 years of age the length of the palm is more than the 97th centile; or, the length of the palm appears relatively long compared to the finger length or the limb length.
Failure to contain infection by a protozoan of the genus Cryptosporidium, leading to spread to many parts of the body.
Arterial inflammation.

Reduced activity of coagulation factor VII. Factor VII is part of the extrinsic coagulation pathway, which is initiated at the site of injury in response to the release of tissue factor (fIII). Tissue factor and activated factor VII catalyze the activation of factor X.
Hypopnea is referring to breathing that is abnormally shallower and/or slow.
Repeated episodes of abortion (Expulsion of the product of fertilization before completing the term of gestation) without deliberate interference.

Dysarthric speech is a general description referring to a neurological speech disorder characterized by poor articulation. Depending on the involved neurological structures, dysarthria may be further classified as spastic, flaccid, ataxic, hyperkinetic and hypokinetic, or mixed.
A focal defect in the elastic lamina of the aortic wall that leads to localized medial disruption and potential rupture.
An abnormal limitation of knee joint mobility.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by excessively rapid and deep breathing.
Abnormally wide bone of the skeleton of forearm.
A severe form of conductive hearing impairment.

Muscular hypotonia is an abnormally low muscle tone (the amount of tension or resistance to movement in a muscle), often involving reduced muscle strength. Hypotonia is characterized by a diminished resistance to passive stretching.
An immunodeficiency characterized by defective cell-mediated immunity or humoral immunity.
A type of lymphoma that originates in B-cells.
Presence of a bifid sacral bone.

A structural anomaly of the tiny blood vessels that connect arterioles with venules and whose walls act as semipermeable membranes that mediate the diffusion of fluids and gases between the blood circulation and body tissues.

An abnormality of mental functioning affecting the personality and behavioural tendencies of an individual and characterized by a rigid and unhealthy pattern of thinking and behavior. The definition of a personal disorder implies that the abnormality is not the result of damage or insult to the brain or from another psychiatric disorder.
Narrowing of a vein due to intimal hyperplasia and fibrosis.
An abnormality of the pulmonary veins.
An abnormality of the cerebral white matter.
Increased width of phalanx of one or more toes.
Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the proximal phalanx of the third finger.
Weakness or partial paralysis in the lower limbs.
Abnormality of the male genital system.
A type of adrenal hypoplasia with congenital onset.

A type of pleural effusion with a transudate (extravascular fluid with low protein content and a low specific gravity). Pleural effusions can be classified as transudates or exudates based on Light's criteria, which classify an effusion as exudate if one or more of the following are present: (1) the ratio of pleural fluid protein to serum protein is greater than 0.5, (2) the ratio of pleural fluid lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) to serum LDH is greater than 0.6, or (3) the pleural fluid LDH level is greater than two thirds of the upper limit of normal for serum LDH.
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the inferior mesenteric artery or superior mesenteric artery .
Absence of the tibia.
An abnormal morphology of the distal phalanx of the fifth toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Underdevelopment of the fovea centralis.
An abnormality of the plantar part of foot, that is of the soles of the feet.
Inability to make fine depth discriminations from parallax provided by the two eyes' different positions on the head.
Abnormally decreased blood carbon dioxide (CO2) level in the cord blood.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glutamic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Ophthalmoplegia is a paralysis or weakness of one or more of the muscles that control eye movement.
A malignant tumor that arises from the transitional (urothelial) epithelial cells lining the urinary tract from the renal calyces to the ureteral orifice.
Naevus flammeus localised in the skin of the neck. This is one of the most common birthmarks and present in approximately 25% of all newborns.
A type of erythrocyte inclusion composed of denatured hemoglobin.

Any deviation from the normal degree of echogenicity of the liver on sonography. Echogenicity refers to the ability of a tissue to reflect or transmit ultrasound waves in the context of surrounding tissues. Whenever there is an interface of structures with different echogenicities, a visible difference in contrast will be apparent on the screen. Based on echogenicity, a structure can be characterized as hyperechoic (white on the screen), hypoechoic (gray on the screen) and anechoic (black on the screen).
Abnormally small penis. At birth, the normal penis is about 3 cm (stretched length from pubic tubercle to tip of penis) with micropenis less than 2.0-2.5 cm.
Patchy and irregular skin pigmentation.
Craniosynostosis involving at least 2 cranial sutures, where the exact pattern of sutures fused has not been precisely specified.
Aplasia (absence) of the urinary bladder.
Applies to a sign, symptom, or other manifestation that recurs with a fixed time interval, i.e., the symptom-free periods are always of the same length.
Any structural anomaly of megakaryocytes. Mature blood platelets are released from the cytoplasm of megakaryocytes, which are bone-marrow resident cells.
A developmental disturbance with extreme ureteral dilatation.
A deviation from the normal amount of time required for food to pass through the intestines.
A progressive form of scoliosis with congenital onset.
An abnormally decreased level of immunoglobulin G (IgG) in blood.
An abnormality of the composition of urine or the levels of its components.
An impaired ability of the eye to move in the outward direction (towards the side of the head).
A malignant melanoma originating within the eye. The tumor originates from the melanocytes in the uvea (which comprises the iris, ciliary body, and choroid).

A heterogeneous group of symptoms that are localized in the epigastric region. Typical dyspeptic symptoms include postprandial fullness, early satiation, epigastric pain and epigastric burning, but other upper gastrointestinal symptoms such as nausea, belching or abdominal bloating often occur.
An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can expel following maximal insipiration, with the test being performed before the administration of a bronchodilating medication.
Bony fusion of the middle and proximal phalanges of the 3rd toe.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of threonine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter visible along the whole brain.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the endocrine system.
Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates that show positive staining with antibodies against ubiquitin within cells of the brain.
An obstruction to the forward flow of blood in the outflow tract of the right ventricle.
Incomplete closure of the embryonic neural tube, whereby some vertebral arches remain unfused and open. The mildest form is spina bifida occulta, followed by meningocele and meningomyelocele.
A abnormal elevation above the normal concentration of beta-C-terminal telopeptide of type I collagen in the blood circulation.

The sacroiliac joint in the bony pelvis connects the sacrum and the ilium of the pelvis, which are joined by strong ligaments. The notch is located directly superior to the joint. This term refers to a reduction in the lateral dimension of the notch.
Increased length of the umbilical cord.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the inner ear.

Nontender, round and firm, but slightly compressible, intradermal or subcutaneous cyst measuring 0.5-5 cm in diameter. Epidermal cysts are intradermal or subcutaneous tumors, grow slowly and occur on the face, neck, back and scrotum. They usually appear at or around puberty, and as a rule an affected individual has one solitary or a few cysts.

?def: Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the distal metaphysis of the femur.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the hallux.
The presence of a neoplasm of the testis with origin in a Leydig cell.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of carnosine in the blood circulation.
The absence of a phalangeal segment of a toe or hallux.
An elevated concentration of urobilinogen in the urine.
A progressive form of hearing impairment.
Asymmetry of the bones of the skull.
A unilateral form of ptosis.
A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the ring finger of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.
A bilateral type of conductive hearing impairment.
The presence of dilatation of the renal pelvis.
Multiple defects in the atrial septum.
Greater than normal amounts of fat in the feces. This is a result of malabsorption of lipids in the small intestine and results in frothy foul-smelling fecal matter that floats.
Redundant eyelid skin pressing the eyelashes against the cornea and/or conjunctiva.

A degree of kidney failure severe enough to require dialysis or kidney transplantation for survival characterized by a severe reduction in glomerular filtration rate (less than 15 ml/min/1.73 m2) and other manifestations including increased serum creatinine.
Compression of the celiac artery.
An anomaly of the labia, the externally visible portions of the vulva.
An abnormality of the lacrimal punctum, an opening on the eyelid close to the medial canthus that drains tears from the conjunctival sac into the lacrimal duct in the same eyelid.
Pattern of blood flow in the heart that deviates from the normal circuit of the circulatory system.
Absence of the quadriceps muscle.

Any deviation from the normal range of the antimullerian hormone, a peptide produced by the granulosa cells of follicles. Anti-Mullerian hormone (AMH), also known as Mullerian inhibiting substance, is produced by the granulosa cells of small antral follicles of the ovary. AMH has an inhibiting role in the ovary, contributing to follicular arrest. AMH levels in women are low until the age of 8, rise rapidly until puberty and decline steadily from the age of 25 until menopause, when AMH production ceases.
A cranial suture that is in addition to canonical membrane-covered openings in the incompletely ossified skull of the fetus or newborn infant.
The presence of only a single nostril.
Increased size of the teeth, which can be defined as a mesiodistal tooth diameter (width) more than 2 SD above mean for age. Alternatively, an apparently increased maximum width of the tooth.
An inflammation of the ovary or ovaries.
An abnormal reduction below the normal concentration of mannose-binding protein in the blood circulation.
Abnormally elevated activity of the enzyme phosphoribosyl pyrophosphatesynthetase, which catalyzes the synthesis of PP-ribose-P from ATP and ribose-5-phosphate.
Episodes of very rapid breathing.
A form of nystagmus in which the eyeball makes rotary motions around the axis.
Decreased activity of the reaction 5-oxo-L-proline + ATP + 2 H(2)O = L-glutamate + ADP + 2 H(+) + phosphate.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the middle ear.
Excessive growth of the bones of cranium, i.e., of the skull.
An abnormality of the medulla oblongata, the lower half of the brainstem.
Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the inferior rectus muscle.
Presence of leukocyte casts (cylindrical structures produced by the kidney in certain disease states) in the urine.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is difficult to treat or cure.

An increased blood concentration of the carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA). CEA is a member of the immunoglobulin supergene family. The human CEA gene family is clustered on chromosome 19q and comprises 29 genes. CEA is highly expressed in embryonic tissue and in some cancers, and is a widely used tumor marker.
A focal type of palmoplantar keratoderma in which only certain areas of the palms and soles are affected.
Detection of amphetamine or its metabolites in urine.
Reduced transparency of the central portion of the corneal stroma.
Urticaria in response to exposure to ultraviolet-A (UVA), ultraviolet-B (UVB), visible and rarely infrared light.
The presence of a hamartoma of the cerebrum.
A reduced level of insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF1) in the blood circulation.
An abnormally increased concentration of the IgG1 subtype in the blood circulation.
An increased number of squamous epithelial cells per high-power field in urinanalysis.
Hypertrophy (increase in size) of muscle cells (as opposed to hyperplasia, which refers to an increase in the number of muscle cells).
Interphalangeal joint stiffness is a perceived sensation of tightness in the interphalangeal joints when attempting to move them after a period of inactivity.
A detachment that involves the peripheral retina that does not extend into the macula.
A cataract that affects the posterior part of the cortex of the lens.
Formation of an anuclear keratin layer
An abnormality of hair pigmentation (color).

The doll's eye reflex (also known as oculocephalic reflex) is a test of brain function that is performed in comatose patients by elevating the head roughly 30 degrees and rapidly rotating the head from side to side with the eyes kept open. A normal response is for the eyes to move in the opposite direction. If the eyes do not move in the opposite direction this may indicate severe brain damage.

Medial degeneration of the aorta is to be used as an overarching term for any aortic surgical specimens that demonstrate one or more of the specific histopathologies mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation, elastic fiber fragmentation and/or loss, elastic fiber thinning, elastic fiber disorganization, smooth muscle cell nuclei loss, laminar medial collapse, smooth muscle cell disorganization, medial fibrosis. Grading of medial degeneration is based on the average overall severity of specific histopathologies as described, considering the worst area(s) sampled from multiple slides and aorta sections.
A rapid heartrate that exceeds the range of the normal resting heartrate for age.
A loss of myelinated nerve fibers in the peripheral nervous system (in general, this finding can be observed on nerve biopsy).
Increased bulk of tissue alongside the nose. The fullness can be caused by both bony and soft tissues.
A condition in which the superior portion of the helix is folded over to a greater degree than normal.
An anomaly of visually evoked potentials (VEP), which are electrical potentials, initiated by brief visual stimuli, which are recorded from the scalp overlying the visual cortex.

An abnormal shape of the incisura, defined as the narrowed downward continuation of the conchal space bounded anteriorly by the borders of the tragus, posteriorly by the antitragus, and along its lower lateral margins and inferior boundary by the connection between the first two. The upper boundary is a somewhat arbitrary line crossing from the apices of the antitragus and the tragus.
The loss of continuity between the left subclavian artery and the aorta, with persistent connection to the homolateral pulmonary artery through the patent (PDA) or nonpatent ductus arteriosus.

A lesion associated with atherosclerosis, a multifactorial and multipart progressive disease manifested by the focal development within the arterial wall of lesions, that ranges from teh development of a fatty streak, plaque progression, and plaque disruption. Atherosclerotic lesions demonstrate consistent morphological characteristics, which indicate that each type may stabilize temporarily or permanently and that progression to the next type may require an additional stimulus.

A conjuctival lesion composed of adipose tissue and dense connective tissue. Such choristomas of dermal elements are normally found at the outer canthus, and have a gelatinous appearance. Classically, there is an indistinct posterior border (with the lesion frequently extending into the orbit) and a well-demarcated anterior border several millimetres posterior to the limbus.
A reduced ability to discriminate between different temperatures.
Any structural anomaly of the hippocampus,

Reduced ability of von Willibrand factor (vWF) to bind collagen. Abnormal response to collagen as manifested by reduced or lacking ability of plasma von WIllebrand Factor to bind collagen. An ELISA-based assay is typically used; the test is sensitive to loss of von Willebrand Factor high molecular weight multimers.

?def: Absence of a testis from the scrotum on one side owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the scrotum.
Complete absence of the interatrial septum with common atrioventricular valve and two atrioventricular connections.
Non-continuity of the aortic arch with an atretic point or absent segment between the innominate and left carotid arteries.
A reduced ability of a B cell to become activated, i.e., the change in morphology and behavior of

Syncope refers to a generalized weakness of muscles with loss of postural tone, inability to stand upright, and loss of consciousness. Once the patient is in a horizontal position, blood flow to the brain is no longer hindered by gravitation and consciousness is regained. Unconsciousness usually lasts for seconds to minutes. Headache and drowsiness (which usually follow seizures) do not follow a syncopal attack. Syncope results from a sudden impairment of brain metabolism usually due to a reduction in cerebral blood flow.
The presence of a sagittal suture (the cranial suture that separates the left and right parietal bones) that is not ossified but rather wide open at an age when it is normally closed.

Chronic loss of joint motion in the 3rd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The term camptodactyly of the 3rd finger is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.
Increased susceptibility to Staphylococcus aureus infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Staphylococcus aureus infection.
Abnormalities of the metatarsal bones (i.e. of five tubular bones located between the tarsal bones of the hind- and mid-foot and the phalanges of the toes).
A hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, that is located in the spleen.

An anomalous radiographic appearance of the developing pelvis, in which the greater ischiadic noth (incisura ischiadica major) is shallow and the pelvis takes on the appearance said to resemble a halberd (a weapon especially of the 15th and 16th centuries consisting typically of a battle-ax and pike mounted on a handle).
An abnormal morphology of one or more middle phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Decreased cell membrane concentration of the glycoprotein complex Ib-IX-V.

Visual impairment (or vision impairment) is vision loss (of a person) to such a degree as to qualify as an additional support need through a significant limitation of visual capability resulting from either disease, trauma, or congenital or degenerative conditions that cannot be corrected by conventional means, such as refractive correction, medication, or surgery.

?def: In a Number 10 Tessier cleft there is an upper central orbital cleft with a cleft of the middle one-third of the upper eyelid, which often results in total ablepharia. The eyebrow is disrupted, being virtually absent medially, whereas the lateral portion angles upward toward the frontal hairline. There may be ocular anomalies, including colobomata of the iris. The skeletal cleft is through the midportion of the supraorbital rim, the adjacent frontal bone, and the orbital roof lateral to the supraorbital nerve. A frontal encephalocele frequently occupies the frontal bony cleft. The palpebral fissure is grossly elongated with an amblyopic eye displaced inferiorly and laterally. There is also a divergent squint of the right eye. The eyebrow is deficient medially and becomes thinned out laterally , where it is contiguous with a broad downward and forward projection of the frontotemporal hairline (this may be seen in both the Number 9 and 10 clefts.) A broad frontal encephalocele bulges forward from the middle one-third of the right forehead, supraorbital ridge, and orbital roof. The bony cleft, through which the frontal encephalocele presents, involves the anterior half of the orbital roof, the supraorbital rim, and two-thirds of the vertical height of the frontal bone lateral to the supraorbital nerve. The bony orbit is inferiorly displaced and widened with the lateral orbital wall shortened and laterally deviated. Similar distortion of the anterior cranial fossa is evident, being broader and more flattened on the affected side. The calvarium above the level of the cleft and the cranial base below is symmetric.
An abnormality of the cornea characterized by the deposition of calcium in a band across the central cornea, leading to decreased vision, foreign body sensation, and ocular irritation.
The epiphysis of the first metacarpal is localized at the proximal end of the metacarpal bone although an accessory epiphysis may be located at the distal end of the metacarpal.

An abnormality of gaze that can be observed following an acute supranuclear cerebral lesion (e.g., stroke) that is characterized by an acute inability to direct gaze contralateral to the side of the lesion and is accompanied by a tendency for tonic deviation of the eyes toward the side of the lesion.
Any structural anomaly of the mitochondria.
An abnormal form or size of neutrophils in the cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormal morphology of the distal phalanx of the big toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Recurrent episodes of apnea that are precipitated by factors such as illness, fatigue, or stress.

An elevation of the level of the enzyme creatine kinase (also known as creatine phosphokinase, CPK; EC 2.7.3.2) in the blood. CPK levels can be elevated in a number of clinical disorders such as myocardial infarction, rhabdomyolysis, and muscular dystrophy.
Increase in thickness of the basal lamina of the glomerulus of the kidney.

Reduced ability affecting mainly visuospatial cognition which may be tested using pattern construction (for example by Differential Ability Scales, which test a person's strengths and weaknesses across a range of intellectual abilities).
A reduction in the expression of CD43 on the cell surface of lymphocytes.
Hyposegmented (hypolobulated) or bilobed neutrophil nuclei in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Acute inflammation of the lung due to an infection.
An abnormal amount of urine production.
Involuntary fecal soiling in adults and children who have usually already been toilet trained.
An increased concentration of all types of amino acid in the urine.
Complete absence of all nasal structures.
Inflammation of cartilage.
A rare birth defect in women where the urethra and vagina both open into a common channel.
Prominence of blood vessels of the deep episcleral tissues.
Yellow nodules of lipoid material are deposited in the skin and mucosae. This gives rise to granulomatous reactions.

A hand or foot with more than five digits that has a recognizable A/P axis of symmetry. The axis can lie within a normally formed or partially duplicated digit resembling a middle finger, index finger, thumb, toe, or hallux. Alternatively, the axis can be in an interdigital space with a flanking pair of digits that resemble a middle finger, index finger, thumb, toe or hallux. The most lateral digits on each side of the hand typically resemble fifth fingers/toes.
Loss of the primary (also known as deciduous) teeth before the usual age.
An anomalous build up of copper (Cu) in the brain.
An abnormal communication between the terminus of a coronary artery, bypassing the myocardial capillary bed and entering the right ventricle.

A duplication of the collecting system of the kidney, defined as a kidney with two (instead of, normally, one) pyelocaliceal systems. The pyelocaliceal system is comprised of the renal pelvis and calices. The duplicated renal collecting system can be associated with a single ureter or with double ureters. In the latter case, the two ureters empty separately into the bladder or fuse to form a single ureteral orifice.
Initial bilateral ptosis followed by limitation of eye movements in all directions and slowing of saccades.
Complete dislocation of the lens of the eye.
Increased width of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger.
The ability of the thumb joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.
A morphological abnormality of the optic disc, i.e., of the portion of the optic nerve clinically visible on fundoscopic examination.
Amniotic constriction rings affecting the arms.
Squamous cell carcinoma of the skin is a malignant tumor of squamous epithelium.
An anomaly of the margin of the cornea overlapped by the sclera.
Severe or complete weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities.
A functional abnormality of the immune system.
An abnormality of a blood vessel of the head, including branches of the arterial and venous systems of the head.
Chronic hepatitis characterized by parenchymal inflammation with formation of large multinucleated hepatocytes in response to a variety of insults to the liver.
A nail plate that has a longitudinal separation with partially separated nails, each with a separate lateral radius of curvature.
An anomalous response to intravenous stimulation by human chorionic gonadotrophin. Stimulation with hCG stimulates testicular Leydig cells to secrete androgens via the Leydig hormone receptors.
Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of a metaphysis of a tibia.
The joint between the second metatarsal and the proximal phalanx of the 4th toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.

An anomalous response to the insulin tolerance test (ITT), in which insulin is administered intravenously and blood glucose and potentially other compounds are measred at intervals. Insulin administration is intended to induce extreme hypoglycemia (bloodgluoce below 40 mg/dl), which in turn induces release of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) and growth hormone (GH). ACTH induces the adrenal gland to release cortisol, which together with GH opposes the action of insulin on the blood glucose level.
An abnormality of Krebs cycle metabolism that is characterized by a decreased rate of fumarate hydratase activity.
An abnormality of the placenta in which there are numerous cystic spaces within the placenta as well as placental enlargement.

Cerebral palsy describes a group of permanent disorders of the development of movement and posture, causing activity limitation, that are attributed to nonprogressive disturbances that occurred in the developing fetal or infant brain. The motor disorders of cerebral palsy are often accompanied by disturbances of sensation, perception, cognition, communication, and behaviour, by epilepsy, and by secondary musculoskeletal problems.
Partial duplication of proximal phalanx of third toe.
Deposits accumulating between the retinal pigment epithelium and Bruch's membrane and that are distributed in multiple foci.
Absence of the scapulae.
A condition characterized by a loss or deficiency of the stem cells in the limbus that are vital for re-population of the corneal epithelium and to the barrier function of the limbus.
V-shaped cut (notch) in the middle of the P wave.
Moderate anterior chamber flare (iris and lens details clear).
Increased addition of sialic acids to N-linked glycans.
A form of monochromacy in which vision is derived from the remaining preserved blue (S) cones and rod photoreceptors.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of the HDL3a subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL3a particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 8.2-8.79 nm.
Chronic infection of the nails by Candida species.
An elevation in bone density in one or more foot bones. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
Any structural abnormality of a facial artery, one of the branches of the external carotid artery.

Elevated ratio between the upper and the lower segment of the body, where the lower segment is defined as the length between the top of pubic symphysis to floor, and the upper segment is defined as the top of head to top of pubic symphysis.
An abnormality of the neurohypophysis, which is also known as the posterior lobe of the hypophysis.
Abnormal morphology of vertebral body.
Reduced diameter of the middle phalanx of finger.
An excessive division of the lobes of the nucleus of a neutrophil in the cerebrospinal fluid.
The Odon device is an instrument for assisted vaginal deliveries that is applied on the head of the baby and used to apply traction to assist the birth process.
Occurrence of epileptiform discharges in occipital, central, temporal and parietal regions during photic stimulation.
Vaginal delivery following induction of labor, a procedure used to stimulate uterine contractions during pregnancy before labor begins on its own.
Malfunction of the abducens nerve as manifested by impairment of the ability of the affected eye to be moved outward.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0271355 SNOMEDCT_US:398963001 MSH:C564661 SNOMEDCT_US:398760006 MSH:D020434 SNOMEDCT_US:398925009

?def: Libman-Sacks valvular lesions are sterile fibrofibrinous vegetations that favor the left-sided heart valves and usually form on the ventricular surface of the mitral valve.
An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in tissue.
An elevation above normal limits of the concentration of estrone in the circulation.
Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the 5th (little) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
Lack of convexity or prominence of the contour of the ridge between the bottom of the incisura and the confluence of the ascending helix and crus helix.
Severe reduction of the ability to see defined as visual acuity less than 6/60 (20/200 in US notation; 0.1 in decimal notation) but at least 3/60 (20/400 in US notation; 0.05 in decimal notation).
Cerebral hemorrhage that occurs before birth.

A type of glomerulonephritis characterized by diffuse mesangial cell proliferation and the thickening of capillary walls due to subendothelial extension of the mesangium. The term membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis is often employed to denote a general pattern of glomerular injury seen in a variety of disease processes that share a common pathogenetic mechanism, rather than to describe a single disease entity
Underdevelopment of the musculature of the pelvis.
A reduction in the concentration of thromboxane B2 in the blood circulation.
An abnormal curvature of the spine in both a coronal (lateral) and sagittal (back-to-front) plane.
Increased concentration of biopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
A medical history of exposure of the mother of a child or fetus to a teratogenic substance during pregnancy.
Any functional defect of the tricuspid valve.
Spasticity (neuromuscular hypertonia) primarily in the muscles of the legs, hips, and pelvis.
A partial dislocation affecting some or all of the metacarpophalangeal joints.
A reduction in the rate of cholesterol esterification.
Inflammation of the biliary ductal system, affecting the intrahepatic or extrahepatic portions, or both.
Displacement or malalignment of one or more joints in the lower extremity (leg).
Triangular shaped middle phalanx of the 5th (little) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
Abnormally increased levels of isoleucine in cerebrospinal fluid.

An abnormality of the cheek- one of two bilateral soft tissue facial structures in the region of the face inferior to the eyes and between the nose and the ear. \Buccal\" means relating to the cheek. The cheek is part of the midface"
Fibroblast proliferation and fiber expansion from the portal areas to the lobule.
Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in the ACTH receptor.

An abnormality in which the abdominal organs are positioned in such a way with respect to each other and the left-right axis as to be not clearly lateralised and thus have neither the usual, or normal (situs solitus), nor the mirror-imaged (situs inversus) arrangements.
A complete or partial duplication of the tragus; expected to lie anterior to the normal tragus.
An episodic form of supraventricular tachycardia with abrupt onset and termination.

Nodular changes affecting the eyelids may have many different causes such as cystic lesions (chalaziae, hordeolae), lipogranulomas, melanomas, infectious diseases (Molluscum contagiosum) and many more.
A contrqacture (chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin) that prevent normal movement of one or more joints of the limbs.
Decreased width of nail.
Blood clot formed within muscle tissue following leakage of blood into the tissue.
A rare congenital vascular anomaly that results when the left superior cardinal vein caudal to the innominate vein fails to regress.

Cholangiocarcinoma is a primary cancer originating in the biliary epithelium i.e., the cholangiocytes, of the extrahepatic and intrahepatic biliary ducts. It is extremely invasive, develops rapidly, often metastasizes, and has a very poor prognosis. They are slow growing tumors which spread longitudinally along the bile ducts with neural, perineural and subepithelial extension.
Increased pressure in the pre-hepatic portal vein.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) and perceived to originate in the abdomen.
Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles of the leg brought on by physical exertion.

A developmental defect of the sacrum characterized by partial or disordered development of the sacrum in which portions of the sacrum, which normally is formed by fusion of five sacral vertebrae S1-S5, fail to form or fail to form normally.
Sustained involuntary muscle contractions that produce twisting and repetitive movements of the body.
Ectopic deposition of calcium salts in the Achilles tendon.
A chronic loss of wrist joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevent normal movement of the joints of the wrist.
An abnormal concentration of corticotropin in the blood.
Present in 0% of the cases.
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphyses of the metacarpals.
An abnormal decrease in the level of lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
An abnormal narrowing of the spinal canal related to a reduction in the interpedicular distance (i.e., the distance measured between the pedicles on frontal [coronal] imaging).

An infection that is caused by a fungus that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such fungi take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.
Developmental hypoplasia (shortening) of proximal phalanx of toe.

A stroke related to a small infarct (2-20 mm in diameter) in the deep cerebral white matter, basal ganglia, or pons, that is presumed to result from the occlusion of a single small perforating artery supplying the subcortical areas of the brain.
Unilateral atrophy (reduction in size) of an arm.

Enlargement of the cardiac ventricular muscle tissue with increase in the width of the wall of the ventricle and loss of elasticity. Ventricular hypertrophy is clinically differentiated into left and right ventricular hypertrophy.
An anomaly of the addition of fucose sugar units to O-linked glycans.
A predominantly right ventricular variant of isolated noncompaction cardiomyopathy.
Triangular shaped phalanges of the 2nd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
Shortening of the arms predominantly affecting terminal parts of the arm in relation to the upper and middle limb segments.
An increased amount of aspartic acid in the blood.
Absence of the musculature of the pelvis.
Complete duplication of the Second proximal phalanx of hand.

Hyperventilation refers to an increased pulmonary ventilation rate that is faster than necessary for the exchange of gases. Hyperventilation can result from increased frequency of breathing, an increased tidal volume, or both, and leads to an excess intake of oxygen and the blowing off of carbon dioxide.
Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the distal phalanx of the second finger.
Caries is a multifactorial bacterial infection affecting the structure of the tooth. This term has been used to describe the presence of more than expected dental caries.
An abnormality of the biliary tree.
A deviation from the normal straight form of the proximal phalanx of the third toe.
The presence of a supernumerary, i.e. third, crus of the helix in the helix, arising at or above the normal bifurcation of the antihelix.
Vaginal birth after Caesarian (VBAC) refers to the situation where the mother has had a previous Cesarean delivery but has now delivered vaginally.
Transient eyelid retraction during refixation from down to straight ahead.
A form of agenesis of the tricuspid valve in which (although the normal orifice between the right atrium and right ventricle exists) there is no tricuspid valvular tissue.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the little finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.

A highly malignant embryonal tumor of infancy and young childhood characterized by neuroectodermal elements organized in distinctive multilayered rosettes. Ependymoblastomas are large lesions that occur in the supratentorial compartment, typically displaying a physical connection to the ventricular system.
Abnormal enlargement in the upper jaw (maxilla) or in the lower jaw (mandible).
Tibial torsion is inward twisting (medial rotation) (PATO:0002155) of the tibia.
Exaggerated anterior convexity of the thoracic vertebral column.
Abnormal response to collagen-related peptide (CRP) as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of CRP.
The presence of a cyst, fistula, or abscess in the sacrococcygeal region (gluteal crease) characteristically accompanied by hair and skin folds.
Muscle fibers contain one or more vacuoles (membrane-bound cavity) associated with collections of membranes arranged in a whorl-like (spiral or circular) manner.

Pseudobulbar signs result from injury to an upper motor neuron lesion to the corticobulbar pathways in the pyramidal tract. Patients have difficulty chewing, swallowing and demonstrate slurred speech (often initial presentation) as well as abnormal behavioral symptoms such as inappropriate emotional outbursts of uncontrolled laughter or weeping etc.
A type of hyperbilirubinemia with neonatal onset.
Prolonged and excessive menses at regular intervals in excess of 80 mL or lasting longer than 7 days.
Absence of the neurohypophysis owing to a developmental defect.
A structural anomaly of the two central microtubules of motile cilia with a 9+2 microtubuluar configuration.

A congenital defect in the skull, whereby there is a protrusion of part of the cranial contents through a congenital defect in the cranium, usually covered with skin or mucous membrane. The term encephalocele refers to a subclass of these lesions in which brain tissue protrudes through the defect.
A form of amyloidosis that affects the kidney.
An abnormality characterized by chronic impairment of the normal functioning of the axons.
A chronic deviation from normal pressure in the systemic arterial system.
Redness of the skin of the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.
An abnormally low concentration of maternal serum human chorionic gonadotropin as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

An abnormally elevated proportion of exhausted T cells (Tex) among circulating T cells. T cell exhaustion is a distinct differentiation state that can be distinguished from naive, effector, and memory T cells. Compared to effector (TE) and memory (TMEM) T cells, exhausted T cells (TEX) display impaired effector functions (e.g., rapid production of effector cytokines, cytotoxicity). TEX have limited proliferative potential, especially compared to some subsets of TMEM and naive T cells.
Punding is a stereotypical motor behavior characterized by an intense fascination with repetitive, excessive and non-goal oriented handling, and examining of objects.
Urine has an increased amount of frothy fine bubbles.

Occurence of adrenarche at a later than normal age. Adrenarche normally occurs between six and eight years of age with increased adrenal androgen secretion; its exact biologic role is not well understood. It is accompanied by changes in pilosebaceous units, a transient growth spurt and the appearance of axillary and pubic hair in some children, but no sexual development.
A form of loss of vision caused by damage to the visual cortex rather than a defect in the eye.
An abnormality of the nasal bone, comprising the left nasal bone and the right nasal bone.
Lichenification affecting primarily flexural areas of the skin.
A lesion located beneath a fingernail or toenail.

Distance between the philtral ridges, measured just above the vermilion border, more than 2 standard deviations below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased distance between the ridges of the philtrum.
Lack of ossification of the sacrum.

The carpus consists of the scaphoid, lunate, triquetal, pisiform, captitate, hamate, trapezoid, and trapezium bones. The tarsus consists of the talus, calcaneus, navicular, cuboid, cuneiform, and navicular bones. This term applies if there is any fusion among the bones of the carpus or tarsus.
A progressive form of ptosis.
An abnormal area of increased brightness (hyperintensity) that occurs in several distinct areas.
An excessive concavity of the posterior surface of one or more vertebral bodies.
Food-induced anaphylaxis is a severe, potentially fatal, systemic allergic reaction that occurs suddenly after contact with an allergy-causing food.
An abnormality of the tricarboxylic acid cycle.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the 5th finger.
An anomaly in the metabolism of a vitamin.
Pelvic asymmetry refers to asymmetric positioning of landmarks on the two sides of the pelvis and may have a structural or functional etiology.
An anomaly of a toe.
Reduced strength and weakness of the muscles of the arms and legs.
A developmental defect resulting in an obstructing membrane in the posterior male urethra.
Jaundice that is sometimes present, sometimes not.
A type of dental misalignment with crowded central incisors, i.e., of maxillary secondary incisor, or of maxillary central primary incisor.
Absence or underdevelopment of the pubic bone.
Failure of growth hormone levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the glucagon stimulation test.
An abnormally reduced concentration of glycine in the blood.

An addictive behavior defined as drinking excessive amounts of alcohol over a long period of time, having difficulty reducing the amount of alcohol consumed, strongly desiring alcohol and experiencing withdrawal symptoms when not drinking alcohol.

A type of heterotaxy where some paired structures on opposite sides of the left-right axis of the body are symmetrical mirror images of each other, and have the morphology of the normal right-sided structures.
It is characterized by one or more symptoms including sneezing, itching, nasal congestion, and rhinorrhea.
Decreased protrusion of the superior crus relative to the prominence of a normal antihelix stem.
An abnormal increase in the average blood pressure in an individual during a single cardiac cycle.

Atrioventricular (AV) dissociation is present if the atria and the ventricles are under the control of two separate pacemakers. AV dissociation can occur in the absence of a primary AV conduction disturbance.
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the tongue.
Displacement of the 4th finger towards the radial side (i.e., towards the thumb).
Chronic supraventricular tachycardia predominantly seen in childhood.
Atrophy (wasting, decrease in size of cells or tissue) affecting the cerebrum.

?def: A tumor of the uterine cervix.
An increase in the level of N-acetyl aspartate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Ossification of carpal bones at an abnormally early age.
Pain experienced with swallowing.
A benign renal neoplasm composed of fat, vascular, and smooth muscle elements.
Congenital deep dermal melanosis in the sacral area.
A type of pulmonary sequestration that is completely enclosed in its own pleural sac, occurring above, within, or below the diaphragm, and without communication with the tracheobronchial tree.
An abnormality of the cortex of the kidney.
An abnormality of the metencephalon. The metencephalon is the part of the hindbrain that consists of the pons and the cerebellum.
Mislocalised thyroid gland.
An excessive desire to eat salt (sodium chloride) or salty foods.

Abnormality of REM sleep. Phases of REM sleep are characterized by desynchronized EEG patterns, increases in heart rate and blood pressure, sympathetic activation, and a profound loss of muscle tonus except for the eye and middle-ear muscles. There are then phases of rapid eye movements.
Deviation from the normal von Willebrand factor multimer pattern.
Loss (reduction of previously present) of subcutaneous adipose tissue in the region of the trunk.
Premature development of the breasts.

Myelocystocele is characterized by a large, ependyma-lined, cystic dilation of the caudal end of the central canal of the spinal cord; it projects dorsally through a lamina defect, with overlying varying amounts of lipomatous subcutaneous tissue. Myelocystoceles are associated with a tethered cord and meningocele, which communicates with the spinal subarachnoid space, but not with the central canal cyst.

Angle formed by the plane of the ear and the mastoid bone greater than the 97th centile for age (objective); or, outer edge of the helix more than 2 cm from the mastoid at the point of maximum distance (objective).
Acute inflammation of the kidney affecting the interstitium of the kidneys surrounding the tubules.
A tendency to turn the face to the right to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.

A spectrum of malformations of cortical development caused by insufficient neuronal migration that subsumes the terms agyria, pachygyria and subcortical band heterotopia. See also neuropathological definitions for 2-, 3-, and 4-layered lissencephaly.
Any anomaly of the structure of the uterus
Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the 5th (little) finger.
Increased catalysis of the reaction: 2 superoxide + 2 H+ = O2 + hydrogen peroxide.
A type of stenosis of the external auditory meatus in which the opening of the external auditory meatus appears as a vertical slit.
Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of a metaphysis of a fibula.

A soft tissue prominence of the ventral aspects of the fingertips. The term \persistent fetal fingertip pads\" is often used as a synonym, but should better not be used because it implies knowledge of history of the patient which often does not exist."
An abnormal reduction in the concentration of corticotropin, also known as adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), in the blood.
Increased concentration of SO3(2-), i.e., sulfite, in the urine.
The presence of a neoplasm of the kidney.

Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx) to a partially fused appearance of the two bones.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the adenohypophysis, which is also known as the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland.
A type of hypoplastic anemia in which the erythrocytes have a normal cell volume (the mean corpuscular volume is within normal limits).
Severely decreased cardiac output with evidence of inadequate end-organ perfusion (i.e., tissue hypoxia) in the presence of adequate intravascular volume.
An anomaly of the control or production of movement in the central nervous system.
Abnormal increase in size of the lower limbs (due to an increase of the size of cells).
The third heart sound (S3) is related to rapid filling in diastole. S3 can be a normal finding in children and adolescents but suggests heart failure in older patients.
Complete bilateral fractures of the pars interarticularis resulting in the anterior slippage of the vertebra.
Any structural abnormality of the sweat gland.
An abnormal concentration of an amino acid in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Benign, slow-growing tumors without any metastatic potential. Despite their benign nature, they can damage nearby structures causing organ dysfunction. Histologically they resemble low-grade fibrosarcomas, but they are very locally aggressive and tend to recur even after complete resection. There is a tendency for recurrence in the setting of prior surgery and the most common localisation of these tumors is intraabdominal from smooth muscle cells of the instestine.

?def: The distal and proximal transverse palmar creases are merged into a single transverse palmar crease.
An abnormality of the distal phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
A type of cataract characterized by punctate, dust-like opacities within the cortical region of the lens.
The ability of the elbow joint to move beyond its normal range of motion.
Partial duplication of the middle phalanx of ring finger, seen on x-rays as a broad and/or bifid phalanx.
A type of cellular urinary cast composed of renal tubular epithelial cells.
An increased consentration of zinc in the blood.
Increased concentration of protein in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Narrowing of a tear duct (lacrimal duct).
The presence of multiple xanthomas (xanthomata) in the skin. Xanthomas are yellowish, firm, lipid-laden nodules in the skin.
The presence of an adenocarcinoma of the pancreas.
A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem.
A developmental defect in which a kidney is located in an abnormal anatomic position.
A secondary ossification center in the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
Death within the first 28 days of life.

Pulmonary hypertension is defined mean pulmonary artery pressure of 25mmHg or more and pulmonary capillary wedge pressure of 15mmHg or less when measured by right heart catheterisation at rest and in a supine position.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:11399002 UMLS:C3203102 UMLS:C0020542 MSH:D006976 MSH:D065627 UMLS:C2973725 SNOMEDCT_US:70995007 SNOMEDCT_US:697898008

?def: The cuticle (properly known as the eponychium, or the medial nail fold or the proximal nail fold), is the thickened layer of skin surrounding fingernails and toenails. Its function is to protect the area between the nail and epidermis from exposure to bacteria. This term refers to the presence of and irregular edge or outline of the cuticle.
An abnormal functionality of the thyroid gland.
A type of onion bulb formation prominently affecting the area of the basal lamina.
A type of nevus sebaceous with a linear form, raised borders and yellowish color.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by pregnancy in a female.
Decreased or impaired activation of T cells in response to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific.
Abnormal structure or form of trabecular bone.
Deposits accumulating between the outer retina and the retinal pigment epithelium and that have a focal distribution.
Wrist is bent inward toward the thumb because of a congenital defect associated with shortening or absence of the radius.
A small/hypoplastic or absent/aplastic 4th (ring) finger.
Increased concentration of amyloid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

This is an upper lateral orbital cleft. The soft tissue deformity is in the lateral one-third of the upper eyelid, and the bony cleft is through the superolateral orbital angle. Microphthalmia is present. The superolateral bony deficiency of the orbits allows a lateral displacement of the globes. The lateral one-third of the upper eyelid and the outer canthus are distorted, thus preventing apposition to the globe. The upper eyelid does not have a true cleft. A soft tissue furrow radiates superiorly and posterisphenoid is symmetric and normal. Mild cranial base asymmetry is reflected in the pterygoid plates. The left pair is more laterally displaced from the midline. Skull vault plagiocephaly is evident with an apparent reduction in the anteroposterior dimension of the anterior cranial fossa.
New growth of vessels on the surface of the iris.
A type of retinal exudate located in the subretinal space between the sensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.
Reduced distance from the anterior border of the naris to the subnasale.
Lack of a part of the pericardium over the diaphragmatic surface of the heart. It is a congenital defect, not the result of a pericardectomy. Pericardium is present on other parts of the heart.
A developmental anomaly associated with the failure of rectum, vagina, and bladder to separate.
Absence of distal phalanx of the second toe as a result of developmental aplasia.
Significant luminal narrowing of a long segment of the descending aorta.
Any abnormality of the epiphyses of the phalanges or metacarpal bones.

A tendency to fall or the inability to keep oneself from falling; imbalance. The retropulsion test is widely regarded as the gold standard to evaluate postural instability, Use of the retropulsion test includes a rapid balance perturbation in the backward direction, and the number of balance correcting steps (or total absence thereof) is used to rate the degree of postural instability. Healthy subjects correct such perturbations with either one or two large steps, or without taking any steps, hinging rapidly at the hips while swinging the arms forward as a counterweight. In patients with balance impairment, balance correcting steps are often too small, forcing patients to take more than two steps. Taking three or more steps is generally considered to be abnormal, and taking more than five steps is regarded as being clearly abnormal. Markedly affected patients continue to step backward without ever regaining their balance and must be caught by the examiner (this would be called true retropulsion). Even more severely affected patients fail to correct entirely, and fall backward like a pushed toy soldier, without taking any corrective steps.
Any functional anomaly of the mitral valve.
A bending or abnormal curvature of the distal portion of the tibia.

An abnormality in perception of contrast. Spatial contrast is a physical dimension referring to the light-dark transition of a border or an edge in an image that delineates the existence of a pattern or an object. Contrast sensitivity refers to a measure of how much contrast a person requires to see a target. Contrast-sensitivity measurements differ from acuity measurements; acuity is a measure of the spatial-resolving ability of the visual system under conditions of very high contrast, whereas contrast sensitivity is a measure of the threshold contrast fur seeing a target.
Pheochromocytoma originating from the adrenal medulla.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:85583005 SNOMEDCT_US:302835009 SNOMEDCT_US:399343007 NCIT:C3326 MSH:D010673 UMLS:C0031511

?def: Absence or underdevelopment involving the musculature of the thigh.

An ocular motility defect where the affected eye(s) does not elevate in adduction but has full depression in adduction. It can be congenital or acquired from injury to or defect of the superior oblique tendon or trochlea and has a positive forced duction test result.
An abnormal decreased number of leukocytes in the blood.
An elevation above the normal concentration of the HDL3a subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL3a particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 8.2-8.79 nm.
Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with an asymmetrical pattern of hypertrophy, with a predilection for the interventricular septum and myocyte disarray.
An abnormality of the chin, i.e., of the inferior portion of the face lying inferior to the lower lip and including the central prominence of the lower jaw.
Drooping of the upper eyebrow below the superior orbital rim.

A deviation from the normal contents of the platelet alpha granules, which normally contain adenosine triphosphate (ATP), adenosine diphosphate (ADP), serotonin, calcium, and pyrophosphate, which are secreted when platelets are activated.
A cessation of the development of a child in the areas of motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and/or emotional skills.
Reduced ability to perceive certain odorants (implies that the sense of smell is maintained for other classes of odorants).
Presence of conjugated bilirubin in the urine.
Increased count of erythroid precursor cells, that is, erythroid lineage cells in the bone marrow.
Decreased ability to react to a delayed hypersensitivity skin test.
No pericardium is present on the righthand side of the heart. It is a congenital absence of pericardium rather than the result of a pericardectomy.
A spherical hollow structure with a smooth muscle coat, lined by a mucous membrane, and attached to any part of the gastrointestinal tract, from the base of the tongue to the anus.
A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the scalp in the parietal area.
Abnormal breath sounds characterized by low-pitched, snoring or rattle-like sounds.
A condition in which the affected individual cannot extend the wrist, which hangs flaccidly.
Increased length and width of the tongue.
Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the distal phalanges of the hand.
Coarctation of the aorta is a narrowing or constriction of a segment of the aorta.
Abnormal increase in systolic blood pressure.
A type of dysmetria involving the limbs.
Presence of arachnoid cysts of the spinal canal extradurally in the epidural space.
An abnormality of thyroid physiology characterized by excessive secretion of the thyroid hormones thyroxine (i.e., T4) and/or 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine zwitterion (i.e., triiodothyronine or T3).
Increased space between two adjacent teeth in the same dental arch.
Difficulty to maintain correct position of the head while standing or sitting.
Absence of the triceps muscle.

A developmental anomaly in which the kidneys are fused and localized on the same side of the midline. This anomaly is thought to result from disruption of the normal embryologic migration of the kidneys.
An abnormal concentration of potassium.
An abnormality of the epiglottis.
Acute appearance of disease manifestations in a period of hours.
A chronic form of lymphadenopathy that is not related to infection.
Abnormality in the process of ejection of semen (usually carrying sperm) from the male reproductive tract.
Yellow-colored streaks, patches, or spots on the intimal surface of arteries. Fatty streaks stain red with Sudan III or Sudan IV.
An abnormality of the aorta.

A deviation from normal of the length of the arm span (length from one end of an individual's arms measured at the fingertips to the other when raised parallel to the ground at shoulder height at a one-hundred eighty degree angle)
A partial dislocation of a joint.
Elevated concentration of sebacic acid in the urine.
A type of ichthyosiform erythroderma with postnatal onset.
An abnormality of the skeletal system.
A reduction in immunoglobulin levels of the IgG2 subclass in the blood circulation.
Agenesis of one or more maxillary lateral incisor, comprising the maxillary lateral primary incisor and maxillary lateral secondary incisor.

A complete duplication affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 5th finger. As opposed to a partial duplication were there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones, a complete duplication leads to two separate bones appearing side to side (radio-ulnar axis) as seen on x-rays. A duplication leading to an accesory bone appearing in the proximo-distal axis on x-rays, this is actually a different entity called a Pseudoepiphyses (see according terms) sometimes also referred to as Hyperphalangism.
A type of crying in an abnormally high-pitched voice.
Pyramidal skinfold extending from the base to the top of the nails is a rare and distinctive anomaly seen in popliteal pterygia syndrome.
Partial/complete duplication of one or more phalanx of toe.
The presence of multiple protuberances (bulges, or knobs) at the ends of the long bones.
Gout affecting the Metatarsophalangeal joint of big toe.
A acute form of pancreatitis.
Urticaria in response to dermal vibration, with coincident degranulation of mast cells and increased histamine levels in serum.
Increased level of IgE antibody against dairy proteins, including casein, alpha-lactalbumin, beta-lactoglobulin or bovine serum albumin contained in cow, sheep or goat milk and milk products.
Being located on the right side of the body.
A lack of facial expression often with staring eyes and a slightly open mouth.
Reduced ability to run.

Dysplasia in the erythroid lineage, which presents with a variety of morphological changes in the bone marrow, including nuclear budding or irregular nuclear contour in erythroblasts. In peripheral blood.
A deviation from the normal concentration of an unsaturated fatty acid in the blood circulation.
A functional anomaly of the medial rectus muscle or lateral rectus muscle.
Generalized excessive, abnormal hairiness.
Inflammation of the renal glomeruli.
Hemorrhage between the skull and periosteum of a newborn resulting from rupture of blood vessels that cross the periosteum.
A reduction below the normal ratio of the volume of red blood cells to the total volume of blood.
Increased amount of autofluorescence in the macula as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.
Any anomaly of the distal phalanx of thumb.
A pattern of hair growth in which there is hair exnteding from the temples to the lateral eyebrows.
An abnormality of a histidine metabolic process.
A structural abnormality of the optic chiasm.The optic chiasm, located below the hypothalamus, is a partial crossing of the optic nerves.
Loss of the outer nuclear layer (photoreceptor layer) as assessed by ocular coherence tomography.
Hemorrhage occurring between the dura mater and the arachnoid mater.
The presence of an abscess located around the anus.
An abnormality of the functioning of the vestibular apparatus.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of carnitine in the blood circulation.
A neoplasm derived from nervous tissue (not necessarity a neoplasm located in the nervous system).

An abnormal spirometry test result. In this test, the individual being tested exhales into a tube connected to a machine called a spirometer, which measures the volume of air expired against time. Patients are asked to take a maximal inspiration and then to forcefully expel air for as long and as quickly as possible.
More pronounced paramedian peaks and median notch of the Cupid's bow.
Complete or partial merging of the posterior part of adjacent ribs.
Accumulation of blood within the pericardial sac.
Depletion of acid or accumulation base in the body fluids.
