Having a minor degree of severity that is considered to be on the boundary between the normal and the abnormal ranges. For quantitative traits, a deviation of that is less than two standard deviations from the appropriate population mean.
An outpouching of the spinal meninges.
An excessive division of the lobes of the nucleus of a neutrophil.
An abnormal increase or decrease in the level of lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
Ketosis-resistant diabetes is a synonym for type II diabetes. This term thus refers to a form of type II diabetes in which patients are dependent on insulin.
A recurrent form of sinusitis.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger.

A longer than normal interval (corrected for heart rate) between the Q and T waves in the heart's cycle. Prolonged QTc can cause premature action potentials during late phase depolarizations thereby leading to ventricular arrhythmias and ventricular fibrillations.
A decreased amount of glycogen in muscle tissue.
Abnormally increased levels of glutamic acid in cerebrospinal fluid.
A thumbnail that is diminished in length and width, i.e., underdeveloped thumb nail.
A localized myotonic contraction in a muscle in reaction to percussion (tapping with the examiner's finger, a rubber percussion hammer, or a similar object).
Atrophy (wasting) affecting primary type 2 muscle fibers. This feature in general can only be observed on muscle biopsy.

A teratoma within the heart. Most commonly, these tumors are detected in the pericardial cavity attached to the pulmonary artery and aorta. The tumour size within the heart varies from 2 to 9 cm in diameter, and intrapericardial tumors as large as 15 cm have been reported. Intracardiac tumors arise from the atrial or ventricular wall as nodular masses protruding into the cardiac chambers. Cardiac and pericardial teratomas are easily detected in the fetus and neonate by two-dimensional echocardiography as heterogeneous and encapsulated cystic masses. Histologically, cardiac teratomas contain multiple immature elements including epithelium, neuroglial tissue, thyroid, pancreas, smooth and skeletal muscle, cartilage and bone.
Absence or underdevelopment of the lacrimal gland.

Chronic loss of joint motion of the carpometacarpal joint of the thumb due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. This joint is formed by the first metacarpal and the trapezial bone and is also called Articulatio carpometacarpalis pollicis, carpometacarpal articulation of thumb, carpometacarpal joint of thumb or first carpometacarpal articulation. Seldom referred to as thumb saddle joint.

Fusion of cervical vertebrae at C2 and C3, caused by a failure in the normal segmentation or division of the cervical vertebrae during the early weeks of fetal development, leading to a short neck with a low hairline at the back of the head, and restricted mobility of the upper spine.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the stomach.
An abnormality of the shoulder, which is defined as the structures surrounding the shoulder joint where the humerus attaches to the scapula.
An abnormally increased proportion of CD4-negative, CD8-negative (double negative or DN) alpha-beta regulatory T cells (Tregs) as compared to total number of T cells.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the phalanges of the 3rd finger.
Abnormal increase in diastolic blood pressure.

Blepharochalasis is characterized by recurrent, non-painful, nonerythematous episodes of eyelid edema. It has been divided into hypertrophic and atrophic forms. In the hypertrophic form recurrent edema results in orbital fat herniation through a weakened orbital septum. Most patients who have blepharochalasis present in an atrophic condition with atrophy of redundant eyelid skin and superior nasal fat pads.
Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the second toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.
Onset of disease manifestations before adulthood, defined here as before the age of 16 years, but excluding neonatal or congenital onset.

Femoral torsion, also known as femoral rotation or femoral version, refers to the twist between the proximal and distal parts of the femur on the transverse plane. Femoral anteversion averages between 30-40 degress at birth, and between 8-14 degrees in adults. This term applies if the amount of femoral torsion deviates from this range.
An increased concentration of orotic acid in the urine.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the leg.

A type of sarcoma (A connective tissue neoplasm formed by proliferation of mesodermal cells) that develops from soft tissues like fat, muscle, nerves, fibrous tissues, blood vessels, or deep skin tissues.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:269469005 UMLS:C1261473 SNOMEDCT_US:2424003 SNOMEDCT_US:424413001 SNOMEDCT_US:424952003 MSH:D012509

?def: Height of the palate more than 2 SD above the mean (objective) or palatal height at the level of the first permanent molar more than twice the height of the teeth (subjective).
An abnormality of the mouth.
A type of vertical phoria in which, in dissociation, the occluded eye deviates downwards.
Underdeveloped nails of the fifth toes.

An exudate is a mass of fluid and cells that has seeped out of blood vessels or an organ, usually related to inflammation. In the esophagus, exudates usually present as whitish plagues on the surface of the esophageal mucosa.
An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the descending thoracic aorta.
An abnormal increase in the size of the kidney.
Decreased concentration of biopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
An abnormal accumulation of fluid and swelling in the tissues of the larynx.
A congenital inclusion cysts that arises from ectodermal cells that normally form skin cells being left behind in the nervous system during development.

An abnormality in the rate and degree to which platelets aggregate after the addition of an agonist that stimulates platelet clumping. Platelet aggregation is measured using aggregometer to measure the optical density of platelet-rich plasma, whereby platelet aggregation causes the plasma to become more transparent.
A congenital absence or considerable underdevelopment of the trachea such that communication between the larynx proximally and the alveoli of the lungs distally is lacking.
A skin abnormality characterized by redness and irritation, with thick, red skin that displays flaky, silver-white patches (scales).
Abnormally increased levels of serine in cerebrospinal fluid.
An intraepithelial adenocarcinoma originating in the anal margin and characterized by presence of typical Paget's cells, appearing as large rounded vacuolated cells.
Reduced diameter of the proximal phalanx of finger.
The percentage of fat as a part of total body weight above the norm, usually defined as 32% for females and 25% for males.
Longitudinal densities on radiographs located in a metaphysis (the narrow region of a long bone between the epiphysis and the diaphysis).
Increase in width (breadth) of the ulnar metaphysis.
An increase in the level of ribitol in the urine. Ribotol is a crystalline pentose alcohol (C5H12O5) and is a metabolic end product formed by the reduction of ribose.
A congenital anomaly in which the pancreas completely (or sometimes incompletely) encircles the second portion of duodenum and occasionally obstructs the more proximal duodenum.
An increased concentration of ammonia in the blood.
An abnormal elevation of the concentration of thyroglobulin, a protein produced in the thyroid gland that acts as a precursor to thyrroid hormones.

Facial nerve palsy is a dysfunction of cranial nerve VII (the facial nerve) that results in inability to control facial muscles on the affected side with weakness of the muscles of facial expression and eye closure. This can either be present in unilateral or bilateral form.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0376175 MSH:D020330 UMLS:C0427055 UMLS:C1858719 MSH:D005158 SNOMEDCT_US:95666008 SNOMEDCT_US:193093009

?def: Anterior chamber cells with 16-25 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.
An abnormal immunoglobulin light chain in the circulation and typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.
Increased urinary excretion of oligosaccharides (low molecular weight carbohydrate chains composed of at least three monosaccharide subunits), derived from a partial degradation of glycoproteins.
An abnormality of a buccal mucosa.

A type of apraxia that is characterized by difficulty or inability to execute speech movements because of problems with coordination and motor problems, leading to incorrect articulation. An increase of errors with increasing word and phrase length may occur.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:361276003 SNOMEDCT_US:361277007 UMLS:C0264611 SNOMEDCT_US:74227009 MSH:D001072 UMLS:C0349391

?def: Decreased intensity of the Achilles reflex (also known as the ankle jerk reflex), which can be elicited by tapping the tendon is tapped while the foot is dorsiflexed.
Persistence of the urachal canal resulting in a canal between the bladder and the umbilicus.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of hemoglobin in the blood.
Inflammation of the cornea.

A reduced ejection fraction and an enlarged left ventricle chamber, the latter by an increased resistance to filling with increased filling pressures. Systolic dysfunction is clinically associated with left ventricular failure in the presence of marked cardiomegaly.
Decreased concentration of fibrinogen in the blood.
An abnormally increased level of alkaline phosphatase, tissue-nonspecific isozyme in the blood.

Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at one or more long bones in the hand, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.
A type of mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation in which the increase in mucoid extracellular matrix alters the arrangement of the lamellar units to varying degrees.

A tumor of the central nervous system that has components of both neurocytic and glial areas, whereby usually the glial component of the tumour predominates. Rossette-forming glioneuronal tumors (RGNT) have biphasic cytoarchitecture with two elements; neurocytic rosettes resembling Homer-Wright rosettes, and astrocytic component resembling a pilocytic astrocytoma. RGNTs are low-grade tumors that lack histopathological signs of malignancy.
Reduced rib length.
One sided alveolar cleft of the maxilla.
Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the distal phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

An arteriovenous malformation is a disruption of the normal vascular pattern in which arteries or arterioles connect directly to the venous collection system, bypassing any capillary bed. This term refers to an arteriovenous malformation located in the hypothalamus.
A discontinuity of the skin exhibiting complete loss of the epidermis and often portions of the dermis and even subcutaneous fat.
The presence of both a prominent heel and a convex contour of the sole.
?xrefs: MSH:D005413 MEDDRA:10066242 MSH:C536345 SNOMEDCT_US:205082007 UMLS:C0240912 SNOMEDCT_US:205359003

?def: Presence of an elevated number of projections from nuclei of neutrophils. These projections can have the shape of hooks, tags, or clubs.
The course a disease typically takes from its onset, progression in time, and eventual resolution or death of the affected individual.

An enchondroma is a benign growth of cartilage that develops within the medullary cavity of bone. Enchondromatosis refers to the presence of multiple enchondromas, and this term refers to the presence of multiple enchondromas within the medulla of metaphyseal bone. Radiographically an enchondroma presents a an oval, linear, or pyramidal osteolytic (radiolucent) lesion with well defined margins.
An anomaly of cerebral veins.
The presence of multiple cutaneous neurofibromas.

Reduced plasma concentrations of chylomicrons, the large lipid droplet (up to 100 mm in diameter) of reprocessed lipid synthesized in epithelial cells of the small intestine and containing triacylglycerols, cholesterol esters, and several apolipoproteins.
Damage to and obliteration of intrahepatic bile ducts (bile ducts that transport bile between the Canals of Hering and the interlobar bile ducts).
Any structural abnormality of a cardiac atrium.

Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
Inflammation of the bronchioles.

A type of anomalous trichromacy associated with defective long-wavelength-sensitive (L) cones, causing the sensitivity spectrum to be shifted toward medium wavelengths. This leads to difficulties especially in distinguishing red and green.

A type of renal tubular acidosis characterized by a failure of acid secretion by the alpha intercalated cells of the cortical collecting duct of the distal nephron. The urine cannot be acidified below a pH of 5.3, associated with acidemia and hypokalemia.
An abnormal amount of hair.
A deviance in the normal connections between two cardiac segements.

Hepatic failure refers to the inability of the liver to perform its normal synthetic and metabolic functions, which can result in coagulopathy and alteration in the mental status of a previously healthy individual. Hepatic failure is defined as fulminant if there is onset of encephalopathy within 4 weeks of the onset of symptoms in a patient with a previously healthy liver.
Deposits accumulating between the outer retina and the retinal pigment epithelium and that are distributed with multiple foci.
A reduction below the normal concentration of the HDL2a subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL2A particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 8.80-9.69 nm.
Missing radius bone on both sides associated with congenital failure of development.
The release of fat globules into the venous circulation, thereby blocking blood circulation to the lung.
Complete shedding (separation) of the nail from the proximal matrix. Onychomadesis is the proximal separation of the nail plate from the nail matrix due to a temporary cessation of nail growth.
A descriptive term for a forearm bone that appears to have an additional bone within it on radiography.
tPA catalyzes the conversion of plasiminogen to plasmin, and thus break down of clots. When there is a deficiency there will be an increase of thrombosis
Presyncope is a state of lightheadedness, muscular weakness, blurred vision, and feeling faint. Presyncope is most often cardiovascular in cause.
Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of the posterior cerebral artery.
A persistent left superior vena cava (PLSVC) that drains into the left atrium instead of the right atrium via the coronary sinus, resulting in a right to left sided shunt.
A state of sudden and severe confusion.
Obesity with a body mass index of 35 to 39.9 kg per square meter.
Death in during childhood, defined here as between the ages of 2 and 10 years.
Loss of hair in the occipital region of the scalp with congenital onset.
Abnormally increased width of the pubic symphysis is the midline cartilaginous joint uniting the superior rami of the left and right pubic bones.

An abnormality of the distal phalanx of the second finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the parenchyma of the spleen.
The presence of spots or rounded patches of abnormally increased density of metaphyseal bone.
A rudimentary tag of skin often containing ear tissue including a core of cartilage and located just anterior to the auricle (outer part of the ear).
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 5th toe.
A subtype of skin dimples occurring on the hands.
A heterogeneous increase in IgE mmunoglobulins characterized by a diffuse band on serum electrophoresis.

A deviation of the normal proportion of class-switched memory B cells (CD19+/CD27+/IgM-/IgD-) in circulation relative to the total number of B cells. Marginal zone B cells undergo limited somatic hypermutation and produce high-affinity IgM and some IgG, whereas class-switched memory B cells synthetize IgG, IgM, and IgA.
The presence of varices (enlarged and convoluted blood vessels) in the colon.

A premature fusion of the epiphyseal plates of the radius. Epiphyseal plates are located at the distal and proximal ends of the long bones, in this case of the radius and premature fusion will have an effect on the growh of the radial bone, inhibiting or at least disturbing the normal growth and development of the bone.
Abnormality of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb. This epiphysis is located on the proximal end of the phalanx.
Inflammatory cells within the wall and ostia of the hair follicle, creating a follicular-based pustule.
Disruptions in the production of speech sounds, with involuntary repetitions of words or parts of words, prolongations of speech sounds, or complete blockage of speech production for several seconds.
Bleeding in the thalamus.
An abnormal distribution of N-acylglycines in the urine. There are numerous different N-acylglycines, and this term refers to pathological alterations in their level or distribution.
An acute leukemia characterized by the proliferation of both neutrophil and monocyte precursors.
An increased number of epithelial cells per high-power field in urinanalysis.
Displacement of the 5th finger from its normal position.
Height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the midline more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently reduced height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the frontal view (subjective).

An abnormally increased number of myelocytes in the peripheral blood circulation. Myelocytes are immature neutrophils with a size of 12-18 micrometers, a round or oval nucleus with no nucleoli, bluish-pink staining cytoplasm with primary and seconday granules, and a nucleus:cytoplasm ratio of 2:1.
Acanthocytosis is a type of poikilocytosis characterized by the presence of spikes on the cell surface. The cells have an irregular shape resembling many-pointed stars.
An abnormality of the nasal septum.
An abnormality in the production or cellular release of tumor necrosis factor.
Partial or complete duplication of the fourth proximal phalanx of hand.
Head circumference which falls below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender because of insufficient head growth after birth.
An abnormality of the nose.

This term applies if one or more of the phalanges of the 4th finger are either partially duplicated, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance of the phalanges, or completely duplicated.
An elevation above the normal concentration of the HDL3c subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL3c particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 7.20-7.79 nm.
Increased width of the cross sectional diameter of the fibula.

An abnormality in perception of contrast as measured by the Pelli-Robson contrast sensitivity chart, which is a large wall-mounted chart, with letters of a fixed size (comprising spatial frequencies appropriate for estimating peak contrast sensitivity) that decrease in contrast.

A congenital auricular deformity, which is mainly characterized by a bulging appearance of the anterosuperior portion of the auricle, a convexly protruded cavum conchae, and a slit-like narrowing of the orifice of the external auditory meatus.

An abnormality of the superior crus of the antihelix is the upper cartilaginous ridge arising at the bifurcation of the antihelix that ends beneath the fold of the ascending helix, and separates the concha from the triangular fossa.
An increased amount of carnosine in the blood.
Muscular atrophy affecting proximally located muscles of the legs, i.e., of the thigh.
Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized proximal to the ductus arteriosus, i.e., to the preductal region of aortic arch.
Episodes of muscle weakness associated with elevated levels of potassium in the blood.

The cardinal symptom is severely pruritic skin lesions. Macular, papular, papulovesicular, urticarial, multiforme- and plaque-like variants are differentiated morphologically, hence the name polymorphous. Usually one morphology dominates in a single individual (monomorphous). The skin lesions develop a few hours to several days after sun exposure. Initially, patchy erythema develops, accompanied by pruritus. Distinct lesions then develop. The upper chest, upper arms, backs of the hands, thighs, and the sides of the face are the primary localizations. The skin lesions resolve spontaneously within several days of ceasing sun exposure and do not leave behind any traces.
Any structural anomaly located between the pleura and the chest wall.
A clonal disorder of keratinization with one or multiple atrophic patches surrounded by a clinically and histologically distinctive hyperkeratotic ridgelike border called the cornoid lamella.

Infection by a Coccidioides species fungus. These are dimorphic, soil-dwelling, fungi known to cause a broad spectrum of disease, ranging from a mild febrile illness to severe pulmonary manifestations or disseminated disease. The genus Coccidioides is comprised of two genetically distinct species: Coccidioides immitis and C. posadasii.

A reduced concentration of circulating alpha-1 antitrypsin, which is a 52-kDa glycoprotein mainly synthesised and secreted by hepatocytes into the bloodstream. Alpha-1 antitrypsin is a serine-proteinase inhibitor that it is crucial in maintaining protease-antiprotease homeostasis in the lungs.

Reduced level of T cell receptor excision circle (TRECs) as measured by the TREC assay. Late in maturation, 70% of thymocytes that will ultimately express alpha/beta-T cell receptors form a circular DNA TREC from the excised TCRdelta gene that lies within the TCRalpha genetic locus. The circles are stable but do not increase following cell division and, therefore, become diluted as T cells proliferate. A quantitative polymerase chain reaction (PCR) reaction across the joint of the circular DNA provides the TREC copy number, a marker of newly-formed, antigenically-nave thymic emigrant T cells.
Inspiratory stridor is a high pitched sound upon inspiration that is generally related to laryngeal abnormalities.
Bleeding that persists for a longer than usual time following circumcision.
Osteoarthritis of facet joints in the spine. Degeneration of cartilage in the facet joints results in bone rubbing on bone and reactive new bone formation visible on X-ray.
Hard, pebble-like deposits that form within the gallbladder.
One or more bent (flexed) toe joints that cannot be straightened actively or passively.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the distal phalanx of the 4th toe.
Reduced number of primary teeth.
Areas of subcutanous fat tissue below the waist that are resistant to (do not respond as expected to) diet, life-style alteration, or bariatric surgery.
A developmental defect characterized by reduced length of the first metacarpal (long bone) of the hand.
Scars that form a depression compared to the level of the surrounding skin because of damage to the collagen, fat or other tissues below the skin.
Abnormal fat accumulation in the kidneys.

Thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a high-resolution computed tomography scan with an irregular appearance of the interlobular septa. THis feature is often associated with distortion of lung architecture.
Reduced size of the superior frontal portion of the cerebral cortex.
Metaphyseal cupping affecting the proximal phalanges.
An increase in the combined thickness of the intima and media of the carotid artery.

A malignant tumor arising from epithelial cells. Carcinomas that arise from glandular epithelium are called adenocarcinomas, those that arise from squamous epithelium are called squamous cell carcinomas, and those that arise from transitional epithelium are called transitional cell carcinomas (NCI Thesaurus).
Osseous fusion of the lunate and triquetrum.
Hyperkeratosis affecting the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot.

Atopic dermatitis (AD) or atopic eczema is an itchy, inflammatory skin condition with a predilection for the skin flexures. It is characterized by poorly defined erythema with edema, vesicles, and weeping in the acute stage and skin thickening (lichenification) in the chronic stage.
A partial or complete adhesion of the palpebral conjunctiva of the eyelid to the bulbar conjunctiva of the eyeball.
Uneven increase in bone density of the proximal phalanx of the fourth toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.
Partial duplication of the fourth proximal phalanx of hand, seen on x-rays as a broad and/or bifid phalanx.
Painless and spontaneous separation of a toenail from the nail bed.
Thinning in the layers of the retina and retinal pigment epithelium around the optic nerve.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one to five (complete syndactyly of all fingers of the hand).
High urine chloride in the presence of hypochloridemia.
Fetal masculinization of female external genitalia.
A defect where there is no connection between the right atrium and right ventricle.
Any structural abnormality of the left atrium.
Width of the palate more than 2 SD below the mean (objective) or apparently decreased palatal width (subjective).
A cancer that originates in the sqamous cells that line the surface of the vulva.
Hyperactivity is a state of constantly being unusually or abnormally active, including in situations in which it is not appropriate.
A form of latent strabismus (heterophoria) in which the occluded eye wheel-rotates on dissociation.
Any abnormality of the proximal epiphysis of the humerus.
Developmental dysplasia of dentin.

This anomaly, also known as Mittendorf dot, is a benign, nonprogressive recognizable lesion that does not cause visual impairment. However, it can resemble a pathological congenital or acquired cataract lesion which may enlarge and cause visual impairment. The dot appears as a black speck that ranges in size from the dot made by a sharp pencil point to the size of a poppy seed. It is usually well defined, although occasionally there may be irregular, fine lines radiating outward from the dot.
An anomaly of the circulating level of luteinizing hormone (LH).

Radiographic evidence of articular calcification that represent calcium pyrophosphate depositions in soft tissue surrounding joints and at the insertions of tendons near joints (Entheses/Sharpey fibers) .
Abnormally increased levels of glycine in cerebrospinal fluid.
A type of seizure characterized by crying or an outburst of crying as a major feature.
Reduced ability to transform factor X into its activated form factor Xa.
A lymph node abnormality.
Abnormal development of the neurohypophysis during embryonic growth and development.
An anomaly of the form or number of cells in the bone marrow.
The distal interphalangeal joint of the 5th toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.
Failure to develop of the pineal gland, defined clinically as the absence of the pineal gland with no indication of the pineal gland even having been present.
A saccular or fusiform dilation and elongation of the ductus arteriosus.
An abnormally high concentration in the circulation of aspartate aminotransferase (AST).
Absence or underdevelopment of the tarsal bones.
Myofibrillar structural changes characterized by abnormal intracellular accumulation of the intermediate filament desmin and other proteins.

A nocturnal episode characterized by disorientation, grogginess, and, at times, substantial agitation upon awakening from slow-wave sleep or following forced awakenings. These characteristics might present as agitation, crying or moaning, disorientation, and particularly slow mentation on arousal from sleep (i.e., sleep inertia). The duration of episodes is typically 5 to 15 min but they might last up to several hours.
Sudden, repetitive, nonrhythmic motor movements (spasms), involving the eyes and muscles of the face.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0338467 UMLS:C4280324 UMLS:C0278151 SNOMEDCT_US:32402008 SNOMEDCT_US:230335009 UMLS:C0858722 UMLS:C4280325

?def: The narrowing or partial blockage of a portion of the small intestine.
Toenail that appears thin when viewed on end.
Reduced activity of the enzyme beta-glucosidase, an enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of glucosylceramide into ceramide and glucose.
An increased amount of unconjugated (indirect) bilurubin in the blood.

A functional anomaly of the superior oblique muscle, a fusiform muscle that originates in the upper, medial side of the orbit. The superior oblique muscle abducts, depresses and internally rotates the eye, and is the only extraocular muscle innervated by the fourth cranial nerve.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the parathyroid gland.

A compound muscle action potential (CMAP) is a type of electromyography (EMG). CMAP refers to a group of almost simultaneous action potentials from several muscle fibers in the same area evoked by stimulation of the supplying motor nerve and are recorded as one multipeaked summated action potential. This abnormality refers to an abnormal increase in the amplitude during the course of the investigation.
Underdevelopment of part or all of the external reproductive organs.
Simulataneous inflammation of multiple nerves.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of proline or a proline metabolite in the blood circulation.
A congenital defect resulting in absence of the lacrimal duct.
Absence of the Achilles reflex (also known as the ankle jerk reflex), which can normally be elicited by tapping the tendon is tapped while the foot is dorsiflexed.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a free fatty acid in the blood circulation.
An abnormality of a frontal process of the maxilla bone.
Abnormal narrowing of the anal opening.
A generalized decrease in bone mineral density.
Prolonged/excessive menses and bleeding at irregular intervals.
Atrophy of the tibialis muscle.
An increase in the quantity of space occupied by the thalamus.
Bending or curvature of a second toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).

An anomaly of the circulating level of a gonadotropin, that is, of a protein hormone secreted by gonadotrope cells of the anterior pituitary of vertebrates. The primary gonadotropins are luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH).
Increased amount of keratin (visible as white scales) surrounding hair follicles.
The formation of a blood clot inside an artery.
Increased thickness of the helix of the ear.

In response to the spring sun distinct inflamed reddened skin develops on the ears, nose, cheeks, fingers, backs of the hands, and the lower arms, on which blisters with serous or hemorrhagic content develop. These dry out with the formation of a blackish scab. After shedding of the scab, depressed, varioliform, often hypopigmented scars remain. In addition, hyper- and hypopigmentation are present together, resulting in a polymorphous skin presentation.
Reduced body temperature due to failed thermoregulation.
Prolongation of the time taken for a standardized skin cut of fixed depth and length to stop bleeding.
An decreased concentration of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
Repeated episodes of a localized, painful cutaneous eruption related to reactivation of varicella zoster virus (VZV) and characterized by a characteristic rash in one or two adjacent dermatomes.
Wide, concave anterior rib end.
Lack of measurable response to stimulation of auditory evoked potentials.
Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the 4th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
A foot for which the measured width is above the 95th centile for age; or, a foot that appears disproportionately wide for its length.
An asymmetriy, i.e., difference in size, shape or position between the left and right ear.
An abdominal hernia that occurs at a site of weakness in the abdominal wall resulting from an incompletely-healed surgical wound.
An decrease in the level of choline-containing compounds in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

A malignant neoplasm of the stomach that grows submocosally in the gastric wall. Necrosis and hemorrhage may be visible radiologically. Histologically, spindle cells with abnormal mitotic activity may be visible.
Involuntary contractions of the esophagus that are irregular, uncoordinated, and painful.
The presence of a V-shaped indentation (notch) in the primary central incisor.
?xrefs: UMLS:C4022912 MSH:D013590 UMLS:C0020186 SNOMEDCT_US:410500004 UMLS:C1444627 SNOMEDCT_US:86443005

?def: Underdevelopment of the serratus anterior muscle, which is involved in abduction, upward Rotation, and elevation of the scapula.
Lack of observable tonsillar tissue.
Unilateral atrophy (reduction in size) of a leg.
Any anomaly in the utilization of energy (calories).
Rhabdomyolysis induced by intake of alcohol.
Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the nail.

A diagnostic reflex elicited by stimulation of the skin over the surface of the lateral malleolus of the foot. The Chaddock refelx is present if there is extension of one or more or all of the toes with or without fanning of them when the external inframalleolar skin is stimulated. The Chaddock sign, similar to the Babinski sign, is taken to be an indication of disease of the spinocortical (pyramidal) tract.
Any abnormality of the periodontium.

Multiple, localized or widespread, asymptomatic or inflammatory dermal cysts involving the pilosebaceous units. Lesions can appear anywhere on the body, but steatocystoma multiplex is more commonly involved with those areas of the skin with a high density of developed pilosebaceous units (e.g., the axilla, groin, neck, and proximal extremities).
Enlargment (swelling) of a lymph node.
Underdevelopment of the vertebral artery on both sides.
Reduced level of CD16 on the fibroblast surface as assessed by flow cytometry.
Insufficient production of growth hormone, which is produced by the anterior pituitary gland. Growth hormone is a major participant in control of growth and metabolism.
A unilateral form of agenesis of the kidney.
An increase in the level of galactitol in the red blood cells.
An eye that is protruding anterior to the plane of the face to a greater extent than is typical.
?xrefs: UMLS:C1862425 UMLS:C1837760 MSH:D005094 UMLS:C1848490 SNOMEDCT_US:18265008 UMLS:C0015300

?def: A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger of the hand.
A morphological abnormality of the vestibule, the central part of the osseous labyrinth that is situated medial to the tympanic cavity, behind the cochlea, and in front of the semicircular canals.

Laxity of the tendon stabilising the medial aspect of the tarsal plate to the anterior and posterior lacrimal crests. This may lead to more than 2mm movement of the punctum when the eyelid is pulled laterally.
Cloacal exstrophy is a severe anterior abdominal wall defect in which the two hemibladders are visible and are separated by a midline intestinal plate, an omphalocele, and an imperforate anus.
Lack of external genitalia in a male or female individual.

Isolated abnormalities of the coronary artery origins. This may be in associated with other structural heart malformations but not the patterns of complex structural heart malformations which result in abnormal course of the coronary arteries.
Anemia with varying degrees of erythrocytic hypoplasia without leukopenia or thrombocytopenia.
A papule with yellow color.
A painful and harmful medical condition in which the erect penis doesn't return to its flaccid state, despite the absence of both physical and psychological stimulation, within four hours.
Inability of velopharyngeal sphincter to sufficiently separate the nasal cavity from the oral cavity during speech.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0042454 MSH:D014681 UMLS:C4280669 SNOMEDCT_US:229727006 SNOMEDCT_US:232416001 SNOMEDCT_US:278714002

?def: Any structural anomaly of the lower motor neuron.
Inflammation (due to infection or irritation) of the pharynx.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the uterine cervix.
An abnormally decreased potassium concentration in the blood occurring periodically with a return to normal between the episodes.
A reduced level of the complement component factor B in circulation.
A type of anemia characterized by an abnormally low concentration of hemoglobin in the erythrocytes and lower than normal size of the erythrocytes.

The renal arteries carry blood from the aorta to the kidney; normally one renal artery is present on each side of the body. Renal artery duplication refers to the presence of two rather than one renal artery on a given side of the body.
The presence of female external genitalia in a person with a male karyotype.
An axonal neuropathy of peripheral sensory nerves.
An abnormality of an inferior thyroid vein.
Excessive, increased hair growth located in the thoracic region.
Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger with another bone.
Increased width of the uvula (subjective finding).
Abnormal embryonic development of the parathyroid gland.
Anterior chamber cells with 6-15 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.
A severe degree of muscular hypotonia characterized by markedly reduced muscle tone.
An increased concentration of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the urine.
An abnormal increase in the concentration of bicarbonate, HCO3[-], in the circulation.
Presence of more than two nipples.
A short discontinuity of the margin of the lower or upper eyelid.
Crystalline deposits in the macula.
Circumscribed area of flaccid skin due to the loss of elastic tissue in the dermis.
Sweating provoked by cold temperature rather than by heat.
Partial dislocation of the lens in a superior direction.
Complete duplication of proximal phalanx of third toe.
Fibrosis of the external ocular muscles such that the eyes of affected individuals are partially or completely fixed in a strabismic position. Residual eye movements are significantly limited.
Defect or defects of the morphogenesis of the aorta and pulmonary arteries.
Accumulation of lipids and inflammatory cells along the inner walls of the pulmonary artery.
An abnormality of the clitoris.
A detrimental reaction to a food, beverage, food additive, or compound found in foods that produces symptoms in one or more body organs and systems that is not mediated by an immune reaction.
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.
Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the tunica media of small arteries.
Inflammation of the periosteum
Any structural anomaly of the lung.
A horizontal cleft of the face, varying from slight widening of the mouth, to a cleft extending to the ear.
A decreased concentration of glucose in the blood.

A deviation from the normal range of the average amount of hemoglobin per red blood cell (27 to 31 picograms/cell). A reduced mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH) may indicate a hypochromic anemia, but the MCH may be normal if both the total hemoglobin and the red blood cell count are reduced.
Underdevelopment of one or more carpal bones.
A type of cardiomyopathy characterized pathologically by hamartomatous lesions of cardiac Purkinje cells.

A type of anomalous trichromacy associated with abnormal M photopigment, such that the absorption spectrum is shifted toward L wavelengths. Affected individuals have difficulties distinguishing between red and green.
Triangular shaped phalanges of the 3rd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
A type of of patterned retinal dystrophy that shows a reticular pattern of pigmentation.
Small protrusion within the pinna.
Abnormally wide morphology of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.
Any anomaly of lymphocyte function.
Repeated and inappropriate mechanical repetition of actions.
An abnormal deviation from normal levels of IgA immunoglobulin in blood.
Abnormality of glycosaminoglycan metabolism.

An entrapment neuropathy of the suprascapular nerve, presenting with shoulder weakness confined to the supraspinatus muscle (this muscle initiates shoulder abduction) or to the infraspinatus (this muscle externally rotates the arm), as well as with pain in the posterior part of the shoulder and upper periscapular region.

A deviation from normal of the relation between the upper and the lower segment of the body, where the lower segment is defined as the length between the top of pubic symphysis to floor, and the upper segment is defined as the top of head to top of pubic symphysis.
Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the 5th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

Reduced functionality of the process in which a precursor cell type acquires the specialized features of a B cell. A B cell is a lymphocyte of B lineage with the phenotype CD19-positive and capable of B cell mediated immunity.
Failure of growth hormone levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the insulin tolerance test (ITT).
High urine calcium in the presence of hypocalcemia.
A functional anomaly of the digestive system.
A neonatal decreased concentration of proteins in the blood.
Deposition of calcium salts within small blood vessels of the brain.
An increased concentration of cystine within cells. This finding can be demonstrated on leukocytes, but is not specific to blood cells.
Body odor characterized by an offensive body odor and the smell of rotting fish due to the excessive excretion of trimethylamine (TMA) in the urine, sweat, and breath of affected individuals.

A type of antinuclear antibody (ANA) positivity revealed by indirect immunofluorescence (IFL). The multiple nuclear dots (MND) pattern is immunomorphologically characterized by the staining of 3-20 dots of variable size distributed all over the cell nucleus, but sparing the nucleoli, and, in contrast to the anticentromere pattern, MND reactivity does not stain the chromosomes in mitotic cells.
Any abnormality of the teeth.
Underdevelopment of the frontal lobe of the cerebrum.

A disorder of esophageal motility characterized by the inability of the lower esophageal sphincter to relax during swallowing and by inadequate or lacking peristalsis in the lower half of the body of the esophagus.
Having only one testis in the scrotum.

An arteriovenous malformation is a disruption of the normal vascular pattern in which arteries or arterioles connect directly to the venous collection system, bypassing any capillary bed. This term refers to an arteriovenous malformation located in the maxilla.
Insufficient production of steroid hormones (primarily cortisol) by the adrenal glands as a result of a primary defect in the glands themselves.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:386584007 SNOMEDCT_US:363732003 UMLS:C0001403 UMLS:C0405580 MSH:D000224 SNOMEDCT_US:373662000

?def: Any abnormality of the distal epiphysis of the ulna.
An autonomic seizure with altered responsiveness.
Affective auras with subjective qualities similar to those experienced in life but are recognized by the subject as occurring outside of actual context.
Absence or abnormal closure of the midnasal cavity.
The presence of renal cell carcinoma in the renal papilla.
An increased susceptibility to bronchitis as manifested by a history of recurrent bronchitis.
Inflammation of the sclera.
Multiple biliary hamartomas are a rare clinicopathologic entity, consisting of small (less than 1.5cm), usually multiple and nodular cystic lesions in the liver.

A type of shock characterized by inadequate cardiac preload due to obstructed venous return (e.g. pericardial tamponade, tension pneumothorax, abdominal compartment) or obstruction of arterial blood flow (e.g. pulmonary embolism).
A structural abnormality of the esophagus.

An increased cellular sensitivity to the DNA cross-linking agent, diepoxybutane (DEB). In the presence of increased sensitivity, DEB causes cell death, chromosome breakage, and accumulation in the G2 phase of the cell cycle.
A reduction in the count of nephrons per kidney.
A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type II that is characterized by dysmorphic neurons (significantly enlarged with accumulation of neurofilament proteins) and balloon cells.
The presence of multiple lung cysts.
Partial or complete loss of foveal tissue that was once present.
A kind of atrial septum defect arising from an enlarged foramen ovale, inadequate growth of the septum secundum, or excessive absorption of the septum primum.
Allergic Conjunctivitis is an allergic inflammation of the conjunctiva.
The presence of extra bones within a cranial suture. Wormian bones are irregular isolated bones which appear in addition to the usual centers of ossification of the cranium.
An abnormality of the middle phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the mandible.
Hyperplasia of the islets of Langerhans with a generalized distribution.
An anomaly identified by motor evoked potentials (MEPs) in the arm.
Toenail changes apart from changes of the color of the toenail (nail dyschromia) that involve partial or complete disruption of the various keratinous layers of the nail plate.
An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase.
An increase in the level of D-threitol in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Intraventricular hemorrhage that occurs in a preterm infant and that has extension into dilated ventricles.
Saccadic undershoot of horizontal saccadic eye movements, i.e., a horizontal saccadic eye movement that has less than the magnitude that would be required to gain fixation of the object.
Abnormality observed by electroencephalogram (EEG), which is used to record of the brain's spontaneous electrical activity from multiple electrodes placed on the scalp.

Fasciculations are observed as small, local, involuntary muscle contractions (twitching) visible under the skin. Fasciculations result from increased irritability of an axon (which in turn is often a manifestation of disease of a motor neuron). This leads to sporadic discharges of all the muscle fibers controlled by the axon in isolation from other motor units.
ABO phenotype AB, corresponding to the genotype AB.
Increased jugular venous pressure.

?xrefs: MSH:D006060 UMLS:C0018051 SNOMEDCT_US:95219002 UMLS:C0687149 MSH:D006059 UMLS:C0018055 SNOMEDCT_US:38804009 SNOMEDCT_US:83579008 SNOMEDCT_US:205681004

?def: Lack of a palpable nasal cartilage.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by drinking or otherwise ingesting ethanol.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the cerebellum.
Excruciating burning pain in the rectal area that may be triggered by defecation.
Increased susceptibility to fatigue.
A subjective feeling of tiredness characterized by a lack of energy and motivation.
An abnormal groove on the midline of the nose that may extend to the nasal tip.
Localized fluid retention and tissue swelling caused by a compromised lymphatic system, affecting mainly the legs.

The elastic properties of the aorta allow the aorta to store half of the cardiac ejected blood volume per beat, whereby aortic recoil during diastole pushes the remaining stored volume forward into the peripheral circulation, a phenomenon known as the Windkessel function. Aortic stiffness occurs as the elastic fibers within the arterial wall become disrupted due to mechanical stress (with age or due to other factors). Aortic stiffness refers to a reduction in the elasticity of the aorta, which is associated with an elevated pulse pressure, increased wave reflection, and often hypertension.

An increase in mean adipocyte cell size. This feature can be measured by determining the average cell diameter of adipocytes microscopically using abdominal subcutaneous adipose tissue obtained by biopsy.
A type of multifactorial inheritance governed by the simultaneous action of many (more than three) gene loci.
Tall head relative to width and length.
A type of megaloblastic anemia (i.e., anemia characterized by the presence of erythroblasts that are larger than normal) that improves upon the administration of thiamine.
An increased concentration of glutaric acid in the blood.

A cyst that is localized in the region of the orbit and exhibits an epithelial lining with a keratin-filled lumen. Hair follicles are one of the adnexal structures that are commonly found in walls of dermoid cysts.
An abnormally increased count of basophils per volume in the blood circulation.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking glucose.
Distance between left and right side of the flaccid penis at the attachment to the skin above the pubic symphysis more than 2 standard deviations above the mean for age.

A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 5th finger. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.
An unusually severe adenovirus infection.
Inflammation of the uveal tract in which the primary site of inflammation is the retina or choroid.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0042167 SNOMEDCT_US:16553002 SNOMEDCT_US:43363007 UMLS:C0008526 MSH:D002833 MSH:D015866

?def: Atypical absence lasting for more than 30 minutes.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against C3 convertase (C3bBb).
Formation of abnormal bony tissue within muscle tissue.
An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fingers. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

Failure to contain thebacillus Calmette-Guerin (BCG) following vaccination leading to spread of BCG to many sites in the body. The tuberculosis vaccine BCG contains live attenuated Mycobacterium bovis.
Increased size of the basal ganglia.
A deviation from the normal count of T cells.
A type of vertical phoria in which, in dissociation, the occluded eye deviates upwards.
Multiple neurofibromas of the spinal nerve roots with a symmetric distribution.
Dorsal extension of the big toe, sometimes accompanied by fanning of the other toes, elicited by compressing the calf muscles (a normal response is no movement of the big toe).
A structural abnormality of the abdomen ('belly'), that is, the part of the body between the pelvis and the thorax.
A form of diabetes insipidus caused by failure of the kidneys to respond to vasopressin (AVP).

A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the pulmonary origin. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
Loss of the superficial layer of the oral mucosa usually resulting in a shallow or crusted lesion.
Western blot shows complete lack of calpain-3 protein in the muscle biopsy tissue.

Adrenogenital syndrome is also known as congenital adrenal hyperplasia, which results from disorders of steroid hormone production in the adrenal glands leading to a deficiency of cortisol. The pituitary gland reacts by increased secretion of corticotropin, which in turn causes the adrenal glands to overproduce certain intermediary hormones which have testosterone-like effects.

Perifollicular fibroma is a rare cutaneous hamartoma that shows differentiation in the connective tissue sheath of hair follicles. It can occur as a solitary papule or as multiple lesions. Histologically, the lesion consists of a concentric arrangement of cellular fibrous tissue around a normal hair follicle.
Partial or complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of big toe.

Absence of the outer dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, which normally are situated within the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.
EEG with generalized sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
An abnormal reduction below the normal number of red blood cells per volume in the circulation.
An abnormality of the combined rod-and-code response on electroretinogram.
Increased width of the midpoint of the mandible (mental protuberance) and overlying soft tissue.
An abnormality of the uvea, the vascular layer of the eyeball.
An impairment in the production by leukocytes of NFKB1-dependent cytokines such as tumor necrosis factor-alpha and interferon-alpha.

Recurrent attacks of acute inflammatory arthritis of a joint or set of joints caused by elevated levels of uric acid in the blood which crystallize and are deposited in joints, tendons, and surrounding tissues.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:170733007 SNOMEDCT_US:90560007 UMLS:C0003868 UMLS:C0018099 MSH:D006073 SNOMEDCT_US:48440001 MSH:D015210 SNOMEDCT_US:190828008

?def: Any anomaly in the process by which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons.
An abnormality of the crus of the helix, which is the horizontal piece of cartilage located outside the ear canal that divides the upper and lower parts of the ear.

A functional anomaly of the superior rectus muscle, an extraocular muscle that is innervated by the superior division of the oculomotor nerve, and whose primary function is the elevation of the globe.
Partial or complete duplication of a middle phalanx of toe.
Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of little toe.
An inflammation of the endocardium, the inner layer of the heart, which usually involves the heart valves.
An abnormally increased muscular tone that causes fixed abnormal postures. There is a slow, intermittent twisting motion that leads to exaggerated turning and posture of the extremities and trunk.
A type of strabismus in which the visual axis of one eye is higher than that of the other.
Increased anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.
An abnormality of the integument, which consists of the skin and the superficial fascia.
A congenital diaphragm defect involving the central tendinous (e.g., amuscular) portion of the diaphragm, whereby the entire rim of diaphragmatic musculature is present.
An abnormal localized reduction in amplitude of the cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
A flat, distinct, discolored area of skin less than 1 cm wide that does not involve any change in the thickness or texture of the skin.
An abnormal shape or form of the proximal phalanx of the big toe.
Vitamin K is a fat-soluble vitamin with a role in promoting the coagulation cascade.
An abnormal accumulation of lipids in skeletal muscle.
The repeated occurrence of bone fractures (implying an abnormally increased tendency for fracture).
?xrefs: UMLS:C3806283 SNOMEDCT_US:5468008 UMLS:C3805574 MSH:D000069076 SNOMEDCT_US:134291007 UMLS:C1833752 UMLS:C0016655

?def: An increased rate of premature chromosome condensation.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 4th finger.
Cases of the disease in question occur without a previous family history, i.e., as isolated cases without being transmitted from a parent and without other siblings being affected.
Increased concentration of fibrinogen in the blood.
Anomalous staining of plakoglobin in cardiomyocytes. Plakoglobin is a component of desmosomes in cardiomyocytes.
Increased susceptibility to parasitic infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of parasitic infection.
The presence of skeletal muscular atrophy (which is also known as amyotrophy).
?xrefs: MSH:D009133 UMLS:C0234958 SNOMEDCT_US:74035001 UMLS:C1843479 UMLS:C0541794 UMLS:C0270948

?def: Generalized weakness or decreased strength of the muscles, affecting both distal and proximal musculature.
Short (hypoplastic) phalanx of finger, affecting one or more phalanges.
Outward turning of the heel, resulting in clubfoot with the person walking on the inner part of the foot.
An increase in bone density affecting the calvaria (roof of the skull).
The presence of hemorrhage within the body.
A tendency to turn the face to the left to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.
Delayed or lack of conduction of atrial depolarizations through the atrioventricular node to the ventricles.

Any structural anomaly of the podocyte, which is a highly specialized cell of the Bowman capsule and which forms multiple interdigitating foot processes. Podocytes are interconnected by slit diaphragms and cover the exterior basement membrane surface of the glomerular capillary.
An aggressive granulosa cell tumor that arises from the ovary.
A moderate delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.
White color (lack of pigmentation) of the eyebrow.
An abnormality of the angular artery, the terminal branch of the facial artery.

Degenerative changes of the peripheral retina consisting of close-packed tiny cystic spaces at the outer plexiform/inner nuclear retinal level. The degeneration is very common in adult eyes and starts adjacent to the ora serrata and extends circumferentially and posteriorly.
Talon cusp is an accessory cusp located near the cingulum (the portion of the lingual or palatal aspect of the tooth that forms a convex protuberance at the cervical third of the anatomic crown).
A deviance from the norm of the origin or course of the right brachiocephalic artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery or the proximal vertebral arteries.

Only part of the septum pellucidum (a thin, triangular, vertical membrane separating the lateral ventricles of the brain) is present. This feature can be appreciated on magnetic resonance tomography or computed tomography of the brain.
Increased space between the primary teeth. Note this phenotype should be distinguished from increased space due purely to microdontia.
Any anomaly of a cranial suture, that is one of the six membrane-covered openings in the incompletely ossified skull of the fetus or newborn infant.
Chronic muscle inflammation accompanied by muscle weakness.
A type of astigmatism related to an irregular shape of the lens.
A reduction below the normal concentration of the HDL3a subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL3a particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 8.2-8.79 nm.
An abnormality of the fingernails.
Sudden feelings of warmth that are generally most pronounced over the face, neck and chest.
Underdevelopment of the patella.
The presence of whitish deposits in the conjunctiva resembling salt. May be related to calcinosis.
Synostosis (bony fusion) involving one or more bones of the carpus (scaphoid, lunate, triquetrum, trapezium, trapezoid, capitate, hamate, pisiform).
Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.
The ability of a joint to move beyond its normal range of motion.
An hormonally active adrenocortical adenoma, that is, an adenoma that secretes excessive amounts of adrenal hormones.
Decreased concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Mirror image atrial arrangement, with morphologic right atrium on the left hand side and morphologic left atrium on the right hand side.
The distal epiphysis (rounded portion of bone at the far end of the radius distal to the growth plate) has an abnormal cone-shaped appearance.
Deeply placed nails.
Underdevelopment of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.
Epistaxis, or nosebleed, refers to a hemorrhage localized in the nose.
Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
Atresia in the intrahepatic bile duct.
Developmental hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of little toe.
Presence of multiple trichilemmomata, a benign tumour originating from the outer root sheath of the hair follicle.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of histidine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Recurrent or excessive bleeding from the mouth.
A collection of pus in the area of the rectum.
The presence of multiple pancreatic islet cell adenomas.
Persistence of the urachal canal with drainage of urine from the bladder through the persistent allantois canal to the umbilicus.
Buildups of minerals that form in the urinary bladder.

A tram-track sign is composed of two enhancing areas of tumor separated from each other by the negative defect of the optic nerve. It is seen on contrast-enhanced CT scan and MRI images, in optic nerve sheath meningioma. The sign helps distinguish between optic nerve sheath meningioma and optic glioma. Optic glioma arises from glial cells within the optic nerve and there is no clear separation between the nerve and the tumor; hence the tram-track sign is not seen in optic gliomas. Calcification may be seen in optic nerve sheath meningiomas in 20-50% of cases and hence the tram-track sign may be seen on nonenhanced CT scan images as a linear calcification around the nerve, but this is less common.
Synostosis (bony fusion) involving one or more bones of the tarsus (calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, cuneiiform bones).

Clasp-knife phenomonen refers to increased muscle tone while bending or stretching a limb, whereby there is a sudden relaxtion (decrease in resistance) as the muscle continues to be streched. This phenomenon has been likened to opening a clasp knife.
Reduced or inadequate esophageal peristalsis, with resultant slow passage of contents through the esophagus.
A 'hemangioblastoma of the cerebellum.

Ethmocephaly is the rarest form of holoprosencephaly, which occurs due to an incomplete cleavage of the forebrain. Clinically, the disease presents with a proboscis, hypotelorism, microphthalmos and malformed ears.
A partial dislocation of the shoulder joint.
Focal epileptiform discharges of different shapes and frequencies.
An anomalous response to the glucagon stimulation test, which like the insulin tolerance test (ITT) stimulates the release of both adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) and growth hormone (GH).
An abnormality of the uvular muscle
EEG showing diffuse slowing without interruption.
Crackles that appear any time after the beginning of inspiration and last till the end of inspiration.
Accumulation of blood in the peritoneal cavity owing to internal hemorrhage.
An abnormality of macrophages.
Absence of molybdenum cofactor(2-), a cofactor for enzymes including sulfite oxidase, xanthine oxidoreductase, and aldehyde oxidase.
Increased width of a non-thumb digit of the hand.
The presence of short and wide phalanges which taper distally (\bullet shaped\")."
An eccentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the descending thoracic aorta that involves only a portion of the circumference of the vessel wall
An increased concentration of histidine in the blood.
The condition in which both atria are joined to a single ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve.
An abnormality of the hip bone.
The presence of an additional membrane in the left or right cardiac atrium which results in the subdivision of the affected atrium (and thus in total three atria, whence the name).
A dislocation of the head of the radius from its socket in the elbow joint.
The presence of recurrent corneal epithelial erosions. Although most corneal epithelial defects heal quickly, some may show recurrent ulcerations.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0010043 UMLS:C4020888 MSH:D003320 SNOMEDCT_US:91514001 UMLS:C0155119 SNOMEDCT_US:2055003

?def: Gentle upward curve of the upper lip vermilion such that the center is placed well superior to the commissures.
Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of the anterior cerebral artery.
An abnormal shift in patterns of thinking, acting, or feeling.
A functional anomaly of the large intestine.
Underdevelopment of the sweat glands.
An irregular surface of the vertebral end plates, which are normally relatively smooth.
Morbus Osgood-Schlatter is a Juvenile aseptic necrosis affecting the Tuberositas tibiae.

A localized hypertrophy of the subaortic segment of the ventricular septum has been frequently described in elderly persons, and variously termed subaortic ventricular septal bulge (VSB), sigmoid-shaped septum, localized or discrete upper septal hypertrophy.
Reduced size of the cerebral cortex.
Vitreous haze is the obscuration of fundus details by vitreous cells and protein exudation.
A reduced ability to synthesize postvaccination antibodies against protein-conjugated polysaccharides in vaccines, as measured by antibody titer determination following vaccination.
The ability of the joints of the hand to move beyond their normal range of motion.
Vomit that has the appearance of coffee grounds, which occurs due to the presence of coagulated blood in the vomit.
Choroid plexus papilloma is a histologically benign neoplasm located in the ventricular system of the choroid plexus.
Recurrent infection involving the vulva, vagina, and adjacent crural areas, whereby the causative agent belongs to the genus Candida.
Bradycardia related to a mean resting sinus rate of less than 50 beats per minute.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of folate in the blood circulation.
A decrease in the maximum amount of pressure of expired air achieved by a person after a full inspiration.

Anomalous coronary origin whereby the left anterior descending (LAD) and the left circumflex artery (LCX) arise separately. Normally, these arteries arise from a common stem, the left main coronary artery (LMCA).

A localized detachment of the vitreous from the retina due to the accumulation of blood. When localized in the macular area, it results in sudden profound loss of vision. Subhyaloid premacular hemorrhage is typically characterized by a circumscribed, round or dumb-bell shaped, bright red mound of blood beneath the internal limiting membrane (ILM) or between the ILM and hyaloid face, in or near to the central macular area.
A progressive detrimental connective tissue deposition (fibrosis) on the kidney parenchyma involving the tubules and interstitial tissue of the kidney.
Abnormal response to convulxin as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of convulxin.
A state of increased circulating antidiuretic hormone despite hyponatremia and hypo-osmolality with normal or increased plasma volume.
The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the cerebrum, also known as the telencephalon, the largest and most highly developed part of the human brain.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by eating or drinking carbohydrates including glucose (sugar).
Vitreous humor of the eye displaying beaded bundles of irregular diameters.
A defect where there is no connection between the left atrium and left ventricle.
Excessive desire to eat sweet foods.

Inflammation of the coronary arteries involving a granulomatous response, i.e., a non-specific inflammatory response involving granulomas, defined as a compact organized collection of mature mononuclear phagocytes including epithelioid and giant cells.
Tremor that occurs during any voluntary movement. It may include visually or non-visually guided movements. Tremor during target directed movement is called intention tremor.
?xrefs: MSH:D014202 SNOMEDCT_US:30721006 UMLS:C0270736 UMLS:C0234376 SNOMEDCT_US:609558009 MSH:D020329

?def: Absence or underdevelopment of the palmar creases.
Areas of the retina lacking pigmentation. Punched out areas of chorioretinal hypopigmentation less than 1 disc diameter in size and tending to be located in the midperiphery of the retina.
Abnormal test result of cardiovascular physiology.
An anomaly of the addition of mannose to N-linked glycans.
A decreased amount of phenylalanine in the blood.
Uncombable hair.

The stria terminalis is a slender, compact fiber bundle that connects the amygdala (amygdaloid body) with the hypothalamus and other basal forebrain regions. The bed nucleus of the stria terminalis is a limbic forebrain structure that receives heavy projections from, among other areas, the basolateral amygdala, and projects in turn to hypothalamic and brainstem target areas that mediate many of the autonomic and behavioral responses to aversive or threatening stimuli. This term refers to an anomaly of the bed nucleus.
Absence or underdevelopment of frontal sinus.
An abnormally decreased sodium concentration in the urine.
Ears that are low-set (HP:0000369) and posteriorly rotated (HP:0000358).
A form of hyperkeratosis characterized by thickening of the cornified layer without retained nuclei.
An abnormal pink color of urine.
A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type I that is characterized by abnormal radial cortical lamination.
The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of one or more long bones.
The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of the distal fibula.
A neoplasm of the trachea.
Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger with the 5th metacarpal.
Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.
A paroxysmal, transient loss of memory function with preservation of immediate recall and remote memory but with a severe impairment of memory for recent events and ability to retain new information.
A form of hydrocephalus characterized by enlarged cerebral ventricles and normal cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) pressure upon lumbar puncture.
Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of a hormone that is involved in the regulation of phosphate and calcium.
Telangiectasia of the mucosa, the mucous membranes which are involved in absorption and secretion that line cavities that are exposed to the external environment and internal organs.
An increased concentration of alanine in the blood.
An abnormality of the pattern of trabecula (small interconnecting rods of bone) in a metaphyseal region of bone.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of ornithine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Frequent menses; menstrual cycles lasting less than 21 days.

Retinal phenotype characterised by cone photoreceptor dysfunction and preserved rod system. The abnormality is typically stationary or very slowly progressive and findings may include reduced central vision, colour vision abnormalities, nystagmus and photophobia.

A type of kinetic tremor that occurs during target directed movement is called intention tremor. That is, an oscillatory cerebellar ataxia that tends to be absent when the limbs are inactive and during the first part of voluntary movement but worsening as the movement continues and greater precision is required (e.g., in touching a target such as the patient's nose or a physician's finger).
Reduced amount of adipose tissue in the region of the neck.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of tyrosine in the blood circulation.
Multiple small zones of sarcomeric disorganization and lack of oxidative activity (known as minicores) in muscle fibers.

Weakness of the muscles responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot, that is, of the movement of the toes towards the shin. The foot dorsiflexors include the tibialis anterior, the extensor hallucis longus, the extensor digitorum longus, and the peroneus tertius muscles.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a fatty acid anion in the blood circulation.
A benign mesenchymal neoplasm arising from smooth, skeletal, or cardiac muscle tissue [NCIT:C4882].
Reduced muscle tone secondary to an abnormality of the central nervous system.
Any abnormality of the submandibular glands, which are the salivary glands that are located beneath the floor of the mouth, superior to the digastric muscles.
A break or crush injury of the thigh bone (femur).

Des-gamma carboxyprothrombin (DCP) or pro-thrombin induced by vitamin K absence-II (PIVKA-II) is an abnormal prothrombin protein that is increased in the serum of patients with HCC. Generation of DCP is thought to be a result of an acquired defect in the post- translational carboxylation of the prothrombin precursor in malignant cells.
An unpleasant sensation of tightness or pressure in the chest.
Abnormality of an amino acid metabolic process.
Detection of methadone and its metabolites in the stool.
A benign or malignant neoplasm (tumour) of the peripheral nervous system.

A type of cardiac amyloidosis related to deposition of an immunoglobulin light chain. The current gold standard of amyloid typing is to determine the precursor protein using laser microdissection mass spectrometry.
The facial appearance is more circular than usual as viewed from the front.
Absence of pubic hair.
The presence of an abnormally large pelvis.
Partial dislocation of the atlantoaxial joint.
An increased concentration of glutamine in the urine.
An anomalous build up of iron (Fe) in the substantia nigra.
An increased concentration of a surfactant protein in the blood circulation.
An abnormal increased in the amount of the carbohydrate antigen 19-9, a recognizable sialo-ganglioside in the blood circulation.
Any abnormality in the proportion of CD8 T cells relative to the total number of T cells.

Increased thickness of the lower lip, leading to a prominent appearance of the lower lip. The height of the vermilion of the lower lip in the midline is more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased height of the vermilion of the lower lip in the frontal view (subjective).
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking foods rich in potassium.
Persistence of blood flow through the ductus venosus for longer than the normal time after birth.
An abnormal increase or decrease in the quantity of three-dimensional space taken up by the pineal gland.
The presence of a bilobed gallbladder, related to a duplication of the gallbladder primordium.
A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger of the hand.
A profound delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
A form of manifest strabismus (heterotropia) in which one eye is deviated downwards when both eyes are open.
ABO phenotype A, corresponding to the genotype AO or AA.
Individuals with Pseudobulbar signs often also demonstrate abnormal behavioral symptoms such as inappropriate emotional outbursts of uncontrolled laughter or weeping etc.
An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the toes. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
A venous pouch within the left ventricular wall, with a neck opening into the coronary sinus.
Edema (swelling) of the bulbar conjunctiva.
Any impairment of reabsorption of chloride by the kidney in order to not lose too much chloride in the urine.
The presence of calcium- and phosphate-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.
An anomaly in the ability to perceive and distinguish scents (odors).
An abnormal reduction in dihydropyrimidine dehydrogenase (NADP+) activity.
A bifid or bifurcated appearance of the femur as seen on x-rays, possible appearing as a more or less severe bowing of the upper leg. Might be associated with hip dysplasia on the affected side.
Enlargement of the muscles of the calf due to their replacement by connective tissue or fat.
An abnormality of the level of activity of circulating fibrinogen.
An impairment of gluconeogenesis.
Neurofibromas originating in the spine.
Hemorrhage occurring within the retina.
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers.
Enlargement of the anterior fontanelle with respect to age-dependent norms.
Reduced variation of beat-to-beat intervals of the heart that occurs in conjunction with the respiratory cycle.
Abnormally diminished capacity to sweat.
An abnormality of the zygomatic arch, also known as the cheek bone.
Depression located on the vermilion of the upper lip, usually paramedian.
Any abnormality of a metatarsal bone epiphysis.
An abnormally reduced level of alkaline phosphatase, placental type in the blood.
Severe weight loss, wasting of muscle, loss of appetite, and general debility related to a chronic disease.
A decreased amount of alanine in the blood.

A reduced ability to synthesize antibodies against antigens from an infectious agent or pathogen (such as bacteria, viruses, parasites, etc.), as measured by antibody titer determination following infection.
Abnormality of the mitral valve apparatus, whereby chordae attach to a single papillary muscle or hypoplastic papillary muscles.
A decreased concentration of 5-methyltetrahydrofolate in the blood.

Lack of observable abnormal electroencephalographic (EEG) patterns in an individual with a history of seizures. About half of individuals with epilepsy show interictal epileptiform discharges upon the first investigation. The yield can be increased by repeated studies, sleep studies, or by ambulatory EEG recordings over 24 hours. Normal interictal EEG is a sign that can be useful in the differential diagnosis.

Atrophy of the interosseus muscles (including the palmar interossei that lie on the anterior aspect of the metacarpals, the dorsal interosseus muscles of the hand, which lie between the intercarpals, the plantar interosseus muscles, which lie underneath the metatarsal bones, and the dorsal interossei, which are located between the metatarsal bones.

A form of closed neural tube defect in which the spinal tissue lies within the spinal cord having a junction between the spinal cord and the lipoma. Intact skin covers the defect. Neurologic findings first appear during the second year of life.
An abnormal anatomic position of the fovea, the small, central pit composed of closely packed cones that is located in the macula of the retina.
A decreased proportion of circulating CD4-positive helper T cells relative to total T cell count.
Absence of the middle ear ossicles, malleus, incus, and stapes.
An abnormally increased level of immunoglobulin D in blood.
An abnormal orientation of the earlobes such that they point out- and upward. That is, the lateral surface of ear lobe faces superiorly.
Atrophy of the superior rectus, the extraocular muscle whose primary function is to elevate the globe.
An abnormality of the birth process.
Crackles that appear at the beginning of inspiration and end before mid-inspiration.
Decreased amount of pigmentation in the fovea centralis.
A fluid filled sac in the kidney.
