An abnormal deviation from normal levels of IgG immunoglobulin in blood.
Asthma attacks following exercise.
Recurrent or persistent genital pain associated with sexual intercourse.
Joint stiffness is a perceived sensation of tightness in a joint or joints when attempting to move them after a period of inactivity. Joint stiffness typically subsides over time.
A type of diabetic metabolic abnormality with an accumulation of ketone bodies.
Excessive wrinkling of the skin of the face.

Absence of germinal centers in lymph nodes. Germinal centers are the parts of lymph nodes in which B lymphocytes proliferate, differentiate, mutate through somatic hypermutation and class switch during antibody responses.
An abnormality of the larynx.

At birth, newborns are endowed with maternal antibodies. IgG production normally begins at the age of two months. A delay in recovery from this physiological hypogammaglobulinemia between the 3rd and the 6th month of life, and of recovery period between 18 and 36 months defines transient newborn hypogammaglobulinemia.
Overgrowth of only one side of the body.
An abnormality of the dental enamel.

Muscular atrophy affecting the muscles that attach to the pelvic girdle (the gluteal muscles, the lateral rotators, adductor magnus, adductor brevis, adductor longus, pectineus, and gracilis muscles).
Subvalvular stenosis is caused by a diaphragm-like membrane. The stenosis is clinically manifested like any other form of aortic stenosis but is often associated with some aortic insufficiency.
Increased level of leucine in urine.

Deviation from normal in the amount of beta sarcoglycan in muscle. The alpha, beta, gamma, and delta sarcoglycans are components of the dystrophin-complex. They are all N-glycosylated transmembrane proteins with a short intra-cellular domain, a single transmembrane region and a large extra-cellular domain containing a cluster of conserved cysteines.
Increased protrusion of the inferior crus relative to the prominence of the antihelix stem.
Atrophy of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the optic nerve.
Abnormality of the urachus.
Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the third finger.
Atrophy of the cerebral subcortical white and gray matter, termed subcortical atrophy, reflects loss of nerve cells in the basal ganglia or fibers in the deep white matter.
A connection of the right and left kidney by an isthmus of functioning renal parenchyma or fibrous tissue that crosses the midline.
Increased height of the tragal ridge with a shallow indentation at the apex, giving the appearance of a double peak.
A reduction in the circulating level of luteinizing hormone (LH).
The congenital absence of the sternum.
An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can expel following maximal insipiration.
A cavity within the cerebral hemisphere, filled with cerebrospinal fluid, that communicates directly with the ventricular system.
Delayed maturation and calcification of the calcaneus.
A progressive form of sensorineural hearing impairment.
A developmental anomaly characterized by abnormal smallness of one eye.

Lymphoid nodular hyperplasia (LNH) of the terminal ileum and colon has been considered a mucosal response to nonspecific stimuli, most often infections, and consequently has been regarded as a pathophysiologic phenomenon during infancy and childhood. LNH can be ascertained by colonoscopy, whereby a lymphoid nodule is defined as an extruding follicle with a diameter of not more than 2 mm, and LNH is defined as a cluster of not more than 10 of such extruding lymphoid nodules (see Figure 1 of PMID:17368236).
Presence of an unusually high number of lentigines (singular: lentigo), which are flat, tan to brown oval spots.
Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the 3rd (middle) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

Temper tantrums whose severity is more severe than usual. For instance, a temper tantrum might be considered to be severe if a child loses control so completely that the child cannot control the tantrum on its own, continuing until it becomes exhausted or a parent intervenes.
The abnormal fusion of neighboring bones across a joint.
A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in tissue.
Delivery by Caesarian section representing where the mother has already had a previous Cesarean delivery, and this is a repeat Cesarean birth.
Soft and hard-palate submucous clefts are characterized by bony defects in the midline of the soft and hard palate that are covered by the lining (ie mucous membrane) of the roof of the mouth.
Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
An increased susceptibility to candida infections, as manifested by a history of recurrent episodes of candida infections.
A reduction in the amplitude of sensory nerve action potential. This feature is measured by nerve conduction studies.
An aneurysm (severe localized balloon-like outward bulging) in the pulmonary artery.
A type of focal cortical dysplasia that is characterized by abnormal cortical layering.
Myelodysplasia with dysplastic changes in two of the myeloid lineages: erythroid, granulocytic, megakaryocytic.
An abnormal increase in magnitude of the pressure in the right atrium.
Presence of IgA antibodies in the dermoepidermal junction that are dsitributed in a linear pattern. This feature can be appreciated by immunofluorescence microscopy.
An abnormally decreased amount of thyroxin-binding globulin (TBG) in blood. TBG is responsible for carrying the thyroid hormones thyroxine (T4) and 3,5,3'-triiodothyronine (T3) in the bloodstream.
Redness of the skin of the face, caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:20255002 SNOMEDCT_US:271811009 UMLS:C4020880 UMLS:C0005874 SNOMEDCT_US:398909004 MSH:D012393 UMLS:C0239488 MSH:D001821 UMLS:C0035854

?def: A ventricular septal defect that is confluent with and involves the membranous septum and is bordered by an atrioventricular valve, not including the type 3 VSDs.
A posterior embryotoxon is the presence of a prominent and anteriorly displaced line of Schwalbe.
A primitive neuroectodermal tumor that originates from the cells of the embryonic medullary canal.
Any deviation from the normal total hemolytic complement activity in the circulation.
Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the middle phalanx of the 4th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
A broad (120 ms or longer in duration) and bifid P-wave in EKG lead II.
An abnormal morphology of the middle phalanx of the third toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

An abnormal origin of the left circumflex artery (LCX) from the right coronary artery. Normally, the left anterior descending (LAD) and the LCX arise from a common stem, the left main coronary artery (LMCA).
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of phalanges of the toes.
Abnormality of the adrenal glands, i.e., of the endocrine glands located at the top of the kindneys.

A reduction below normal proportion of naive B cells (CD19+/CD27-/IgD+/IgM+) relative to total number of B cells. Naive B cells represent one of the subtypes of B cells in the peripheral blood, and are B cells that have not been exposed to antigen.
Narrow ridge in the midline of the philtral groove.

A typical absence seizure is a generalized seizure with abrupt onset and offset of altered awareness which can vary in severity (see specific syndromes). Memory for events during the seizures is usually impaired although there may be some retained awareness particularly for adolescents. Clonic movements of eyelids, head, eyebrows, chin, perioral or other facial parts may occur, most typically at 3Hz. Myoclonus of limbs can rarely occur. Oral and manual automatisms are common and there may be perseveration of behaviors occurring prior to seizure onset.

?def: Lung parenchymal involvement with lymphoma.
An abnormality of the platysma muscle.
A deviation from the normal size of the pituitary gland.
Increased amplitude (0.1 mV or more) and/or duration (40 ms or more) of the S wave as measured in lead I of the electrocardiogram.
Severe chills with violent shivering. A rigor is an episode of shaking or exaggerated shivering which can occur with a high fever.
An anomaly of the proximal phalanx of third toe.
The gradual reduction in girth of the toe from proximal to distal.
Underdeveloped pedicle of the fifth lumbar vertebra.
Excretion of excess amounts of aspartylglucosamine in the urine.
A bening tumor of bone composed of a central zone named nidus which is an atypical bone completely enclosed within a well vascularized stroma and a peripheral sclerotic reaction zone.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger is affected.
A soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between fingers 3 and 4.
The presence of a cleft in the cerebral cortex unilaterally or bilaterally, usually located in the frontal area.

Polymicrogyria (an excessive number of small gyri or convolutions) that is maximal in perisylvian regions (the regions that surround the Sylvian fissures), which may be symmetric or asymmetric and may extend beyond perisylvian regions. The Sylvian fissures often extend posteriorly and superiorly.
Length of penis more than 2 SD below the mean for age accompanied by hypospadias.
The severe form of a neural tube defect where the open neural tube appears as a flattened, plate-like mass of nervous tissue with no overlying membrane.

An intrauterine state characterized by suboptimal values in the fetal heart rate, oxygenation of fetal blood, or other parameters indicative of compromise of the fetus. Signs of fetal distress include repetitive variable decelerations, fetal tachycardia or bradycardia, late decelerations, or low biophysical profile.

Reduced criculating level of apolipoprotein AI, which is the major protein component of high density lipoprotein (HDL) in plasma. Defects in this gene are associated with HDL deficiencies, including Tangier disease.

An impaired immune response mediated by cells expressing specific receptors for antigen produced through a somatic diversification process, and allowing for an enhanced secondary response to subsequent exposures to the same antigen (immunological memory).
An abnormality of the pylorus.
The presence of a fistula between the vagina and the urethra.

A deviation from the normal range of the ratio of the albumin concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) to the concentration in serum (which may be defined as 3.2-9.0). This is an index of blood-brain barrier (BBB) integrity, adjusted for the serum albumin concentration, and an increased ratio is taken as a sign of a loss of integrity of the BBB with leakage of albumin into the CSF.
Repeated episodes of headache with rapid onset, reaching a peak within minutes and of short duration (less than one hour) with pain that is throbbing, pulsating, or bursting in quality.
A type of dystonia that affects all or most of the body.
Bullae (defined as fluid-filled blisters more than 5 mm in diameter with thin walls) of the skin with an acral distribution (affecting peripheral regions such as hands and feet=.
An abnormality of actions or reactions of a person taking place during interactions with others.
Increased level of IgE antibody against nut food products such as peanuts or tree nuts, such as hazelnuts, walnuts, cashews, and almonds.

A benign, well circumscribed sweat gland neoplasm with eccrine or apocrine differentiation. It usually presents as a solitary, dome-shaped papule, nodule, or plaque on acral sites. It is characterized by a proliferation of uniform basaloid cells in the dermis and it is associated with the presence of focal ductal and cystic structures [NCIT:C27273].
Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements.
An elevation in the normal proportion of marginal zone B cells (CD19+/CD27+/IgM+/IgD+) in circulation relative to the total number of B cells.
A mild reduction in the ability to perceive visual contrast characterized by 0.20-0.59 log unit contrast sensitivity loss.
A fluid-filled sac (cyst) located within the central nervous system.
Complete lack of functioning of the vestibular apparatus.
An abnormally increased concentration of the IgG4 subtype in the blood circulation.
An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the tongue.
Hyperkeratosis of the gingiva.

Increased plasma concentrations of chylomicrons, the large lipid droplet (up to 100 mm in diameter) of reprocessed lipid synthesized in epithelial cells of the small intestine and containing triacylglycerols, cholesterol esters, and several apolipoproteins.
Cleft palate of the midline of the palate.
A turning outward of the lip or lips, that is, eversion of the lips.
An abnormal decrease in orotidine 5'-phosphate decarboxylase activity.
Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
An abnormally increased height of the forehead.
A deviation from normal concentration of glucose content in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Any abnormality of the mouth floor.
Watery voluminous diarrhea resulting from an imbalance between ion and water secretion and absorption.
Generalized seizures with sustained increase in muscle contraction lasting a few seconds to minutes.
Forceful ejection of the contents of the stomach through the mouth by means of a series of involuntary spasmic contractions.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:422400008 SNOMEDCT_US:300359004 UMLS:C0042963 SNOMEDCT_US:249497008 MEDDRA:10047700 MSH:D014839

?def: Present in 1% to 4% of the cases.
The right common carotid artery normally originates from the brachiocephalic artery. This term refers to an origin of this artery directly from the aorta.
Excessive thirst manifested by excessive fluid intake.
A structural abnormality of the pineal gland.
An increased concentration of homovanillic acid in the urine.
The presence of a single coronary artery ostium from which both coronary arteries arise.
Deposition of calcium salts in the retina.

Dystonic gait disorders frequently appear bizarre, particularly because activity increases dystonic tonus and posture. The abnormal posture of the foot in dystonic gait typically involves inversion, plantar flexion and tonic extension of the big toe. In many patients complex types of walking, such as walking backwards and running are paradoxically less impaired than walking forward and may seem completely unaffected. Sensory tricks, for instance, if the affected individual rests a hand on his or her neck, may improve or even normalize dystonic gait in some patients.
An anterior retrosternal or parasternal hernia that can result in the herniation of liver or intestines into the chest cavity.
The presence of large polyhedral cells with eosinophilic granular cytoplasm and enlarged nuclei in the adrenal cortex.

An inflammatory process in skin caused by an exogenous agent that directly or indirectly injure the skin. If the offending agent is identified and removed, the eruption will resolve. An unusual or patterned eruption may be a clue to the presence of a contact dermatitis. Patch testing may be helpful in the differential diagnosis.
An increased amount of nitrogen in the form of urea in the blood.
The appearance of yellow/white crystalline-like (hence the name) spots in the retina and thickening of the peripheral part of the vitreous.

Excessive eyelid tissue laxity, typically affecting both upper eyelids and associated with spontanteous tarsal eversion during sleep. It is more common in the obese, it may be associated with obstructive sleep apnea and it may result in corneal exposure or chronic papillary conjunctivitis.
Complete duplication of the distal phalanx of index finger.
Any anomaly of the S wave, which is the third component of the QRS wave complex. The S wave signifies the final depolarization of the ventricles at the base of the heart.
The left common carotid artery normally originates from the aortic arch. This term refers to an origin of this artery from the main pulmonary artery.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against voltage-gated calcium channels.
Depression located paramedially on the vermilion of a lip.
An anomaly of the PR segment, which begins at the endpoint of the P wave and ends at the onset of the QRS complex. The PR segment is normally flat and isoelectric.

A nasolacrimal duct obstruction presenting as a grey-blue cystic swelling just below the medial canthus. Believed to be a result of concomitant upper obstruction of the Rosenmuller valve and lower obstruction of the Hasner valve.
The presence of a fistula of the vagina.
Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of second toe.
An anomaly of the arch of aorta.
The presence of subcutaneous lipoma.
An abnormal form or size of neutrophils.
An abnormality of the ureter.
An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in leukocytes.
Nonparallel arrangement/disarray of elastic fibers of the media of the aorta as identified on a stain for elastic fibers.
A type of ectopia cordis with the heart partially in the cervical region with a defect of the superior portion of the sternum.
An abnormality of ocular smooth pursuit characterized by an impairment of the ability to track horizontally moving objects.
An abnormal increase in the thickness of the atrial septum.

Abnormally small dimension of the Maxilla. Usually creating a malocclusion or malalignment between the upper and lower teeth or resulting in a deficient amount of projection of the base of the nose and lower midface region.
Increased susceptibility to ear infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of ear infections.
A contracture of the Achilles tendon.
Pain in the vulvar area
An elevated level of circulating N-terminal part of the prohormone of B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP).
An abnormality of the stroma of cornea, also known as the substantia propria of cornea.
Any anomaly of the pigmentation of the fundus, the posterior part of the eye including the retina and optic nerve.
A chronic, autoimmune type of thyroiditis associated with hypothyroidism.
A displacement or misalignment of the humerus with respect to the other bones of the should joint. Note that a subluxation is a partial dislocation.
Epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb having multiple bony fragments.
A type of cryptotia associated with reduction in size of the antihelix and inferior crus that are affected.
Increased width of the distal phalanx of the 4th finger.
Absence of the acoustic reflex, an involuntary contraction of the stapedius muscle that occurs in response to high-intensity sound stimuli.
A function abnormality of the endocrine pancreas.

A congenital branchial sinus is a remnant of the embryonic branchial arches and their intervening clefts and pouches that has failed to regress completely. Sinuses typically have their external orifice inferior to the ramus of the mandible. They may traverse the parotid gland, and run in close vicinity to the facial nerve in the external auditory canal.
An increased concentration of 5-aminolevulinic acid (CHEBI:17549) in the urine.
Clonus is an involuntary tendon reflex that causes repeated flexion and extension of the foot. Knee clonus can be tested by rapidly pushing the patella towards the toes.
The presence of osteophytes (bone spurs), i.e., of bony projections originating from the acetabulum.
An tongue-like extension of hair towards the cheeks.
Separation of the odontoid process from the body of the axis.

Tiny deposits corresponding to cells floating in the anterior chamber of the eye. This appearance is typically associated with intraocular inflammation leading to breakdown of the blood-aqueous barrier and resulting in an increase in the number of cells and in the aqueous humor. Grading (SUN Working Group) is performed by estimating the number of cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.
Reduced width of the skin of vermilion border region of upper lip.
Bony fusion between the humerus and scapula, leading to an impairment in mobility of the affected shoulder joint.

An abnormally increased number of band cells in the peripheral blood circulation. Band cells are immature neutrophils with a size of 10-18 micrometers, a horseshoe-shaped nucleus with no nucleoli, light-pink staining cytoplasm with many small seconday granules, and a nucleus:cytoplasm ratio of 1:2.
The presence of a neoplasm of the adrenal medulla.
Increased rigidity and reduced mobility of the tongue.
Displacement of the hand or of fingers of the hand from their normal position.
Presence of an increased number of neutrophils in the urine.
A cessation of the development of a child in the areas of motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and/or emotional skills, following the onset of epilepsy.
Inflammation of the spinal cord.

Anomalous mitral valve arcade is diagnosed based on the following features (1) An adequately sized mitral valve orifice; (2) short, thick, and poorly differentiated chordae with direct union of the papillary muscles to the anterior leaflet; (3) narrow or nearly nonexistent spaces between the abnormal chordae; and (4) greater differentiation of the chordae attached to the posterior papillary muscle.
Reduction in the activity of lipoprotein lipase in the blood.
The presence of a fistula (abnormal tunnel) between the anal canal and the perineum.
Amyloid deposition in the walls of leptomeningeal and cortical arteries, arterioles, and less often capillaries and veins of the central nervous system.
Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the tunica media of medium-sized (muscular or distributive) arteries.
The left main coronary artery (LMCA) is absent and the left anterior descending (LAD) and left circumflex (LCX) arteries arise from separate but adjacent ostia in the left sinus of Valsava.
Fusion of the interphalangeal joints of the 2nd toe.
Progressively reduced or lacking hair growth.
Reduced amplitude of the pulse pressure (systolic blood pressure minus diastolic blood pressure).
An exaggeration of emotional affects such as laughing crying, or yawning beyond what the person feels.
An abnormal buildup of lactic acid in the body, leading to acidification of the blood and other bodily fluids.
Widening of the nostrils upon inhalation as a manifestation of respiratory distress.
A structural anomaly of sperm.
Increased variation of beat-to-beat intervals of the heart that occurs in conjunction with the respiratory cycle.
Having a relatively minor degree of severity. For quantitative traits, a deviation of between two and three standard deviations from the appropriate population mean.

Any anomaly of the inflammatory response, a response to injury or infection characterized by local vasodilation, extravasation of plasma into intercellular spaces and accumulation of white blood cells and macrophages.

A reduction below the normal concentration of thyroxine in the blood. Thyroxine (also known as T4) is the main hormone secreted by the thyroid gland into the blood. It can be converted into the active form triiodothyronine (also known as T3).
The presence of an unusually high plantar arch. Also called high instep, pes cavus refers to a distinctly hollow form of the sole of the foot when it is bearing weight.
An elevated concentration of free 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine in the blood circulation.
Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the ring finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
Accumulation of scar tissue within the glomerulus.
Focal proliferation of glial cells in the cerebellum.

A type of megaloblastic anemia that does not improve upon administration of folate. Since vitamin B12 acts by promoting recycling of folate, administration of vitamin B12 also does not improve this type of anemia.
A neurenteric cyst located within the skull.
An increase in the level of GABA in the serum.

A type of heterotaxy where some paired structures on opposite sides of the left-right axis of the body are symmetrical mirror images of each other, and have the morphology of the normal left-sided structures.
Seizures that start from several different areas of the brain (i.e., with multiple ictal onset locations).
Irreversible damage to heart tissue (myocardium) due to lack of oxygen after a heart attack (myocardial infarction).
A detachment that involves the peripheral retina that involves the macula itself. The detachment usually starts in the temporal periphery although can also involve the nasal retina as well.

Systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve (SAM) is a paradoxical motion of the anterior, and occasionally posterior, mitral valve leaflet towards the left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) during systole.
A decrease in alkaline phosphatase activity measured within leukocytes below detectable levels .
This term refers to the loss of eyelashes that were previously present.

The presence during the prenatal period of a cystic mass with multiple septa with multiple, asymmetric, thin-walled cysts near the posterior aspect of the neck. Fetal cystic hygroma can be defined as nuchal translucency with or without septations measuring greater than 3.0 mm.
Decreased size of the maxillary permanent incisor.
A type of conductive deafness with congenital onset.
Pneumothorax occurring neonatally without traumatic injury to the chest or lung.
Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced beta sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.

Lack of normal alpha rhythm in the EEG. Alpha rhythm has been defined as a rhythm at 8-13 Hz occurring during wakefulness over the posterior regions of the head, generally with higher voltage over the occipital areas. Amplitude is variable but is mostly below 50 microvolt in adults. It is best seen with eyes closed and under conditions of physical relaxation and relative mental inactivity. It is blocked or attenuated by attention, especially visual and mental effort. One should here note the difference between the terms alpha rhythm and alpha activity: Alpha activity refers to activity in the range of 8-13 Hz and alpha rhythm is the activity of 8-13 Hz with specific characteristics as defined above.
A Malignant mesothelioma of the testis.
Increased width of the diaphysis of long bones.
The presence of a papillary adenocarcinoma of the thyroid gland.
An abnormal curved or vaulted (capped) structure covering the middle third of the dorsal pontine tegmentum and projecting into the fourth ventricle.
A deviation from the normal concentration of beta globulin. The beta globulins are a group of globular (globe-shaped) proteins in blood.
Absence or hypoplasia of toes.
The presence of calcium deposition within brain structures that is present already at the time of birth.
An abnormality related to a defect of vertebral separation of sacral vertebrae during development.
Unstable emotional experiences and frequent mood changes; emotions that are easily aroused, intense, and/or out of proportion to events and circumstances.
An abnormality of the leg.
A benign, painful, tumor of bone characterized by the formation of osteoid tissue, primitive bone and calcified tissue.
A pain characteristic is defined as a subjective category or type of pain.
A type of Macrodactyly affecting one or several toes.

Juvenile granulosa cell ovarian tumor (JGCOT) is a rare sex cord stromal tumor, occuring most frequently in premenarchal girls or young women. In contrast to adult granulosa cell tumor, JGCOT has a high mitotic index and more aggressive tumor growth. Microscopically it is seen as diffuse and regularly distributed neoplastic cells with a wide cytoplasm and pleomorphic hyperchromatic nucleus. Follicle formation, in various sizes and shapes, is important in JGCOT. Call-Exner bodies are infrequently seen in JGCOT in contrast to the adult type.
A duplication of the renal pelvis.
An increased concentration of non ceruloplasmin bound copper in the blood.
Paralysis of the iris and ciliary apparatus.

A specific combination of heart defects including a primum atrial septal defect and cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet. There is not an inlet ventricular septal defect present. There are two valve annuluses and two valve orifices.

Axenfeld's anomaly is a bilateral disorder characterized by a prominent, anteriorly displaced Schwalbe's line (posterior embryotoxon) and peripheral iris strands which span the anterior chamber angle to attach to Schwalbe's line.
Lateral deviation of the great toe (i.e., in the direction of the little toe).
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:415692008 UMLS:C0018536 MSH:D000071378 UMLS:C0006386 MSH:D006215 SNOMEDCT_US:122480009

?def: This term applies to a family member in whom the diagnosis that is the primary focus of investigation is excluded.
A reduction in the freedom of movement of one or more joints.
Narrowing (becoming gradually narrower) of the distance between lumbar vertebral pedicles that gets progressively more severe towards to caudal (lower) end of the vertebral column.

Dissolution or attenuation of mesangial matrix and degeneration of mesangial cells. In essence, mesangiolysis is an injurious process which affects the glomerular mesangium without causing obvious damage to the capillary basement membranes. The matrix swells, loosens, and eventually dissolves; the mesangial cells may show only edema and vacuolization, or may undergo severe degeneration and necrosis.
Reduced size of the proximal epiphysis of the tibia.
A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in leukocytes.
Reduced diameter of a long bone with a more pronounced reduction of the diameter of the diaphysis of the long bones.
Lack of separation of the upper and lower lips.
Bending or curvature of a thumb towards the ulnar side (towards the ring finger).
Presence of a single diverticulum (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urinary bladder.

Accumulation of blood located in the retina's inner nuclear and outer plexiform layers, and having a dot-like or blot-like shape. THe shape results from intraretinal compression, restricting the hemorrhages within a specific location.

A scintillating scotoma is a common visual aura that can preced a migraine, whereby a spot of flickering light near the center of the visual fields occurs. The spot prevents vision, and is thus termed scotoma. The scotoma can extend into one or more shimmering arcs of white or colored flashing lights.

An abnormal inversion of the eyelid towards the globe resulting from inferior retractor muscle dysfunction with tissue laxity and, possibly, overriding of the preseptal orbicularis muscle over the pretarsal orbicularis muscle.
An increase in the length of time required for food to pass through the intestines.
Hypoplastic/small middle phalanx of the 4th finger, also known as the ring finger.
A membrane-like structure that extends across the laryngeal lumen close to the level of the vocal cords.
An decreased concentration of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate aldolase in the serum.
A conduction block of the left branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a generalized disturbance of QRS morphology on EKG.
The presence of blood in the urine. Hematuria may be gross hematuria (visible to the naked eye) or microscopic hematuria (detected by dipstick or microscopic examination of the urine).
A decreased concentration of insulin in the blood.
An increase in the level of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the urine.
Presence of nodules in the conjunctiva of the eye.
An increase in the amount of very-low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
An abnormality of the physiological functioning of B cells.
Increased susceptibility to chicken pox, as manifested by recurrent episodes of chicken pox.

Sarcomatoid (spindle cell) carcinomas of the tongue is a variant of squamous carcinoma of tongue that is monoclonal, having evolved from a conventional squamous carcinoma with dedifferentiation associated with sarcomatoid transformation.
Abnormal bleeding of the umbilical stump following separation of the cord at approximately 7-10 days after birth.
Small, underdeveloped vertebral bodies.
Loose, wrinkled skin of hands and feet.

Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) whereby the aortic arch is hypoplastic or interrupted, and a large patent ductus arteriosus is present.
Elevated concentration of beta-2-microglobulin in the blood.
Eyelid partly covered by skin when eyes are open.

Aplasia or Hypoplasia affecting the 1st metacarpal. In contrast to the metacarpals 2-5, the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5 (whereas the proximal phalanx of the thumb is equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits).
A progressive degree of muscular rigidity (continuous contraction of muscles with constant resistance to passive movement).
Difficulty in swallowing.
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 5th finger.
An abnormal enlargement or swelling in the abdomen.
Paralysis of one or more extraocular muscles that are responsible for eye movements.

An abnormality of the distal phalanx of the fourth finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
A congenital defect with an abnormal joining of the gums of the upper and lower jaw.
Histoplasmosis is caused by the fungus Histoplasma capsulatum and is consider to be an opportunistic infection in immunosuppressed persons.
A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a diffuse hypointensity affecting all of the basal ganglia.

Budd-Chiari syndrome (BCS) is caused by obstruction of hepatic venous outflow at any level from the small hepatic veins to the junction of the inferior vena cava (IVC) with the right atrium, 1 and occurs in 1/100,000 of the general population worldwide. The most common presentation is with ascites, but can range from fulminant hepatic failure (FHF) to asymptomatic forms. Obstruction of hepatic venous outflow is mainly caused by primary intravascular thrombosis, which can occur suddenly or be repeated over time, accompanied by some revascularization, accounting for the variable parenchymal hepatic damage and histologic presentation. Budd-Chiari syndrome is thus a disease, but since it occurs as a manifestation of several other diseases, this term is kept for the present for convenience.

A congenital inclusion cysts that arises from the inclusion of ectodermally committed cells at the time of neural tube closure (3rd-5th week of embryogenesis). The capsule of dermoid cysts consists of simple epithelium supported by collagen. In thicker parts, the lining is supplemented with dermis containing hair follicles, sebaceous glands, and apocrine glands.
This modifer can be applied to a phenotypic feature that does not vary in severity or amount over time.

Absence of the corpus callosum as a result of the failure of the corpus callosum to develop, which can be the result of a failure in any one of the multiple steps of callosal development including cellular proliferation and migration, axonal growth or glial patterning at the midline.

An abnormality of the retina characterized by pigment deposition. It is typically associated with migration and proliferation of macrophages or retinal pigment epithelial cells into the retina; melanin from these cells causes the pigmentary changes. Pigmentary retinopathy is a common final pathway of many retinal conditions and is often associated with visual loss.
High levels of ketone bodies in the urine.
A complication of pregnancy and delivery in which the umbilical cord wraps around the fetal neck once or multiple times.
A type of vertical tropia in which, when one eye is fixing, the other eye is deviated downwards.
An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in leukocytes.
A Schmorl's node is the herniation of nucleus pulposus through the cartilaginous and bony end plate into the body of the adjacent vertebra.
An abnormally reduced concentration of hepcidin in the blood circulation.
Inflammation of the tongue.
Chronic loss of joint motion in one or more distal interphalangeal joints of the fingers.
Lack of strength of the proximal muscles that becomes progressively more severe.
An abnormal structure or appearance of hemidesmosomes, multiprotein complexes that facilitate the stable adhesion of basal epithelial cells to the underlying basement membrane.
A type of choroidal neovascularization in which the area of neovascularization overlaps with the center of the fovea.

An increase in collagen fibers creating areas of substitutive fibrosis or a widening of intralamellar spaces in the media of the aorta. This can be seen in conjunction with a loss to varying degrees of parallel arrangement of the elastic lamellae (or lamellar units).
A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the little finger of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.
Inflammation of a synovial bursa.
A variable severity of phenotypic features.
Abnormally increased levels of lysine in cerebrospinal fluid.

An abnormal pattern of respiration characterized by cycles of respiration that are increasingly deeper then shallower with possible periods of apnea. Affected patients may display a 10 to 20 second episode of hypoventilation or apnea, followed by respiration of increased depth and frequency over the course of about one minute. The cycle repeats every 45 seconds to 3 minutes.
Any increased amount from normal of valine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
A difference in length or diameter between the left and right leg.
A fluid filled sac located in the Fallopian tube.
Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the fallopian tube.
Inflammation of the thyroid gland.
The presence of a hernia of the diaphragm present at birth.
Wasting of thenar muscles, which are located on palm of the hand at the base of the thumb.

Ocular flutter is an abnormal eye movement consisting of repetitive, irregular, involuntary bursts of horizontal saccades without an intersaccadic interval. It is generally superimposed on normal oculomotor behaviour and its occurrence may be favoured by various events, such as blinks, the triggering of normal saccades or optokinetic stimulation.
An increased concentration of citrulline in the blood.

Disseminated multifocal hemangiomatous or lymphangiomatous lesions of the skeleton. The lesions are lytic, well-defined, round or oval lesions within the medullary cavity, and they have an intact cortex, and manifest variable peripheral sclerosis and may exhibit endosteal scalloping.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the acetabular part of hip bone.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the proximal phalanx of the hallux.
A sloped configuration of the metaphysis (shaft) of the ulna.
An abnormal increase in the size of the foramen magnum.
The presence of multiple granulomata (small nodular inflammatory lesions containing grouped mononuclear phagocytes) in the lung.
Congenital underdevelopment of the iris.
Presence of an additional phalanx-like bone, producing an extra, wedge-shaped bone at the base of the proximal phalanx of the second finger.

A clonal (malignant) hematopoietic disorder with an acute onset, affecting the bone marrow and the peripheral blood. The malignant cells show minimal differentiation and are called blasts, either myeloid blasts (myeloblasts) or lymphoid blasts (lymphoblasts).
Bilateral convulsive seizures are focal seizure with secondary bilateral motor phenomena, not primary generalized seizures.
A congenital abnormality of the distribution of hair growth.
An abnormality of the pancreas.
Applied to pain that wakes the affecting individual from sleep.
Superior margin of the scrotum superior to the base of the penis.

Eye strain, i.e., a feeling of fatigue or discomfort of the eyes related to 'overuse' of the eyes in activities such as reading or working at the computer and often accompanied by lacrimation or headache.
A type of seizure characterized by laughing or an outburst of laughing as a major feature.

A deviation from normal of muscle alpha-dystroglcan expression. Alpha-dystroglycan is a heavily glycosylated peripheral-membrane component of the dystrophin-associated glycoprotein complex (DAPC), which, in addition to laminin alpha2, binds perlecan and agrin in the extracellular matrix, whereas beta-dystroglycan, derived from the same gene, is a transmembrane protein that links to dystrophin intracellularly.
Irregularly shaped metacarpal bones of varying degree.
A functional anomaly of the hepatobiliary system
Bony outgrowths that extend laterally from the margin of the metaphysis.

An abnormality of the middle-ear ossicles (three small bones called malleus, incus, and stapes) that are contained within the middle ear and serve to transmit sounds from the air to the fluid-filled labyrinth (cochlea).
Any structural anomaly of the posterior circulating artery (PCOM).
A chronic irritative conjunctivitis, which commonly presents with general irritation and redness of the eyes, with a burning, dry, or foreign-body sensation of the eyes.
A squamous cell carcinoma that originates in the anal canal.
Weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities. Paraplegia refers to a severe or complete loss of strength, whereas paraparesis refers to a relatively mild loss of strength.
A form of cataract in which the lens substance has shrunk, leaving a collapsed, flattened capsule with little or no cortex or epithelium on the lens.
An abnormality of coagulation related to a decreased concentration of antithrombin-III.
An abnormal increase in the ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disc.
Fixed sarcastic grimace and anxious expression. Caused by spasms of the masseter and other facial muscles.
A reduced level of the complement component C4b in circulation.
Abnormal appearance of material expectorated (coughed up) from the respiratory system and that is composed of mucus but may contain other substances such as pus, blood, microorganisms, and fibrin.

A type of skin nodule (a lesions that is greater than either 10mm in both width and depth, and most frequently centered in the dermis or subcutaneous fat) with a yellowish coloration (that reflects a high lipid content of the lesion).
An abnormality of the calcaneus, also known as the heel bone, one of the or heel bone, one of the components of the tarsus of the foot which make up the heel.
Underdevelopment of the pectoralis major.
An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the second toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
An ability of the toe joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.
Greater than average forward and/or lateral protrusion of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.
The presence of a supernumerary toe (not a hallux) involving the third or fourth metatarsal with associated osseous syndactyly.
A type of Horner syndrome with congenital onset.
Increased concentration of trimethylamine in the urine.

An elevated number of elastic fibers, that is of bundles of proteins and glycoproteins in the extracellular matrix in the reticular dermis. Elastic fibers can stretch and recoil back to their original length. This feature can be appreciated on histology with hematoxylin and eosin or other staining methods.

Damage to cerebral nuclei caused in infants by highly increased levels of unconjugated bilirubin. The basal ganglia and brainstem nuclei could be shown to have a yellow staining historically in infants who died of kernicterus, that is, kernicterus is strictly speaking a pathological diagnosis. The presence of kernicterus may be inferred in infants with characteristic acute or chronic bilirubin-induced neurological dysfunction.
Obesity with a body mass index of 40 kg per square meter or higher.

The presence of convoluted folds and furrows formed from thickened skin of the scalp, resembling cerebriform pattern. The scalp has convoluted and elevated folds, 1 to 2 cm in thickness. The convolutions generally cannot be flattened by traction.

A reduced concentration of prealbumin in the blood. Prealbumin, also known as transthyretin, has a half-life in plasma of about 2 days, much shorter than that of albumin. Prealbumin is therefore more sensitive to changes in protein-energy status than albumin, and its concentration closely reflects recent dietary intake rather than overall nutritional status.

Fetal choroid plexus cysts (CPCs) are sonographically discrete, small cysts found in the choroid plexus within the lateral cerebral ventricles of the developing fetus at 14 to 24 weeks gestation. Imaging of the choroid plexus is performed in the transverse plane of the fetal head at the same level that the lateral cerebral ventricle is evaluated. The choroid plexus should be inspected bilaterally for the presence of cysts. The size of CPCs is not of clinical relevance (pmid:16100637).
An abnormality of the fontanelle.

IWith incomplete partition II, the cochlea consists of 1.5 turns; the apical and middle cochlea turns are undifferentiated and form a cystic apex. The vestibule is normal while the vestibular aqueduct is always enlarged. Developmental arrest occurs at the seventh week of gestation.

A lower midline facial cleft, also known as the median mandibular cleft. It is a rare anomaly, which may be limited to a defect in the soft tissue of the lower lip. However, in the more severe form, it may extend into the bony mandibular symphysis.
A benign or malignant neoplasm (tumour) originating in the vascular system.
?xrefs: NCIT:C3262 SNOMEDCT_US:699605009 SNOMEDCT_US:126736007 UMLS:C0282607 MSH:D009383 MSH:D019043 UMLS:C0027668 SNOMEDCT_US:115235003

?def: Bowing (bulging out) of the muscular part of the interventricular septum of more than 10-15 mm into the cavity of an adjacent ventricle (usually into the right ventricle).
Any structural abnormality of the vagina.

Trichorrhexis nodosa is the formation of nodes along the hair shaft through which breakage readily occurs. It is thus a focal defect in the hair fiber that is characterized by thickening or weak points (nodes) that cause the hair to break off easily. The result is defective, abnormally fragile hair.
An abnormally increased tendency to fractures of bones caused by an abnormal reduction in bone strength that is generally associated with an increased risk of fracture.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against a 60-kd peptide contained in the liver cytosolic fraction.
Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms.

This term applies if one or more of the distal phalanges of the hand are either partially duplicated, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance of the phalanges, or completely duplicated.
A type of cyclophoria (latent strabismus in which the occluded eye wheel-rotates on dissociation.) in which the upper poles of the globes are rotated outward (laterally) to each other.

A type of urinary cast that contain bacteria. Bacterial casts can be difficult to identify and can be distinguished from other types of casts using phase contrast microscopy. Bacterial casts are diagnostic of acute pyelonephritis or intrinsic renal infection.
Abnormally small size of one or more of the epiphyses of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms.
A secondary ossification center in the proximal phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
Increased volume of dental pulp of permanent molar.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the first metatarsal.
An abnormality of the distal phalanx of the thumb in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 5th finger of the hand.
Punctate opacification (reduced transparency) of the corneal stroma.
Bluish discoloration of the skin and mucosa due to poor circulation or inadequate oxygenation of arterial or capillary blood.
A structural anomaly of the adjacent structures (i.e., adnexa) of the eye, defined as the lacrimal apparatus, the extraocular muscles and the eyelids, eyelashes, eyebrows and the conjunctiva.
Abnormal response to ristocetin as manifested by increased aggregation of platelets upon addition of low-dose ristocetin to platelet-rich plasma.
An abnormal pupil shape that is elliptical, i.e., egg-like.
Abnormal concentration of sebacic acid in the urine.
A benign epithelial skin tumor manifesting as a slightly elevated circular plaque or nodule with a red, pink or brown color and a diameter up to 22 mm.
An abnormality of the morphology or counts of the cells that make up the immune system.
A sensation of tightness in the knee joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

A genital phenotype that is not clearly assignable to a single gender. Ambiguous genitalia can be evaluated using the Prader scale: Prader 0: Normal female external genitalia. Prader 1: Female external genitalia with clitoromegaly. Prader 2: Clitoromegaly with partial labial fusion forming a funnel-shaped urogenital sinus. Prader 3: Increased phallic enlargement. Complete labioscrotal fusion forming a urogenital sinus with a single opening. Prader 4: Complete scrotal fusion with urogenital opening at the base or on the shaft of the phallus. Prader 5: Normal male external genitalia. The diagnosis of ambiguous genitalia is made for Prader 1-4.
Both lungs have three lobes. Normally, the left lung has two lobes, whereas the right lung has three lobes.
The presence of reduced numbers of intrahepatic bile duct than normal.
Increase in bulk of the ala nasi.
Underdevelopment of the heel bone.
A form of polydactyly in which the extra digit or digits are localized on the side of the fifth finger or fifth toe.
A deviation from the normal straight shape of the first metacarpal.
An abrupt loss of heart function.
Additional scrotum, or part of a scrotum in an abnormal location.
Patchy increase in bone density of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger.
A secondary ossification center in the proximal phalanx of the fifth finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
Mutliple skin lesions resembling those characteristic of the disease lichen planus. These lesions are violaceous (reddish-purple). shiny, isolated, flat-topped papules and plaques.

A malignant bone tumor that usually develops during adolescence and usually affects the long bones including the tibia, femur, and humerus. The typical symptoms of osteosarcoma comprise bone pain, fracture, limitation of motion, and tenderness or swelling at the site of the tumor.
Conjunctival icterus is a condition where there is yellowing of the whites of the eyes. This is most commonly seen in patients who have liver disease.
Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the perineal region.
Presence of IgG antibodies in the dermoepidermal junction that are dsitributed in a linear pattern. This feature can be appreciated by immunofluorescence microscopy.
A secondary ossification center in the middle phalanx of the fourth finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
An abnormal reduction in numbers of all blood cell types (red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets).

A functional defect characterized by reduced total lung capacity (TLC) not associated with abnormalities of expiratory airflow or airway resistance. Restrictive lung disease may be caused by alterations in lung parenchyma or because of a disease of the pleura, chest wall, or neuromuscular apparatus.

Height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the midline more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the frontal view (subjective).
Positioning of the anterior surface of the ear lobe in a more coronal plane than the remainder of the ear.
A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more phalanges of the fourth toe.

The primitive reflexes are a group of behavioural motor responses which are found in normal early development, are subsequently inhibited, but may be released from inhibition by cerebral, usually frontal, damage. They are thus part of a broader group of reflexes which reflect release phenomena, such as exaggerated stretch reflexes and extensor plantars. They do however involve more complex motor responses than such simple stretch reflexes, and are often a normal feature in the neonate or infant.
Uncontrolled episodes of crying, without apparent motivating stimuli.
An anomaly of the rhythm or depth of breathing.
Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
A deformity of the elbow in which there is a deviation of the forearm toward the midline of the body.
Presence of cysts at the corticomedullary junction of the kidney in combination with tubulointerstitial fibrosis.
The J wave is a positive convex deflection that occurs at the junction of the QRS complex and ST segment, the J-point.
Abnormal platelet response to ADP as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of ADP.
Deposition of fibrillar material that can be found on all anterior segment structures bathed by aqueous humor.
The presence of megakaryocytes in the bone marrow whose nuclei are less lobulated than expected for the size of the nucleus.
A type of neutropenia that is observed in the presence of granulocyte-specific antibodies.
Short or anteriorly attached lingual frenulum, associated with limited mobility of the tongue.
An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of any of the tarsal bones, seven bones of the foot comprising the calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, and the cuneiform bones.
Extension of the ridge of the crus helix across the ear and connection of the crus to the antihelix.
An elevated level of propionylcarnitine in the circulation. Propionylcarnitine is present in high abundance in the urine of patients with Methylmalonyl-CoA mutase (MUT) deficiency.
An increased density in the cranial sutures following obliteration.
Complete absence of any auricular structures.

Heterophorias are latent deviations that are controlled by fusion. In certain circumstances (specific visual tasks, fatigue, illness, etc.), fusion can no longer be maintained and decompensation occurs.

An abnormality of the distal phalanx of the fifth finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

Situs inversus of thoracic and abdominal viscera with the heart remaining normally situated on the left; usually associated with congenital cardiac abnormalities such as transposition of the great vessels and/or spleen defects including asplenia or polysplenia.
Fusiform collagen fibers with abnormally long spacing (exceeding 100 nm) between electron-dense bands.

A failure to achieve the ability to walk at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children learn to walk in a series of stages, and learn to walk short distances independently between 12 and 15 months.
An increased susceptibility to pneumonia as manifested by a history of recurrent episodes of pneumonia.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:699014000 UMLS:C1859117 UMLS:C0876973 UMLS:C0694550 SNOMEDCT_US:128601007 UMLS:C0748140

?def: Congenital lack, i.e., aplasia of the diaphragm.
An increased concentration of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate aldolase in the serum.
Distortion of the course of the normal folds of the ear and the appearance of supernumerary crura and folds.

A congenital defect of the macula distinct from coloboma associated with optic fissure closure defects. Macular coloboma is characterized by a sharply defined, rather large defect in the central area of the fundus that is oval or round, and coarsely pigmented.
Deterioration or loss of the tissues of the saccule of the vestibule.

A developmental malformation of the occipital bone and upper end of the cervical spine, in which the latter appears to have pushed the floor of the occipital bone upward such that there is an abnormal flattening of the skull base.
The presence of atheromas or atherosclerotic plaques in the aorta.
Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of cells, which may result in the expansion of a cell population.
Presence of elevated levels of ketone bodies in the body.
A neurological anomaly with gross overeating associated with an abnormally strong desire or need to eat.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:72405004 SNOMEDCT_US:58424009 UMLS:C0020505 SNOMEDCT_US:267023007 MSH:D006963 UMLS:C0232461

?def: The presence of inflammatory cells such as lymphocytes and macrophages in the vitreous.

Apical hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (AHCM) is diastolic dysfunction due to abnormal stiffness of the left ventricle during diastole, with resultant impaired ventricular filling. In AHCM thickened apical segments produce a crowded, spade-shaped, small apical cavity.
A tumor that arises from an element of the autonomic nervous system.

An abnormality of the middle phalanx of the third finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
An increased concentration of prostate specific antigen (PSA) in the circulation.
Habitual clasping and squeezing of the hands.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a serine family amino acid in the blood circulation.
A subset of motor impersistence, defined as the inability to perform more than two of the simple voluntary acts simultaneously, such as closing the eyes and protruding the tongue.
Decreased density/number and/or decreased diameter of medial eyebrow hairs.
An abnormality of a lingual tonsil.
Increased concentration of total (conjugated and unconjugated) bilirubin in the blood.
An abnormal appearance or structure of the ring of pigmented skin that surrounds the nipple.
An abnormality of the arm.
Linear vertical groove in the midline of the forehead, extending from hairline to glabella.

An abnormality of the C-shaped rings of hyaline cartilage, normally 16 to 20 in number, that occupy the anterior two-thirds of the circumference of the trachea (the posterior portion of the ring is completed by fibrous and smooth muscle tissue).
An abnormally reduced number of granulocytes in the blood.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the genitourinary system.

Characteristic neurologic anomaly resulting form degeneration of dopamine-generating cells in the substantia nigra, a region of the midbrain, characterized clinically by shaking, rigidity, slowness of movement and difficulty with walking and gait.
A type of decreased nerve conduction velocity that affects the motor neuron.
Excessive, increased hair growth located in the region of the forehead and temple.
Exotropia in an individual who has previously had esotropia or esophoria.
Hair that lacks the lustre (shine or gleam) of normal hair.
A bone tumor composed of cellular spindle-cell stroma containing scattered multinucleated giant cells resembling osteoclasts.
An abnormality of a risorius muscle.
Underdevelopment of the pharynx.
A type of urinary cast composed of cells incorporated in a protein matrix. The cells can be those found in the urinary sediment (erythrocytes, leuklocytes, renal tubular epithelial cells).

Infiltration of eosinophils in the stomach mucosa, that is diagnosed by an upper endoscopy and microscopy that shows more than 20 eosinophils per high-power field in association with peripheral eosinophilia and the absence of secondary cause of eosinophilia.
A reduced ability of the skin of the fingertips to wrinkle when exposed to stimuli such as soaking in water or application of EMLA cream (the fingertip remains smooth).
A kind of anemia in which the volume of the red blood cells is reduced.
Cyclic neutropenia arising from an impaired proliferation and maturation of myeloid progenitor cells in the bone marrow.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the pancreas.

The shoulder, or pectoral, girdle is composed of the clavicles and the scapulae. Shoulder-girdle weakness refers to lack of strength of the muscles attaching to these bones, that is, lack of strength of the muscles around the shoulders.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger.
Phocomelia affecting only the lower limbs.
A focal dystonia of the fingers, hand, and/or forearm that appears when the affected person attempts to do a task that requires fine motor movements such as writing or playing a musical instrument.
An increase in size of the ventricular system of the brain.
Ossification affecting the set of cartilages of larynx.
Hypergranulosis is an increased thickness of the stratum granulosum.
A dislocation of the head of the radius from its socket in the elbow joint in an ulnar direction.
A type of third degree heart block in which the escape rhythm arises at a relatively low part of the conduction system (below the atrioventricular node), which produces a wide QRS complex.
A state of exceeding restlessness and excessive motor activity associated with mental distress or a feeling of inner tension.
Thickening of the heart walls in both ventricles.
Divergence of the longitudinal axis of the hand at the wrist in a posterior (ulnar) direction (i.e., towards the little finger).
An elevation of circulating IgG level predominantly related to an elevation of one of the four IgG subtypes.
Impaired egress of mature neutrophils from bone marrow causing neutropenia.
Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of substances in red blood cells.
A type of polymicrogyria with a gradient of severity (anterior more severe than posterior) extending from frontal poles posteriorly to precentral gyrus and inferiorly to frontal operculum.
Decreased cell membrane concentration of thromboxane A2 receptor that is stimulated by thromboxane A2 (TBXA2).
Underdevelopment of the vestibular nerve.
Proliferation of astrocytes in the area of a lesion of the central nervous system.
Elastic fibers in the dermis exhibit an increased number of breaks associated with disorganization of the structure of the elastic fibers.
Failure of cortisol levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the corticotropin releasing hormone stimulation test.
Excessive, increased hair growth located in the facial region.
The presence of asymmetrical breasts.
Loss of round patches of scalp hair.

Any structural abnormality of the pyramidal tract, whose chief element, the corticospinal tract, is the only direct connection between the brain and the spinal cord. In addition to the corticospinal tract, the pyramidal system includes the corticobulbar, corticomesencephalic, and corticopontine tracts.
Longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter visible along the occipital cortex.
Abnormally increased variability in the size of platelets.
Increased level of IgE antibody against house dust mites, a common allergen.
A type of posterior cortical cataract characterized by dense lenticular opacities.

A deviation from the normal concentration of free triiodothyronine (T3) in the blood circulation. A proportion of T3 is bound to plasma proteins in the blood, including mainly thyroxine binding globulin, transthyretin, and albumin. T3 that is not bound to a protein is referred to as free T3.
Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disc (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).
Any structural anomaly of the hypothalamus.
A chronic loss of wrist joint motion on one side only.
Increase in mass of the tunica media of the arteries in the pulmonary circulation.
A decreased concentration of potassium(1+) in the urine.
An abnormal shape of the lens.
Skin that splits easily with minimal injury.
Downbeat nystagmus is a type of fixation nystagmus with the fast phase beating in a downward direction. It generally increases when looking to the side and down and when lying prone.
Pectus excavatum (defect of the chest wall characterized by depression of the sternum) affecting primarily the inferior region of the sternum.

A morphological abnormality of the scapula in which there is a flat (horizontal) inferior edge of the scapula. The entire scapula is said to resemble a square, leading to the designation sqaring of the scapula (in Figure 1 of PMID:24706940 the scapulae have a roughly rectangular shape).
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphyses of the 4th finger.
An abnormality of the helix. The helix is the outer rim of the ear that extends from the insertion of the ear on the scalp (root) to the termination of the cartilage at the earlobe.
Episodic fever that recurs at regular intervals.

An anomalous response to the corticotropin releasing hormone (CRH) stimulation test. Normally,CRH is released by the hypothalamus to induce adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) release by the anterior pituitary. In the stimulation test, CRH is administered intravenously and ACTH and cortisol are measured at intervals.
Displacement or malalignment of joints.
Increased concentration of glycerol in the blood.
An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the aortic arch.
Auras with sensation of odor, usually disagreeable.

One of the three types of glia cells that, with the nerve cells, compose the central nervous system and are characterized by sheetlike processes that wrap around individual axons to form the myelin sheath of nerve fibers.

Auras with abdominal discomfort including nausea, emptiness, tightness, churning, butterflies, malaise, pain, and hunger; sensation may rise to chest or throat. Some phenomena may reflect ictal autonomic dysfunction.
A condition associated with a limitation of the horizontal ocular movement with retraction of the globe and narrowing of the palpebral fissure on adduction
Any structural anomaly of the cortex of the cerebellum.
Stiffness of the limbs (acondition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm) occurring in an asymmetric pattern.
Ectopic deposition of calcium salts found in the gingiva.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand.
A benign central bone tumor composed of fibrous connective tissue within which bone is formed.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:25603007 SNOMEDCT_US:302862001 SNOMEDCT_US:80699009 SNOMEDCT_US:302863006 UMLS:C0206640 MSH:D018214

?def: A cerebrovascular accident (stroke) that occurs because of thromboembolism.

Stenosis of the cerebral aqueduct (also known as the mesencephalic duct, aqueductus mesencephali, or aqueduct of Sylvius), which connects the third cerebral ventricle in the diencephalon to the fourth ventricle, which is between the pons and cerebellum.
Complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of fifth toe.
A functional anomaly of the eye.
Acute occurrence of a dissection (tear within the tunica intima and entry of blood into the tunica media) of a coronary artery.
The presence of a hernia in the abdominal wall.
An increase in circulating IgM characterized by two or more bands in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase.
The occurrence of repeated episodes of generalized muscular hypotonia.
Insufficient production of steroid hormones (primarily cortisol) by the adrenal glands.
Vestigial vitreous gel occupying the immediate retrolental space and minimal to no discernable gel in the central vitreous cavity, giving the appearance of an empty vitreous cavity.
Maxillary teeth cover the mandibular teeth when biting to an increased degree.
?xrefs: UMLS:C1305740 UMLS:C0266063 UMLS:C0266067 SNOMEDCT_US:251293001 SNOMEDCT_US:63783001 SNOMEDCT_US:10816007 SNOMEDCT_US:60476005 MSH:D057887

?def: An elevated level of insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF1) in the blood circulation.
Impaired ability to recognize letters or numbers drawn by an examiner's fingertip on the patient's skin (the patients eyes are closed or covered throughout this examination).
An anomaly that is characterized progressive airflow obstruction that is only partly reversible, inflammation in the airways, and systemic effects or comorbities.
Epiphysis of the 1st metacarpal having multiple bony fragments.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the skeleton.
Cyclodeviation is defined as the rotation of an eyeball along the anteroposterior axis and cyclotropia as a misalignment of cyclodeviation between the two eyes.
Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger with another bone.
A fourth finger with short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Bending or curvature of a fourth toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).
Deposition of calcium salts in point-like foci within the anterior portion of one or more ribs.

A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 3rd finger. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.
A defect in the understanding of complex motor commands and in the execution of certain learned movements, i.e., deficits in the cognitive components of learned movements.
An outward deviation of the foot at the talocalcaneal or subtalar joint.
A type of cirrhosis characterized by the presence of large regenerative nodules.

Any deviation from normal in the amount of uptake on the radioactive iodine uptake (RAIU) test, which utilizes a radioisotope of iodine to measure how much iodine the thyroid gland absorbs from the blood. The radioactive marker is measured 4-6 hours and in some cases also 24 hours after administration of the radioactive marker.
An abnormality in the production or cellular release of interferons (a class of cytokines).

Fracture or fragmentation at the lateral portion of the metaphysis of a long bone. The radiographic appearance is that of a small corner of metaphysis separated from the metaphyseal edge by thin linear radiolucency. This feature can be observed in child abuse but fragmented appearance of the metaphysis or facture-like lesions can also be detected in the setting of certain skeletal dysplasias.
Horizontal nystagmus dating from or present at birth.
Rhabdomyolysis induced by anesthesia.
An anomaly of the musculature of foot.
An abnormality of zinc ion homeostasis.
A partial or complete positional exchange between the penis and the scrotum, with positioning of the scrotum superior to the penis.
Sensorineural hearing impairment with childhood onset.
A heart murmur that occurs during diastole, i.e., in the time between S2 and the subsequent S1.
Testis in inguinal canal. That is, absence of one or both testes from the scrotum owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the testis.
Yellow-white intraretinal deposits in the macula typically associated with damaged outer blood-retina barrier and exudation of serous fluid and lipids from the retinal microvasculature.
An increase above the normal concentration of ribitol in the blood.
Premature loss of teeth not related to trauma or neglect.
An anomaly of the intracellular membrane complexes known as the dense tubular system.
Agenesis specifically affecting one of the classes incisor, premolar, or molar.
An abnormal reduction in quantity or strength of fetal movements.

Spasticity is manifested by increased stretch reflex which is intensified with movement velocity. This results in excessive and inappropriate muscle activation which can contribute to muscle hypertonia. Spastic gait is characterized by manifestations such as muscle hypertonia, stiff knee, and circumduction of the leg.
A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the lumen of the colon. That is, there is an abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the colon.
Abnormally small size of the epiphysis of the 1st metacarpal with respect to age-dependent norms.
Focal epileptiform discharges with spreading to the hemisphere on the same side of the brain.
Multiple circumscribed bony excrescences located in the ribs.
Complete duplication of the third proximal phalanx of hand.

The sacroiliac joint in the bony pelvis connects the sacrum and the ilium of the pelvis, which are joined by strong ligaments. The notch is located directly superior to the joint. This term refers to a reduction in the height of the notch.
A rudimentary tag of ear tissue often containing a core of cartilage and located just in back of the auricle (outer part of the ear).

An abnormality of the middle phalanx of the fifth finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
Apnea resulting from depression of the respiratory centers in the medulla oblongata. There is a lack of respiratory effort rather than obstruction of airflow.
Absence or underdevelopment of the fibula.
Complete lack of the M photopigment, which is replaced with the L photopigment. Affected individuals tend to confuse red and green.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.

A round circumscribed space within a lung that is surrounded by an epithelial or fibrous wall of variable thickness. A cyst usually has a thin and regular wall (less than 2 mm) and contains air, although some may contain fluid.
Increased susceptibility to bacterial infections of the skin, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infectious dermatitis.
Increased side-to-side width of the xiphoid process of the sternum.

A neural tube defect arises when the neural tube, the embryonic precursor of the brain and spinal cord, fails to close during neurulation. The cranial region (anencephaly) or the low spine (open spina bifida; myelomeningocele) are most commonly affected although, in the severe NTD craniorachischisis, almost the entire neural tube remains open, from midbrain to low spine.
Increased width of the columella.

An anomaly of the trabecular meshwork, which is the porelike structure surrounding the entire circumference of the anterior chamber at the base of the cornea and near the ciliary body. The trabecular mesh work is responsible for draining the aqueous humor into the canal of Schlemm.
Absence or abnormal closure of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture).
A reduction below normal concentration of estradiol in the circulation.
A deviation from the normal circulating concentration of ferritin. Ferritin concentration can be measured in serum or plasma.
Abnormal increase in size of the brainstem.
An unusually severe infection by a parainfluenza virus.
Cholangitis associated with mixed inflammatory infiltrates and the presence of fibrosis or sclerosis of the biliary tree.
A degree of pneumatization that is increased compared to age-related norms.
The presence of characteristic findings of denervation on electromyography (fibrillations, positive sharp waves, and giant motor unit potentials).
Increase in size of the tonsils, small collections of lymphoid tissue facing into the aerodigestive tract on either side of the back part of the throat.
A type of uniparental disomy in which the two different chromosomes (or chromosome segments) of the same parent are transmitted.

A group of phenotypically heterogeneous genetic disorders characterized by profound deficiencies of T- and B-cell function, which predispose the patients to both infectious and noninfectious complications.

A separation of the layers within the wall of the ascending aorta. Tears in the intimal layer result in the propagation of dissection (proximally or distally) secondary to blood entering the intima-media space.
An abnormally decreased proportion of naive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Increased frequency of urination.

A double outlet right ventricle with a subaortic ventritricular septal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that extends anterosuperiorly and are closely related to the pulmonary artery as well, are considered to be doubly committed. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
Atrial septal defect (ASD) is a congenital abnormality of the interatrial septum that enables blood flow between the left and right atria via the interatrial septum.
?xrefs: ICD-10:Q21.1 MSH:D006344 Fyler:2050 SNOMEDCT_US:70142008 UMLS:C0018817 SNOMEDCT_US:253366007 SNOMEDCT_US:405752007

?def: The presence of multiple hemangiomas in the choroid. These are generally reddish or orange or can have increased pigmentation maiking them difficult to distinguish from choroidal melanomas.

A height below that which is expected according to age and gender norms. Although there is no universally accepted definition of short stature, many refer to \short stature\" as height more than 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender (or below the 3rd percentile for age and gender dependent norms)."
A bilateral form of developmental dysplasia of the kidney.
Hyperplasia of the parathyroid gland.
Developmental hypoplasia of the mandible.
?xrefs: Fyler:4163 UMLS:C0240295 SNOMEDCT_US:32958008 UMLS:C1857130 UMLS:C0025990 MSH:D008844

?def: Any anomaly in the function of thrombocytes.
Hepatocytes (liver parenchymal cells) exhibit a bloated appearance because of expansion of the cytoplasm by accumulated material.
A type of speech characterized by the presence of an abnormally increased nasal airflow during speech.
Displacement of the urethral opening on the dorsal (superior) surface of the penis.
Keratinization of the bulbar conjunctiva near the limbus (corneoscleral junction), resulting in a raised spot.
An abnormality of the immune system.
Abnormally increased concentration of hydrogencarbonate in the urine.
