Two sided hypoplasia of the kidney.
Abnormality of the corpus callosum.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glycerol in the blood.
Accentuated, prominent philtral ridges giving rise to an exaggerated groove in the midline between the nasal base and upper vermillion border.
A secondary ossification center in the distal phalanx of the fourth finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
One or more digit that appears disproportionately short compared to the hand/foot, whereby either the entire digit or a specific phalanx is shortened.
A type of gliosis that occurs in the vicinity of injured neurons.

An accumulation of fluid in one or more of the perinephric spaces, which consist of the subcapsular, perirenal, anterior and posterior pararenal spaces. This abnormality can be demonstrated by cross-sectional imaging, particularly computed tomography.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the ring finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.
Severe distention of the kidney with dilation of the renal pelvis and calices.
The closed form of spina bifida with incomplete closure of the vertebra L5 with intact overlying skin.
A plaque is a solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter.

Pseudarthrosis, or \false joint\" of the tibia is the result of a developmental failure in the tibia progressing to spontaneous fracture and subsequent fibrous nonunion. The fracture is rarely present at birth but commonly develops during the first 18 months of life."
A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the trunk or the limbs.
Meeting of the medial eyebrows in the midline.
An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in abdominal aorta.
An involuntary and painless delay in the relaxation of skeletal muscle following contraction or electrical stimulation.
An abnormal flattening of the distal epiphysis of femur.
An abnormally decreased concentration of leukotriene C4 in the blood circulation.
A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the second to the fifth fingers that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

An abnormal functioning of phagocytosis. Phagocytosis is an elegant but complex process for the ingestion and elimination of pathogens, but it is also important for the elimination of apoptotic cells and hence fundamental for tissue homeostasis. Phagocytosis can be divided into four main steps: (i) recognition of the target particle, (ii) signaling to activate the internalization machinery, (iii) phagosome formation, and (iv) phagolysosome maturation.
An increased or decreased activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain.
Abnormality of the growth of the pubic hair. Pubic hair is part of the secondary sexual hair, which normally ensues during puberty.
An abnormality of the third finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
A softening and breaking down of skin resulting from prolonged exposure to moisture. Macerated skin becomes soft and wrinkly and takes on a whitish hue.
An increase in the number of eosinophils in myocardial tissue.
Benign congenital lesion of the supraauricular soft tissue consisting of a blind-ending narrow tube or pit.
A spinal cord hemangioma located in the lumbosacral spine region.
A systolic murmur that begins after S1 and ends before S2, typically with a crescendo-decrescendo pattern.
Increased concentration of methylmalonic acid in the urine.
Increased amount of peripheral myelination.
A murmur that occurs in the middle of the diastolic phase.
An excessive number of histiocytes (tissue macrophages).
An anomaly identified by motor evoked potentials (MEPs) in the leg.
Loss of elasticity of the upper and lower eyelids causing the skin to sag and bulge.
Difficulty with discriminating red and green hues.
Applies to an abnormality that affects the distal portions of limbs (hand, foot) and head (ears, nose).
An increased number and denisty of the trabeculae in the apex (tip) of the left ventricle.
Partial or total incontinence of bowel or bladder.
Enlargement of the diameter (cross-section) of a coronary artery as defined by a focal dilation of a segment at least 1.5 times larger than the reference vessel.
A depression located on a lip.
The progressive development of an abnormally large skull.
Reduced strength of the musculature of the distal extremities.
Atrophy of the muscles of the pelvic girdle (also known as hip girdle), i.e., the gluteal muscles, the lateral rotators, the adductors, the psoas major and the iliacus muscle.
An anomaly of the little toe.
A reduced ability to synthesize postvaccination antibodies against proteins in vaccines, as measured by antibody titer determination following vaccination.
Average platelet volume above the upper limit of the normal reference interval.
Posterior displacement of the tongue into the pharynx, i.e., a tongue that is mislocalised posteriorly.
The presence of tall, peaked P waves in EKG lead II.
An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the lip.
A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the scalp.
Localized loss of fat tissue.
Swelling related to fluid accumulation within the palate.
This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to bruising (purpura, petechiae, or ecchymoses).
Increase in size of one or more mesenteric lymph nodes.
The presence in the axillary region (armpit) of an increased number of freckles, small circular spots on the skin that are darker than the surrounding skin because of deposits of melanin.
An increase in the level of L-fucose in the urine.
Any structural anomaly of the sebaceous glands.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the thyroid gland.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the heart.
The presence of a meningioma, i.e., a benign tumor originating from the dura mater or arachnoid mater.
Truncal ataxia is a sign of ataxia characterized by instability of the trunk. It usually occurs during sitting.
The prolapse of the female urethra into the vagina.
The presence of an abnormally thin calvarium.

Cholangitis characterized by the presence of numerous polymorphonuclear cells around and within the wall as well as within the lumen of the ducts. This may involve ducts of any size and is occasionally associated with abscess formation (cholangitic abscess).
The combination of pendular nystagmus, head nodding, and torticollis.

A vascular malformation resulting from a developmental error of venous tissue composed of dysmorphic channels lined by flattened endothelium and exhibiting slow turnover. A venous malformation may present as a blue patch on the skin ranging to a soft blue mass. Venous malformations are easily compressible and usually swell in thewhen venous pressure increases (e.g., when held in a dependent position or when a child cries). They may be relatively localized or quite extensive within an anatomic region.
A lacy pattern or iris pigmentation that resembles the spokes of a bicycle wheel.
Fusion of the terminal/distal and middle phalanges of the 3rd finger.
The presence of small (ca. 0.5-1.0 mm) dilated blood vessels near the surface of the mucous membranes of the palate.
An anomaly of a finger.
A state of disinterestedness, listlessness, and indifference, resulting in difficulty performing simple tasks or concentrating.
A small, sac-like aneurysm (outpouching) of a cerebral blood vessel.
Abnormally decreased concentration of hydrogencarbonate in the urine.
An angulation of a digit at an interphalangeal joint in the plane of the palm (finger) or sole (toe).
Abnormally flat shape of the heads of the metatarsal bones.
Reduced strength of the muscles that lift or otherwise move the foot at the ankle.
Epileptiform discharges being identified at multiple locations in both hemispheres.
A hemorrhage occurring within the lung.

A congenital abnormality of the cerebral hemisphere chacterized by lack of gyrations (convolutions) of the cerebral cortex. Agyria is defined as cortical regions lacking gyration with sulci great than 3 cm apart and cerebral cortex thicker than 5 mm.
Reduction in diameter of the internal auditory canal.
Increased level of IgE antibody against fungus, such as molds like zygomycota, ascomycota and deuteromycota.
Enlargement of the adrenal gland.
Epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.
Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the fourth toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.
A small hole through the whole thickness of the retina.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:95690009 MSH:D012167 SNOMEDCT_US:232003005 UMLS:C0035321 SNOMEDCT_US:302888003 SNOMEDCT_US:40024006

?def: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fifth finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
EEG background activity at 4-5/second.

Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) whereby one of the two pulmonary artery branched does not arise from the common pulmonary trunk, but instead from the ductus arteriosus or directly from the aorta.
Gross dilatation of the vein of Galen, being fed by large anomalous vessel or vessels arising from the carotid or basilar circulation.
Underdevelopment of the abdominal musculature.
An abnormality of thyroid physiology (HP:0002926) characterized by increased levels of thyroxine without evidence of clinical thyroid disease.
Absence of a digit or of one or more phalanges of a toe.
Alteration of the normally smooth radiographic contour of phalanges producing an irregular appearance.
Pain in the jaw or ear induced by chewing or otherwise moving the jaw.
Abnormal levels of interferon gamma measured in the blood circulation.
Lack of formation of bone in the epiphysis of the humerus.
Immunohistochemistry shows accumulation of desmin protein in the muscle biopsy.

A form of watery eye associated with overproduction of tears due to reflex tearing in response to a local irritant (e.g. trichiasis or foreign body), chronic ocular surface disease (e.g. blepharitis) or systemic disease (e.g. thyroid eye disease).
Syndactyly with fusion of toes three to five.
Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in the neonatal period and affecting the entire musculature.
Abnormal coordination of muscles involved in speech.

Refractive error in which the vertical meridian is relatively hypermetropic and the horizontal meridian is relatively myopic (or ocular astigmatism in which the refractive power of the horizontal meridian is the greatest).
Groups of small caliber axons in peripheral nerve biospies indicative of axonal regeneration.
Weakness of the muscles of the arms.
Mitral annular calcification (MAC) results from progressive calcium deposition along and beneath the mitral valve annulus.
Eversion of a hollow organ and exposure, inside out, and protruded through the abdominal wall.
Increased thickness of the external ear.
A reduction of the distance between thoracolumbar vertebral pedicles.
An abnormality of the pulmonary lymphatic chain.
A cough that does not produce phlegm or mucus.
Developmental hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of third toe.
Hypercellularity due to increased number of cells within glomerular capillary lumina, causing narrowing of the lumina.
A kind of polydactyly characterized by the presence of a supernumerary toe or toes.
Partial or complete duplication of phalanx of fourth toe.
Abnormal twisting of arteries or veins.
Asymmetric head shape, which is usually a combination of unilateral occipital flattening with ipsilateral frontal prominence, leading to rhomboid cranial shape.
?xrefs: UMLS:C1450010 SNOMEDCT_US:254024005 MSH:D059041 UMLS:C0265529 UMLS:C4280807 UMLS:C4280598 UMLS:C4072830 UMLS:C4280597 SNOMEDCT_US:21850008 MSH:D049068

?def: A fixed reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids with short palpebral fissures on one side only.
Any abnormality of the size or morphology of the cornea.
A congenital cataract in which opacity is limited to layers of the lens external to the nucleus (i.e., the perinuclear region), i.e., between the nuclear and cortical layers of the lens.
Absence of thumb nail.
Increased inferior-superior length of the neck.
Cyclopia is a congenital abnormality in which there is only one eye. That eye is centrally placed in the area normally occupied by the root of the nose.

Any structural anomaly of a cerebral artery. The cerebral arteries comprise three main pairs of arteries and their branches, which supply the cerebrum of the brain. These are the anterior cerebral artery, the middle cerebral artery, and the posterior cerebral artery.
An anomaly of the amount or nature of abdominal sounds. Abdominal sounds (bowel sounds) are made by the movement of the intestines as they promote passage of abdominal contents by peristalsis.
An abnormality of the nasal dorsum, also known as the nasal ridge.
Any anomaly of distal epiphysis of phalanx of finger.
A functional anomaly of the natural killer cell.
A trigger is defined as an external factor that leads to the manifestation of a sign or symptom in a person with a susceptibility to developing that manifestation.
An abnormality of the Meninges, including any abnormality of the Dura mater, the Arachnoid mater, and the Pia mater.
Apparently small scrotum for age.
The presence of inflammatory cells in the aqueous humor of the anterior chamber of the eye.
Alkalosis due to excess loss of carbon dioxide from the body.
Adhesions between the iris and the lens.
A type of atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) where the are the accessory pathway is used for anterograde conduction and the atrioventricular node for retrograde conduction.
A morphological abnormality of the mouth in which the angle of the mouth is downturned. The oral commissures are positioned inferior to the midline labial fissure.
Onset prior to birth but after 8 weeks of gestation.

Loss of bone mass occurring beneath the periosteum (the periosteum is the connective-tissue membrane that surrounds all bones except at the articular surfaces). This process may create a serrated and lace-like appearance in periosteal cortical bone.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
Infections of the skin that happen multiple times.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of isoleucine in the blood circulation.
The presence of circulating autoantibodies to anticardiolipin in the mother.
Absence of the epiphyses of the metacarpal bones, which are normally located at the distal ends of the metacarpals.

Applied to a sign, symptom, or other manifestation that occurs multiple times at usually irregular intervals. The occurences are separated by an interval in which the sign, symptom, or manifestation is not present.
An atrophic scar (fibrous connective tissue resulting from incomplete healing of a wound) that has stretched (gotten wider), a manifestation of tissue fragility.
A reduction in the proportion of CD4 T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
An unpleasant sensory and emotional experience associated with actual or potential tissue damage, or described in terms of such damage.
An increase in the level of choline-containing compounds in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Abnormal results of a MRI for the heart.

Reduced ability of lexical discrimination, which refers to the process of distinguishing a stimulus word from other phonologically similar words. Lexical discrimination can be defined as the process of correctly identifying words in the mental lexicon to match the phonological input of a stimulus.
Absence of the middle phalanx of the ring (4th) finger.

A type of multifactorial inheritance governed by the simultaneous action of a few gene loci. It is recommended this term be used for traits governed by three loci, although it is noted that usage of this term in the literature is not uniform.
Decreased intensity of the patellar reflex (also known as the knee jerk reflex).
Inflammed tongue with hyperplastic (enlarged) fungiform papillae that is said to resemble a strawberry or raspberry.
An infection of the lung caused by environmental mycobacteria. SUch infections can occur in individuals with predisposing lung disease or immune disease.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.
Abnormally increased frequency of loose or watery bowel movements.
Congenital malformation of the thoracic wall with partial or total displacement of the heart outside the thoracic cavity. This feature is associated with sternal cleft or absence of the sternum.
A type of encephalopathy (brain disease, damage, or malfunction accompanied by an altered mental state) that is characterized by evidence of necrosis of brain tissue.
A reduction below the normal concentration of fibronectin the the blood circulation.
Mitral stenosis with congenital onset.
Lens of the eye is smaller than normal and spherically shaped.
Underdeveloped acetabulae.
The presence of a germ cell tumor of the cerebrum.
Absence or underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the middle phalanx of the little (5th) finger.
Abnormally short chordae tendineae of the mitral valve.
An excessive number of small gyri (convolutions) on the surface of the brain in the frontoparietal region.
Underdevelopment of the musculature of the upper arm, which may include the deltoid, the triceps, the biceps, and the brachioradialis.
An increased amount of bowel sounds.

This term applies if the proximal phalanx of the thumb is either small/hypoplastic or absent. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
A structural abnormality of an infra-orbital nerve. The infraorbital nerve arises from the maxillary branch of the trigeminal nerve and normally traverses the orbital floor in the infraorbital canal.
The eyebrows extend towards - or even all the way down to - the margin of the upper eyelid.
A decreased amount of hydroxyproline in the blood.

A midline anterior-posterior cleft of the epiglottis that involves at least two-thirds of the epiglottic leaf. It is a useful feature for clinical diagnosis because it appears to be very rare in syndromes other than Pallister-Hall-Syndrome and is also rare as an isolated malformation.
Underdevelopment of the deltoid muscle.
Presence of iris pigment epithelium on the anterior surface of the iris.
A defect in the ability to concentrate the urine.
A type of T-cell lymphoma in which cancerous T-cells may present in the blood (leukemia), lymph nodes (lymphoma), skin or in multiple areas.
A deviation from the normal straight form of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe.
Abnormality of the spatial relationship of the atria to other components of the heart.
Absence or underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the proximal phalanx of the little (5th) finger.
Excretion of peptides conjugated to sialic acid in the urine.
Congenital non-progressive ophthalmoplegia with multiple extraocular muscle restrictions. Typically, there is ptosis and variable degrees of restriction of horizontal and vertical eye movements.
Present in 5% to 29% of the cases.
Structural abnormality affecting one or more of the cranial nerves, which emerge directly from the brain stem.
The presence of verrucous, cobblestone-like papules and nodules in a region of skin that is said to have an appearance like that of cobblestones.
An abnormality of a blood vessel of the neck, including branches of the arterial and venous systems of the neck.
Telangiectasia (that is, the presence of small dilated superficial blood vessels) of the lips.
An abnormal anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.
Abnormal functionality of the cardiovascular system.
Decreased secretion of luteinizing hormone-releasing hormone by the hypothalamus.
Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the extremities.

Bradykinesia literally means slow movement, and is used clinically to denote a slowness in the execution of movement (in contrast to hypokinesia, which is used to refer to slowness in the initiation of movement).
The epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal surrounds the diaphysis, having a bracket-like form.
A concentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the aortic arch that involves the full circumference of the vessel wall.
A form of strabismus with one or both eyes deviated outward.

Scaphocephaly is a subtype of dolichocephaly where the anterior and posterior aspects of the cranial vault are pointed (boat-shaped). Scaphocephaly is caused by a precocious fusion of sagittal suture without other associated synostosis.
Insufficient amount of androgenic activity.
Ossification of hand bones is less advanced than would be expected according to age-adjusted norms.
Cephalgia, or pain sensed in various parts of the head, not confined to the area of distribution of any nerve.
A congenital defect in the occipital region of the skull, covered by skin of the scalp and containing meninges or remnants of glial or neural tissues.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a nitrogen compound in the blood circulation.

A chronic form of disseminated intravascular coagulation in which a persistent weak or intermittent activating stimulus is present and destruction and production of coagulation factors and platelets are balanced.
A state of moror restlessness, usually in the lower extremities, that is often but not always accompanied by a subjective sense of inner restlessness, an urge to move, and anxiety or dysphoria.
Failure of the foramen ovale to seal postnatally, leaving a potential conduit between the left and right cardiac atria.

A specific combination of heart defects with a primum atrial septal defect, cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet, and an inlet ventricular septal defect. There are two valve annuli and two valve orifices.

Projection of the tip of the dens more than 5 mm above a line joining the hard palate to the posterior lip of the foramen magnum (Chamberlain's line) or the tip of the dens is greater than 7 mm above McGregor's line (the back of the hard palate to the lowest point of the occipital squama).
Any deviation from the normal amount of the thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), which is produced by the anterior pituitary gland and stimulates the function of the thyroid gland.
A developmental defect consisting in the complete duplication of the first metatarsal bone.
A developmental defect characterized by absence of the retina.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glutamate in the blood circulation.
An unusually happy aspect over time which can also may be observed during inappropriate situations that should be causing for example distress, fear or anger.
An abnormality of a masseter muscle.
An abnormality in which the internal thoraco-abdominal organs demonstrate abnormal arrangement across the left-right axis of the body.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:24614000 SNOMEDCT_US:14821001 UMLS:C0266642 MSH:D059446 Fyler:0190 Fyler:190

?def: Abnormal response to epinephrine as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of epinephrine.
Absence of one or more epiphyses of the 4th finger.
Asymmetry of the posterior part of the skull.
The occurence of an elevated body temperature of the mother during pregnancy.
An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of any bone of the skeleton of foot.
Deficiency of factor XIII subunit A, leading to a reduced factor XIII activity. Activated Factor XIII cross-links fibrin polymers solidifying the clot.
Developmental hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 5th toe.
The presence of a cavernous hemangioma. A hemangioma characterized by large endothelial spaces (caverns) is called a cavernous hemangioma.
?xrefs: NCIT:C3086 MEDDRA:10055899 SNOMEDCT_US:56975005 SNOMEDCT_US:33377007 MSH:D006392 UMLS:C0018920 SNOMEDCT_US:416824008

?def: Neoplasm categorized according to type of histological abnormality.
Reduced bone mineral density of the femur.

Hordeola interna are acute purulent infections affecting the meibomian sebacious glands, often caused by staphylococcus infections. In contrast to chalazia (chronic epithelioid cell granulomatous inflammation of the meibomian gland caused by inflammation of a blocked meibomian gland), hordeola are extremely painfull and can cause extreme local swelling.
Agenesis of upper secondary incisor.
Increased level of amylase in the blood, an enzyme which helps digest glycogen and starch. It is produced mainly in the pancreas and salivary glands.
A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone can be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone.
An increased level of iron in liver tissues.
An increased concentration of lysine in the blood.
A type of dysharmonic skeletal maturation in which there is a delay in skeletal maturation whose degree differs markedly in different bones.
Feeding problem necessitating nasogastric tube feeding.

An abnormal phenomenon characterized by a classic tetrad of excessive daytime sleepiness with irresistible sleep attacks, cataplexy (sudden bilateral loss of muscle tone), hypnagogic hallucination, and sleep paralysis.
Abnormal development of large mammary glands in males resulting in breast enlargement.
A dermatosis characterized by thickened, hyperpigmented plaques, typically on the intertriginous surfaces and neck.
The presence of a carcinoma of the esophagus.
Glaucoma which forms during the early years of a child's life is called developmental or congenital glaucoma.
Pterygia are 'winglike' triangular membranes occurring in the neck, eyes, knees, elbows, ankles or digits.
Retinal exudate within the retinal tissue itself.
Rhabdomyolysis induced by a viral infection.

Absence of fine and sharp appearance of brows, nose, lips, mouth, and chin, usually because of rounded and heavy features or thickened skin with or without thickening of subcutaneous and bony tissues.
Delayed descent of the upper eyelid on downgaze. Also described by some authors as von Graefe sign.
A notched form of the helix of the ear. That is, a defect in the continuity of the helix, which may occur at any point along its length.
Increased number of calices of the kidney.
Acute progressive areflexic weakness and mild sensory changes resulting from myelin breakdown and axonal degeneration.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

The presence of foam cells, a type of macrophage that localizes to fatty deposits on blood vessel walls, where they ingest low-density lipoproteins and become laden with lipids, giving them a foamy appearance.
An abnormally increased concentration of the IgG3 subtype in the blood circulation.
A state of abnormally strong desire for sleep during the daytime.
Abnormal plane of direction of the heart from the base to the apex. Left sided is normal.
A distortion of the sense of taste, often characterized by the sensation of a metallic taste.

The sacroiliac joint in the bony pelvis connects the sacrum and the ilium of the pelvis, which are joined by strong ligaments. The notch is located directly superior to the joint. This term refers to a increase in the lateral dimension of the notch.
Hair whose growth is slower than normal.
Presence of multiple polyps in the duodenum.
Reduced superior to inferior length of the nasal septum.
Decreased addition of sialic acids to N-linked glycans.
A lack of strength of the proximal muscles of the legs.
Thinned, deficient, or excessively arched ala nasi.
Ultra-low vision but with retained ability to perceive the difference between light and dark.
An anomaly detectable in [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography (PET) brain scans. Glucose uptake measured with FDG-PET is a marker of neuronal metabolic activity.
An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the tubular part of the ascending aorta.

Pilomatricoma is an asymptomatic slowly growing benign cutaneous tumor, differentiating towards the hair matrix of the hair follicle. It is covered by normal or hyperemic skin, and usually varies in size from 0.5 to 3 cm.
A lack of bone mineralization of the vertebral bodies.
An abnormal reduction of the cell motility of neutrophils.
Reduced size of the Distal epiphysis of femur.
Any defect in the valve connecting the heart and the pulmonary artery.
Coarctation of the aorta is a narrowing or constriction of a long segment of the arch of the aorta.
A lateral deviation of the nail plate of the great toe along the longitudinal axis due to the lateral rotation of the nail matrix. The nail plate grows out in ridges.
Detection of benzodiazepine metabolites, primarily nordiazepam, oxazepam, and temazepam, in urine.
A congenital anomaly characterized by a joining (fusion) of two or more cervical vertebral bodies with one another.
Nail that appears thin when viewed on end.
Lack of strength of the proximal musculature occurring late in the clinical course.
Ocular abnormality characterised by premature degeneration of the vitreous and the retina that may be associated with increased risk of retinal detachment.

The patient stands with the feet placed together and balance and is asked to close his or her eyes. A loss of balance upon eye closure is a positive Romberg sign and is interpreted as indicating a deficit in proprioception.
Abnormal formation of the keratinocytes of the epidermis characterized by persistence of nuclei, incomplete formation of keratin, and moistness and swelling of the keratinocytes.
Increase in size of a peripheral nerve. This finding can be appreciated by palpation along the axis of the nerve.
A Malignant mesothelioma originating from cells of the pleura (the thin layer of mesothelium lining the lungs). Pleural mesothelioma is the most common form of mesothelioma.

Autism is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by impaired social interaction and communication, and by restricted and repetitive behavior. Autism begins in childhood. It is marked by the presence of markedly abnormal or impaired development in social interaction and communication and a markedly restricted repertoire of activity and interest. Manifestations of the disorder vary greatly depending on the developmental level and chronological age of the individual (DSM-IV).

An abnormality of histiocytes, in which the cells take on a sea blue appearance due to abnormally increased lipid content. Histiocytes are a type of macrophage. Sea-blue histiocytes are typically large macrophages from 20 to 60 micrometers in diameter with a single eccentric nucleus whose cytoplasm if packed with sea-blue or blue-green granules when stained with Wright-Giemsa.
An elevated activity of the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase in serum.
Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the tunica media of arteries.

These are spontaneous firing action potentials stimulated by needle movement of an injured muscle fiber. There is propagation to, but not past, the needle tip. This inhibits the display of the negative deflection of the waveform.
The presence of abnormal electromyographic patterns indicative of myopathy, such as small-short polyphasic motor unit potentials.
A type of chronic kidney disease with moderately reduced glomerular filtration rate (GFR 30-59 mL/min/1.73 m2).
Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of middle finger, seen on x-rays as a broad and/or bifid phalanx.
Grey-green or brownish-pigmented ring in the deep epithelial layers at the outer border of the cornea.
Complete duplication of the distal phalanx of second toe.
Decreased cell membrane concentration of glycoprotein VI.
An excessive upward convexity of the lateral clavicle.
A ventricular septal defect that lies beneath the semilunar valve(s) in the conal or outlet septum.
The absence of the normal curvature of the vertebral column.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against topoisomerase I.
Small expansion of the helical fold at the junction of the superior and descending portions of the helix.
A type of megaloblastic anemia that improves upon administration of pyrimidine supplements such as uridylic acid and cytidylic acid.

An abnormal increase in intracellular lipid droplets In a muscle. The number and size of these drops can increase with somd disorders of lipid metabolism affecting muscle. See pmid 20691590 for histological images.
Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disc is 0.8 (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).
An abnormality of the clivus, which is the inclined bony region of the posterior cranial fossa located between the sella turcica and the foramen magnum.
Abnormal concentration of urate in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

Talipes calcaneovalgus is a flexible foot deformity (as opposed to a rigid congenital vertical talus foot deformity) that can either present as a positional or structural foot deformity depending on severity and/or causality. The axis of calcaneovalgus deformity is in the tibiotalar joint, where the foot is positioned in extreme hyperextension. On inspection, the foot has an \up and out\" appearance, with the dorsal forefoot practically touching the anterior aspect of the ankle and lower leg."

A type of bladder dysfunction caused by neurologic damage. Neurogenic bladder can be flaccid or spastic. Common manifestatios of neurogenic bladder are overflow incontinence, frequency, urgency, urge incontinence, and retention.
A medical history of a fetus or child born to a mother with an autoimmune disease.
Underdevelopment of the arch of aorta.
Typical absence seizures starting before the age of 4 years.

An abnormal distribution in the number of CD56 bright NK cells, as measured by flow cytometry. CD56 the adhesion molecule mediating homotypic adhesion, and is used as a functional marker for NK cells.

Lymphangiomas are rare congenital malformations consisting of focal proliferations of well-differentiated lymphatic tissue in multi cystic or sponge like structures. Lymphangioma is usually asymptomatic due to its soft consistency but compression of adjacent structures can be seen due to the mass effect of a large tumor.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:254836000 NCIT:C8965 MSH:D008202 SNOMEDCT_US:69044001 SNOMEDCT_US:253057002 UMLS:C0024221 SNOMEDCT_US:400178008

?def: Fragile, easily breakable hair, i.e., with reduced tensile strength.
An abnormality of the knee joint or surrounding structures.
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the inferior mesenteric artery .
The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells. Inclusion bodies are aggregates (deposits) or stainable material, usually misfolded proteins.
A type of dystonia (abnormally increased muscular tone causing fixed abnormal postures) that affects muscles of the arms.
Increase in diameter of the veins located underneath the skin of the abdomen.
Uhl anomaly of the right ventricle refers to the almost complete absence of right ventricular myocardium, normal tricuspid valve, and preserved septal and left ventricular myocardium.
An abnormality of the lower urinary tract.
A congenital disorder of the aortic valve in which the orifice of the valve fails to develop.

The bone-in-bone sign is a radiographic finding produced by increased sclerosis (abnormally dense bone) occurring intermittently with zones of relatively normal bone density. This term should be used to describe such a finding in the carpal bones.
An increased concentration of carnosine in the urine.
Dilation and elongation of the duodenum with hypertrophy of all layers of the duodenum.
A decrease in the level of erythritol in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Any abnormality of bones of the arms or legs.
A disease or lesion affecting the muscles of the thorax.
Absence of the tarsal bones.
Decreased distance from the nasal tip to the nasal base.
A reduced ability to synthesize postvaccination antibodies against a pneumococcus antigen, as measured by antibody titer determination following vaccination.
Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the superior oblique muscle.

A type of chest pain that arises in the or under the left breast and often described as throbbing, stabbing, or burning, and lasting hours or longer. The pain may arise with or after effort, and may spread to the left arm or left side of the neck.
Absence of fleshy non-cartilaginous tissue inferior to the tragus and incisura.
A teratoma arising in the sacro-coccygeal region.
A malignant epithelial tumor with a glandular organization that originates in the intestines.
An abnormality of a mylohyoid muscle.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the colon.
Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the proximal metaphysis of the femur.
Extravasation of chyle into the peritoneal cavity.
A bilateral vestibular Schwannoma (acoustic neurinoma).
An abnormality of the nasolacrimal drainage system, which serves as a conduit for tear flow from the external eye to the nasal cavity.
An abnormality of the ovulation cycle.
A congenital anomaly characterized by the presence of supernumerary fingers or toes.
Increased distance between the attachments of the alae nasi to the face.

A type of abnormal location of the ears in which the position of the ears is characterized by posterior rotation (the superior part of the ears is rotated towards the back of the head, and the inferior part of the ears towards the front).
Aplasia, that is failure to develop, of the ovary.
Impaired proliferation and expansion of a T cell population following activation by an antigenic stimulus.

An abnormality of the premaxilla (the embryonic structure that forms the anterior part of the maxilla) causing it to appear relatively large in size compared to the other parts of the maxilla or other facial structures.
A kind of bronchopulmonary sequestration that is incorporated into the normal surrounding lung.
Abnormal displacement or malposition of the anus.
An increased concentration of an amino acid in the urine.
Abnormal cell death involving muscle fibers usually associated with break in, or absence of, muscle surface fiber membrane and resulting in irreversible damage to muscle fibers.
Increased level of IgE antibody against animal dander, tiny scales shed from animal skin or hair, such as from pet dogs or cats.

Gustatory lacrimation results from an aberrant innervation of fibres from the seventh cranial nerve to the pterygopalatine ganglion which are destined originally for the submandibular ganglion. This aberrant innervation leads to uncontrollable tearing while eating or in anticipation of a meal.
Developmental hypoplasia of the fallopian tube.
An abnormality of any of the muscles of facial expression, which are innervated by the seventh (VII) cranial nerve and control facial expression.

Reduced activity of coagulation factor X. The extrinsic and intrinsic pathways converge at factor X (fX). The extrinsic pathway activates fX by means of d factor VII with its cofactor, tissue factor. The intrinsic pathway activates fX by means of the tenase complex (Ca2+ and factors VIIIa, IXa and X) on the surface of activated platelets. Factor Xa in turn activates prothrombin (factor II) to thrombin (factor IIa).
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the celiac artery.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of pyruvate-family amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormality of the fetal circulation system or fetal echocardiogram.
Atrophy of the intrinsic muscle groups of the hand, comprising the thenar and hypothenar muscles; the interossei muscles; and the lumbrical muscles.
An abnormally low concentration of serum alpha-fetoprotein as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

An abnormality of the middle phalanx of the fourth finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
An abnormal concentration of gastrin in the blood.
Increase in size of the folds of skin between the outer labia.
The presence of many cysts in the kidney.
Low blood glucose is accompanied by elevated levels of ketone bodies in the body.
A deviation from the normal concentration of dehydroepiandrosterone in the circulation.
A structural abnormality of the sperm mid-piece.
Absence or developmental hypoplasia of the sweat glands.

Pulsatile tinnitus is generally classified a kind of objective tinnitus, meaning that it is not only audible to the patient but also to the examiner on auscultation of the auditory canal and/or of surrounding structures with use of an auscultation tube or stethoscope. Usually, pulsatile tinnitus is heard as a lower pitched thumping or booming, a rougher blowing sound which is coincidental with respiration, or as a clicking, higher pitched rhythmic sensation. Pulsatile tinnitus may be associated with vascular abnormalities such as arterioevenous shunts or glomus tumors or the jugular vein, arterial bruits related to a high-riding carotid artery (close to the auditory areas) or carotid stenosis, or venous abnormalities such as a dehiscent jugular bulb or to hypertension. Finally, in some patients, mechanical abnormalities such a spatulous eustachian tubes, palatomyoclonus (small spasms of muscles in the soft palate area), or idiopathic stapedial muscle spasm may represent the underlying cause of pulsatile tinnitus.
Reduced ability to perceive painful stimuli.
Defective structure, size or content of alpha granules, platelet organelles that contain several growth factors destined for release during platelet activation at sites of vessel wall injury.
Immunohistochemistry shows accumulation of valosin-containing protein in the muscle biopsy.

A condition which is considered to be due to the subsequent atrophy and disappearance in fetal life of an initially normal testis. In the presence of spermatic cord structures is evidence of the presence of the testis in early intrauterine life. When associated with a blind-ending spermatic cord, this entity is named as his absence of a testis in an otherwise normal 46XY male is usually unilateral and is assumed to be a consequence of intrauterine or perinatal torsion or infarction.
Increased width of the skin of vermilion border region of upper lip.

An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the eye that is worse in certain directions of gaze and during prolonged gaze holding.
Presence of only 10 (instead of the usual 12) pairs of ribs.
Inflammation of the urinary bladder.
Abnormal difficulty in staying asleep. Affected individuals tend to wake up at night and have difficulty returning to sleep.
Bilateral lack of development of the lungs.
Horizontal nystagmus made apparent by looking to the right or to the left.
Any functional anomaly of the liver.

Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
The presence of a hypoplastic gallbladder.
An abnormality of the face.

?def: Abnormal (non-physiological) constriction of the pupil.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the temporal region.
A urodynamic anomaly characterized by bladder outlet obstruction from detrusor muscle contraction with concomitant involuntary urethral sphincter activation.
Abnormally increased levels of threonine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Small areas of bleeding (hemorrhage) under the fingernail or toenail.
The anterior fontanelle generally ossifies by around the 18th month of life. A persistent open anterior fontanelle is diagnosed if closure is delayed beyond this age.

Pheochromocytomas (also known as chromaffin tumors) produce, store, and secrete catecholamines. Pheochromocytomas usually originate from the adrenal medulla but may also develop from chromaffin cells in or about sympathetic ganglia. A common symptom of pheochromocytoma is hypertension owing to release of catecholamines.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:85583005 SNOMEDCT_US:302835009 SNOMEDCT_US:399343007 NCIT:C3326 MSH:D010673 UMLS:C0031511

?def: An anomaly of alpha or dense granules or platelet lysosomes.
The joint between the first metatarsal and the proximal phalanx of the first (big) toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.

Repeated, individually recognizable, intermittent movements or movement fragments that are almost always briefly suppresable and are usually associated with awareness of an urge to perform the movement.
A type of hearing impairment affecting primarily the middle frequencies of sound (1000 Hz to 3000 Hz).
A functional anomaly of the superior or inferior rectus muscle.

Abnormally increased level of blood lactate (2-hydroxypropanoic acid). Lactate is produced from pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase during normal metabolism. The terms lactate and lactic acid are often used interchangeably but lactate (the component measured in blood) is strictly a weak base whereas lactic acid is the corresponding acid. Lactic acidosis is often used clinically to describe elevated lactate but should be reserved for cases where there is a corresponding acidosis (pH below 7.35).
Head is bent in the posterior direction in a permanent fashion.
Undergrowth of the outer labia.
An increased concentration of E selectin in the blood circulation.
A type of cyclotropia (torsion of one or both eye about the visual axis of the eyes) in which the upper poles of the globes are rotated inward (medially) to each other.
Reduced velocity and acceleration in the pupillary light response.
The ability of the finger joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.
Underdevelopment of the fibula.
Muscular atrophy of distal arm muscles.
Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen.
Any abnormality in the proportion T cells subsets relative to the total number of T cells.
Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the lateral rectus muscle.
Bleeding into the biliary tree.
An acquired language impairment of some or all of the abilities to produce or comprehend speech and to read or write.
This term describes abnormality of the white matter of the cerebrum resulting from damage to the myelin sheaths of nerve cells.
Abnormally small dimension of the maxilla (upper jaw) relative to the mandible (lower jaw).
Overproduction of the mineralocorticoid aldosterone by the adrenal cortex.
A condition in which the superior portion of the helix is folded over to a lesser degree than normal.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the nervous system.
Dorsiflexion of the big toe, sometimes accompanied by fanning of the other toes, elicited by stroking along the medial side of the tibia (the normal response would be no movement of the big toe).
Intrauterine growth retardation that is at least 3 standard deviations (SD) below average, but not as low as 4 SD, corrected for sex and gestational age.

Defects in the lysosomal glycosidases or specific co-activators, result in accumulation of the substrates, such as glycosphingolipids, including gangliosides in GM1 gangliosidosis (Tay-Sachs disease) and GM2 gangliosidosis (Sandhoff disease).
Impaired production of memory cells, the B cells that persist for years or an entire lifetime and which confer rapid and enhanced response to secondary challenge.
A chronic loss of elbow joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevent normal movement of the joints of the elbow.
Reduced fluid intake (drinking) in a clinical situation where the plasma molarity or sodium concentration normally would induce greater fluid intake.
Secondary hyperparathyroidism refers to the production of higher than normal levels of parathyroid hormone in the presence of hypocalcemia.
Any abnormality of the third metacarpal bone.
Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the metaphysis of the ulna.
The presence of fibrosis of that part of the liver with congenital onset.
Agenesis of lower secondary incisor or lower primary incisor.
Severe head pain with sudden onset, reaching its maximum intensity in less than one minute and lasting from one hour to ten days.
Mid upper eyelash length >10 mm or increased length of the eyelashes (subjective).
Absence or underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum.

An upper medial orbital cleft produces a cleft of the medial one-third of the upper eyelid that extends through the eyebrow into the frontal hairline. The skeletal element of the cleft in the region of the frontal process of the maxilla may either pass lateral to the ethmoid, through the supraorbital rim, or it may pass through the ethmoidal labyrinth to produce orbital hypertelorism. This cleft usually accompanies the Number 3 cleft. The soft tissue features include a cleft of the medial portion of the upper eyelid, an irregularity in hair orientation at the medial end of the eyebrow, and a long tongue-like projection of the frontal hairline onto the forehead. There is a mild flattening of the frontal process of the maxilla and extensive pneumatization of both the ethmoidal and frontal sinuses, both of which are more prominent on the cleft side. No bony clefting of the supraorbital rim or frontal bone is evident. The cranial base and sphenoid architecture, including the pterygoid processes, are symmetric and normal.
Bleeding from the small intestine.
A sense of intense joy or happiness that is beyond what would be expected under the given circumstances.
The presence of a folate sensitive fragile site at chromosome Xq28.
The presence of a vaginal septum, thereby creating a vaginal duplication. The septum is longitudinal in the majority of cases.
Congenital absence or underdevelopment of the fovea centralis.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the proximal phalanx of the thumb is affected.

A varicocele is a widening of the veins along the spermatic cord, leading to enlarged, twisted veins in the scrotum, and manifested clinically by a painless testicle lump, scrotal swelling, or bulge in the scrotum.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against fungus.

Small ectopic arteries or arterial branches that connect the aorta, aortic branches and/or subclavian artery regions directly to the lung parenchyma, usually seen in conjunction with pulmonary atresia, ventricular septal defect (VSD) and/or closed ductus arteriosus.
A type of gait (walking) characterized by by dragging one's feet along or without lifting the feet fully from the ground.
Reduced diameter of a long bone.
Increased concentration of interferon alpha in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
An abnormal elevation above the normal concentration of mannose-binding protein in the blood circulation.
Patchy loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.
An abnormality of the pupil.
Fasciculations affecting the tongue muscle and the musculature of the face.
A kind of neoplasm of the liver that originates in hepatocytes and presents macroscopically as a soft and hemorrhagic tan mass in the liver.
?xrefs: MSH:D006528 UMLS:C1867955 SNOMEDCT_US:187769009 UMLS:C2239176 SNOMEDCT_US:25370001 UMLS:C1862761 NCIT:C3099 SNOMEDCT_US:109841003

?def: EEG abnormalities (epileptiform discharges) evoked by flashing lights or black and white striped patterns.
The presence of unusually deep creases (ridges/wrinkles) on the skin of sole of foot located between the first and second toe.
A high concentration of one or more electrolytes in the urine in the presence of low serum concentrations of the electrolyte(s).
This term applies to an individual who requires help transferring to the toilet, cleaning self or who uses bedpan or commode.
A term to describe when farsightedness is masked when the accommodative muscles are used to increase the focusing power of the eye.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of aspartate in the blood circulation.
A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex III, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.
Onset of disease manifestations in adulthood, defined here as at the age of 16 years or later.
A diffuse loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.
Dminished sexual desire in female.
An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the fourth toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
The presence of multiple pits (small, pinpoint-large indentations on the surface of the skin) located on the skin of sole of foot.
Visually assessable vertical indentation, cleft, or depression of the nasal bridge, ridge and tip.
Increased susceptibility to herpesvirus, as manifested by recurrent episodes of herpesvirus.
A reduction in the level of thymic horomone.
A reduced count of megakaryocytes.

The vestibulo-ocular reflex is responsible for the stabilization of the retinal image during movement. The visual vestibular ocular reflex (VVOR) or visual enhanced VOR, maintains ocular stability during head motion by generating compensatory eye movement opposite to head movement, and is a major component of visual vestibular interaction. This feature is an impairment of this reflex, manifested as the combined impairment of the three compensatory eye movement reflexes, namely the vestibulo-ocular reflex (VOR), smooth pursuit (SP) and optokinetic reflex (OKR).
Simultaneous enlargement of the liver and spleen.
Delivery by Caesarian section representing the first time the mother has delivered by Caesarian section.

Abnormal dilatation of the pulmonary lymphatic vessels. Lymphatic fluid in the lung is derived from normal leakage of fluid out of the blood capillaries in the lung. In pulmonary lymphangiectasia, the pulmonary lymphatics are not properly connected and become dilated with fluid.
An abnormal reduction in the mobility of ejaculated sperm.
A type of abdominal pain characterized by a feeling of contractions and typically fluctuating in intensity.

Any structural anomaly of the elastic fibers of the skin. Elastic fibers are the essential extracellular matrix macromolecules comprising an elastin core surrounded by a mantle of fibrillin-rich microfibrils.
Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.

Fiber splitting or branching is a common finding in human and rat skeletal muscle pathology. Fiber splitting refers to longitudinal halving of the complete fiber, while branching originates from a regenerating end of a necrotic fiber as invaginations of the sarcolemma. In fiber branching, one end of the fiber remains intact as a single entity, while the other end has several branches.
Increased susceptibility to bacterial infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of bacterial infection.
Absence or developmental hypoplasia of the uterus.
An increase above the normal proportion of non-class-switched memory B cells relative to the total number of B cells.
Abnormal proliferation of blood vessels within the cardiac cavities attached to the endocardium.
An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater in the region surrounding the cerebellum.

The occurrence of multiple or unique whitish or normal in color small papules or nodules in oral cavity, especially on labial and buccal mucosa, lower lip and tongue, and less often on the upper lip, gingiva and palate.
A glioma affecting the cerebellum.
An increased concentration of copper in the urine.
An increase in the level of L-2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the urine.

An abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the second finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
Abnormal thickening of the skin of the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet.
Pain in the ear can be a consequence of otologic disease (primary or otogenic otalgia), or can arise from pathologic processes and structures other than the ear (secondary or referred otalgia).
A form of convergent strabismus (esotropia) in which the deviation is present under all conditions (ie at all distances and at all times).
An erosion or abrasion of the cornea's outermost layer of epithelial cells.
Type 4 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
Deviation from normal concentration of albumin in the blood.
The presence of a neoplasm of the testis with origin in a Sertoli cell.
Areas of subcutanous fat tissue that are resistant to (do not respond as expected to) diet, life-style alteration, or bariatric surgery.
Any deviation from the normal motor coordination of the eyes that allows for bilateral fixation on a single object.
Reduced functioning of the vestibular apparatus.
Hypoplasia of the triceps muscle.
An abnormal increase in the binding affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen.
Upper insertion of the ear to the scalp below an imaginary horizontal line drawn between the inner canthi of the eye and extending posteriorly to the ear.
An abnormality of platelets.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0040015 MSH:D013915 SNOMEDCT_US:32942005 UMLS:C4020863 SNOMEDCT_US:127566005 UMLS:C0151854

?def: An anomaly of the adnexa, uterus, and vagina (in female) or seminal tract and prostate (in male).

Dryness of the eye related to deficiency of the tear film components (aqueous, mucin, or lipid), lid surface abnormalities, or epithelial abnormalities. Keratoconjunctivitis sicca often results in a scratchy or sandy sensation (foreign body sensation) in the eyes, and may also be associated with itching, inability to produce tears, photosensitivity, redness, pain, and difficulty in moving the eyelids.
?xrefs: UMLS:C2930821 UMLS:C0013238 MSH:D007638 MSH:D015352 SNOMEDCT_US:302896008 UMLS:C0043349 SNOMEDCT_US:46152009 MSH:C531719 MSH:D014985 SNOMEDCT_US:363677007 UMLS:C0022575

?def: The QRS complexes of the electrocardiogram alternate in height.
Protrusion of the contents of the abdominal cavity through the inguinal canal.
Inflammation of any part of the lung parenchyma.
Senile plaques are extracellular deposits of amyloid in the gray matter of the brain.
Positioning of the nasal septum to the right or left in contrast to the normal midline position of the nasal septum.
Lichen amyloidosis presents with multiple localized or rarely generalized, hyperpigmented grouped papules with a predilection for the shins, calves, ankles, and dorsa of the feet and thighs.
Blockage of venous return (flow of blood from the periphery back towards the right atrium) in a vein.
Pallor of the perifoveal macula of the retina with appearance of a small circular reddish choroid shape as seen through the fovea centralis due to relative transparancy of the macula.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes one to four.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the kidney.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the nail.

A reduction compared to the predicted value of the forced expiratory flow over the middle one-half of the FVC; the average flow from the point at which 25% of the FVC has been exhaled to the point at which 75% of the FVC has been exhaled. Here, the test is performed after the administration of a bronchodilating medication.
Retinopathy which is a residual crescent of retina anterior to zone II.
Upper eyelid partly covered by skin when eyes are open.
A benign nerve sheath tumor composed of Schwann cells.
Reduced ability to flex the femur, that is, to pull the knee upward.
Formation of excess fibrous connective tissue in the tunica intima (innermost layer) of arteries.
Deposition of calcium salts in the fibrous sheet that connects the radius and the ulna.
The presence of a peripheral schwannoma.
Immunohistochemistry shows complete lack of gamma sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.

Arnold-Chiari type I malformation refers to a relatively mild degree of herniation of the posteroinferior region of the cerebellum (the cerebellar tonsils) into the cervical canal with little or no displacement of the fourth ventricle.
The left common carotid artery has a common origin with the innominate artery.
Loss of all scalp hair with congenital onset.
A diffuse, non-pitting edema and thickening of the skin usually on the anterior aspect of the lower legs spreading to the dorsum of the feet.
Broadening of the soft tissues (non-edematous swelling of soft tissues) of the digital tips in all dimensions associated with an increased longitudinal and lateral curvature of the nails.
Increased concentration of 1-methylhistidine in the urine.
Any functional abnormality of erythrocytes (red-blood cells).
An anomaly of middle phalanx of finger.
An increased concentration of proline in the blood.
Sparseness of the body hair.
Abnormal concentration of sulfate in the urine.
A sinus in the coccygeal region (the region of the intergluteal cleft). A pilonidal sinus often contains hair and skin debris.
Applies to an abnormality that affects the legs more than the arms, trunk, head.
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 4th finger.
Hypoplasia of the maxillozygomatic complex.
A tendency to hold the chin elevated by about 20 to 30 degrees to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.
An autoimmune form of hemolytic anemia.
Reduced ability to move the vertebral column with a resulting limitation of neck and trunk flexion.

An abnormality of the primary sensation that is mediated by peripheral nerves (pain, temperature, touch, vibration, joint position). The word hypoesthesia (or hypesthesia) refers to a reduction in cutaneous sensation to a specific type of testing.
Progressively worsening joint contractures.
Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of one or more forearm bones.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of isoleucine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Serum sample with a grossly white (milk-like, i.e., lactescent) appearance. This feature is indicative of an extremely elevated serum triglyceride level.
Underdevelopment of the right-sided structures of the heart.
Inflammation of the Achilles tendon.
An abnormality of the distribution of hair growth.
An abnormality of the radius.
A abnormal increase in the inflammatory response to injury or infection.
An increased concentration of catecholamine in the urine.
A confluent, generalized overgrowth of silvery blonde to gray lanugo hair at birth.
Focal dilation of the umbilical vein.
Regular circumferential periaortic fibrosis involving the whole aorta and leading to a coated aorta appearance on computed tomography scans
A neuroendocrine tumor originating in a hormone-producing cell (islet cell) of the pancreas.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:76345009 SNOMEDCT_US:237596009 SNOMEDCT_US:126864006 MSH:D007516 UMLS:C0242363 SNOMEDCT_US:399528006 SNOMEDCT_US:128878003

?def: Curvilinear intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material within axons.
A lateral bending or abnormal curvature of the femur.

Repeated episodes of segmental demyelination and remyelination lead to the accumulation of supernumerary Schwann cells around axons, which is referred to as onion bulb formation. This finding affects peripheral nerves.
Periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs)are periodic, lateralized, and epileptiform. PLEDs show a relatively constant interval between discharges (0.5 to 3 seconds).
Underdevelopment of the trapezium.
A pale yellow discoloration of the entire optic disc.
Increased susceptibility to infections with Burkholderia cepacia, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection with this agent.
A general term referring to a defect in immunity resulting from impaired antibody production.
An abnormally low level of uric acid in the blood.
An abnormally reduced proportion of memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood.
Increased width of the humeral epiphysis.
A progressive loss of the ability to remember the meaning of words, faces and objects.
An abnormality of the lower lip.
Chronic otitis media refers to fluid, swelling, or infection of the middle ear that does not heal and may cause permanent damage to the ear.
Sharply demarcated hyperpigmentation which is congenital found in around 3-5% of the population and of no functional significance.

A thickening of the skin thickness in the posterior aspect of the fetal neck. A nuchal fold measurement is obtained in a transverse section of the fetal head at the level of the cavum septum pellucidum and thalami, angled posteriorly to include the cerebellum. The measurement is taken from the outer edge of the occiput bone to the outer skin limit directly in the midline. A measurement 6 mm or more is considered significant between 18 and 24 weeks and a measurement of 5 mm or more is considered significant at 16 to 18 weeks (pmid:16100637).
The presence of calcium deposition in the choroid plexus.
A type of ventricular tachycardia that is characterized by uniform QRS complexes within each lead (i.e., each QRS is identical or nearly so).
Increased susceptibility to protozoan infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of protozoan infection.
A Lamellar cataract with a pulverulent (punctate, \dust-like\" opacities) appearance."
A mild degree of slow or limited growth after birth, being between two and three standard deviations below age- and sex-related norms.
A form of severe hemolytic anemia characterized by erythrocyte morphology reminiscent of that seen in patients after a thermal burn.
A decreased amount of dystrophin in muscle fiber tissue.
A loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers from segments of the peripheral nervous system.

An acute and life-threatening complication of pregnancy, which is characterized by the appearance of tonic-clonic seizures, usually in a patient who had developed pre-eclampsia. Eclampsia includes seizures and coma that happen during pregnancy but are not due to preexisting or organic brain disorders.
Abnormal results from the diagnostic tests resulting from cardiac catheterization.
An increased concentration of sedoheptulose in the urine. Sedoheptulose is a monosaccharide with seven carbon atoms and a ketone functional group.
A low-grade variant of squamous cell carcinoma of the tongue with a warty (verrucous) appearance.
Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles brought on by exposure to cold temperatures.
A developmental defect characterized by absence or poor development of proximal renal tubules.
Hypoplasia of the cerebellum, pontine nuclei, and inferior olivary nucleus.
Tiny, repetitive muscle contractions in the eyelids, causing the appearance of twitching.
Small cartilaginous prominence on the posterior concha.
A dental anomaly characterized by the presence of a two fused teeth.
An increased creatine kinase level more than 50X above the upper normal level.

A temper tantrum is an emotional outburst usually triggered by a sense of frustration and manifested as whining and crying, screaming, kicking, hitting, and breath holding. Temper tantrums are normal in toddlers and young children and usually happen between the ages of one to three years. Temper tantrums may be considered abnormal if they occur at an unusually high frequency, are of unusual severity, or occur at an old age than usual.
An abnormality of the acetabulum, i.e., the Acetabular part of hip bone, which together with the head of the femur forms the hip joint.
Detection of norcotinine, a metabolite of nicotine, in urine.
Any abnormal noise generated by the beating heart.
A kind of anemia in which the volume of the red blood cells is normal.

Intense feelings of nervousness, tenseness, or panic, often in reaction to interpersonal stresses; worry about the negative effects of past unpleasant experiences and future negative possibilities; feeling fearful, apprehensive, or threatened by uncertainty; fears of falling apart or losing control.
A type of T-cell lymphoma that exhibits malignant infiltration of the skin.
Neglecting one's own needs and well-being.
An abnormality of the telencephalon, which is also known as the cerebrum.
Bilateral absence (atresia) of the posterior nasal aperture (choana).
Detection of methadone or its metabolite 2-ethylidene-1,5-dimethyl-3,3- diphenylpyrrolidine (EDDP) in plasma or serum.
Presence of abnormal cells inside a milk duct, that is, non-invasive breast cancer. Ductal carcinoma in situ is considered to be a precursor lesion to invasive breast cancer.
?xrefs: MSH:D002285 SNOMEDCT_US:373176000 SNOMEDCT_US:86616005 SNOMEDCT_US:109889007 UMLS:C0007124 SNOMEDCT_US:278053004

?def: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type III that is characterized by alterations in architectural organisation (cortical dyslamination) or cytoarchitectural composition (hypertrophic neurons outside Layer 5) in patients with hippocampal sclerosis (HS, syn. Ammon's horn sclerosis).

Irregular, small-amplitude myoclonic movements of the hands and/or fingers on keeping outstretched posture (jerky postural tremor). Polyminimyoclonus is stimulus-sensitive and accentuated during voluntary movements. A cortical origin can be demonstrated by back-averaging techniques, and somatosensory evoked potentials (SSEPs) are sometimes giant.
An increased concentration of ethylmalonic acid in the urine.
A severe crack in a lip. A lip fissure may be painful, may bleed and often is a recurring manifestation.
A deviation from normal in the expression of dysferlin in muscle tissue. Dysferlin is an ubiquitous 230-KDa transmembrane protein involved in calcium-mediated sarcolemma resealing.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the epididymis, an duct that transports spermatozoa from the testis to the vas deferens.
A decreased concentration of C-peptide in the circulation. Since C-peptide is secreted in equimolar amounts to insulin, this feature correlates with reduced insulin secretion.
A form of amyloidosis that affects the conjunctiva.
Absence of the mandible.
Weakness of the cartilage in the trachea and the bronchi, resulting in a floppy (non-rigid) airway. Affected persons may have difficulties to maintain patency of the airways.
An abnormality of the spleen.

A type of bicuspid aortic valve (BAV) characterized by a single raphe between the left and noncoronary cusps (LN fusion pattern). There is thus one completely developed right cusp, two completely developed commissures, and one raphe between the underdeveloped left and noncoronary coronary cusps extending to the corresponding malformed commissure.
Carpal bones with irregular or fragmented margins.
A decreased concentration of total carnitine in the blood.
An abnormal distribution of eyebrow hair growth in the medial direction.
An ocular deviation caused by a palsy to one or more of the extraocular muscles or nerves supplying them.
Proliferation (excess production) of hemopoietically active tissue or of tissue which has embryonic hemopoietic potential.
Consolidation refers to an exudate or other product of disease that replaces alveolar air, rendering the lung solid (as in infective pneumonia).
Muscular atrophy of distal leg muscles.

A type of atrial arrhythmia characterized by atrial rates of between 240 and 400 beats per minute and some degree of atrioventricular node conduction block. Typically, the ventricular rate is half the atrial rate. In the EKG; atrial flutter waves are observed as sawtooth-like atrial activity. Pathophysiologically, atrial flutter is a form of atrial reentry in which there is a premature electrical impulse creates a self-propagating circuit.
The presence of intraceullar inclusion bodies (aggregates of stainable substances, usually proteins) in leukocytes.
Tonic seizures with a sustained, forced conjugate ocular, cephalic and/or truncal rotation or lateral deviation from the midline.

A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on one of the autosomes (i.e., the human chromosomes 1-22) in which a trait manifests in individuals with two pathogenic alleles, either homozygotes (two copies of the same mutant allele) or compound heterozygotes (whereby each copy of a gene has a distinct mutant allele).

An increased level of 17-hydroxyprogesterone in the blood. 17-hydroxyprogesterone is an intermediate steroid in the adrenal biosynthetic pathway from cholesterol to cortisol and is the substrate for steroid 21-hydroxylase.
Abnormal bladder function (increased urge or frequency of urination or urge incontinence) resulting from abnormal functioning of the autonomic nervous system.
Underdevelopment of the thymus.
An abnormality of vibrational conductance of sound to the inner ear leading to impairment of sensory perception of sound.
A form of heart failure characterized by reduced cardiac output. This may be seen in patients with heart failure owing to ischemic heart disease, hypertension, cardiomyopathy, and other causes.
A reduction below the normal proportion of non-class-switched memory B cells relative to the total number of B cells.
The presence of a carcinoma of the urinary bladder with origin in a transitional epithelial cell.
A rare cancer originating in the lung or pleural cavity that occurs most often in infants and young children but also has been reported in adults. Pleuropulmonary blastoma is regarded as malignant.
A malformation of the auricle of the ear.
Present in 30% to 79% of the cases.
An abnormality of XY sexual development characterized by the absence of both testes at birth.
A failure to achieve the ability to sit at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children sit with support at 6 months of age and sit steadily without support at 9 months of age.
A decreased amount of valine in the blood.
The inability to synthesize postvaccination antibodies against a tetanus antigen, as measured by antibody titer determination following vaccination.
An abnormal color of the urine, that is, the color of the urine appears different from the usual straw-yellow color.
Progressive loss of previously present language abilities.
The presence of amyloid deposition in one or more tissues. Amyloidosis may be defined as the extracellular deposition of amyloid in one or more sites of the body.
Underdevelopment of a fingernail.
Absence of a region of the retina, retinal pigment epithelium, and choroid.
A type of skin nodule that has a small depression that resembles a navel (i.e., is umbilicated).
A schwannoma (benign, usually encapsulated slow growing tumor composed of Schwann cells) located in the orbit.
A thickening of the stratum corneum in the region beneath the nails.
Papilledema refers to edema (swelling) of the optic disc secondary to any factor which increases cerebral spinal fluid pressure.
Fibrosis of only some of the external ocular muscles such that the eyes of affected individuals are partially or completely fixed in a strabismic position.
A thickening of the stratum corneum, the outer layer of the skin, in the region surrounding the nails.
An abnormally reduced amount of adipose tissue in the thoracic cavity.
Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as phenobarbital in the gastric fluid.
Distance between the oral commissures more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased width of the oral aperture (subjective).
Recurrent infections at an early age with improvement in later childhood.
An abnormality of the line of Schwalbe.
A structural anomaly of the nonstriated, involuntary muscle tissue of the intestine.

Abnormally increased dimension of the maxilla, especially relative to the mandible, resulting in a malocclusion or malalignment between the upper and lower teeth or in anterior positioning of the nasal base, increased convexity of the face, increased nasolabial angle, or increased width (transverse dimension of the maxilla.
?xrefs: UMLS:C4073209 SNOMEDCT_US:28070007 UMLS:C4280272 UMLS:C2227090 UMLS:C4280273 UMLS:C0266081

?def: An abnormality of the liver.
An elevated concentration of lactate in the caudate nucleus. This finding can be elicited by magnetic resonance spectroscopy imaging.
A loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.
A deviation from the normal count of dense granules per thrombocyte.
Involuntary, fine, continuous, undulating contractions of the eyelid.
An abnormal dark color of the urine.
Absence of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger.
The absence of the major creases of the palm (distal transverse crease, proximal transverse crease, or thenar crease).
Yellow/white, sharply delineated lesion, typically of inflammatory nature, involving the macula.
An atrioventricular valve that has failed to open (atretic).
Presence of multiple cystic changes in multiple areas or multiple bones.
Tearing of the aortic wall generally associated with profuse internal bleeding.

Elevation of the voltage (height) of the QRS complex. There are several criteria in use, but the most common is the Sokolov-Lyon criterion (S wave depth in V1 + tallest R wave height in V5-V6 greater than 35 mm).

An atypical absence seizure has less abrupt onset and offset of loss of awareness than typical absence seizures. They are often associated with other features such as loss of muscle tone of the head, trunk or limbs (often a gradual slump) and subtle myoclonic jerks. Atypical absence seizures often occur in individuals with intellectual impairment.The loss of awareness may be minimal with the patient continuing an activity, but more slowly or with mistakes.
A white patch or plaque occurring on the surface of the esophageal mucous membranes that cannot be rubbed off and cannot be characterized clinically as any other disease.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of phenylalanine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
A decreased blood concentration of growth hormone binding protein.
A form of developmental hypoplasia of the mandible in which the mandible is mislocalised posteriorly.
An abnormality of a nasalis muscle.
The presence of lymphangiectasis of the thyroid gland.
A structural anomaly of the vessel that contains or conveys lymph fluid.
Abnormally long and slender fingers (\spider fingers\")."
An anomaly in the number of osteoclasts, bone-resorbing cells that develop from macrophages.
