A type of retinal detachment arising due to a combination of contracting retinal membranes, abnormal vitreoretinal adhesions, and vitreous changes. It is usually seen in the context of diseases that induce a fibrovascular response, e.g. diabetes.
A type of dystonia that is localized to a specific part of the body.
Average platelet volume below the lower limit of the normal reference interval.
A hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, that is located in the glottic or supraglottic regions.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the retina.
The presence of cerebellar signs and symptoms such as lack of balance associated with quadrupedal gait (locomotion on all four extremities with a 'bear-like' gait with the legs held straight).
Width of the forehead or distance between the frontotemporales is more than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or apparently increased distance between the two sides of the forehead.
A structural abnormality of the sperm neck.
A lesion of the skin with a ring-like distribution.
An abnormality of the duodenum, i.e., the first section of the small intestine.
A comedo in which the top of the pore is not stretched open and thus does not expose the clogged portion (which would appear black), hence the name whitehead.
Increased concentration of disaccharide in the urine.
The presence of two or more accessory spleens.
An abnormality of the structure or composition of the teeth.
Decreased concentration of 3-methylhistidine in the urine.

A functional anomaly of the inferior oblique muscle, an extraocular muscle that has its origin on the maxillary bone just posterior to the inferior medial orbital rim and lateral to the nasolacrimal canal and that is innervated by the inferior branch of the oculomotor nerve.

A histological alteration of muscle fibers that resembles a necklace (necklace fibers). A substantial proportion of fibers (4-20% in PMID:19084976) show internalized nuclei aligned in a basophilic ring (necklace) at 3 micrometers beneath the sarcolemma. Ultrastructurally, such necklaces consist of myofibrils of smaller diameter, in oblique orientation, surrounded by mitochondria, sarcoplasmic reticulum and glycogen granules.
Lack of subcutaneous adipose tissue.
An abnormal position of the hand in which the wrist is bent toward the radius (i.e., toward the thumb).
Benign tumor of the nasolacrimal sac.
Lasting (uncontrolled) presence of cytomegalovirus in the blood circulation.
Reduced length of the distal phalanx of the second toe as a result of developmental hypoplasia.

Presence of a pseudoaneurysm in the artery that supplies the gallbladder and cystic duct with blood. A pseudoaneurysm, also known as a false aneurysm, forms when blood leaks through a breach of the arterial wall but is contained by the adventitia or surrounding perivascular soft tissue.
An abnormality of the femoral head.
Abnormal reduction in length of proximal phalanx of third toe.
Abnormality of glycoside metabolism.
An increased amount of creatinine in the blood.
Abnormally elevated blood carbon dioxide (CO2) level.
Abnormality of the lacrimal gland, i.e., of the almond-shaped gland that secretes the aqueous layer of the tear film for each eye.
Absence (aplasia) of the sacrum.
An abnormality of eye movement characterized by impaired smooth-pursuit eye movements.

A creamy appearance of the retinal blood vessels that occurs when the concentration of lipids in the blood are extremely increased, with pale pink to milky white retinal vessels and altered pale reflexes from choroidal vasculature.
Complete duplication of the fourth proximal phalanx of hand.
Abnormally increased levels of glutamine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Slowed relaxation of muscles in the face.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the calcaneus.
Blue and green cones only; no functional red cones.

Widening of the wall of capillary blood vessels in the glomerulus. This feature may be produced by deposits and other changes affecting either subepithelial and subendothelial regions or the glomerular basement membrane itself.
Slightly elevated lesions on or in the skin with a diameter of over 5 mm.
EEG with sharp waves in the central region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.
The occurrence of an unusually high amount of muscle pain following exercise.
Any abnormality of the epiphysis of the second metacarpal bone.

An abnormally increased number of metamyelocytes in the peripheral blood circulation. Metamyelocytes are immature neutrophils with a size of 10-18 micrometers, an indented or kidney-shaped nucleus, pinkish-blue staining cytoplasm with seconday granules, and a nucleus:cytoplasm ratio of 1.5:1.
The presence of complexes of spikes and waves (>3.5 Hz) in electroencephalography (EEG).

A benign uni- or multicystic, intraosseous tumor of odontogenic origin, with a characteristic lining of parakeratinized stratified squamous epithelium and potential for aggressive, infiltrative behaviour.
Deficiency of parathyroid hormone with congenital onset.
Partial duplication of the middle phalanx of the 5th toe.
Increased length of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
Persistent deficits in social interaction and communication and interaction as well as a markedly restricted repertoire of activity and interest as well as repetitive patterns of behavior.
This term applies to an individual who requires help to bathe more than one part of the body, get in or out of the tub or shower, or who requires total bathing.
Spontaneous development of hematomas (hematoma) or bruises without significant trauma.

An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the urinary bladder. Bladder pain may be more pronounced with a full bladder and relieved upon urination, but this is not always the case.
An abnormality of an infraorbital artery.
A form of divergent strabismus (exotropia) in which the eye turns outward at all distances and at all times.

Pineoblastoma is a rare primitive neuroectodermal tumour (PNET) arising in the pineal gland. Pineoblastomas are classified as a WHO grade IV tumour and comprise one-fourth to one-half of pineal parenchymal tumours. Pineoblastoma is a highly cellular tumor originating in the pineal gland and containing small, poorly differentiated cells.
Pterygia affecting the neck.
An abnormal decrease of the C-reactive protein level in serum.
An abnormally decreased magnesium concentration in the blood.
A deviation from equal (50%) inactivation of each parental X chromosome in maternal cells.
Excessively active peristalsis (wave of contraction of the tubular organs of the gastrointestinal tract) marked by excessive rapidity of the passage of food through the stomach and intestine.

A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial proton-transporting ATP synthase complex, which makes ATP via oxidative phosphorylation, and is sometimes described as Complex V of the electron transport chain.
An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation of the iris.
An abnormality of chromosome segregation.

A type of strabismus in which the fixating eye is always the same one, while the other eye is constantly deviated. Monocular strabismus is to be distinguished from alternating strabismus, in which either of the eyes 'squints' at different times.
An abnormal increase in the amount of intraabdominal fat tissue.
Abnormal eating habit with excessive or insufficient consumption of food or any other abnormal pattern of food consumption.
Inflammation of the esophagus.

A separation of the layers within the wall of the descending aorta. Tears in the intimal layer result in the propagation of dissection (proximally or distally) secondary to blood entering the intima-media space.
Osteomyelitis is an inflammatory process accompanied by bone destruction and caused by an infecting microorganism.
A delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more long bones that are part of the elbow.

A type of weakness of the muscles involved in swallowing that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.
A form of hypotension characterized by a sudden fall in blood pressure that occurs when a person assumes a standing position.
The presence of squamous cell carcinoma of the skin.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0751688 UMLS:C0007137 SNOMEDCT_US:28899001 NCIT:C2929 MSH:D002294 SNOMEDCT_US:402815007 MSH:D018307

?def: Increased susceptibility to middle ear infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of middle ear infections
Fusion of the terminal/distal and middle phalanges of the 4th finger.
Inflammation and thickening (localized fibrosis) of the fascia, the tissue under the skin and over the muscle, typically associated with a build up of eosinophils in the muscles and tissues.
Any abnormality of the cardiovascular system.
A cataract that occurs congenitally as the result of a developmental defect, in contrast to the majority of cataracts that occur in adulthood as the result of degenerative changes of the lens.

An anomaly of the vertebral artery, the major artery of the neck that originates from the subclavian artery and merges to form the single midline basilar artery in a complex called the vertebrobasilar system.
Abnormal slowness of thought processes.
Generalized slowing of EEG activity at frequencies between 4-7 Hz.

An increased cellular sensitivity to the DNA cross-linking agent, mitomycin C (MMC). In the presence of increased sensitivity, MMC causes increased cell death, chromosome breakage, and accumulation in the G2 phase of the cell cycle.
Complete duplication of the middle phalanx of ring finger.
Defect in the epithelium of the esophagus, essentially an open sore in the lining of the esophagus.
Reduced ability to flex (bend) the fingers. This can manifest as incomplete closure of the hand due to weakness in finger flexion.
EEG with generalized sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.
A type of cyclotropia (torsion of one or both eye about the visual axis of the eyes) in which the upper poles of the globes are rotated outward (laterally) to each other.

A type of retinal hemorrhage that is located within the nerve fiber layer (NFL) of the retina and that exhibits a characteristic flame shape which results from constraints by the structure of the NFL (axons of the ganglion cells).

This is a postural deformity in which the foot is positioned up against the tibia. The heel (calcaneus) is positioned downward (that is, the ankle is flexed upward), and the heel is turned outward (valgus).

Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) with a short pulmonary trunk arises from the truncus arteriosus, giving rise to both pulmonary arteries.
Deviation from the normal range of size of the thalamus.

A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin in multiple or solitary non-inflammatory, well-demarcated, oval or circular ulcers with a diameter of about 1 to 2 cm. Aplasia cutis congenita most commonly occurs on the scalp, but may present in the face, trunk, or limbs.
?xrefs: MSH:D004476 UMLS:C0265989 SNOMEDCT_US:74223008 SNOMEDCT_US:254237003 MEDDRA:10002963 SNOMEDCT_US:35484002 UMLS:C0282160

?def: A purpuric lesion that is larger than 1 cm in diameter.
A skin texture that is unusually soft (and may feel silky), and has a malleable consistency resembling that of dough.
Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger.
Inflammation of the lip.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of nicotinurate in the blood.
A type of intraretinal hemorrhage that is located in the superficial retina between the inner limiting membrane and the retinal nerve fiber layer.
An abnormally reduced concentration of corticosterone in the blood.
Underdevelopment of the Third metatarsal bone leading to a short (hypoplastic) third metatarsal bone.
An increase in the level of ribose in the cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormal level of a circulating protein in the blood.
A net-like pattern of increased pigmentation of the oral cavity.
A pulling inward of the soft tissues between the ribs upon inhalation. This is a sign of increased use of the chest muscles for breathing and is a manifestation of respiratory distress.
Increased length of the uvula.
A tumor that originates in cells from the primitive neural crest. This group of tumors is characteirzed by the presence of primitive cells with elements of neuronal and/or glial differentiation.
A developmental anomaly in which the mastoid process fails to form and is thus found to be congenitally absent.

Any functional anomaly of the skin adnexa (skin appendages), which are specialized skin structures located within the dermis and focally within the subcutaneous fatty tissue, comprising three histologically distinct structures: (1) the pilosebaceous unit (hair follicle and sebaceous glands); (2) the eccrine sweat glands; and (3) the apocrine glands.
Aplasia or hypoplasia of the paranasal sinuses.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.
An abnormality of the spinal cord (myelon).
Hypoplasia of the kidney.
Absence or underdevelopment of the tibia.
A 'hemangioblastoma of the spinal cord.
Spasticity that increases in degree with time.
Reduction in thickness of the basal lamina of the glomerulus of the kidney.
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against neutrophils.
An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of an epiphysis.

An exaggerated whealing tendency when the skin is stroked, that is, formation of red, itchy bumps and lines on the skin as a result of pressure on the skin (for instance, stroking the skin with a pen or tongue depressor).
An abnormality of the complement system.

A functional anomaly of the upper motor neuron. The upper motor neurons are neurons of the primary motor cortex which project to the brainstem and spinal chord via the corticonuclear, corticobulbar and corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts. They are involved in control of voluntary movements. Dysfunction leads to weakness, impairment of fine motor movements, spasticity, hyperreflexia and abnormal pyramidal signs.
Any structural abnormality of a cricoid cartilage, that is, of the ring-shaped cartilage of the larynx.
An abnormality of the hip joint.
Inflammation of a salivary gland.
Underdevelopment of the lesser trochanter.
Excessive growth or abnormal thickening of bone tissue.
Distance between the medial and lateral canthi is more than 2 SD below the mean for age (objective); or, apparently reduced length of the palpebral fissures.
Syncope following a quick change in position from lying down to standing.
Abnormally small dimension of the mandible (lower jaw) relative to the maxilla (upper jaw).
Presence of a xenobiotic in gastric fluid.
An abnormality of the optic nerve in which the optic nerve is large and funneled and displays a conical excavation of the optic disc. The optic disc appears dysplastic.
A region of high intensity (brightness) observed upon magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scans of the spinal cord.
Optic neuritis that occurs in the section of the optic nerve located behind the eyeball.
A deviation from the normal straight shape of a proximal phalanx of the 1st metatarsal bone.
Inaccurate saccades (rapid movement of the eye between fixation points) in the horizontal direction.
A non-midline cleft of the upper lip on the left and right sides.
Habitual biting of one's own fingernails.

Glucose intolerance (GI) can be defined as dysglycemia that comprises both prediabetes and diabetes. It includes the conditions of impaired fasting glucose (IFG) and impaired glucose tolerance (IGT) and diabetes mellitus (DM).
A deviation from the normal straight form of the middle phalanx of the third toe.
An abnormality of the conduction of electrical impulses by peripheral (motor or sensory) nerves. This finding is elicited by a nerve conduction study (NCS).
An abnormal decrease in ornithine in the blood.

Webbing or fusion of the toes, involving soft parts and including fusion of individual bones of the toes. Bony fusions are referred to as \bony\" Syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a tibial-fibular axis. Fusions of bones of the toes in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as \"Symphalangism\"."
A type of aortic medial fibrosis in which the increase in collagen is more scar-like, altering the arrangement of the lamellar units.
Absence of the proximal interphalangeal flexion creases of the fingers.
Vomiting that ejects the gastric contents with great force.
Muscular atrophy involving the quadriceps muscle.
An abnormally increased sensitivity to the effects of ionizing radiation.
Glossy appearance of the entire tongue surface.
A type of cry that is abnormal because it is consists of unusually shortened and detached vocalizations.
Absence of the second long bone of the hand.
An impairment of a fructose metabolic process.
A deviation from the normal concentration of thyroglobulin, a protein produced in the thyroid gland that acts as a precursor to thyrroid hormones.
Absence of one or more middle phalanx of a finger.
Increased width of the phalanges of the 3rd finger.
Absence or underdevelopment of the uvea, the pigmented middle layer of the eye consisting of the iris and ciliary body together with the choroid.
An anomaly of the pituitary gland.
Displacement of the 5th finger towards the ulnar side.
An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can forcefully expel in one second, with the test being performed after the administration of a bronchodilating medication.
This type of brachydactyly is characterized by short and broad terminal phalanges of the thumbs and big toes.
Combined syndactyly and polydactyly of the foot on the lateral side (i.e., on the side of the little toe).

A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the distal phalanges of the hand. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.

Reduced amplitude (height) of the QRS complex of the electrocardiogram (EKG), defined as amplitudes of all the QRS complexes in the limb leads are less than 5 mm or amplitudes of all the QRS complexes in the precordial leads less than 10 mm.

Any of the various types of human blood whose antigen characteristics determine compatibility in transfusion. While the ABO and Rhesus sytems are the most well known, there are in total about 300 different blood type antigens distributed across 34 different blood type systems.

Origin of the right coronary artery (RCA) from the left sinus of Valsalva or of the left main (LM) or left anterior descending (LAD) coronary artery from the right sinus of Valsalva, with the additional feature that the artery passes between the two great arteries. This carries a risk of the artery being compressed by these two vessels,
Rubral tremor is characterized by a slow coarse tremor at rest that is exacerbated by postural adjustments and by guided voluntary movements.
An abnormality of fear/anxiety-related behavior, which may relate to either abnormally reduced fear/anxiety-related response or increased fear/anxiety-related response.
Increased count of eosinophils in the blood.
Delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more phalanx.
The presence of nipples that instead of pointing outward are retracted inwards.
A reduction in the quantity of space occupied by the thalamus.
Displacement of the 4th finger from its normal position.
Location of the urethral opening on the inferior aspect of the penis.
A persistent left superior vena cava (PLSVC) that drains into the right atrium via the coronary sinus. This is the case in 80-92% of cases of PLSVC and results in no hemodynamic consequence.
Any structural anomaly of the glossopharyngeal nerve, the ninth paired cranial nerve (CN IX).
An abnormality of the forebrain, which has as its parts the telencephalon, diencephalon, lateral ventricles and third ventricle.
Epidermal naevi are due to an overgrowth of the epidermis and may be present at birth (50%) or develop during childhood.
Partial duplication of the middle phalanx of middle finger, seen on x-rays as a broad and/or bifid phalanx.
A hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, that is located in the upper lip.

Abnormal morphology of collagen fibers in cartilage. In cartilage, collagen II, actually a collagen II:IX:XI heterofibril, is by far the most important type of collagen. A number of abnormalities may be appreciated by electron micrography or biochemical investigations, including sparse collagen fibers in the cartilage matrix.
An abnormality of the microglial cells. They are also known as brain-resident macrophages or hortega cells.
Linear, circumferential indentation in the convexity of the outer surface of the helix.
A subtype of skin dimples occurring in the shoulder region.
A grey discoloration of the dental enamel.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by pregnancy in a female.
An erythematous (red), flat facial rash that affects the skin in the malar area (over the cheekbones) and extends over the bridge of the nose.

Unroofed coronary sinus (CS) is a rare congenital cardiac anomaly in which there is partial (either focal or fenestrated) or complete absence of the roof of the CS, which results in a communication between the CS and the LA. Unroofed CS is the rarest type of atrial septal defect. It is often associated with persistent left superior vena cava (LSVC) and other forms of complex congenital heart disease, usually heterotaxia syndromes. The morphological types have been classified into 4 groups: Type I, completely unroofed with persistent LSVC; type II, completely unroofed without persistent LSVC; type III, partially unroofed mid portion; and type IV, partially unroofed terminal portion.
Decreased length of the umbilical cord.
Underdevelopment of the lacrimal puncta.
A chronic form of lactic acidemia.
Muscle hypertrophy affecting the calf muscles.
Spermatozoa with very small cranial ends devoid of any nuclear material, that is, lacking a typical sperm head.
Abnormal keratinization of the epidermal stratum coreum (horny layer) with increased keratin formation, preservation of the nuclei in the superficial cells, and absence of the stratum granulosum.
Any deviation from the normal number of eosinophils per volume in the blood circulation.
An abnormality of the density of hair growth.
No pericardium over the diaphragmatic surface of the heart. It is a congenital defect, not the result of a pericardectomy. Pericardium is present on other parts of the heart.
Abnormal concentration of neopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
An abnormality of the upper urinary tract.
Deviation from the norm of height with respect to that which is expected according to age and gender norms.
Presence of multiple adenomatous polyps in the colon.
Complete duplication of the fifth proximal phalanx of hand.
A type of urethral stricture affecting the pendulous urethra, which is straight and fixed to the corpora cavernosa.
An abnormal reduction in the components of the alternative complement pathway, such as the C3 protein or its cleavage products.

The presence of more than 5 juvenile polyps of the colon. The term juvenile polyps refer to a special histopathology and not the age of onset as the polyp might be diagnosed at all ages. The juvenile polyp has a spherical appearance and is microscopically characterized by overgrowth of an oedematous lamina propria with inflammatory cells and cystic glands.

An increased concentration of type 1 collagen N-terminal telopeptide (NTx) level in the urine. Generally the test is performed over a period of time, for instance, 10cc of morning urine can be collected following 12 hours overnight fasting or for 24 hours.
A partial dislocation of some or all of the small joints of the hand.
An abnormal bluish coloration of the sclera.

Hyperkeratosis lenticularis perstans (HLP), also known as Flegel disease, is a keratinization abnormality characterized by small, asymptomatic erythematous papules that leave characteristic punctate bleeding when they become detached. The lesions generally occur symmetrically along the top of the foot and on the legs, appearing more rarely on the arms, forearms, palms, and soles, and even on the oral mucosa.

An anomalous mirror-imaged arrangement of some bronchial structures. Right isomerism is defined as a subset of heterotaxy where some paired structures on opposite sides of the left-right axis of the body are symmetrical mirror images of each other, and have the morphology of the normal right-sided structures (vice versa for left isomerism).
Disproportionately long fibulae.
Reduced or lacking hair growth in a generalized distribution.
A reduction in the number of corneal endothelial cells.
Absence of the distal interphalangeal flexion creases of the fourth finger.
Tendency for the visual ais of one eye to be higher than that of the other.
Absence or underdevelopment of the patella.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the middle phalanx of the 4th toe.

An inability to perceive odors. This is a general term describing inability to smell arising in any part of the process of smelling from absorption of odorants into the nasal mucous overlying the olfactory epithelium, diffusion to the cilia, binding to olfactory receptor sites, generation of action potentials in olfactory neurons, and perception of a smell.
The presence of discolored lateral incisors.
Tremulousness (trembling) of the lens of the eye.
A type of third degree heart block in which the escape rhythm arises at the atrioventricular node, which produces a narrow QRS complex.
Chronic loss of joint motion in a finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.
Any structural abnormality of a jugular vein.
Early ossification of the costochondral junction, which is the joint between the ribs and costal cartilage in the front of the rib cage.

Reduced activity of plasminogen activator inhibitor 1. This protein down-regulates fibrinolysis in the circulation by inhibiting the two major plasminogen activators: tissue-plasminogen activator and urokinase-plasminogen activator.
Applies to an abnormality whose localization corresponds to the dermatomes, i.e., the nerve root distribution.
An anomaly of the pigmentation in the fovea centralis.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the 5th finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.
An abnormal irregularity of cortical bone.
Inflammation of the iris.
Dilated, glial-lined cavity in spinal cord. This cavity does not communicate with the central canal, and usually is between the dorsal columns unilaterally or bilaterally along the side of the cord.
Congenital anomaly characterized by closure or failure to develop an opening in the urethra.
Abnormally low FEV1/FVC (FEV1 - forced expiratory volume in 1 second; FVC forced vital capacity).
Noises from the temporomandibular joint during mandibular movement (e.g., chewing). Temporomandibular joint crepitus is often described as a clicking, popping, grating sound.

A type of divergent strabismus (exotropia) in which an eye tends to turn outwards (i.e., the eye squints) mainly when looking at distant objects. The eyes tend to remain straight when they look at near objects. Distance exotropia may be constant or intermittant.
An increased thickness of the eyelid not related to acute inflammation.
Chronic loss of joint motion in the thumb due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The term camptodactyly is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.

Multiple subcutaneous non-fragile and skin-coloured papules characterized by interstitial infiltrate of spindle and epithelioid histiocytes, and mucin. There are well circumscribed aggregates of epithelioid histiocytes and mucin in the upper and middle dermis,with the histiocytes arranged between collagen bundles and separated from the epidermis by a Grenz zone.

Dental malocclusion refers to an abnormality of the occlusion, or alignment, of the teeth and the way the upper and lower teeth fit together, resulting in overcrowding of teeth or in abnormal bite patterns.
?xrefs: MSH:D008310 UMLS:C4280613 SNOMEDCT_US:707598004 UMLS:C0024636 UMLS:C4280614 SNOMEDCT_US:47944004

?def: An abnormality of the melanosomes, i.e., of the cellular organelles in which melanin pigments are synthesized and stored within melanocytes (the cells that produce pigment in the dermis).
A developmental defect in which a kidney is located in an abnormal anatomic position within the pelvis.
A type of cataract that is not apparent at birth but that arises in childhood or adolescence.
Aortic dissection refers to a tear in the intimal layer of the aorta causing a separation between the intima and the medial layers of the aorta.
Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the big toe.
Any cystic lesion associated with the umbilical cord.
A cancer originating in lymphocytes and presenting as a solid tumor of lymhpoid cells.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:118600007 UMLS:C0024299 MSH:D008223 SNOMEDCT_US:188676008 SNOMEDCT_US:115244002 NCIT:C7065 SNOMEDCT_US:21964009

?def: A structural abnormality of the autonomic nervous system.
Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the 5th finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
Bony fusion of the middle and proximal phalanges of the 2nd toe.
A type of focal cortical dysplasia that is characterized by cortical lamination abnormalities associated with a principal lesion, usually adjacent to or affecting the same cortical area/lobe.
Complete duplication of middle phalanx of third toe.
Increased susceptibility to Klebsiella infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Klebsiella infection.
Pattern of blood flow in the heart that deviates from the normal circuit of the circulatory system from both right side of the heart to the left and vice versa.
Absence of the combined rod-and-code response on electroretinogram.
Defect or defects of the morphogenesis of the right heart identifiable at birth.
Any abnormality of the epiphysis of the 4th metacarpal bone.
A type of genetic anticipation observed predominantly upon transmission from affected males.
The term large for gestational age applies to babies whose birth weight lies above the 90th percentile for that gestational age.
An abnormal enlargement of the distal epiphysis of the femur.
Abnormal mineralization of the metaphyseal area of bones.
A bleb is a cystic space one cm or less in diameter.
A central nervous system neoplasm with neuronal and, less consistently, glial differentiation.
A functional abnormality affecting the lower cranial nerves, which include the paired 9th (glossopharyngeal), 10th (vagal), 11th (accessory) and 12th (hypoglossal) cranial nerves.
Functional neurological abnormalities related to dysfunction of the pyramidal tract.
Generalized epileptiform discharges induced by hyperventilation (overbreathing) in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
Rapid and unexpected death.

Bronchial breath sounds contain much higher frequency components than normal breath sounds due to alteration of the low pass filtering function of the alveoli, as occurs in consolidation. It is loud, hollow, and high pitch. Expiratory phase is longer than inspiratory phase with the inspiratory-expiratory ratio (I:E) changing from normal 3:1 to 1:2. There is distinct pause between inspiration and expiration due to absent alveolar phase. It is associated with whispering pectoriloquy.
A kind of anemia characterized by inadequate production of erythrocytes.
A partial dislocation of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the little finger.
A neoplasm of the pineal gland.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0031941 NCIT:C3328 MSH:D010871 SNOMEDCT_US:47598005 SNOMEDCT_US:127026004 SNOMEDCT_US:359619007

?def: A foot where the longitudinal arch of the foot is in contact with the ground or floor when the individual is standing; or, in a patient lying supine, a foot where the arch is in contact with the surface of a flat board pressed against the sole of the foot by the examiner with a pressure similar to that expected from weight bearing; or, the height of the arch is reduced.
A widely spaced gap between the first toe (the great toe) and the second toe.
An abnormality of an orbicularis oris muscle.
Underdevelopment of the pons.
An abnormality of the fourth ventricle.
A hole (perforation) in the wall of the colon.
A structural abnormality of the central nervous system.
An anomaly of the joint that connects the upper and the lower arm.

An increased count in the peripheral blood of cells that are precursors to mature circulating blood cells such as neutrophiles, monocytes, lymphocutes, and erythrocytes. Blasts are not usually found in significant numbers in the peripheral blood circulation, but can be observed in hematopoietic neoplasms such as leukemia, severe infections, and as a result of certain medications.
The presence of a carcinoma of the urinary bladder.
Reduced movement by the inferior rectus muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.
An elevation in bone density in the proximal phalanx of the second toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
The epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux surrounds the diaphysis, having a bracket-like form.
Any abnormality in the relative amount of CD4+ and CD8+ T lymphocytes.
A deviation from normal concentrations of estradiol in the circulation.
An abnormality of the concentration of glucose in the blood.
Underdeveloped scapula.
A limitation of the range of movement of the shoulder joint.

Normally, the posterior and lateral fontanelles are obliterated by about six months after birth, the anterior fontanelle closes by about the middle of the second year. This term refers to the situation in which the fontanelles close at an inappropriately early time point.
?xrefs: MSH:D003398 SNOMEDCT_US:1667003 UMLS:C4072853 SNOMEDCT_US:57219006 UMLS:C0277827 UMLS:C0010278

?def: Abnormally decreased weight-to-height squared ratio, calculated by dividing the individual's weight in kilograms by the square of the individual's height in meters and used as an indicator of underweight compared to averages.
Increased size of the vestibular aqueduct.
Collection of neutrophils in the dermis.
Congenital defect with failure of the development of the cerebral white matter.
Raised tissue masses located on the palpebral conjunctiva with a central vessel. Papillae are created by a focal infiltration of inflammatory cells.
There is normally one ossification center in the head of the femur. This term applies if there are multiple such centers.
An increased amount of asparagine in the blood.
Applies to a sign, symptom, or other manifestation that is episodic with a fixed time interval of one day (24 hours).
An abnormally increased level of bone isoforms of alkaline phosphatase, tissue-nonspecific isozyme in the blood.
The presence of fibrosis affecting the interlobular stroma of liver.

A stereotypy is a repetitive, simple movement that can be voluntarily suppressed. Stereotypies are typically simple back-and-forth movements such as waving of flapping the hands or arms, and they do not involve complex sequences or movement fragments. Movement is often but not always rhythmic and may involve fingers, wrists, or more proximal portions of the upper extremity. The lower extremity is not typically involved. Stereotypies are more commonly bilateral than unilateral.
?xrefs: MSH:D019956 UMLS:C0038271 SNOMEDCT_US:5507002 SNOMEDCT_US:84328007 MSH:D013239 UMLS:C0038273

?def: An anomaly of the color of the nail.
An abnormal immunoglobulin (heavy and light chain) in the circulation and typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.
Increased prominence of the xiphoid process of the sternum.
Perceived flashes of light.
Increased side-to-side width of one or more phalanges of the fingers or toes.
A form of anomalous pulmonary venous return in which not all pulmonary veins drain abnormally. Partial anomalous pulmonary venous return frequently involves one or both of the veins from one lung.
An anomaly in the number of macrophages.
Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the ovary.
The presence of a teratoma in the ovary.
Asymmetry of the bones of the skull and the face.

A type of retinal detachment arising from damage to the outer blood-retinal barrier that allows fluid to access the subretinal space and separate the neurosensory retina from the retinal pigment epithelium.
Hyperkeratosis affecting the sole of the foot.
Onset prior to birth.

A complete duplication affecting one or more of the phalanges of the hand. As opposed to a partial duplication were there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones, a complete duplication leads to two separate bones appearing side to side (radio-ulnar axis) as seen on x-rays. A duplication leading to an accesory bone appearing in the proximo-distal axis on x-rays, is a different entity called a Pseudoepiphyses (see according terms) sometimes also referred to as Hyperphalangism.
Benign congenital lesion of the postauricular soft tissue consisting of a blind-ending narrow tube or pit.

Fundus autofluorescence (FAF) is a non-invasive retinal imaging modality used in clinical practice to provide a density map of lipofuscin, the predominant ocular fluorophore, in the retinal pigment epithelium. Autofluorescent patterns result from the complex interaction of fluorophores such a lipofuscin, which release an autofluorescent signal, and elements such as melanin and rhodopsin, which absorb the excitation beam and attenuate autofluorescence. Other structures such as retinal vessels and the crystalline lens may also influence autofluorescence through blocking and interference.
A malignant epithelial tumor with a glandular organization that originates in the duodenum.
?xrefs: NCIT:C2852 UMLS:C0278804 MSH:D004379 UMLS:C0541912 SNOMEDCT_US:408644002 SNOMEDCT_US:254570009

?def: The presence of a fibroma of the ovary.
Reduction of the diameter of the coronary arteries as the result of an accumulation of atheromatous plaques within the walls of the coronary arteries before age of 45.
Pale reddish slightly elevated papules and plaques of 0.5-3 cm in diameter and not accompanied by pruritus.

Abnormality of the paranasal (cranial) sinuses, which are air-filled spaces that are located within the bones of the skull and face and communicate with the nasal cavity. They comprise the maxillary sinuses, the frontal sinuses, the ethmoid sinuses, and the sphenoid sinuses.
Developmental acceleration of ossification of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.
Episodes of choreoathetosis that can occur following triggers such as quick voluntary movements.
A decreased ability of the eye to adjust and thereby enable sharp vision of objects at different distances.
Inflammation of one or all portions of the uveal tract.
Acute hepatitis complicated by acute liver failure with hepatic encephalopathy occurring less than 8 weeks after the onset of jaundice.
An abnormality of the metabolism of folic acid, which is also known as vitamin B9.

A congenitally corrected transposition of the great arteries with a ventricular septal defect: a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart. The ventricular septal defect is centered around the most superior aspect of the ventricular septum.

Any abnormality of the skeletal muscle cell. Muscle fibers are subdivided into two types. Type I fibers are fatigue-resistant and rich in oxidative enzymes (they stain light with the myosin ATPase reaction), and type II fibers are fast-contracting, fatigue-prone, and rich in glycolytic enzymes (these fibers stain darkly). Normal muscle tissue has a random distribution of type I and type II fibers.

A type of paralysis in which a muscle becomes soft and yields to passive stretching, which results from loss of all or practically all peripheral motor nerves that innervated the muscle. Muscle tone is reduced and the affected muscles undergo extreme atrophy within months of the loss of innervation.
A papule with white color.
An anomaly of collagen fibers of the skin that is said to resemble a cauliflower and can be appreciated by electorn microscopy.
Aplasia or Hypoplasia affecting the 5th metacarpal.
The presence of distinct colors in the central (pupillary) zone of the iris than in the mid-peripheral (ciliary) zone.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of albumin in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Malfunction of a peripheral nerve resulting from mechanical compression of the nerve roots from internal or external causes and leading to a conduction block or axonal loss.
An abnormally increased width of the cranial sutures for age-related norms (generally resulting from delayed closure).
A tumor that arises from a gland cell.
An abnormality of the hair of head.
Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger with the 3rd metacarpal.
Respiratory failure in the newborn.
The development of two teeth from a single tooth bud, leading to a larger fused tooth.
A generalized form of microdontia.

A type of weakness of the muscles involved in breathing (respiration) that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in one or more epiphyses during the neonatal period.
An abnormal osseous union (fusion) between the radius and the ulna.
A disease where there is cellular death (necrosis) of bone components due to interruption of the blood supply.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0085660 UMLS:C0520474 SNOMEDCT_US:398199007 SNOMEDCT_US:240196003 UMLS:C0877326 SNOMEDCT_US:72756009 MSH:D010020 UMLS:C0029445

?def: Abnormality of the tibia (shinbone).
Absent 5th (little) finger.
Any abnormality of the epiphysis of the fifth metacarpal bone.
An increase in the level of myristic acid in the serum.
Eccentric fixation in which the angle of eccentricity equals the objective angle of deviation.
Insertion of the posterior columella below the nasal base.

A congenital anomaly of the pancreas that results from failed fusion of the dorsal and ventral ducts during embyological development. Three variants have been described: type 1 or classical divisum in which there is total failure of fusion; type 2 in which dorsal drainage is dominant in the absence of the duct of Wirsung; and type 3 or incomplete divisum where a small communicating branch is present.
A structural anomaly of the gallbladder.
Lack of improvement of muscle strength in response to administration of an acetylcholine esterase inhibitor.
An abnormal growth that projects from the mucous membrane of the urinary bladder.
Increased amount of pigmentation in the macula lutea.
Over-sensitivity to certain frequency ranges of sound.
Formation of crystals owing to an increased concentration of orotic acid in the urine.
Reduced number or density of facial hair.
A fibroblastic sarcoma is a malignant tumor derived from fibrous connective tissue and characterized by immature proliferating fibroblasts or undifferentiated anaplastic spindle cells.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of aromatic amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.
The presence of two to five cafe-au-lait macules.
An abnormally reduced level of liver isoforms of alkaline phosphatase, tissue-nonspecific isozyme in the blood.
Congenital absence of the optic nerve.
Underdevelopment (reduced size) of the tibia.

Electromyographic (EMG) findings characteristic of axonal neuropathy, with normal or slightly decreased nerve conduction velocities, normal or slightly prolonged distal latencies, but significantly reduced motor potentials and sensory amplitudes. There may be spontaneous activity upon needle EMG studies, such as increased insertional activity, positive sharp waves, and fibrillation potentials.
An increased susceptibility to lower respiratory tract infections as manifested by a history of recurrent lower respiratory tract infections.

Microscopic aneurysms of the retinal arterioles near the central part of the fundus, visible as small round dark red dots on the retinal surface (not arising from visible vessels) that are by definition less than the diameter of the major optic veins as they cross the optic disc.
Increased megakaryocyte number, i.e., of platelet precursor cells, present in the bone marrow.
A type of astigmatism associated with abnormal curvatures on the anterior and/or posterior surface of the cornea.
An abnormality of leukocytes.
Detection of norpropoxyphene in the blood, a major metabolite of the opioid analgesic drug dextropropoxyphene.
Inequality of refractive power of the two eyes.

Sharply demarcated area of partial or complete depigmentation of the fundus reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss. The margins of the de-pigmented area are usually scalloped and the large choroidal vessels are visible through the atrophic retinal pigment epithelium.

Intermittent claudication is a symptom of peripheral arterial occlusive disease. After having walked over a distance which is individually characteristic, the patients experience pain or cramps in the calves, feet or thighs which typically subsides on standing still.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the ring finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.
Decreased width of the wing (or ala) of the ilium (which is the large expanded portion which bounds the greater pelvis laterally).

A fluid-filled mass that is a distention of a preexisting bursa in the popliteal fossa, most commonly the gastrocnemio-semimembranosus bursa. This bursa is unique in that it communicates with the knee joint, unlike other periarticular bursae, via an opening in the joint capsule posterior to the medial femoral condyle.
Weakness of the muscles of the legs.
An abnormality of adipose tissue, which is loose connective tissue composed of adipocytes.

Any structural abnormality of a lateral crico-arytenoid muscle, which extends from the lateral cricoid cartilage to the muscular process of the arytenoid cartilage, and can adduct the vocal cords, which closes the rima glottidis and thereby protects the airway.
The presence of an abnormal shape of the palpebral fissure.
The presence of multiple diverticula of the intestine.
Coronary disease that has not progressed to the point of causing significant occlusion (blockage) of the coronary arteries.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glycine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Negative opinion about oneself characterized by low self-confidence and exaggeratedly critical feelings about oneself.
Partial or complete duplication of middle phalanx of fourth toe.

Chronic active Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) infection is an uncommon outcome of EBV infection and may present as a waxing and waning or fulminant syndrome. Unlike acute infectious mononucleosis, wherein EBV establishes lifelong infection and survives by maintaining a delicate balance with the host as a latent infection, in chronic active EBV infection the host-virus balance is disturbed.
When viewed on end (with the finger tip pointing toward the examiner's eye) the curve of the fingernail forms a tighter curve of convexity.

Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen, resulting from a defect in the production of spermatozoa in the testes. Can be differentiated from obstructive azoospermia on the basis of testicular biopsy.
An anomaly of the white matter of brainstem.
Complete duplication of distal phalanx of third toe.
The presence of a notch in the margin of the ala nasi.
An abnormal anatomical location of the parathyroid gland.
Habitual striking of one's own head against a surface such as a mattress or wall of a crib.

Less than normal number of natural killer cells, a type of lymphocyte in the innate immune system with an ability to mediate cytotoxicity and produce cytokines after the ligation of a germline-encoded activation receptor.

This term groups terms representing abnormal findings derived from chest X-ray investigation of the lung. In general, lung abnormalities can manifest as opacities (areas of increased density) or as regions with decreased density.
A benign central bone tumor of the jaw composed of fibrous connective tissue within which bone is formed.
An abnormality of coagulation associated with an increased risk of thrombosis.
An abnormality in biotinidase activity, an enzyme that releases biotin from biocytin, the product of biotin-dependent carboxylases degradation.
Absence of the nasopharyngeal adenoids as a developmental defect.
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against proteins predominantly expressed in perinuclear region of neutrophils.
An ichthyosiform abnormality of the skin with congenital onset.
An anomaly of the space between the medial and lateral canthi of the two open eyelids.
Onset of adrenarche at an earlier age than usual.
The presence of abnormal calcium deposition lesions in the pancreas.

A type of infection that is regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection. There are five general subtypes. (i) Opportunistic infection, meaning infection by a pathogen that is not normally able to cause infection in a healthy host (e.g., pneumonia by Pneumocystisjirovecii or CMV); (ii) Unusual location (focus) of an infection (e.g., an aspergillus brain abscess); (iii) a protracted course or lack of adequate response to treatment (e.g., chronic rhinosinusitis); (iv) Unusual severity or intensity of an infection; and (v) unusual recurrence of infections.
A sensation consistent with involvement of the autonomic nervous system, including cardiovascular, gastrointestinal, sudomotor, vasomotor and thermoregulatory functions.
Unusual prominence of the median palatal raphe, which is the ridge formed by the fusion of the two plates of the skull that form the hard palate.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the middle phalanx of the 3rd toe.
Variably shaped, cartilage-containing tissue anterior to the external auditory meatus.
Breakage of the sclera.
A solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter that is characterized by hardening (sclerosis) of the affected skin area (related to collagen thickening).
The presence of a moderate form of hearing impairment.
Congenital occlusion of the vagina or adhesion of the walls of the vagina causing occlusion.
Presence of a protracted or persistent infection by a pathogen potentially related to an underlying abnormality of the immune system that is not able to clear the infection.
Pathological deposition of calcium salts in one or more arteries.
Premature tooth eruption, which can be defined as tooth eruption more than 2 SD earlier than the mean eruption age.
An decreased concentration of chloride in the urine.

Exaggerated bulkiness of the crease or fold of skin running from the lateral margin of the nose, where nasal base meets the skin of the face, to a point just lateral to the corner of the mouth (cheilion, or commissure).
A deviation from the normal straight form of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe.
Being confined or restricted to a particular location.
An abnormal increase in the amount of intracellular lipid droplets in hepatocytes.
Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of stainable substances within cardiomyocytes.
Inflammation of the large airways of the lung with rapid onset and short course usually associated with cough, mucus production, shortness of breath, wheezing, and chest tightness.
An increased white blood cell count in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Placement of the nipples at a lower than normal location.
Developmental hypoplasia of the adrenal glands.
A deformity of foot and ankle that has different subtypes that are talipes equinovarus, talipes equinovalgus, talipes calcaneovarus and talipes calcaneovalgus.
The presence of a fistula connecting the urinary bladder to the vagina.

A pituitary functional deficit affecting all the anterior pituitary hormones (growth hormone, thyroid-stimulating hormone, follicle-stimulating hormone, luteinizing hormone, adrenocorticotropic hormone, and prolactin).
A type of myocardial fibrosis characterized by excessive diffuse collagen accumulation concentrated in perivascular spaces.
Raised, well-circumscribed areas of erythema and edema involving the dermis and epidermis. Urticaria is intensely pruritic, and blanches completely with pressure.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:126485001 MSH:D014581 MEDDRA:10046735 SNOMEDCT_US:247472004 SNOMEDCT_US:64305001 UMLS:C0042109

?def: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the first metacarpal bone.
An abnormal site of the kidney.
A form of poikilocytosis in which the abnormally shaped erythrocytes have notches that results in projections that look like horns.
A zone of darker pigmentation around the central part of the iris with a roughly cloverleaf or flower shape.
Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located near the surface of the skin of the cheeks.
Partial duplication of a phalanx of second toe.
An abnormality of the hindbrain, also known as the rhombencephalon.
A condition in which the eyelids do not close to cover the eye completely.
Displacement of the 3rd finger towards the radial side (i.e., towards the thumb).
The presence of complexes of spikes and waves (2.5-3.5 Hz) in electroencephalography (EEG).
Decreased density/number of eyelashes.
An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in tissue.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the 4th finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.
An abnormally decreased calcium concentration in the urine.
A close blood relative had heart disease.
Congenital developmental defect arising from the primitive branchial apparatus.

A form of subcortical heterotopia with mislocalized gray matter within the white matter.It is defined as longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter. It is part of the lissencephaly spectrum.
Inability to see well at night or in poor light with onset in adulthood.

A benign tumor made up of mostly myofibroblasts that appears almost exclusively on the digits of the hands and feet, rarely involving the thumb or big toe. The lesion displays a proliferation of bland intradermal spindle cells arranged in whorls, fascicles, or a storiform pattern in a collagenous background of varying degrees. Also usually present are perpendicular tumor cell fascicles that extend to the epidermis. The small intracytoplasmic inclusions are said to appear similar to red blood cells. The inclusion bodies have been shown to be made up of densely packed vimentin and actin filaments. The tumor often causes a dome-shaped elevation of the overlying structures, forming a protuberant or polypoid nodule. The overlying epidermis can display a host of changes, including acanthosis, hyperkeratosis, parakeratosis, rete ridge flattening, entrapment of adnexal structures, and, rarely, ulceration.
Fusion of cervical vertebrae at C3 and C4, caused by a failure in the normal segmentation or division of the cervical vertebrae during the early weeks of fetal development.
A deviation from the normal concentration in the circulation of angiostatin, an endogenous angiogenesis inhibitor, which blocks the growth of new blood vessels.
Inflammation of the liver.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against cow milk protein.
An abnormal morphology of the ribs consisting of shorted, abnormally curved ribs. On posteroanterior chest radiography, the ribs show a curvature resembling that of a coat hanger (clothes hanger).
Any deviation from the normal concentration of the HDL2a subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL2A particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 8.80-9.69 nm.

A hemangioblastoma is a benign vascular neoplasm that arises almost exclusively in the central nervous system. Hemangioblastomas consist of a tightly packed cluster of small blood vessels forming a mass of up to 1 or 2 cm in diameter.
A deviation from normal in the ratio of choline to creatine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 5th finger.
A type of anemia caused by premature destruction of red blood cells (hemolysis).
A piece of food that has gotten stuck in the esophagus and prevents further swallowing.

A uniocular condition in which there is fixation of an object by a point other than the fovea. This point adopts the principal visual direction. The degree of the eccentric fixation is defined by its distance from the fovea in degrees.
The presence of a dilated inner part of external acoustic meatus.
An abnormal deviation from normal levels of IgM immunoglobulin in blood.
An abnormality of nerve cell cluster or a group of nerve cell bodies located in the autonomic nervous system.
A colon of abnormally small caliber.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger.
An anomaly of the third toe.

A chronic inflammatory bowel disease that includes characteristic ulcers, or open sores, in the colon. The main symptom of active disease is usually constant diarrhea mixed with blood, of gradual onset and intermittent periods of exacerbated symptoms contrasting with periods that are relatively symptom-free. In contrast to Crohn's disease this special form of colitis begins in the distal parts of the rectum, spreads continually upwards and affects only mucose and submucose tissue of the colon.
A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position.
A kind of breech presentation in which the hips are flexed and the knees are flexed.
Complete duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb. On x-ray two separate bones appear side to side.
The presence of both ovarian and testicular tissues either in the same or in opposite gonads. Affected persons have ambiguous genitalia and may have 46,XX or 46,XY karyotypes or 46,XX/XY mosaicism.
A deviation from the normal straight form of the proximal phalanx of the big toe.
Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the little finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the scalp vertex, often just lateral to the midline.

Chronic accumulation and overgrowth of the fungus Candida albicans on the mucous membranes of the mouth, generally manifested as associated with creamy white lesions on the tongue or inner cheeks, occasionally spreading to the gums, tonsils, palate or oropharynx.
The presence of a triangular form of the mouth.
Ribs that are increased in width and taper to the posterior ends.
Any anomaly of ovarian function.
A clot that obstructs blood flow in a mesenteric vein (the superior and the inferior mesenteric vein drain blood from the small and large intestine).
An increase in the level of hippuric acid in the urine.
Aplasia (congenital absence) of the pectoralis minor on only one side of the chest.
A deviation from the normal concentration of cobalamin (vitamin B12) in the blood. Vitamin B12 is one of the eight B vitamins.
An anomaly of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.
Absence of the distal phalanges of the toes.
An increase in the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
An increased concentration of N,N-dimethylglycine in the urine.
A partial duplication of the ureter such that the duplicated ureters fuse to a single ureter before their insertion into the bladder.
Multiple vesicles distributed in mutiple distinct groups consisting of multiple adjacent vesicles.
A confined region of lax skin that hangs below the level of the surrounding skin. Histopatholigically, there is a loss of elastic fibers in the dermis of the affected region.
An altered ability of any enzyme or their cofactors to act as catalysts. This term includes changes due to altered levels of an enzyme.
A temporary reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood.
A reduced concentration of free 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine in the blood circulation.
The term progressive intellectual disability should be used if intelligence decreases/deteriorates over time.
Lack of skin pigmentation (coloring) of the arms and legs.
A nail of the fifth finger that is diminished in length and width, i.e., underdeveloped nail of little finger.
Clefting of the upper lip affecting the lateral portions of the upper lip rather than the midline/median region.
Dysfunction of the urinary bladder.
A oval and round, colored (usually medium-to dark brown, reddish brown, or flesh colored) lesion. Typically, a melanocytic nevus is less than 6 mm in diameter, but may be much smaller or larger.
An abnormality of the structure or form of the tendons, also often called sinews.
Any structural anomaly of the principal vein draining blood from the upper portion of the body and delivering it to the right ventricle of the heart.
Hemorrhage from the vessels of the choroid.
Progressive spinal muscular atrophy, i.e., muscular weakness and atrophy related to loss of the motor neurons of the spinal cord and brainstem.
A first-trimester prenatal ultrasound finding of abnormal blood flow in the umbilical vein.
Asymmetry observed in the face of a neonate or infant whose face appears symmetric at rest and asymmetric during crying as the mouth is pulled downward on one side while not moving on the other side.
An elevated concentration of luteinizing hormone in the blood.

Histoplasmosis infection involving multiple sites of the body. Disseminated histoplasmosis can involve various organs, including reticuloendothelial organs, gastrointestinal tract, adrenal glands, central nervous system, endovascular structures, kidney, and skin. It typically presents with systemic symptoms like fever, generalized fatigue, night sweats, weight loss, and the symptoms related to the specific organ involved. Severe disseminated disease can manifest as septic shock, multi organ failure, and ARDS.

An increased susceptibility to bacterial upper respiratory tract infections as manifested by a history of recurrent bacterial upper respiratory tract infections (running ears - otitis, sinusitis, pharyngitis, tonsillitis).

A wavering, unsteady voice that reflects involuntary and approximately sinusoidal oscillation of motor unit firings of laryngeal muscles. Vocal tremor results in low frequency modulations of voice frequency or amplitude and intermittent voice instability.

A lymphoproliferative abnormality of the intestine characterized by numerous visible mucosal nodules measuring up to, and rarely exceeding, 0.5 cm in diameter Histologically, hyperplastic lymphoid follicles with large germinal centres are seen in the lamina propria and superficial submucosa. There is enlargement of the mucosal B cell follicles caused by hyperplasia of the follicle centres; surrounded by a normal appearing mantle zone. Disease may involve the stomach, the entire small intestine, and the large intestine.

Os odontoideum is classified into two anatomic types (orthotopic and dystopic). Os odontoideum is defined as an ossicle that consists of smooth and separate caudal portions of the odontoid process. With orthotopic os odontoideum, the ossicle moves with the anterior arch of the atlas, while the dystopic type consists of an ossicle near the basion, or one that is fused with the clivus
A dislocation of the head of the radius from its socket in the elbow joint in an posterior direction.

A developmental defect characterized by abnormal connection of one or more pulmonary veins to the superior or inferior vena cava, the right atrium, or the coronary sinus, resulting in a left-to-right shunt of oxygenated blood.

Normal peripheral blood lymphocytes, when stimulated by phytohemagglutinin (PHA) are cytotoxic for homologous and heterologous cells but not for autologous cells in monolayer culture. The cytotoxic effect is thought to be indicative of the immunological competence of the lymphocytes.
An outward turning (eversion) or rotation of the eyelid margin.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against animal proteins.
An arachnoid cyst located at the margin of the cerebellum and pons.
Any abnormality of the soft tissues, including both connective tissue (tendons, ligaments, fascia, fibrous tissues, and fat).

A skin rash that is characterized by diffuse cutaneous erythema with areas of skin elevation. It may evolve to vesicles or papules as part of a more severe clinical entity. Different degrees of angioedema with involvement of subcutaneous tissue may also appear.
A type of pituitary adenoma that is of unknown cellular origin and that lacks immunocytochemical or fine structural markers. Null cell adenomas are not associated with hormone excess.

Any deviation from the normal level of growth hormone (GH) in the blood circulation. GH or somatotropin is a peptide hormone that stimulates growth, cell reproduction, and cell regeneration. Its secretion from the pituitary is regulated by the neurosecretory nuclei of the hypothalamus, which can release Growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH or somatocrinin) and Growth hormone-inhibiting hormone (GHIH or somatostatin) into the hypophyseal portal venous blood surrounding the pituitary. GH is secreted in a pulsatile manner, which is one of the reasons why an isolated measurement of its blood concentration is not meaningful.
Short (hypoplastic) fifth metatarsal bone.
EEG without electrical activity.
Absence of the biceps muscle.
Inflammation of the sac-like covering around the heart (pericardium).

Strabismus in which the angle of deviation differs depending upon the direction of gaze or according to which eye is fixing, associated with: (i) defective movement of the eye, (ii) asymmetrical accommodative effort.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of the HDL3c subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL3c particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 7.20-7.79 nm.
An abnormality in the size of the ocular globe (eyeball).
Obstruction of the flow of urine through the urethra.
A decreased functionality of the gonad.

A raised growths on the skin of older individuals. The lesion usually is initially light tan and may darken to dark brown or nearly black. The consistent feature of seborrheic keratoses is their waxy, pasted-on or stuck-on look.
Trilobar skull configuration when viewed from the front or behind.
Lack of ossification of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.
Connection of the right atrium to the left ventricle and of the left atrium to the right ventricle in a biventricular heart.
Abnormality of the nostril.
Abnormality of the optic nerve.
Deposition of calcium in the skin.
An abnormality of the development of the fingernails.
A large pigmented lesion measuring 5-15 mm in diameter with irregular, notched, and ill defined border and with color that may range from tan to dark brown to pink.
Abnormally reduced activity of the enzyme phosphoribosyl pyrophosphatesynthetase, which catalyzes the synthesis of PP-ribose-P from ATP and ribose-5-phosphate.

A scaly, crusty lesion caused by damage from the ultraviolet radiation of the sun, with typical location on sun-exposed areas of the skin. Actinic keratosis lesions are often elevated, rough, and wartlike, and may be red, or occasionally tan, pink, or flesh-toned in color.
Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from locations distant from the ventricular system.
Onset of disease at up to 8 weeks of gestation.
An epidermoid cyst in the armpit.
Transient neutropenia caused by an infection, such as with a virus, bacteria or protozoan.
Deposition of calcium salts on both sides of the brain.
An abnormal path of a coronary artery.
An abnormality of chromosome condensation.
Overgrowth of the stratum corneum characterized by flesh-coloured or slightly pigmented smooth or warty papules on the upper surface of hands and feet.

An anomaly in the process of visual accommodation, which is the process of adjustment of the eye to enable sharp vision of objects at different distances. Accommodation is mediated by contraction of the ciliary muscles, which alter the convexity of the lens and, consequently, its refractive power.
A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in a dried blood spot.
The presence of normal overall immunoglobulin levels with deficiency of specific immunoglobulins directed against bacterial polysaccharides.

Engagement in dangerous, risky, and potentially self-damaging activities, unnecessarily and without regard to consequences; lack of concern for one's limitations and denial of the reality of personal danger.
Loss of previously present motor (i.e., movement) abilities.
Benign congenital lesions of the periauricular soft tissue consisting of a blind-ending narrow tube or pit.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes two and three.
Fatty tumors on the eyelids.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the ceruminal gland.
A foot for which the measured width is below the 5th centile for age; or, a foot that appears disproportionately narrow for its length.
Decreased concentration of 1-methylhistidine in the urine.
Reduced ability to move the femur outward to the side.
Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the 4th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
The presence of a row of multiple rounded expansions (beadlike prominences) at the junction of a rib and its cartilage.
A kind of congenital cataract that is characterized by a hollow sphere of punctate opacities involving the fetal nucleus and that usually occurs bilaterally.

A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the aortic origin. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
Presence of more than one exostosis. An exostosis is a benign growth the projects outward from the bone surface. It is capped by cartilage, and arises from a bone that develops from cartilage.
Class to represent frequency of phenotypic abnormalities within a patient cohort.
A type of purpuira in which the lesions are raised (and can therefore be appreciated upon palpation).
An anomaly of the circulating level of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH).
Chronic loss of joint motion of the metacarpophalangeal joint of the 3rd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.
Butterfly vertebrae have a cleft through the body of the vertebrae and a funnel shape at the ends.
Aplasia (absence) of the lymphatic vessels.
An abnormal morphology (form) of the face or its components.

?def: The presence of hypertrophy of the breast.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0020565 MSH:C536821 SNOMEDCT_US:372283008 UMLS:C2225524 SNOMEDCT_US:372281005 SNOMEDCT_US:372285001 UMLS:C0392533

?def: A type of glaucomatous optic neuropathy in an eye that has evidence of angle closure (i.e. significant iridotrabecular contact).
A functional abnormality of the pineal gland.
An increased concentration of the MM isoform of creatine kinase in the blood circulation.
An abnormal restriction of fetal growth with fetal weight below the tenth percentile for gestational age.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:22033007 UMLS:C1386048 UMLS:C0021296 MSH:D005317 MSH:D007236 SNOMEDCT_US:199612005 UMLS:C0015934

?def: Y-shaped metacarpals are the result of a partial fusion of two metacarpal bones, with the two arms of the Y pointing in the distal direction. Y-shaped metacarpals may be seen in combination with polydactyly.

A type of atrial flutter associated with rounded or bimodal positive deflections in inferior leads II, III and aVF, and a very characteristic bimodal negative wave in the shape of a W is seen in lead V1.
The presence of cyst of the intrahepatic bile duct.
Seizures with regularly repetitive myoclonus, involving the same muscle groups, at a frequency of about 2-3 c/sec.
Recurrent obsessions or compulsions that are severe enough to be time consuming (i.e., they take more than 1 hour a day) or cause marked distress or significant impairment (DSM-IV).
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:12479006 SNOMEDCT_US:191736004 MSH:D009771 MSH:D003192 UMLS:C0600104 UMLS:C0028768

?def: Delay of conduction through the atrioventricular node, which is manifested as prolongation of the PR interval in the electrocardiogram (EKG). All atrial impulses reach the ventricles.
A deviation from the normal serum concentration/activity of lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), which catalyzes the reduction of pyruvate to form lactate.
Abnormally increased body weight.
Small (typically about 1 mm or less in size) depressions on the dorsal nail surface.
Applied to pain that is dull, i.e., not severe but that continues over a long period of time.
The joint between the second metatarsal and the proximal phalanx of the 5th toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.
An acute form of rhabdomyolysis.
A congenital heart defect characteizred by a specific combination of heart defects with a common atrioventricular valve, primum atrial septal defect and inlet ventricular septal defect.
Osteomyelitis of the lower jaw.

Venous dilatation and arteriolar tortuosity of the posterior retinal vessels and may later increase in severity to include iris vascular engorgement, poor pupillary dilatation (rigid pupil), and vitreous haze. This definition has been further refined in the later clinical trials in which the diagnosis of plus disease could be made if sufficient vascular dilatation and tortuosity are present in at least 2 quadrants of the eye.

A deep skin ulcer with a well defined border, which is usually violet or blue. The ulcer edge is often undermined (worn and damaged) and the surrounding skin is erythematous and indurated. The ulcer often starts as a small papule or collection of papules, which break down to form small ulcers with a so called cat's paw appearance. These coalesce and the central area then undergoes necrosis to form a single ulcer.
A form of astigmatism in which one meridian is hyperopic while the one at a right angle to it has no refractive error.
Displacement of the 3rd finger towards the ulnar side (i.e., towards the ring finger).
A thinning out of elastic fibers of the media of the aorta that creates widening of intralamellar spaces, as identified on a stain for elastic fibers.
An abnormality of a hypopharynx.
Partial duplication of middle phalanx of second toe.
A benign bony growth projecting outward from a bone surface within the external auditory canal.
Reduction in the amount of blood flow to the iris.
A unilateral form of developmental dysplasia of the kidney.
A reduction of the addition of fucose sugar units to O-linked glycans.

Femoroacetabular impingement (FAI) results from one or more bony abnormalities that lead to abnormal contact between the acetabulum and the femoral head or neck. The femoral abnormality is proposed to cause compression and shear stresses in the region between the labrum and cartilage, anterosuperiorly. These stresses cause a separation between the labrum and cartilage as the labrum is pushed outwards and the cartilage is pushed centrally. This eventually leads to articular degeneration and eventually global hip osteoarthritis.
Any functional anomaly of the pumonary valve.

The neovascularization accumulates at the edge of the vascularized retina and extends into the vitreous (also called extra retinal fibrosis proliferation). In cases of Zone 2 and Zone 3, this may be sausage shaped. In more posterior Zone 1 disease, the stage 3 can appear as a direct extension of the normal retinal vessels but extending tangentially over the avascular retina.
Recurrent attacks of severe anxiety, whose occurence is not restricted to any particular situation or set of circumstances and is therefore unpredictable.
Loss of visual acuity (implying that vision was better at a certain timepoint in life). Otherwise the term reduced visual acuity should be used (or a subclass of that).
A increased anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.
An abnormality of the normal developmental rotation of the kidney leading to an abnormal orientation of the kidney.

A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the middle phalanges of the hand. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against granulocyte-macrophage colony stimulating factor.
An abnormality of the dermatoglyphs, i.e., an abnormality of the patterns of ridges of the skin of palm of hand.
A type of aortic medial fibrosis in which the increase in collagen does not significantly alter the arrangement of the lamellar units.
A kind of focal dystonia characterized by forceful contractions of the face, jaw, and/or tongue causing difficulty in opening and closing the mouth and often affecting chewing and speech.
The dividing wall between left and right sides of the heart, thickens and bulges into the left ventricle.
Absence or underdevelopment of the distal phalanges of the toes.
A type of lymphoma characterized microscopically by the absence of multinucleated Reed-Sternberg cells.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:1929004 MSH:D008228 SNOMEDCT_US:128929007 UMLS:C0024305 SNOMEDCT_US:118601006 SNOMEDCT_US:188675007

?def: 2,3-diphosphoglycerate (2,3-DPG) controls the movement of oxygen from red blood cells to tissues. Anemia is usually accompanied by an increased level of 2,3-DPG in order to promote tissue oxygenation. This term refers to an inappropriate low 2,3-DPG concentration in erythrocytes.
A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in red blood cells.
Wasting of the sural nerve, a sensory nerve in the calf region of the leg.
Presence of some auricular structures, but none of these structures conform to recognized ear components.
Photosensitivity of the skin occurring early in life.
Contractures of one ore more joints of the feet meaning chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.
