Underdevelopment of the body of ilium.
Abnormally low glucose concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Ribs with a reduced diameter.
An elevation of bone density in the distal phalanx of the thumb.

The term osteoma refers to the anomalous presence of ossification (bone formation) in the interior of the dermis or epidermis. The dermal or subcutaneous bone formation presents as stony hard nodules. The osteomata appear as irregular, hardened small nodules that are well circumscribed and generally of the same color as the skin.
A greater than normal concentration of 2-oxoglutaric acid in the urine.

Interrupted inferior vena cava with azygous continuation is the result of connection failure between the right subcardinal vein and the right vitelline vein. Consequently, venous blood from the caudal part of the body reaches the heart via the azygous vein and superior vena cava.

The term Maturity-onset diabetes of the young (MODY) was initially used for patients diagnosed with fasting hyperglycemia that could be treated without insulin for more than two years, where the initial diagnosis was made at a young age (under 25 years). Thus, MODY combines characteristics of type 1 diabetes (young age at diagnosis) and type 2 diabetes (less insulin dependence than type 1 diabetes). The term MODY is now most often used to refer to a group of monogenic diseases with these characteristics. Here, the term is used to describe hyperglycemia diagnosed at a young age with no or minor insulin dependency, no evidence of insulin resistence, and lack of evidence of autoimmune destruction of the beta cells.
An abnormality of the dentate nucleus.
The presence of an odontoma.
Isolated patches of hardened skin (scleroderma).
Absence of tear secretion.
An increased level of alanine in the urine.
Detection of molindone in the blood, an antipyschotic used for treatment of schizophrenia.

Multicystic dysplasia of the kidney is characterized by multiple cysts of varying size in the kidney and the absence of a normal pelvicaliceal system. The condition is associated with ureteral or ureteropelvic atresia, and the affected kidney is nonfunctional.
Secretion of gonadotropin-releasing hormone that does not occur in a pulsatile fashion.
Detectable but decreased IgA levels that are more than 2 standard deviations below normal age-adjusted means.
Abnormal conduction in all three divisions of the intraventricular conducting tissue.
Abnormally flat configuration of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.
An anomaly of the process of formation of bone in the humerus.
The proximal interphalangeal joint of the 3rd toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.
A malignancy of the parathyroid glands. Parathyroid carcinoma usually secretes parathyroid hormone, leading to hyperparathyroidism.
A congenital defect characterized by the absence of one or more permanent teeth, including oligodontia, hypodontia, and adontia of the of permanent teeth.
A type of chronic kidney disease with mildly reduced glomerular filtration rate (GFR 60-89 mL/min/1.73 m2).
Complete duplication of the first metacarpal bone.
Muscular atrophy that does not display a progression in severity with time.
The presence of renal casts (cylindrical, cigar-shaped structures produced by the kidney in certain disease states) in the urine.
An increase in the level of galactitol in the urine.
Hemorrhage occurring between the dura mater and the skull.
Dysfunction of the proximal tubule, which is the portion of the duct system of the nephron of the kidney which leads from Bowman's capsule to the loop of Henle.
Decreased width of the metacarpal bones (that is, reduced diameter).
Any functional anomaly of the ear.
A moderate degree of slow or limited growth after birth, being between three and four standard deviations below age- and sex-related norms.
Decreased concentration of dopamine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
Hematuria that is visible upon inspection of the urine.

Anteriorly-facing nostrils viewed with the head in the Frankfurt horizontal and the eyes of the observer level with the eyes of the subject. This gives the appearance of an upturned nose (upturned nasal tip).
The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of retinal blood vessels (arteries, arterioles, veins, venules).
Increased susceptibility to infections.
Curved appearance of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.
Abnormal anatomic location of the anterior pituitary gland.

An abnormally reduced head circumference in a growing child. Head circumference is measured with a nonelastic tape and comprises the distance from above the eyebrows and ears and around the back of the head. The measured HC is then plotted on an appropriate growth chart. Microcephaly is defined as a head circumference (HC) that is great than two standard deviations below the mean of age- and gender-matched population based samples. Severe microcephaly is defined with an HC that is three standard deviations below the mean.
Increased circulating level of apolipoprotein B, which is the main apolipoprotein of chylomicrons and low density lipoproteins. It occurs in plasma as two main isoforms, apoB-48 and apoB-100.
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 4th finger.

An increase in circulating immunoglobulins characterized by a single band in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase in circulating immunoglobulins.
Involuntary sounds produced by moving air through the nose, mouth, or throat. The vocal cords are not involved in all tics that produce sound.
A type of lymphoma characterized microscopically by multinucleated Reed-Sternberg cells.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:118599009 SNOMEDCT_US:118606001 SNOMEDCT_US:46923007 SNOMEDCT_US:14537002 SNOMEDCT_US:74189002 UMLS:C0019829 MSH:D006689 SNOMEDCT_US:70600005 SNOMEDCT_US:118602004 SNOMEDCT_US:118605002

?def: Abnormally decreased levels of threonine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Blisters arising in the mouth.
An abnormal reduction of the concentration of bicarbonate, HCO3[-], in the circulation.
Partial or complete wasting (loss) of hippocampus tissue that was once present.
Curved appearance of the phalanges of the 4th (ring) finger.
Bowing (abnormal curvature) of the femur.

An increase in the distance between vertebral pedicles, which are the two short, thick processes, which project backward, one on either side, from the upper part of the vertebral body, at the junction of its posterior and lateral surfaces.
Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of all or part of the middle ear.
A mode of inheritance in which a trait or disorder results from a de novo mutation occurring after conception, rather than being inherited from a preceding generation.
A secondary ossification center in the fourth finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

Complete absence of the dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, that is, absence of the inner and the outer dynein arms, which normally are situated inside and outside of the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.
Any structural anomaly in the areas surrounding the hair follicles.
Loss of strength in all four limbs. Tetraplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas Tetraparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength.

A structural abnormality of the peripheral nervous system, which is composed of the nerves that lead to or branch off from the central nervous system. This includes the cranial nerves (olfactory and optic nerves are technically part of the central nervous system).
An abnormal shape of occiput.
An increased amount of urobilinogen present in the stool.
An increased lymphocyte count in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced alpha dystroglycan protein in the muscle biopsy. Alpha-dystroglycan is a heavily glycosylated peripheral-membrane component of the dystrophin-associated glycoprotein complex (DAPC), which, in addition to laminin alpha2, binds perlecan and agrin in the extracellular matrix, whereas beta-dystroglycan, derived from the same gene, is a transmembrane protein that links to dystrophin intracellularly.
A deviation from the normal size of the pancreas.
A type of carcinoma of the kidney with origin in the epithelium of the proximal convoluted renal tubule.
The femur is shortened and displays flaring (widening) of the metaphyses.

Patchy (irregular) changes in bone mineral density. These changes can either be patchy reduction or increase of mineral density as seen on x-rays. Depending on the pathomechanism and the underlying disease, these changes can either appear solely as reduction or increase or as a combination of both (patches of bone showing an increased density while others are affected by reduction of mineral density).
Rupture of the eyeball not due to trauma.
An anomaly of a glycosylation process, i.e., a process involved in the covalent attachment of a glycosyl residue to a substrate molecule.
Hypercortisolemia associated with a primary defect of the adrenal gland leading to overproduction of cortisol.
Lack of formation and mineralization of the ribs in utero.

The clinical electro-oculogram (EOG) is an electrophysiological test of function of the outer retina and retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) in which changes in electrical potential across the RPE are recorded during successive periods of dark and light adaptation.

A ranula is a mucocele that occurs in the floor of the mouth and usually involve the major salivary glands. Specifically, the ranula originates in the body of the sublingual gland, in the ducts of the sublingual gland, in the Wharton's duct of the submandibular gland or infrequently from the minor salivary glands at this location.
A type of aganglionic megacolon in which the aganglionic segment comprises the entire colon.
Any abnormality of the neuromuscular junction, which is the synapse between the motor end plate of a motor neuron and the skeletal muscle fibers.
Complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of big toe.
Recurrent episodes of marked eosinophilia that resolve spontaneously.
Decreased posterolateral protrusion of the tragus.
A functional anomaly of the gallbladder.
A reduced level of osteocalcin in the blood.
Forearm shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the forearm.
A type of tumor of the pancreatic beta cells that secretes excess insulin and can result in hypoglycemia.
Aplasia of the pancreas.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the wrist.
Absence of the globe or eyeball.
A delay in the development of skills required to feed oneself in the toddler period (between one and three years of age).
The presence of radial grooves in the skin surrounding the mouth (see Figure 4 of PMID:27833976).
A bending or abnormal curvature of a long bone.
Segmental accumulation of scar tissue in individual (but not all) glomeruli.
Abnormally reduced sulfite oxidase activity.

A type of encephalocele (that is, a a protrusion of part of the cranial contents including brain tissue through a congenital opening in the cranium, typically covered with skin or mucous membrane) in the occipital region of the skull. Occipital encephalocele presents as a midline swelling over the occipital bone. It is usually covered with normal full-thickness scalp.
A deviation from the normally well coordinated pattern of intracellular and intercellular synchrony of motile cilia. Dyskinetic cilia usually beat out of synchrony relative to neighboring cilia.
Being unable to focus one's attention or mental effort on a particular object or activity.
Chronic loss of joint motion of the metacarpophalangeal joint of the thumb due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. This joint is also called Articulatio metacarpophalangealis pollicis.

This term applies if one or more of the phalanges of the 5th finger are either partially duplicated, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance of the phalanges, or completely duplicated.

Cleft of the soft palate (also known as the velum, or muscular palate) as a result of a developmental defect occurring between the 7th and 12th week of pregnancy. Cleft soft palate can cause functional abnormalities of the Eustachian tube with resulting middle ear anomalies and hearing difficulties, as well as speech problems associated with hypernasal speech due to velopharyngeal insufficiency.
A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone cannot be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone or similar glucocorticoids.
Hyperhidrosis that occurs with gustatory stimulation (e.g., moisture on face from sweating that occurs after eating).

A low-grade papillary epithelial neoplasm (adenocarcinoma) with a slow growth pattern. The endolymphatic duct emerges from the posterior wall of the saccule (of the inner ear) and ends in a blind pouch, the endolymphatic sac. Endolymphatic sac tumors (ELSTs) are known under different names in the literature (Heffner tumor, aggressive papillary middle ear tumor, and low-grade adenocarcinoma of endolymphatic sac origin).
A positional abnormality marked by outward bowing of the legs in which the knees stay wide apart when a person stands with the feet and ankles together.
An abnormality of the medullary cavity (medulla, innermost part), which is the central cavity of bone shafts where red bone marrow and/or yellow bone marrow (adipose tissue) is stored.
The presence of a neoplasm of the urethra.
Swelling of the hand at the knuckles, that gives the fingers a spindle shape (i.e., a round stick with tapered end and a broader base).
Synostosis affecting only one of the coronal sutures.
An increased concentration of L-phenylalanine in the blood.

Paralysis of voluntary muscles means loss of contraction due to interruption of one or more motor pathways from the brain to the muscle fibers. Although the word paralysis is often used interchangeably to mean either complete or partial loss of muscle strength, it is preferable to use paralysis or plegia for complete or severe loss of muscle strength, and paresis for partial or slight loss. Paralysis due to lesions of the principle motor tracts is related to a lesion in the corticospinal, corticobulbar or brainstem descending (subcorticospinal) neurons.
An anomaly of the forehead.
Increased width of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.
An abnormality of the prostate.
Patchy increase in bone density of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger.
The loss of intercellular connections, such as desmosomes, resulting in loss of cohesion between keratinocytes.
The presence of telangiectasia of the ear.
An increase in the level of N-acetylneuraminic acid in the urine.
An abnormal immunoglobulin heavy chain in the circulation and typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.

Fifth finger clinodactyly is defined by a hypoplastic or absent mid-phalanx of the fifth digit. Ultrasound identification of the fetal hand must first be undertaken and then appropriate magnification accomplished. The evaluation requires stretching of the 5 fingers. The diagnosis is established when the middle phalanx of the fifth finger is markedly smaller than normal or absent, which often causes the finger to be curved inward (pmid:16100637).
Hemangioma is a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells. This term refers to facial hemangiomas that have a plaque-like morphology.
Underdevelopment of the radius.
Nuclear lobes of neutrophils in the bone marrow are thickened and condensed, and individual lobes are connected by unusually long chromatin filaments.
A severe form of periodontitis.
Elevated concentration of galactose in the urine.
Affective, mnemonic or composite perceptual auras with subjective qualities similar to those experienced in life but are recognized by the subject as occurring outside of actual context.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking sodium.
Deficiency of factor XIII subunit B, leading to a reduced factor XIII activity. Activated Factor XIII cross-links fibrin polymers solidifying the clot.
Reduced ocular movement of the superior oblique muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.
Decrease in width of the nasal tip.
Persistence of virus in the blood circulation longer than would be normal in an immunocompentent host.
The presence of a size difference between the left and right cornea.

Small cell lung cancer (SCLC) is a type of highly malignant lung cancer that is composed of small ovoid cells. In the past, SCLC was called oat cell carcinoma because the microscopic appearance of the cells was felt to resemble oats. SLCLC usually originates near the bronchi and in many cases may grow and metastasize quickly.
Absence or underdevelopment of the femur.

Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking galactose. Galactose usually is ingested as lactose, which is composed of equimolar amounts of glucose and galactose.
An abnormality of the head.
Atrophy of the levator palpebrae superioris, the extraocular muscle that elevates the superior eyelid.
An abnormal phosphate concentration in the urine.
An abnormality of the upper respiratory tract.
An increase in the level of hippuric acid in the blood.
An abnormality that involves the tubules and interstitial tissue of the kidney.
A type of vertical tropia in which, when one eye is fixing, the other eye is deviated upwards.
Areas of brighter than expected MRI signal in the white matter of the brain whereby individual patches run together.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger.

A joint disorder caused by blood deprivation in the subchondral bone causing the subchondral bone to die in a process called avascular necrosis. The bone is then reabsorbed by the body, leaving the articular cartilage it supported prone to damage. The result is fragmentation (dissection) of both cartilage and bone, and the free movement of these osteochondral fragments within the joint space, causing pain and further damage.
A deviation from the normal concentration of amylase in the blood, an enzyme which helps digest glycogen and starch. It is produced mainly in the pancreas and salivary glands.
Febrile seizures with generalized tonic-clonic semiology, duration less than 15 minutes, and without recurrence within the next 24 hours.
A type of glaucomatous optic neuropathy occuring in the presence of a narrow anterior chamber angle.
Increased width of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger.
A condition in which the skin can be stretched beyond normal, and then returns to its initial position.
An inward turning (inversion) of the margin of the upper eyelid.
The age group when the cessation of life happens.
Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the ring finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
A state of renal tubular unresponsiveness or resistance to the action of aldosterone.
Decreased strength of the superior rectus muscle.
Reduced anteroposterior thickness of the retina. This phenotype can be appreciated by retinal optical coherence tomography (OCT).
Asymmetry between the two irides or asymmetry between different parts of one iris.
A saccade that overshoots the target with the dynamic saccade.

Interictal refers to a period of time between epileptic seizures. Electroencephalographic (EEG) patterns are important in the differential diagnosis of epilepsy, and the EEG is almost always abnormal during a seizure. Some persons with seizures may show EEG abnormalities between seizures, while others do not. In some cases, multiple interictal EEGs must be recorded before an abnormality is observed. In most cases the electrographic pattern of seizure onset is completely different from the activity recorded during interictal discharge.
An abnormality of canine tooth.
Abnormally increased sensitivity to pain.
A decreased magnitude of the sensory perception of sound.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0018772 SNOMEDCT_US:103276001 SNOMEDCT_US:95828007 UMLS:C1384666 MSH:D003638 MSH:D034381 UMLS:C0011053 SNOMEDCT_US:15188001 Fyler:4868 UMLS:C0339789 SNOMEDCT_US:343087000

?def: The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the corpus callosum.
Protrusion of the meninges and portions of the spinal cord through a defect of the vertebral column.
An increase in the degree of curvature of the cornea compared to normal.
Multiple skin warts located in multiple parts of the body, e.g., neck, trunks, and extremities.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a monocarboxylic acid in the blood circulation.
A type of blistering that affects the skin of the tibial region.
An abnormality of the palm, that is, of the front of the hand.
A structural abnormality of a diaphysis of the arm.
A decreased anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.
Muscular atrophy affecting the muscles of the limb girdle.

Metachromasia (also known as metachromacy) is a characteristic color change which certain aniline dyes exhibit when bound to particular substances or when concentrated in solution. For example, the basic dye toluidine blue becomes distinctly pink when bound to cartilage matrix. In the sense used here, the metachromasia refers to a change in color not observed with normal tissues, anomalous staining with the cationic dyes toluidine blue O and Alcian blue resulting from excessive amounts of the polyanionic glycosaminoglycans.
An abnormal reduction in the inflammatory response to injury or infection.
Absence of globe, optic nerve, chiasm and optic tracts. No evidence of ocular tissue on MRI scan or examination.
An inflammatory cellular deposit deposited on the corneal endothelium and visible as spots on the cornea.
If positive, the ferric chloride test indicates an increased concentration of phenols in the urine or blood.
Reduced density of hairs.
An increased concentration of tryptophan in the urine.
An abnormality of the cerebral cortex.
Underdevelopment of the optic nerve.
The presence of multiple polyps in the small intestine.
An elevated level of myoinositol in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Absence of melanin pigment in various areas, which is found at birth and is permanent. The lesions are known as leucoderma and are often found on the face, trunk, or limbs.
An abnormality of a ciliary ganglion.
The areola (ring of pigmented skin surrounding the nipple) is filled out so as to produce a rounded shape.
A developmental defect characterized by a cleft of some portion of the eye or ocular adnexa.
A tongue-like protusion from the anterior aspect of lumbar vertebral bodies.
An acute form of disseminated intravascular coagulation. Acute DIC can occur following sudden exposure of blood to procoagulants, with the compensatory hemostatic mechanisms becoming overwhelmed.
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.
An abnormality in voluntary or involuntary eye movements or their control.
Median longitudinal ear length less than two SD above the mean determined by the maximal distance from the superior aspect to the inferior aspect of the external ear.

Underdevelopment of the zygomatic bone [UBERON_0001683]. That is, a reduction in size of the zygomatic bone, including the zygomatic process of the temporal bone of the skull, which forms part of the zygomatic arch.
A diminished activity of the classical complement pathway as measured by the assay for 50% haemolytic complement (CH50) activity of serum.
Excessive action of the superior rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.
A congenital anomaly with lack of part of the pericardium on the righthand side of the heart.
Reduced volume of the testicle (the male gonad).
Bizygomatic (upper face) and bigonial (lower face) width greater than 2 standard deviations above the mean (objective); or an apparent increase in the width of the face (subjective).
Reduced amount of myelin in the central nervous system resulting from defective myelinogenesis.
Abnormally increased serum levels of alkaline phosphatase activity.
A loss of adipose tissue.
An abdominal mass formed by bleeding into a follicular ovarian cyst or corpus luteum cyst.
Short first metatarsal bone.
A benign brown pigmented area over the iris representing proliferation of melanocyte cells in the stromal layer of the iris. An iris nevus can be flat or occasionally slightly elevated.
Some or all of the metacarpal bones (i.e., metacarpal II to V) have a pointed proximal appearance.
A chronic form of sinusitis.
A deviation of the normal proportion of non-class-switched memory B cells in circulation relative to the total number of B cells.

Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at one or more long bones in the foot, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.
A deviation from normal of the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
Underdevelopment of frontal sinus.
A tumor that originates in the pineal gland, has moderate cellularity and tends to form rosette patterns.
Noncompaction cardiomyopathy that affects both ventricles.
A type of age-related cataract that primarily affects the cortex of the lens.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger is affected.
Attachment of the lobe to the side of the face at the lowest point of the lobe without curving upward.
Any abnormality of the fifth metacarpal bone.
Malignant tumor of melanocytes of the ciliary body.
Regional increase in the width (height) of the eyebrow.
An anomalous amount or location of cell junction proteins such as plakoglobin or Cx43.
Infantile spasms represent a subset of \epileptic spasms\". Infantile Spasms are epileptic spasms starting in the first year of life (infancy)."
Fusion of the epiphysis and metaphysis of one or more phalanges prior to the normal age or stage of growth.
Antihelical ridge that forms an acute angle between the antitragus and its bifurcation (stem) instead of a gently curving arc.
An increased concentration of chondroitin sulfate (CHEBI:37397) in the urine.
An aggravating factor is defined as an external factor that leads to a sign or symptom that is already present getting worse or becoming more severe.
Focal proliferation of glial cells in the hypothalamus.
Spontaneous pain is a kind of neuropathic pain which occurs without an identifiable trigger.
A structural anomaly of the globe of the eye, or bulbus oculi.
An inflammation of the choroid and retina.
An abnormal concentration of insulin in the body.
An decreased number of circulating monocytes.
Inflammation of a vein associated with venous thrombosis (blood clot formation within the vein).
Ultra-low vision but with retained ability to identify a moving object (typically hand motion at distance of 30 cm).
Metaphyseal cupping affecting the metacarpal bones.
Inability to elicit tendon reflexes in the upper limbs.

A sensation of tightness in the neck when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity. Neck stiffness often involves soreness and difficulty moving the neck, especially when trying to turn the head to the side.

Multiple foci of adipocytes within the testicular interstitium, usually presenting as multiple bilateral ill-defined hyperechoic intratesticular lesions of different sizes but generally with maximum diameter of 4 mm.
A soft tissue prominence of the ventral aspects of the fingertips or toe tips.
An abnormally increased ability of the skin to permit light to pass through (translucency) such that subcutaneous structures such as veins display an increased degree of visibility.
Spasticity and weakness of the leg and hip muscles.
A decrease in the level of erythritol in the urine.
Reduced length of the proximal phalanx of second toe as a result of developmental hypoplasia.
Antihelix protrusion directed more anteriorly than laterally, forming a shelf overlying the posterior concha.
Increased width of the proximal part of the shaft (metaphysis) of the femur.
Any anomaly in the formation of the bony substance of the sternum.
Supernumerary digits located at the ulnar side of the hand with a complete extra finger and extra metacarpal.
A recurrent infection of the GI tract with helicobacter pylori, a gram-negative, microaerophilic bacterium usually found in the stomach.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of serine in the blood circulation.
Severely slow or limited growth after birth, being four standard deviations or more below age- and sex-related norms.
Divergence of digits along the anteroposterior axis (in the plane of the sole).
An abnormally decreased concentration of transferrin in the blood circulation.
A gonad that contains both ovarian follicles and testicular tubular elements.

?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:248342006 SNOMEDCT_US:262285001 UMLS:C1844806 UMLS:C0041667 UMLS:C1262477 MSH:D015431 MSH:D013851 SNOMEDCT_US:89362005 SNOMEDCT_US:161832001

?def: An increased amount of cystine in the blood.

Diffusely widened perivascular spaces in the basal ganglia, affecting especially the corpus striatum. Status cribrosum is usually symmetrical, with the perivascular spaces showing CSF signal and without diffusion restriction. The word cribriform means sievelike, with multiple perforations.
An increase in the number of immune cells in myocardial tissue concentrated in the spaces surrounding blood vessels.
An abnormal reduction in the amplitude of the a-wave.
Absent 3rd finger.
Dilatation of small blood vessels of the retina.

?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:77121009 SNOMEDCT_US:414629003 UMLS:C0024314 MSH:D008232 SNOMEDCT_US:277466009 SNOMEDCT_US:84631004

?def: Persistent overgrowth of Candida albicans in the gastrointestinal tract.

An ostium primum atrial septal defect is located in the most anterior and inferior aspect of the atrial septum. The ostium primum refers to an anterior and inferior opening (ostium) within the septum primum, which divides the rudimentary atrium during fetal development. The ostium primum is normally sealed by fusion of the superior and inferior endocardial cushions around 5 weeks' gestation. Ostium primum defects result from a failure of the fusion of the embryologic endocardial cushion and septum primum.
?xrefs: MSH:C548006 Fyler:1110 SNOMEDCT_US:253373002 UMLS:C0344735 UMLS:C0741296 MSH:C536112

?def: A benign fluid filled simple cyst of bone filled with serous fluid.
A condition characterized by intermittent involuntary contraction of muscles (spasms) related to hypocalcemia or occasionally magneisum deficiency.

The normal epiphysis of the fifth metacarpal is localised at the distal end of the metacarpal bone. This term aplies if an accesory epiphysis, located at the proximal end of the metacarpal bone, is present.
Abnormal growth of tissue projecting from a mucous membrane of the endocervix.
A structural abnormality of the biliary tree.
Obstruction of conducting airways of the lung.

Reduced bulkiness of the crease or fold of skin running from the lateral margin of the nose, where nasal base meets the skin of the face, to a point just lateral to the corner of the mouth (cheilion or commissure).

By the 14th week of gestation it is nearly always possible to visualized the fluid-filled fetal stomach bubble on prenatal sonography. This term refers to the absence of a normal fetal stomach bubble on fetal ultrasonography performed at around 16 to 20 weeks' gestation.

A supranuclear gaze palsy is an inability to look in a vertical direction as a result of cerebral impairment. There is a loss of the voluntary aspect of eye movements, but, as the brainstem is still intact, all the reflex conjugate eye movements are normal.
A mode of inheritance that depends on a mixture of major and minor genetic determinants possibly together with environmental factors. Diseases inherited in this manner are termed complex diseases.
An abnormally high concentration of serum conjugated estriol as compared to normal values for gestational-age.
An abnormality of the morphology of the epidermis.
A series of rhythmic and involuntary muscle contractions (at a frequency of about 5 to 7 Hz) that occur in response to an abruptly applied and sustained stretch.
A fluid filled cavity that develops with a bone.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:203467005 SNOMEDCT_US:203465002 SNOMEDCT_US:66954000 SNOMEDCT_US:112643007 MSH:D001845 UMLS:C0005937

?def: Inflammation in any serous cavity.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of cholesterol in the blood circulation.
Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the third toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.
A nodule of the skin that exhibits an increased amount of pigmentation.

The term tinea means fungal infection, whereas dermatophyte refers to the fungal organisms that cause tinea. This term refers to a tinea infection that is chronic or recalcitrant to treatment and may be reflective of an immune defect.
An abnormality of a facial vein.
Decreased activity of coagulation factor V.
Overproduction of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) by the anterior pituitary gland.
A decreased amount of histidine in the blood.
An abnormality in perception of contrast as measured by the Vistech wall chart sine wave grating test.
Blockage of the nasolacrimal sac.
Horizontal crease or fold situated below the vermilion border of the lower lip and above the fatty pad of the chin, with the face at rest.
A tumor originating in a bronchus.
Inflammation of the gingiva.
An abnormality of the autonomic nervous system.
An enlargement of the cornea with normal clarity and function. Megalocornea is diagnosed with a horizontal corneal diameter of 12 mm or more at birth or 13 mm or more after two years of age.

Petechiae are pinpoint-sized reddish/purple spots, resembling a rash, that appear just under the skin or a mucous membrane when capillaries have ruptured and some superficial bleeding into the skin has happened. This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to developing petechiae.
An abnormally increased width of the cranial fontanelles and sutures.
Abnormally reduced serum levels of alkaline phosphatase activity.

Any abnormality in the series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a cytokine to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.
An abnormality of the talus.
Diverticulum (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urinary bladder.
A facial cleft characterized by involvment of the orbit.
The presence of an abnormally thick calvaria.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the pancreas.
?xrefs: NCIT:C3262 UMLS:C0030297 UMLS:C1842408 UMLS:C0346647 SNOMEDCT_US:363418001 SNOMEDCT_US:126859007 MSH:D010190

?def: An increased susceptibility to meningitis as manifested by a medical history of recurrent episodes of meningitis.
A reduced concentration of 5-methyltetrahydrofolate(2-) in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). 5-methyltetrahydrofolate is the active folate metabolite.
Inner aspect of the upper lip vermilion (normally apposing the teeth) visible in a frontal view, i.e., the presence of an everted upper lip.
So-called honeycombs (variably sized cysts in a background of densely scarred tissue) located in the subpleural space.
Osteolysis involving metatarsal bones.
In otosclerosis, a callus of bone accumulates on the stapes creating a partial fixation. This limits the movement of the stapes bone, which results in hearing loss.
Punctal stenosis is a condition in which the external opening of the lacrimal canaliculus is narrowed or occluded.
A type of aganglionic megacolon in which the aganglionic segment extends proximal to the sigmoid.
Underdevelopment of the hippocampus.
Presence of myoglobin in the urine following exercise.
Diffuse enlargement of the entire cerebral hemispheres leading to macrocephaly (with or without overlying cortical dysplasia).
A reduced circulating concentration of adiponectin, a 30-kDa complement C1-related protein that is the most abundant secreted protein expressed in adipose tissue.
A circumscribed, solid elevation of skin with no visible fluid that is reddish (erythematous) in color.
Reduced resistance to rupture of capillary blood vessels. Capillary fragility may manifest as a bleeding diathesis with spontaneous ecchymoses (bruises).
Absence of the knee jerk reflex, which can normally be elicited by tapping the patellar tendon with a reflex hammer just below the patella.
An abnormality of premolar tooth.
A tremor present when the limbs are active, either when outstretched in a certain position or throughout a voluntary movement.
A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance beween the vertebral endplates affecting the thoracic spine.
An increased susceptibility to abscess formation, as manifested by a medical history of recurrent abscesses.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of bicarbonate, HCO3[-], in the circulation.

A chronic granulomatous inflammatory disease of the intestines that may affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus, causing a wide variety of symptoms. It primarily causes abdominal pain, diarrhea which may be bloody, vomiting, or weight loss, but may also cause complications outside of the gastrointestinal tract such as skin rashes, arthritis, inflammation of the eye, tiredness, and lack of concentration. Crohn's disease is thought to be an autoimmune disease, in which the body's immune system attacks the gastrointestinal tract, causing inflammation.
Multiple small zones of sarcomeric disorganization and lack of oxidative activity (known as minicores) in type 1 and type 2 muscle fibers.
A type of exotropia in which either eye may be used for fixation.
Absence of urine, clinically classified as below 50ml/day.
Any structural anomaly of the putamen, a brain nucleus which together with the caudate nucleus and fundus striati makes up the striatum.
A bony projection (spur, osteophyte) originating from the femur, often in the medial femoral neck.
Always present, i.e. in 100% of the cases.
Arteriosclerosis occurring at an age that is younger than usual.
An abnormality of the coccyx.

Abnormal reduction in length of a tendon which tends to pull (retract) the attached muscle tissue with shortening of the muscle fibers often accompanied by atrophy and fatty degeneration of the affected muscle tissue.
Atrophy (loss or wasting) of the retinal pigment epithelium observed on fundoscopy or fundus imaging.
Increased size of the ridge of tissue that extends along the midline of the scrotum.
Deviation from the normal concentration of ornithine in the blood circulation.
The presence of an abnormal lateral curvature of the spine.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0037932 SNOMEDCT_US:111266001 UMLS:C0700208 MSH:D013121 SNOMEDCT_US:64217002 Fyler:4160

?def: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the distal epiphysis of the ulna.

Distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border.
Formation of clumps or aggregates that make up small protuberances from elastic fibers within the dermis (especially the reticular dermis).
Recurrent episodes of brain dysfunction that may be triggered by factors such as metabolic disturbances or infections.

The controller signal for saccadic eye movements has two components: the pulse that moves the eye rapidly from one point to the next, and the step that holds the eye in the new position. When both the pulse and the step are not the correct size, a dysmetric refixation eye movement results.
Absence or underdevelopment of the musculature of the upper limbs.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the tongue.
A condition in which superficial veins (i.e., veins just under the skin) are more conspicuous or noticable than normal.
A kinked appearance of the brainstem, i.e., an exaggerated flexure.

Corneal guttata are droplet-like accumulations of non-banded collagen on the posterior surface of Descemet's membrane. The presence of focal thickenings of Descemet's membrane histologically named guttae. Cornea guttata can be easily diagnosed in vivo and ex vivo by means of specular microscopy as it gives dark areas where no endothelial cells are visible.
A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in lung parenchyma, which leads to a cavity, and after formation of bronchopulmonary fistula, can manifest as an air-fluid level inside the cavity.
Numerous lymphocytes surrounding blood vessels in the superfical part of the dermis.
One or more bent (flexed) joints of the fifth toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.
An abnormality of the second finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
Benign neoplasia derived from lipoblasts or lipocytes of white or brown fat. May be angiomatous or hibernomatous.
?xrefs: MPATH:417 MSH:D008067 UMLS:C0023798 MEDDRA:10024612 SNOMEDCT_US:46720004 SNOMEDCT_US:93163002

?def: An abnormality of the neck.
A loss of the ability to move the vocal fold on both sides.
An abnormally increased chloride concentration in the blood.
An abnormality of the structure or form of the diaphysis, i.e., of the main or mid-section (shaft) of a long bone.
Passing the age when puberty normally occurs with no physical or hormonal signs of the onset of puberty.
An abnormality of the middle ear.
An anomaly of the humeral epiphysis.
A functional anomaly of the nervous system.

A lamellar pattern visible on radiographs and mainly localized at the metaphyses of the long tubular bones. Pathologic-anatomical studies revealed that these benign signs on x-rays are the result of a juvenile metaphyseal bone necrosis. Calcifications in the necrotic marrow lead to this lamellar or lattice-like appearance.
An increased concentration of leptin in the blood.
Increased width of the distal part of the shaft (metaphysis) of the femur.
The presence of a neoplasm of the gallbladder.

This sign is created by a nonenhancing thrombus in the dural sinus surrounded by triangular enhancing dura as seen on cross-section. The sign, seen on contrast-enhanced CT scan images, suggests dural sinovenous thrombosis. It is best seen on wider window settings. It is a reliable sign of sinus thrombosis but is seen only in 25-30% of these cases.
Hyperexcitability of the neuromuscular system related to abnormally low level of calcium in the blood, resulting in carpopedal or generalized spasms.
Tinnitus is an auditory perception that can be described as the experience of sound, in the ear or in the head, in the absence of external acoustic stimulation.
A reduction in the number of axons in the peripheral nervous system.
An inability or difficulty differentiating among the fingers of either hand as well as the hands of others.
A reduction from the normal level of major histocompatibility complex class II molecules expressed at the cell surface.
Aorto-ventricular tunnel is a congenital, extracardiac channel which connects the ascending aorta above the sinutubular junction to the cavity of the left, or (less commonly) right ventricle.
Decreased quantity of von Willebrand factor.
An abnormality of the distribution of hair growth that is acquired during the course of life.

A form of extranodal, high-grade non-Hodgkin B-cell neoplasm, usually large cell or immunoblastic type that originates in the brain, leptomeninges, spinal cord, or eyes and typically remains confined to the CNS.
Descreased amplitude of eletrical response upon electroretinography.
Demyelinating neuropathy is characterized by slow nerve conduction velocities with reduced amplitudes of sensory/motor nerve conduction and prolonged distal latencies.

A halo or spoke-wheel arrangement of cells surrounding a central core or hub. The central hub may consist of an empty-appearing lumen or a space filled with cytoplasmic processes. The cytoplasm of each of the cells in the rosette is often wedge-shaped with the apex directed toward the central core; the nuclei of the cells participating in the rosette are peripherally positioned and form a ring or halo around the hub.
A tendency towards rising very late in the morning and going to bed late at night.
A reduction in immunoglobulin levels of the IgG3 subclass in the blood circulation.
The pattern in which a particular genetic trait or disorder is passed from one generation to the next.
An abnormality of dermatoglyphs on the toes and soles, i.e., an abnormality of the patterns of ridges of the skin of sole of foot.
Failure of oocytes to proceed through the stages of meiosis with stoppage at the first metaphase stage.
A structural anomaly of a neuron.
Absence or underdevelopment of the carpal bones.
Abnormal development (dysgenesis) of the anterior segment of the eye globe. These structures are mainly of mesenchymal origin.
Absence or underdevelopment of the Maxilla.
A benign biphasic tumor of the breast with epithelial and stromal components.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of neopterin in the blood circulation.
An increase in the level of D-threitol in the plasma.
Nails whose growth is slower than normal.
Depression of profile in both temporal regions.
Multifocal slowing of cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
A type of stereotypic behavior in which the affected individual repeatedly waves the hands up and down.
An abnormality of the stapes, a stirrup-shaped ossicle in the middle ear.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the lower back.
Lack of the lunula at the base of a nail. The lunula is the crescent-shaped whitish area of the bed of a fingernail or toenail.
A teratoma located within the mediastinum (the cavity between the pleural sacs that contains the heart and all of the thoracic viscera except the lungs).
Increased concentration of porphobilinogen in the urine.
A secondary ossification center in the proximal phalanx of the third finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
Atrophy of the muscles of the ankle.
Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the 4th (ring) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
Premature rupture of membranes (PROM) is a condition which occurs in pregnancy when the amniotic sac ruptures more than an hour before the onset of labor.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against bacteria.
Fusion of a metacarpal bone with the proximal phalanx of the finger distal to it across the corresponding metacarpophalangeal joint.
A benign epithelial neoplasm composed of layers of oncocytes (small round nucleus, micro-granular, eosinophilic cytoplasm with numerous tightly-packed mitochondria.
A reduced ability to synthesize postvaccination antibodies against a hepatitis B antigen, as measured by antibody titer determination following vaccination.
Absence of the eyebrow.
?xrefs: UMLS:C4280582 UMLS:C0431448 SNOMEDCT_US:422441003 UMLS:C0578682 SNOMEDCT_US:253208007 UMLS:C4280581

?def: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe.
Inflammation of the liver due to infection with enterovirus.
Seizures with sudden loss or diminution of muscle tone with a preceding myoclonic or tonic event lasting one to two seconds or more, involving head, trunk, jaw or limb musculature.

A type of rigidity in which a muscle responds with cogwheellike jerks to the use of constant force in bending the limb (i.e., it gives way in little, repeated jerks when the muscle is passively stretched).
A basal cell carcinoma that originates in the anal margin.
Increased length of the middle phalanx of finger.
An anomaly of the addition of fucose sugar units to N-linked glycans.
Absence of the musculature.
A progressive type of conductive deafness.
Inflammation of a superficial vein associated with venous thrombosis (blood clot formation within the vein).
Increased length of the upper eyelashes.
An increase above normal limits of the ratio of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) albumin concentration to serum albumin concentration.
Progressive maculopathy characterized by concentric regions of hyper- and hypo-pigmentation.
Decreased inferosuperior length of the sternum.

An abnormality of the vestibulo-ocular reflex (VOR). The VOR attempts to keep the image stable on the retina. Ideally passive or active head movements in one direction are compensated for by eye movements of equal magnitude.
A small pupil (typically diameter less than 2 mm) that dilates poorly or not at all in response to topically administered mydriatic drugs.
Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in the small bile ducts within the liver.
Poikiloderma refers to a patch of skin with (1) reticulated hypopigmentation and hyperpigmentation, (2) wrinkling secondary to epidermal atrophy, and (3) telangiectasias.

The presence of multiple serrated polyps in the intestine. Unlike conventional adenomas, which are uniformly dysplastic, the vast majority of serrated lesions contain no dysplasia. The serrated class includes the hyperplastic polyps, which are not considered precancerous; sessile serrated polyps (also called sessile serrated adenomas); and traditional serrated adenomas. Sessile serrated polyps are larger on average and more often located in the proximal colon. Sessile serrated polyps have a more irregular surface, a pattern to the surface that has been called cloudlike, and indistinct edges compared with hyperplastic polyps. Sessile serrated polyps also have large open pits on the surface (type O pits) when viewed with magnification.
Low output of urine, clinically classified as an output below 300-500ml/day.

The cisterna magna is measured on a transaxial view of the fetal head angled 15 degrees caudal to the canthomeatal line. The anterior/posterior diameter is taken between the inferior/posterior surface of the vemis of the cerebellum to the inner surface of the cranium. An enlarged cisternal magna is defined by an anterior/posterior diameter of 10 mm or more (pmid:16100637).
Malignant hyperthermia is characterized by a rapid increase in temperature to 39-42 degrees C in response to inhalational anesthetics such as halothane or to muscle relaxants such as succinylcholine.
This term applies to a triangular shaped 1st metacarpal.
Curved appearance of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger.
Irregularities of the iliac crest that produce the appearance of a lace border around it.
Detection of delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) or other cannabinoid metabolites in urine.
Abnormal concentration of dopamine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
A structural anomaly of the trachea.
Any structural anomaly of the ear.
An abnormality of the balance or maintenance of the balance of acids and bases in bodily fluids, resulting in an abnormal pH.

An autoimmune disease where the thyroid is overactive, producing an excessive amount of thyroid hormones (a serious metabolic imbalance known as hyperthyroidism and thyrotoxicosis). This is caused by autoantibodies to the TSH-receptor (TSHR-Ab) that activate that TSH-receptor (TSHR), thereby stimulating thyroid hormone synthesis and secretion, and thyroid growth (causing a diffusely enlarged goiter). The resulting state of hyperthyroidism can cause a dramatic constellation of neuropsychological and physical signs and symptoms, which can severely compromise the patients.
Reduced strength of the distal musculature of the legs.
An abnormally elevated concentration of globulins in the blood.
An abnormality of the function of the cardiac atria.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to sound or noise.
An inflammatory arthritis characterized by purulent synovial fluid with neutrophil accumulation, but with negative cultures.
An abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the third toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
The age group in which disease manifestations appear.
A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in thyrotropin-releasing hormone activity.
A specific learning disability involving mathematics and arithmetic.
A form of latent strabismus (heterophoria) in which, on dissociation, the occluded eye deviates downwards.
The presence of small (ca. 0.5-1.0 mm) dilated blood vessels near the surface of the mucous membranes of the conjunctiva.

Pain is an unpleasant sensation that can range from mild, localized discomfort to agony, whereby the physical part of pain results from nerve stimulation and is often accompanied by an emotional component. This term groups abnormalities in pain sensation presumed to result from abnormalities related to the specific nerve fibers that carry the pain impulses to the brain.

A spindled-to-epithelioid, oncocytic, nonendocrine neoplasm of the anterior hypophysis that manifests in adults and follows a benign clinical course. Pituitary spindle cell oncocytomas are firm, fibrous, and adherent to surrounding structures and are highly vascular.
Decreased platelet cell membrane concentration of glycoprotein Ib.
An abnormal conformation of the femur that becomes gradually enlarged towards the distal end. This feature affects the distal femoral metaphysis and epiphysis.
The presence of a xenobiotic in blood.
A tumor of the skin or mucous membrane with finger-like projections.
The presence of free monoclonal lambda immunoglobulin light chains in the urine.
The presence of an abnormally prominent of the crus of the helix. That is, development of the crus helix to the same degree as an average antihelix stem or helix.
Abnormality of the eleventh cranial nerve.
Decreased number of head hairs per unit area on the anterior region of the scalp.
An abnormal widening of the diameter of the pulmonary artery.
Presence of a monoclonal immunoglobulin M protein in the serum.
Constant exotropia occurring before 6 months of age.; often associated with a large angle of deviation and ocular/CNS abnormalities.
Malignant neoplasms which probably originate in primitive mesenchymal stem cell populations differentiating down a lipomatous pathway.
Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
An anomaly of the outer shell (cortex) of a hand bone.
Inaccurate saccades (rapid movement of the eye between fixation points) in the vertical direction.
Structural abnormality of the basal ganglia related to defective development.
A type of supraventricular tachycardia that originates in the atrioventricular node.
Abnormally short finger associated with developmental hypoplasia.
Decreased strength of the superior oblique muscle.

Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at one or more long bones in the radius, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.
An elevation above the normal concentration of the HDL2b subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL2b particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 9.7-12 nm.
An anomaly of the neck of the uterus (lower part of the uterus), called the uterine cervix.
An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation (reduced or absent) of the iris and retina.
One or more bent (flexed) joints of the fourth toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.
An increase in the amount of fluid present in the peritoneal cavity (between the layers of the peritoneum that lines the abdomen).
An abnormality of the external ear.
Bony swelling of the distal interphalangeal joint (DIP) associated with the formation of osteophytes (calcific spurs) of the articular (joint) cartilage that are visible radiographically.

A condition characterized by obstruction of the airway and by pauses in breathing during sleep occurring many times during the night. Obstructive sleep apnea is related to a relaxation of muscle tone (which normally occurs during sleep) leading to partial collapse of the soft tissues in the airway with resultant obstruction of the air flow.

A type of ulcer that is caused when an area of skin is subject to pressure over a prolonged period of time, ranging in range in severity from patches of discolored skin to open wounds that expose the underlying bone or muscle. The most common sites are the sacrum, coccyx, heels and the hips.
Increased concentration of methylmalonic acid in the blood.
An abnormality of the skeleton of foot.
Elongated and tortuous mesenteric veins, which comprise the inferior mesenteric vein and the superior mesenteric vein.
Wasting of the pectoral muscles, i.e., of the pectoralis major and pectoralis minor.
An abnormally increased concentration of hepcidin in the blood circulation.
An anomaly of cellular morphology or physiology.

A form of watery eye associated with overproduction of tears due to an increased parasympathetic drive to the secretory component of the lacrimal system (lacrimal gland); this could be due to pro-secretory drug use (e.g. pilocarpine) or autonomic disturbance.
Arteriosclerosis (increased thickness, increased stiffness, loss of elasticity) of the small arteries of the brain.
A type of strabismus in which the visual axis of one eye is lower than that of the other.
Recurrent episodes of muscle flaccidity, a type of paralysis in which a muscle becomes soft and yields to passive stretching.
Delayed myelination in the peripheral nervous system.
A benign tumor of the parathyroid gland that can cause hyperparathyroidism.
A gap in the lip or lips.
A type of aganglionic megacolon in which the aganglionic segment does not extend beyond the upper sigmoid.
A nonprogressive (i.e., stationary) form of difficulties with night blindness with congenital onset.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:232061009 SNOMEDCT_US:193687000 MSH:C537743 MSH:C536122 UMLS:C3551052 UMLS:C4048798 UMLS:C1306122 UMLS:C0339535

?def: An ulcer of the gastrointestinal tract.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against seafood.
Anomaly in the level or the function of hemoglobin, the oxygen-carrying protein of erythrocytes.
Decreased concentration of sulfate in the urine.

Increased amount of stacking of erythrocytes into long chains. Rouleaux (singular: rouleau) is derived from a French word that can refer to a stack of coins put into a cylindircal paper roll. Rouleaux formation is observed with increased serum proteins, particularly fibrinogen and globulins, and represents the cause of increased erythrocte sedimentation rate because rouleaux sediment more readily than isolated red blood cells.
An elevation above the normal concentration of manganese in the blood.
Abnormally increased levels of ornithine in cerebrospinal fluid.
An anomaly of metabolism or structure of the brain identified by imaging.
Abnormality of the lung parenchyma extending to the pulmonary interstitium and leading to diffuse pulmonary fibrosis.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb.
A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus. This term refers to a diffuse hypointensity affecting the entire thalamus.
Being located on the left side of the body.
Anterior chamber cells with less than one cell in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.
A condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm.
An increased concentration of glycine in the urine.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of C-reactive protein in the blood circulation.
A secondary ossification center in the distal phalanx of the fifth finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
Columella extending inferior to the level of the nasal base, when viewed from the side.
The giant congenital nevus is greater than 8 cm in size, pigmented and often hairy. A giant congenital nevus is smaller in infants and children, but it usually continues to grow with the child.
Irregular morphology of one or more metacarpal bones.
A sensation of tightness in the hip joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.
Abnormally lax upper eyelid associated with tissue relaxation.
An abnormality of the upper lip.
An anomaly of trapezium.
Wasting (atrophy) of the retinal pigment epithelium present in small, isolated areas.

Loss and/or fragmentation of elastic fibers of the media of the aorta creating increasingly extended translamellar spaces, with absence of elastic fibers, and increased gaps in elastic fiber lamellae as identified on a stain for elastic fibers.
A change in horizontal ocular alignment, unrelated to accommodation, that is brought about solely by a change in the balance of visual input from the two eyes.

Specific drugs interfere selectively with the different cellular mechanisms involved in neuromuscular transmission (synthesis, storage, release, action and inactivation of transmitter). The response of a patient to a specific drug can therefore be useful information for the differential diagnosis.
An elevation above normal limits of estriol concentration in the circulation.
Abnormal shortening of the larynx in the anteroposterior (front to back) axis.
Stagnation of head growth seen as flattening of the head circumference curve.
An decreased concentration of magnesium the urine.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the occipital region.
An abnormal morphology of the middle phalanx of the second toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Impaired function of the exocrine pancreas associated with a reduced ability to digest foods because of lack of digestive enzymes.
Obstruction affecting the biliary tree.
Radiolucency (reflecting a reduction in the bony substance) around the apex (the tip of the dental root).
?xrefs: MSH:D010484 MSH:D011842 SNOMEDCT_US:89988002 UMLS:C4280609 SNOMEDCT_US:81407003 UMLS:C0031029 UMLS:C1852169 UMLS:C0034543

?def: Describes a foot digit resting on the dorsal surface of an adjacent digit when the foot is at rest.
Progressive deterioration of peripheral axons.
Warts, benign growths on the skin or mucous membranes that cause cosmetic problems as well as pain and discomfort. Warts most often occur on the hands, feet, and genital areas.
Bleeding beneath the mucous membrane that lines the inner surface of the eyelid.
Seizures with sudden, brief (< 100 msec) involuntary single or multiple contraction(s) of muscles(s) or muscle groups of variable topography (axial, proximal limb, distal).
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:37356005 UMLS:C0751778 MSH:D020191 UMLS:C0014550 SNOMEDCT_US:267581004 MSH:D004831 UMLS:C4021759 SNOMEDCT_US:192992007

?def: Delayed tooth eruption, which can be defined as tooth eruption more than 2 SD beyond the mean eruption age.
Abnormal amplitude of the QRS complex of the electrocardiogram (EKG).
An abnormality of the right ventricle of the heart.
An increased amount of subcutaneous fat tissue around the neck.
Weakness of the muscles involved in neck flexion (sternocleidomastoid, longus capitus, longus colli, and scalenus anterior).
An abnormal increase in the size of nasopharyngeal adenoids.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of aspartic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Calcified deposits in soft tissue structures outside a joint.
Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts, affecting arteries distributed throughout the body.
Abnormally short distal phalanx of toe of all toes.
A type of acne in which open and closed comedones comprise the majority of the lesions, with substantially fewer papules and pustules.
Increase posterolateral protrusion of the tragus.
An abnormally increased sodium concentration in the blood.
Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the thumb with the 1st metacarpal.
Intraventricular hemorrhage that occurs in a preterm infant and that has extension into normal-sized ventricles and typically fills less than 50% of the volume of the ventricle.
A condition in which production of hydrochloric acid in the stomach is absent.
Anosmia for one particular odor.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 4th finger.
A decreased concentration of methionine in the blood.
An entrapment neuropathy of the ulnar nerve in the cubital tunnel (in the elbow) characterized by numbness in the ring and little fingers and weakness of the intrinsic muscles in the hand.
Reduced antithrombin antigen. A reduced level of antithrombin may lead to an increased risk of thrombus formation.
Fetal megacystis is an abnormally enlarged bladder identified at any gestational age.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the middle phalanx of the 5th finger is affected.
Developmental hypoplasia (shortening) of all phalanges of the foot.
Congenital absence of the left half of the diaphragm.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger.
An increase in the magnitude or amount of ossification of the skull.

A hamartomatous proliferation containing malformed hair follicles in various stages of development. Panfolliculomas are well-circumscribed lesions demonstrating all stages of follicular differentiation.
Focal epileptiform discharges induced by hyperventilation (overbreathing) in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
An abnormal morphology of the distal phalanx of the second toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Any anomaly of the function of the endocrine system.
A benign tumor of striated muscle.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0035411 SNOMEDCT_US:302846007 MSH:D012207 NCIT:C3358 SNOMEDCT_US:402877008 SNOMEDCT_US:43375002

?def: Ambulation or other complex motor behaviors after getting out of bed in a sleep-like state. During sleepwalking episodes, the sonambulating individual appears confused or dazed, the eyes are usually open, and he or she might mumble or give inappropriate answers to questions, or occasionally appear agitated.
Failure to thrive (FTT) refers to a child whose physical growth is substantially below the norm.
An increased blood concentration of carcinoma antigen 125 (CA-125). CA-125, also known as mucin 16, can exhibit increased blood levels in certain types of cancer.
Fetor hepaticus is the characteristic breath of patients with severe parenchymal liver disease, which has been said to resemble the odor of a mixture of rotten eggs and garlic.
Demyelination of peripheral motor nerves.
The affected individual has received an organ transplant previous to the current medical encounter.
Adrenocortical adenomas are benign tumors of the adrenal cortex.
An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the second finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
Heart rate of greater than 100 beats per minute.

A deviation from the normal amount of lamin A/C in muscle tissue. The LMNA gene gives rise to at least three splicing isoforms including the two main isoforms, lamin A and lamin C. These are constitutive components of the fibrous nuclear lamina and have different roles, ranging from mechanical nuclear membrane maintenance to gene regulation.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes one to five (complete syndactyly of all toes of the foot).
Prominent positioning of the premaxilla in relation to the rest of the maxilla, the facial skeleton, or mandible. Not necessarily caused by an increase in size (hypertrophy of) the premaxilla.

A reduced erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR). The ESR is a test that measures the distance that erythrocytes have fallen after one hour in a vertical column of anticoagulated blood under the influence of gravity. The ESR is a nonspecific finding. A decreased ESR may be seen in polycythemia or in certain blood diseases in which red blood cells have an irregular or smaller shape that causes slower settling.
Coarctation of the aorta is a narrowing or constriction of a segment of the abdominal aorta.
The presence of calcium- and oxalate-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.
A type of muscular ventricular septal defect characterized by the presence of multiple small defects in the ventricular septum.
A neutrophil abnormality.
Thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a high-resolution computed tomography scan with a nodular or beaded appearance of the interlobular septa.
Reduced size of cervical vertebrae.
A type of primitive reflex characterized by an involuntary contraction of the mentalis muscle of the chin caused by stimulation of the thenar eminence of the palm.
Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms.
Absence of the parotid gland.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glutamine in the blood circulation.
The presence of a melanoma of the skin.
Enuresis occurring during waking hours of the day.
Failure of cortisol levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the glucagon stimulation test.
A functional abnormality of the autonomic nervous system.
Any anomaly of the function of the breast.
A type of nephrogenic rest associated with multiple lesions in the periphery of the renal lobe.
A congenital vascular malformation consisting of superficial and deep dilated capillaries in the skin which produce a reddish to purplish discolouration of the skin.
Abnormality of the amniotic fluid, which is the fluid contained in the amniotic sac surrounding the developing fetus.
Clumping together of platelets in the blood in a platelet aggregation test without addition of agents normally used to induce aggregation.
A subjective feeling that an experience which has occurred before is being experienced for the first time.

Fluid which has escaped from retinal blood vessels with a high concentration of lipid, protein, and cellular debris with a typically bright, reflective, white or cream colored appearance on the surface of the retina.
Cyst on the surface of the placenta consisting of amnion and chorion.
A habitual positioning of the body with the head and upper back bent forward.
An abnormally increased concentration of N-Acetylaspartic acid in the blood circulation.
Any abnormality of nasopharyngeal adenoids.
An anomaly of the the pubic bone, i.e., of the ventral and anterior of the three principal components (publis, ilium, ischium) of the hip bone.
A markedly blue coloration of the iris.
Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of ring finger, seen on x-rays as a broad and/or bifid phalanx.
Short (hypoplastic) second metatarsal bone.

The two portions of the clavicle (corresponding to the two primary ossification centers of the clavicle) are connected by a fibrous bridge that is contiguous with the periosteum, and a synovial membrane develops, resulting in a clavicle with a bipartite appearance radiographically. Congenital pseudarthrosis of the clavicle generally presents as a painless mass or swelling over the clavicle.
Abnormally increased levels of aspartic acid in cerebrospinal fluid.
Marked, involuntary jerking of the eyelids.
Absence of the pituitary gland resulting from a developmental defect.

A type of astigmatism in which an unequal curvature of the cornea and some cases additionally of the lens causes one meridian of the eye to be hyperopic (farsighted) and a second meridian that is perpendicular to the first to be myopic (nearsighted).
Underdevelopment of the alveolar process (also known as alveolar bone).
?xrefs: UMLS:C4280451 UMLS:C4280452 SNOMEDCT_US:708494003 UMLS:C3872671 UMLS:C1848905 UMLS:C4280453

?def: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd toe.
Formation of abnormal bony tissue within ligament tissue.
The presence of a neoplasm of the adrenal cortex.
A decreased proliferative response of lymphocytes in vitro or in vivo, when stimulated with an anti-CD3 antibody against the T-cell co-receptor, CD3.
Inflammation of the nasolacrimal sac.
The onset of puberty before the age of 9 years in boys.
An abnormally elevated concentration of 11-deoxycortisol in the urine.

Pterygium colli is a congenital skin fold that runs along the sides of the neck down to the shoulders. It involves an ectopic fibrotic facial band superficial to the trapezius muscle. Excess hair-bearing skin is also present and extends down the cervical region well beyond the normal hairline.
An abnormally wavy surface or edge of the ribs.
A type of dysharmonic skeletal maturation in which there is an acceleration in skeletal maturation whose degree differs markedly in different bones.
The presence of a adenoma of the thyroid gland.

Overproduction of the hormone of cortisol by the adrenal cortex, resulting in a characteristic combination of clinical symptoms termed Cushing syndrome, with truncal obesity, a round, full face, striae atrophicae and acne, muscle weakness, and other features.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:237735008 UMLS:C0001622 UMLS:C0342443 SNOMEDCT_US:47270006 MSH:D000308 SNOMEDCT_US:275437005 UMLS:C4025651

?def: The presence of a fistula affecting the genitourinary system.

?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:52564001 UMLS:C4072835 UMLS:C4073292 MEDDRA:10048017 UMLS:C0343073 UMLS:C4072836

?def: Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against allergens contained in meat products.
Mucin-producing and septated cyst-forming epithelial neoplasia of the pancreas with a distinctive ovarian-type stroma.

Neuroblastoma is a solid tumor that originate in neural crest cells of the sympathetic nervous system. Most neuroblastomas originate in the abdomen, and most abdominal neuroblastomas originate in the adrenal gland. Neuroblastomas can also originate in the thorax, usually in the posterior mediastinum.
An abnormality of the choroid and retina.
A teratoma located in the craniofacial region.
Nystagmus made apparent by looking to the right or to the left.
A structural abnormality of the brain, which has as its parts the forebrain, midbrain, and hindbrain.
An abnormality of a cardiac ventricle.
ABO phenotype O, corresponding to the genotype OO.
CSF total protein level is below the lower limit of normal.
A smooth muscle connective tissue tumor, which is rare type of cancer that is a malignant neoplasm of smooth muscle. When such a neoplasm is benign, it is called a leiomyoma.
Reduced convexity of the occiput (posterior part of skull).
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by abstaining from eating food (fasting).
Inflammation of the connective and adipose tissues surrounding the kidney.
Diminution of tendon reflexes, which is an invariable sign of peripheral nerve disease.

The presence of multiple juvenile polyps in the stomach and intestine. The term juvenile polyps refer to a special histopathology and not the age of onset as the polyp might be diagnosed at all ages. The juvenile polyp has a spherical appearance and is microscopically characterized by overgrowth of an oedematous lamina propria with inflammatory cells and cystic glands. Juvenile polyps are a specific type of hamartomatous polyps.
An abnormally high concentration of maternal serum human chorionic gonadotropin as compared to normal values for gestational-age.
An abnormality of the globus pallidus.

This term applies if the proximal phalanx of the thumb is partially duplicated. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx) to a partially fused appearance of the two bones. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
Gain-of-function thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR) defect.
Slender, slit-like aperture of the nostril.
?xrefs: UMLS:C4280390 SNOMEDCT_US:249339005 UMLS:C0426436 SNOMEDCT_US:249336003 UMLS:C0426439 UMLS:C1849366

?def: An abnormality of the fourth finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
Abnormal function of the left ventricule during left ventricular relaxation and filling.
A hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, that is located in the vulva.
The presence of degenerative changes of the liver.
Increased concentration of 4-hydroxyphenylacetic acid in the urine.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the distal phalanx of the 3rd toe.

Abnormality of the iris characterized by, typically bilateral, complete or partial iris hypoplasia. The phenotype ranges from mild defects of anterior iris stroma only to almost complete absence of the iris.
The presence of an adenoma in the cortex of the kidney.
An abnormality in the production or cellular release of interleukins (a class of cytokines).
An abnormally high concentration of serum alpha-fetoprotein as compared to normal values for gestational-age.
Reduced ability to climb stairs.

A double outlet right ventricle with a subaortic ventritricular septal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that extends anterosuperiorly and are closely related to the pulmonary artery as well, are considered to be doubly committed. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the fourth finger, also known as the ring finger.
Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
A cataract that affects the region of the lens directly beneath the capsule of the lens.
Presence of only one (instead of two, as normal) interphalangeal crease of the fifth finger.
Type 1 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
An abnormality of glycolipid metabolism.
