Insertion of the posterior columella superior to the nasal base.
A murmur that occurs in the latter phase of systole.
Abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the little (5th) finger.
Decreased strength of the inferior rectus muscle.
An abnormal accumulation of protein in the glomerulus.
Abnormally increased level of blood lactate following a meal.
A structural anomaly of the respiratory system.

Lipofuscin, a generic term applied to autofluorescent lipopigment, is a mixture of protein and lipid that accumulates in most aging cells, particularly those involved in high lipid turnover (e.g., the adrenal medulla) or phagocytosis of other cell types (e g., the retinal pigment epithelium or RPE; macrophage). This term pertains if there is an increase in the extraneuronal accumulation of lipofuscin (also known as autofluorescent lipoprotein) more than expected for the age of the patient.
Separation of the vitreous humor from the retina.
Partial or complete loss of vision in one half of the visual field of one or both eyes.

Congenital cystic adenomatoid malformation (CCAM) can be diagnosed prenatally if ultrasound shows a cystic or solid lung tumor. A CCAM does not have systemic arterial blood supply (in contrast to bronchopulmonary sequenstration). It is a cystic area within the lung that originates from abnormal embryogenesis.
Circumscribed depigmentation of the hair of the head or the eyelashes.
The presence of a hernia of the vagina.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the little finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.

The formation of a blood clot inside a blood vessel that subsequently travels through the blood stream from the site where it formed to another location in the body, generally leading to vascular occlusion at the distant site.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:13713005 UMLS:C0040038 MSH:D013923 SNOMEDCT_US:371039008 MSH:D016769 UMLS:C0085307

?def: Hepatitis that lasts for more than six months.
An abnormality of the septum pellucidum, which is a thin, triangular, vertical membrane separating the lateral ventricles of the brain.
Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the 5th (little) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
Developmental hypoplasia of the primary teeth.
Recurrent loss, or shedding, of the nails of the fingers and toes.
An increase in the level of ribose in the urine.
A decreased amount of isoleucine in the blood.
Elevated concentration of galactose in the blood.
An increase in width of the distal phalanx of the big toe.
An abnormality of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
An abnormal (non-anatomic) location of the spleen.
An anomaly of the small joints located between and behind adjacent vertebrae.
A decrease in uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase activity in plasma. Uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase catalyzes the reaction: UDP-glucose = UDP-galactose.

Increased activity of coagulation factor V, Factor V, which is activated to factor Va by means of minute amounts of thrombin (and inactivated by larger amounts of thrombin). Activated factor V (fVa) is a cofactor in the formation of the prothrombinase complex.
Fusion of the proximal and middle phalanges of the 4th finger.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the distal phalanx of the hallux.
Abnormality of the corneal endothelium, that is, the single layer of cells on the inner surface of the cornea.
Absence or underdevelopment of the quadriceps muscle.
Presence of xenobiotic in stool.
An elevation in bone density in one or more diaphyses of the arms. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.
Sharply demarcated, typically linear and approximately horizontal, indentations in the outer surface of the ear lobe.
A sensation that the heart is pounding or racing, which is a non-specific sign but may be a manifestation of arrhythmia.

An anomaly of podocyte morphology characterized by the loss of the interdigitating foot process pattern (generally called foot process effacement; FPE). The term FPE designates the loss of the usual interdigitating pattern of foot processes of neighboring podocytes, leading to relatively broad expanses of podocyte processes covering the glomerular basement membrane (GBM). It is widely viewed as a pathological derangement that is associated with leakage of macromolecules such as albumin through the glomerular filtration barrier.
A deviation from the normal rotation of the midgut during embryologic development with mislocalization of the small bowel.
A structural anomaly of the double-walled capsule (Bowman capsule) that opens into a renal tubule.
Pregnancy-induced hypertension in association with significant amounts of protein in the urine.

A condition of not having consistently high levels of phenylalanine in the blood but of experiencing temporary hyperphenylalaninemia following ingestion of large quantities of phenylalanine (for instance, following an oral loading test with phenylalanine).
Elevated glycogen content in the sarcoplasm (cytoplasm) of muscle fibers.
Fusion of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger with another bone.
Posterior positioning of the glabella, i.e., of the midline forehead between the supraorbital ridges.
Absence or underdevelopment of the clavicles (collar bones).
This term applies for all abnormalities of the big toe, also called hallux.
An abnormality of the morphology or structure of the middle ear.
A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the ring finger of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.
Excessive amount of hair growth on forehead.
Reduced proportion of helper T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Accumulation of excessive amounts of lymphatic fluid (chyle) in the pleural cavity.
Excessive growth of the craniofacial bones.
An abnormality of the homeostasis (concentration) of transition element cation.
An abnormality of the skin.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:95320005 UMLS:C0037268 UMLS:C0037274 SNOMEDCT_US:199879009 MSH:D012871 MSH:D012868

?def: Any complex of structural, architectural, contractile or electrophysiological changes affecting the atria with the potential to produce clinically relevant manifestations.
The abrupt and transient increase in the annual growth rate normally observed in adolescent individuals does not occur.
Generalized abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin, or in one or more cavities of the body.
A bilateral form of agenesis of the kidney.
A type of hypoplastic anemia with congenital onset.
?xrefs: UMLS:C1260899 SNOMEDCT_US:88854002 MSH:D000742 SNOMEDCT_US:52951008 MSH:D029503 UMLS:C0002876 SNOMEDCT_US:234371002

?def: Abnormality of the cerebral ventricles.
Accumulation of blood in the vagina usually due to vaginal obstruction.
A developmental defect characterized by agenesis of one or more vertebral bodies.
The sternal cleft is a rare congenital anomaly resulting from a fusion failure of the sternum.
A characteristic appearance resulting from defective ossification of craniofacial bones.
A digit with two nails, with at least some soft tissue between them.
Developmental hypoplasia of the adrenal medulla.
An increased concentration of citrulline in the urine.
Abnormal alignment, positioning, or spacing of the teeth, i.e., misaligned teeth.
Vertical crease fold situated below the vermilion border of the lower lip and above the fatty pad of the chin with the face at rest.
An abnormally reduced diameter of the femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft).
A type of urinary cast composed of a proteinaceous matrix without a substantial number of cells.
A bending or abnormal curvature affecting a long bone of the arm.
An eyebrow that extends laterally beyond the orbital rim rather than turning gently downward at that location.
Pain of the gastrocnemius muscle.
A localized defect in the posterior eye wall with protrusion of uveal tissue due to alterations in scleral thickness and structure.
An abnormality of one or more metaphysis, i.e., of the somewhat wider portion of a long bone that is adjacent to the epiphyseal growth plate and grows during childhood.
Deterioration of the tissues of the lateral corticospinal tracts.
Lack of paramedian peaks and median notch of the upper lip vermilion.
A congenital malformation with abnormal connection between one of the coronary arteries and a heart chamber or another blood vessel.
An abnormal reduction in xanthine dehydrogenase activity.

A personality disorder characterized by impulsive behavior and unpredictable and capricious mood. Affected individuals show a liability to outbursts of emotion and an incapacity to control the behavioural explosions.
An anomaly of the vermis of cerebellum.
Repeated transient episodes of metabolic acidosis, that is, of the buildup of acid or depletion of base due to accumulation of metabolic acids.

Hypercellularity (increased number of cells) in the renal glomerulus but external to the glomerular capillaries, i.e., in the Bowman space or more than one layer of parietal or visceral epithelial cells.
An abnormally decreased concentration of parathyroid hormone.
A type of sacrococcygeal teratoma that is predominantly external and projects from the sacrococcygeal region and presents with distortion of the buttocks.
Asymmetry of the anterior part of the skull.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0432124 UMLS:C4280330 UMLS:C4023413 UMLS:C4280328 UMLS:C4280329 SNOMEDCT_US:254020001

?def: A reduced sense of touch (tactile sensation) on the skin of the distal limbs. This is usually tested with a wisp of cotton or a fine camel's hair brush, by asking patients to say 'now' each time they feel the stimulus.
Decreased levels of immunoglobulin A (IgA).
A structural abnormality of the sperm tail.
A benign tumor of cardiac striated muscle.
A type of gastritis characterized by excessive proliferation of the gastric mucosa and diffuse thickening of the gastric mucosal folds.

Elevations of the levels of SGOT and SGPT in the serum. SGOT (serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase) and SGPT (serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase) are transaminases primarily found in the liver and heart and are released into the bloodstream as the result of liver or heart damage. SGOT and SGPT are used clinically mainly as markers of liver damage.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0877359 SNOMEDCT_US:166643006 UMLS:C1842003 UMLS:C0086565 UMLS:C0235996 UMLS:C1848701 SNOMEDCT_US:75183008 SNOMEDCT_US:166603001 UMLS:C0438717 UMLS:C0151766 UMLS:C0438237 MSH:D008107

?def: The presence of tufts of 8-15 hairs that appear to emerge from a single follicular orifice.
Substantially shortened length of the small intestine as a result of a developmental defect.
Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the superior rectus muscle.
Absence of the patella.
A deviation from the normal concentration of circulating estrone.
An intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material in a trabecular or fingerprint-like pattern.
An abnormality of a mandible condylar process.
An abnormality of the pulmonary pleura, the thin, transparent membrane which covers the lungs and lines the inside of the chest walls.
An abnormality of the iris, which is the pigmented muscular tissue between the cornea and the lens, that is perforated by an opening called the pupil.
A hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart. The defect is centered around the most superior aspect of the ventricular septum.
A congenital defect with aplasia (absence) of one of the right or left pulmonary artery.
A neural tube defect characterized by sac-like protrusions of the brain and the membranes that cover it through openings in the skull.
An increased concentration of leucine in the blood.
A fluorescein angiographic finding of absence of the normal background fluorescence (a dark choroid).
Reduced desire for sexual activity on the part of a male.
A pathological narrowing of the esophagus that is caused by the development of a ring of scar tissue that constricts the esophageal lumen.
An abnormal fear of being in a closed or narrow space with no escape.
Increased susceptibility to streptococcus pneumoniae infections as manifested by a history of recurrent infections by streptococcus pneumoniae.
Renal fibrosis is the consequence of an excessive accumulation of extracellular matrix that occurs in virtually every type of chronic kidney disease.
The presence of a medullary carcinoma of the thyroid gland.
An increase in the concentration of bile acid in the blood.
Atrophy affecting the cerebellum and the spinocerebellar tracts of the spinal cord.
An anomaly of the circle of Willis, also known as the cerebral arterial circle.
An abnormal concentration of a hormone in the blood.
White color (lack of pigmentation) of the eyelashes.
Any structural anomaly of the annulus of the tricuspid valve. The annulus is a ring composed of fibrous and myocardial tissue and is the structure onto which the cusps of the valve attach.
Intracellular aggregates of actin and actin-associated proteins within nerve cells.
Deterioration or loss of the tissues of the cochlea.
An abnormal difference between the left and right sides of the face.
Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the bones of the lower limbs.

A deviation from normal of the amount of laminin beta 1 in muscle fiber tissue. Laminin 2 is a major component of the basal lamina of skeletal muscle cells. It is a heterotrimer composed of 3 chains: merosin (laminin alpha 2 chain), beta 1, and gamma 1.
Edema in the region of the eyelids.
Inflammation, or an inflammatory state in the large intestine.
Persistence of immune complexes in the blood circulation.
Shortening of the legs related to developmental hypoplasia of the bones of the leg.

Type VI atherosclerotic lesions generally have the underlying morphology of type IV or V lesions, surface disruptions, hematoma, and thrombosis may be (although less often) superimposed on any other type of lesion and even on intima without an apparent lesion. Complicating features may arise because of individual differences in risk factors and tissue reactions. These may include differences in composition of the blood, the relative quantities and distributions in the components of the underlying lesion or intima, as well as modifications of shear and tensile forces to which the lesion or intima is exposed. Clinical imaging of lesions may be expected to contribute greatly to the understanding of type VI lesions and the associated clinical syndromes.
Presence of a unitary trichilemmoma, a benign tumour originating from the outer root sheath of the hair follicle.
Facial myokymia is a fine fibrillary activity of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).
A sensation of stiffness in the joints that occurs following waking up in the morning.
Underdevelopment of the uterus.
Testicular inflammation.
Abnormality of the female genital system.

A form of hypersociability that presents as mostly inappropriate people-orientation and friendliness towards others on an inadequate level which might go as far as being dangerous considering for example young children following strangers without restriction.
Skin crease extending from below the inner canthus laterally along the malar process of the maxilla and zygoma.
Presence of thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a CT scan.
Faint anterior chamber flare.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger is affected.

A writing disability in the absence of motor or sensory deficits of the upper extremities, resulting in an impairment in the ability to write regardless of the ability to read and not due to intellectual impairment.
Bony fusion of malleus, incus, and stapes.
An increased concentration of dermatan sulfate in the urine.

Osteoporosis is a systemic skeletal disease characterized by low bone density and microarchitectural deterioration of bone tissue with a consequent increase in bone fragility. According to the WHO criteria, osteoporosis is defined as a BMD that lies 2.5 standard deviations or more below the average value for young healthy adults (a T-score below -2.5 SD).

A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the mitochondrial genome. Because the mitochondrial genome is essentially always maternally inherited, a mitochondrial condition can only be transmitted by females, although the condition can affect both sexes. The proportion of mutant mitochondria can vary (heteroplasmy).
A large maternal clot that separates the chorionic plate from the villous chorion.
Any anomaly of a subclavian artery.
Echogenic bowel is defined as fetal bowel with homogenous areas of echogenicity that are equal to or greater than that of surrounding bone.
Shortening of the middle parts of the limbs (forearm and lower leg) in relation to the upper and terminal segments.
Curving course of the crus of the helix, approaching or joining the antitragus.
Any abnormality of the size of the skull.
Series of hypermetric saccades attempting to narrow in on the target (ocular past-pointing).
A form of undifferentiated malignant lymphoma commonly manifested as a large osteolytic lesion in the jaw or as an abdominal mass.
?xrefs: MSH:D002051 SNOMEDCT_US:77381001 SNOMEDCT_US:22197008 SNOMEDCT_US:118617000 UMLS:C0006413 SNOMEDCT_US:277571004 SNOMEDCT_US:397400006

?def: A contraction of the diaphragm that repeats several times per minute. In humans, the abrupt rush of air into the lungs causes the epiglottis to close, creating a hic sound. Also known as synchronous diaphragmatic flutter (SDF), or singultus, from the Latin singult, the act of catching one's breath while sobbing. The hiccup is an involuntary action involving a reflex arc.
Reduced ability of the liver to perform its functions.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0086565 SNOMEDCT_US:75183008 MSH:D008107 UMLS:C0232744 UMLS:C3279149 SNOMEDCT_US:77981007

?def: Loss of the outer layer of the epidermis in large, scale-like flakes localized to the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot.
A benign neoplasm that usually arises from the sympathetic trunk in the mediastinum, representing a tumor of the sympathetic nerve fibers arising from neural crest cells.
Osteosclerosis of the endosteal surface of the diaphyses (shafts) of the metatarsal bones.
Hypoplastic/small distal phalanx of the fourth finger.
U wave inversion that is induced by exercise stress testing.
Recurrent bouts of sudden, severe apnea that may be life-threatening.
Positioning of the nasal tip inferior to the nasal base.
The presence of a sebaceous adenoma with origin in the sebum secreting cells of the skin.
Abnormalities of the overall muscle bulk based on clinical observation.
Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased sensation of itching over the skin of the breast.
A deviation from the normal level of major histocompatibility complex class II molecules expressed at the cell surface.

Inflammatory changes in the synovial membranes and articular structures with widespread fibrinoid degeneration of the collagen fibers in mesenchymal tissues, as well as atrophy and rarefaction of bony structures.
The presence of inflammation in the pancreas.
Increased mobility and flexibility in the joint due to the tension in tissues such as ligaments and muscles.
Abnormality of the nail.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the tongue.
An abnormality in the amount of volume occupied by intravascular blood.
Applies to an abnormality that affects the arms, trunk, head more than the legs.
A sheet like projection that can result from uterine synechiae that has been encompassed by the expanding chorion and amnion.
A type of primitive reflex that is elicited by tapping the upper lip lightly. The contraction of the muscles causes the mouth to resemble a snout [NCBI Books:NBK395].
A deviation from the normal odor of the urine.
Abnormality of galactoside metabolism. A galactoside is a glycoside (a suger moiety bound to some other moiety) containing galactose.
Acute appearance of disease manifestations in a period of days.

The presence of one or more obsessive-compulsive personality traits. Obsessions refer to persistent intrusive thoughts, and compulsions to intrusive behaviors, which the affected person experiences as involuntary, senseless, or repugnant.
A reduction in the ability to maintain sustained attention characterized by reduced altertness.

An abnormal proportion of memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. Memory T cells have previously encountered and responded to their cognate antigen and upon a repeated encounter with the antigen can mount a faster and stronger response.
Abnormally decreased levels of alanine in cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormality of the hepatic veins, which normally drain de-oxygenated blood from the liver into the inferior vena cava, whereby the hepatic veins drain into the left atrium.
An abnormal green color of urine.
A benign tumor typically found at the junction of the cornea and sclera (limbal epibullar dermoid).
A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more phalanges of the big toe.

Osteomalacia is a general term for bone weakness owing to a defect in mineralization of the protein framework known as osteoid. This defective mineralization is mainly caused by lack in vitamin D. Osteomalacia in children is known as rickets.
Lack of dystrophin in muscle tissue. Immunohistochemistry reveals absent dystrophin protein in the muscle biopsy.
Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of ring finger.
An abnormality of mental functioning including various affective, behavioural, cognitive and perceptual abnormalities.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0004941 SNOMEDCT_US:277843001 UMLS:C0233514 MSH:D000066553 SNOMEDCT_US:25786006 MSH:D001526

?def: A secondary ossification center in the distal phalanx of the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
An abnormal increase in the carrying angle, which is the angle he long axis of the extended forearm as it lies lateral to the long axis of the arm.
Complete duplication of proximal phalanx of second toe.
Anterior malposition of the anus.
A corrugated white lesion of the oral mucosa that usually occurs on the lateral or ventral surfaces of the tongue and may have a shaggy or frayed appearance.
The presence of 11 instead of the normal 12 thoracic vertebrae.
Supernumerary clitoris.
Sclerosis (increased density) affecting vertebral end plates.
Repeated infections of the urinary bladder.
Overgrowth of only one arm.
An abnormal increase in quantity or strength of fetal movements.

A deviation from the normal concentration of creatine in the blood circulation. Creatine is a derivative of glycine having methyl and amidino groups attached to the nitrogen. Creatine is naturally produced from amino acids, primarily in liver and kidney, and acts as an energy source for cells, primarly for muscle cells.
The epiphysis of the 1st metacarpal are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.
A type of dystonia that affects the midline muscles, i.e., the chest, abdominal, and back muscles.
A malignant epithelial tumor with a glandular organization that originates in the small intestine.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the uterus.

An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate with a high signal on T1-weighted sequences and high- or isointense signal on T2 sequences. Modic type II signals are thought to indicate fatty replacement in the bone marrow.
Abnormality of Descemet's membrane, which is the basement membrane of the corneal endothelium.
Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of stainable substances within cells of the brain.
Double rather than single peak of the antitragus.
The right pulmonary artery originates from the ascending aorta in the presence of a pulmonary valve and main pulmonary artery.
Any structural anomaly of the acrosome resulting in a round sperm head.
An anomalous structure of the periosteum, i.e., of the membrane that covers the outer surface of bones.
An abnormally slow velocity of the saccadic eye movements.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of methionine in the blood circulation.
Impaired conduction of cardiac impulse occurring anywhere along the conduction pathway.
Well-demarcated area(s) of partial or complete depigmentation in the fundus, reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss.
A reduced concentration of folic acid, which is also known as vitamin B9 in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Amelia of all four limbs.
An abnormal increase or decrease of weight or an abnormal distribution of mass in the body.

A form of lymphoid leukemia or lymphoma in which too many T-cell lymphoblasts are found in the blood, bone marrow, and tissues. Leukemia or lymphoma classification depends on which feature is more prominent.
Aorta descends on right instead of on the left.
Any structural abnormality of the choroid.
An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall of the iliac artery.
The presence of a fistula connecting the urinary bladder to another organ or the skin. The fistula can involve the bowel, the vagina, or rarely, the skin.
An abnormality of the aryepiglottic fold.
Unusual gonadal development in a person with a 46,XY male karyotype, leading to an unassigned sex differentiation.
Recurrent episodes of ulceration of the oral mucosa, typically presenting as painful, sharply circumscribed fibrin-covered mucosal defects with a hyperemic border.
?xrefs: MSH:D013281 SNOMEDCT_US:110426005 SNOMEDCT_US:427617000 UMLS:C2937365 SNOMEDCT_US:426965005 UMLS:C0038363 SNOMEDCT_US:398870000

?def: A skin change elicited by briskly rubbing the skin lesion in urticaria pigmentosa (UP), whereby the area begins to itch and becomes raised and surrounded by erythema. Unlike other forms of dermatographism, Darier's sign refers to urtication that is limited to the UP involved areas and, as in this case, spares the skin unaffected by UP.
The distal interphalangeal joint and/or the proximal interphalangeal joint of the second to fifth fingers cannot be extended to 180 degrees by either active or passive extension.
Presence of multiple small cysts containing keratin (skin protein) and presenting as tiny pearly-white bumps just under the surface of the skin.
A transient visual disturbance that is typically caused by a circulatory, ocular or neurological underlying condition.

It is a bilateral reticular pattern of linear or lineonodular densities that are most pronounced in basilar portions of the lungs on standard chest x-ray. It is the third minor criterion for scleroderma diagnosis.
A benign tumor (adenoma) of the pituitary gland
The presence of only one working lower chamber in the heart, usually with a virtual absence of the ventricular septum and usually present in conjunction with double inlet left or right ventricle.

A slowly progressing leukemia characterized by a clonal (malignant) proliferation of maturing and mature myeloid cells or mature lymphocytes. When the clonal cellular population is composed of myeloid cells, the process is called chronic myelogenous leukemia. When the clonal cellular population is composed of lymphocytes, it is classified as chronic lymphocytic leukemia, hairy cell leukemia, or T-cell large granular lymphocyte leukemia.
An abnormally short femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft).
A reduction of joint mobility resulting from changes involving the articular surfaces.
Any abnormality in the proportion of CD4 T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Holoprosencephaly is a structural anomaly of the brain in which the developing forebrain fails to divide into two separate hemispheres and ventricles.
A glioma originating in the optic nerve or optic chiasm.
A reduction in the number of nerve cells in the basal ganglia.

The presence of ectopic thymus tissue. Normally, cells of the ventral bud of the third pharyngeal pouch detach and migrate in the eighth gestational week caudally and medially towards the location of the mature thyroid. They migrate further retrosternally into the superior mediastinum. There are two main ways ectopic thymus tissue can develop. Either cells detach along the descensus path and proliferate, thereby forming accessory thymus tissue, or the entire gland fails to descend.
Decreased width of the foramen obturatorium. The foramen obturatorium (also known as the obturator foramen) is a hole located between the ischium and pubis bones of the pelvis.
Localized or generalized increased genital pigmentation.
An infection of the upper or lower respiratory tract.
Excessive action of the medial rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.
An abnormally round shape of the middle phalanx of the finger.
Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

A form of anomalous eating behavior characterized by binge eating is followed by self-induced vomiting or other compensatory behavior intended to prevent weight gain (purging, fasting or exercising or a combination of these).
Generalized tonic-clonic seizures that are triggered by flashing or flickering light.
An abnormality of the nipple.
The presence of prolapse of the uterus.
Abnormal calcification of a cardiac valve.
A decreased amount of carnosine in bood.
Loss of the outer layer of the epidermis in large, scale-like flakes localized to one or more fingertips.
Abnormality of the midnasal cavity which includes the cavity between the nares and the choanae.
Abnormally prominent umbilicus (belly button).
Agenesis of one or more vertebrae of the cervical vertebral column.
Underdevelopment of the brainstem.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against the insulin receptor.
Aorto-left ventricular tunnel (ALVT) is a congenital extracardiac channel connecting the ascending aorta above the sino-tubular junction to either left ventricular cavity.
Stiffness (a condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm) of the axial musculature.

In wound repair, neovascularization (NV) involves the sprouting of new vessels from pre-existent vessels to repair or replace damaged vessels. In the retina, NV is a response to ischemia. The NV adheres to the inner surface of the retina and outer surface of the vitreous. NV are deficient in tight junctions and hence leak plasma into surrounding tissue including the vitreous. Plasma causes the vitreous gel to degenerate, contract, and eventually collapse which pulls on the retina. Since retinal NV is adherent to both retina and vitreous, as the vitreous contracts the NV may be sheared resulting in vitreous hemorrhage or the NV may remain intact and pull the retina with the vitreous resulting in retinal elevation referred to as traction retinal detachment.
An abnormal blue color of the urine.
A benign vascular tumor of the retina without any neoplastic characteristics.
Decreased level of amylase in the blood, an enzyme which helps digest glycogen and starch. It is produced mainly in the pancreas and salivary glands.
Increased susceptibility to systemic pyogenic infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of systemic pyogenic infections.
A phenotypic abnormality that is present at birth.

Febrile seizures are convulsions induced by a fever in infants or small children and are generally characterized by loss of consciousness and tonic-clonic movements. Most febrile seizures last a minute or two.
Hair on the neck extends less inferiorly than usual.
Underdevelopment of the larynx.
Reduced or inadequate peristalsis, with resultant slow passage of contents through the digestive tract.
Presence of irregular redundant loops of focally folded myelin in a peripheral nerve.
Fusion of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger with another bone.
Recurrent episodes of apnea occurring during infancy.
Acute lymphoblastic leukemia of T-cell origin. It comprises about 15% of childhood cases and 25% of adult cases. It is more common in males than females.
An abnormality of the cardiac ventricular function.
Severe hypertrophy (increase in size) of muscle cells.
Absence or underdevelopment of the breasts.
A tricuspid valve that has failed to open.
Any abnormality in the proportion of naive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the duodenum.
A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex I, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.
Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
Phocomelia involving all four extremities.
Irregular surface of the normally relatively smooth capital femoral epiphysis.
A hole (perforation) in the wall of the small intestine.
Febrile seizures with focal semiology, duration of more than 15 minutes, or occurring in a cluster of 2 or more convulsions within 24 hours.

Acting on the spur of the moment in response to immediate stimuli; acting on a momentary basis without a plan or consideration of outcomes; difficulty establishing or following plans; a sense of urgency and self-harming behavior under emotional distress.
As vascular abnormalities of the posterior pole that are insufficient for the diagnosis of plus disease but that demonstrate more arterial tortuosity and more venous dilatation than normal.
A papillary or cauliflower-like growth characterized by the presence of foamy histiocytes within the elongated dermal papillae forms.
A neurenteric cyst located in the spine.

Scar tissue that forms a continuous sheet coming up from the edge of the vascularized retina. This scar tissue can grow toward the vitreous base/posterior lens capsule resulting in traction, distortion, and even detachment.
The onset of puberty before the age of 8 years in girls.
A type of monoclonal elevation of IgG in which the involved immunoglobulin has an abnormal structure with a kappa light chain but not a heavy chain.
An abnormality of the cerebral subcortex.
The onset of growth of pubic hair at an earlier age than normal.
EEG with sharp waves in the temporal region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.
The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of one or more long bones of the arm.
A deviation from normal concentration of the hormone estrogen in the blood circulation.
A concentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the abdominal aorta that involves the full circumference of the vessel wall
An anomaly of a muscle that is innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).
A type of muscle stiffness that occurs following physical exertion.
Abnormality of the phalanges of the 3rd (middle) finger.
Death between the age of 16 and 40 years.
Deterioration of the tissue of the fovea, i.e.,the region of sharpest vision within the macula of the retina.
Longitudinal, linear prominences in the fingernail plate.
An increased susceptibility to Aspergillus infections, as manifested by a history of recurrent episodes of Aspergillus infections.
A secondary ossification center in the distal phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

A hemangioma is a benign tumor characterized by blood-filled spaces lined by benign endothelial cells. A hemangioma characterized by large endothelial spaces (caverns) is called a cavernous hemangioma (in contrast to a hemangioma with small endothelial spaces, which is called capillary hemangioma).
?xrefs: NCIT:C3085 UMLS:C0018916 SNOMEDCT_US:253053003 SNOMEDCT_US:2099007 SNOMEDCT_US:400210000 MSH:D006391

?def: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the chest.

A benign hair follicle tumor whose tumor cells form rudimentary hair follicles but not actual hair shafts. A trichoepithelioma is usually less than one centimeter, firm, round, and shihy with yellow, pink, brown, or bluish color. They may occur multiply, usually on the face, and may gradually increase in number with age.
Abnormal response to thromboxane as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of thromboxane A2 receptor agonists.
A secondary ossification center in the phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
Underdevelopment of the anterior pituitary gland.
Increased width of the distal segment of a finger.
An abnormality of morphology of primary molar.
Developmental dysplasia of dentin affecting only the primary dentition.
Non-continuous diffuse slowing of electroencephalographic patterns.
Underdevelopment of the lacrimal gland.
A neuropathic disorder characterized by episodes of intense pain in the face, originating from the trigeminal nerve. One, two, or all three branches of the nerve may be affected.
Abnormal response to calcium Ionophore (such as A23187) as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of the ionophore.
An abnormal, increased fatiguability of the musculature.
An early onset of puberty, in this case early does not refer to precocious.

Any anomaly of the structure of the acellular zone that is between the dermis and the epidermis and which functions to bind the epidermis to the dermis and to serve as a selective barrier allowing the control of molecular and cellular exchanges between the two compartments.
Any abnormality of the salivary glands, the exocrine glands that produce saliva.
Excessive daytime sleepiness.
A developmental defect resulting in the presence of fewer than the normal number of fingers.
An abnormality of an internal jugular vein.
An abnormally increased level of alkaline phosphatase, intestinal type in the blood.

Absence of the outer dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, which normally are situated outside of the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.
Any structural anomaly of a great auricular nerve.
Absence or underdevelopment of the spleen.
Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the distal phalanx of the fourth finger.
Increased excretion of glycopeptides in the urine. Glycopeptides are peptides with carbohydrate moieties covalently attached to the side chains of the amino acid residues.
A closed sac, having a distinct membrane and division compared to the nearby tissue located within the anterior chamber. The sac that may contain air, fluids, or semi-solid material.

A skin lesions that resembles the lesions observed in psoriasis, viz., an erythematous plaque covered by fine silvery scales. Psoriasiform lesions can be observed in psoriasis as well as in other conditions including allergic contact dermatitis, seborrhoeic dermatitis, Atopic dermatitis, pityriasis rubra, and lichen simplex chronicus.
Inflammation of the vitreous body, characterized by the presence of inflammatory cells and protein exudate in the vitreous cavity.
A congenital vascular malformation in the liver composed of masses of blood vessels that are atypical or irregular in arrangement and size.
Failure to form (agenesis) of one or more epiphyses of the big toe.
A type of focal cortical dysplasia that is characterized by disrupted cortical lamination and specific cytological abnormalities.
An abnormal concentration of creatinine in the blood.
Lack of recognizable penile structures.
A defect of the chest wall characterized by a depression of the sternum, giving the chest (\pectus\") a caved-in (\"excavatum\") appearance."

The term proximal symphalangism refers to a bony fusion of the middle and proximal phalanges of the digits of the hand, in other words the proximal interphalangeal joint (PIJ) is missing which can be seen either on x-rays or as an absence of the proximal interphalangeal finger creases.
Any anomaly of the scalp, the skin an subcutaneous tissue of the head on which head hair grows.

A type of malformation of cortical development that primarily affects areas of neocortex. It can be identified on conventional magnetic resonance imaging as focal cortical thickening, abnormal gyration, and blurring between gray and white matter, often associated with clusters of heterotopic neurons.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the 4th finger.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) and perceived to originate in the flank.
Any physiological abnormality of the esophagus.
Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disc is 1.0 (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).
Underdevelopment of the operculum.
Obliteration of the pulp chambers owing to mineralization of the dental pulp.
A cancer arising in a cell of the Bartholin gland, a racemose gland located slightly posterior to the opening of the vagina.
A neoplasm of the central nervous system.
An odontogenic tumor of the cementum of tooth.
A small/hypoplastic or absent/aplastic 2nd finger.
Increased discharge of mucus from the nose.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the eye.

A personality disorder characterized by shallow and labile affectivity, self-dramatization, theatricality, exaggerated expression of emotions, suggestibility, egocentricity, self-indulgence, lack of consideration for others, easily hurt feelings, and continuous seeking for appreciation, excitement and attention.
Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
A state characterized by a feeling of weakness and loss of strength leading to a generalized weakness of the body.

Narrowing (becoming gradually narrower) of the distance between vertebral pedicles that gets progressively more severe towards to caudal (lower) end of the vertebral column. Note that normally, the interpedicular distances get progressively wider as one proceeds down the spine.
Excretion of non-amino organic acids in urine.
Presence of all the normal ear components and the median longitudinal length more than two standard deviations below the mean.
Pain or discomfort of the scalp elicited by palpation.
An elevation in bone density in one or more diaphyses. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
An anomaly of the shape or form of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.
Severely increased amount of excretion of protein in the urine, defined as 3.5 grams per day or more in adults and 40 mg per meter-squared body surface area per hour in children.
A moderate delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
Persistent pain, usually defined as pain that has lasted longer than 3 to 6 months.
A decreased concentration of arginine in the blood.
A severe form of hypermetropia with over +5.00 diopters.
Increased depth of the anterior chamber, i.e., the anteroposterior distance between the cornea and the iris is increased.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the proximal phalanx of the 5th toe.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 4th finger.
History of repeated intermittent involuntary muscle contractions that were painful.
An abnormality in which the nuclei of sarcomeres take on an abnormally central localization (or in which this feature is found in an increased proportion of muscle cells).
An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation (reduced or absent) of skin, hair and eye (iris and retina).
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against plant products.
Absence (aplasia) of the spleen.
Yellow, white or greyish lesions in the macula that are well-defined/distinct, individual and mostly uniform in size.
Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
A type of pituitary adenoma that produces growth hormone.
Weakness of the peroneal muscles.
A conical (cone-shaped) appearance of the epiphysis of the first metatarsal of the foot.
Generalized tonic-clonic seizures on awakening are a form of Generalized tonic-clonic seizures that occur upon awaking.
An abnormally reduced concentration of globulins in the blood.
A malformation of the neural tube with a large amount of protruding brain tissue and absence of calvarium.
A reduction in the speed at which electrical signals propagate along the axon of a neuron.

Reduced pigmentation of the fundus, typically generalised. Fundoscopy may reveal a low level pigment in both RPE and choroid with clear visibility of choroidal vessels (pale/albinoid) or low pigment level in the RPE with deep pigment in choroid so that visible choroidal vessels are separated by deeply pigmented zones (tesselated/tigroid).
An abnormally elevated concentration of corticosterone in the blood.
Chronic hepatitis associated with recurrent clinical exacerbations, extrahepatic manifestations, and progression to cirrhosis.

The tumor cells that form the Flexner-Wintersteiner rosette circumscribe a central lumen that contains small cytoplasmic extensions of the encircling cells; however, unlike the center of the Homer Wright rosette, the central lumen does not contain the fiber-rich neuropil.
Absence or underdevelopment of the nasal septum.

Periglomerular fibrosis is defined as glomeruli with open capillaries, but lamellated, frequently wrinkled, Bowman capsular basement membrane and circumferential layers of interstitial-type collagen around, within, or between the usually thickened, frequently lamellated, Bowman capsule basement membrane.
An abnormality of the spinal dura mater, which is the outermost of the three layers of the meninges surrounding the spinal cord.
A delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more long bones of the upper limbs.
An abnormality of the pericardium, i.e., of the fluid filled sac that surrounds the heart and the proximal ends of the aorta, vena cava, and the pulmonary artery.
Any abnormality of the cervical vertebral column.
An abnormality of the concentration of deoxycorticosterone in the blood. Deoxycorticosterone comprises 11-deoxycorticosterone and 21-deoxycorticosterone.
An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate according to a widely used classification published by Dr. Michael Modic.
Pregnancy-induced toxic reactions of the mother that can be as harmless as slight Maternal hypertension or as life threatening as Eclampsia.
Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the proximal phalanx of the fourth finger.
An abnormal conical morphology of the primary incisor.
A cleft of the muscular (soft) portion of the palate that is covered by mucous membrane. Soft-palate submucous clefts are characterized by a midline deficiency or lack of muscle tissue.
A type of incomitant strabismus in which both elevator muscles (i.e., the inferior oblique and superior rectus muscles) of the same eye are weak leading to restricted elevation and hypotropia.
A congenital deformity characterized by a dorsiflexed, inverted, and adducted foot, i.e., a combination of talipes calcaneus and talipes varus.
Increased addition of fucose sugar units to O-linked glycans.
Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 4th (ring) finger.
A darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter.
Reduced motility of the gallbladder with reduced emptying fraction.
Increased level of IgE antibody against bacteria.
A variant of retinitis pigmentosa in which there is a regional distribution of the retinal degeneration.
A nonspecific term denoting degeneration of the retinal pigment epithelium and/or retinal photoreceptor cells of the macula lutea.

?xrefs: UMLS:C0271355 SNOMEDCT_US:398963001 MSH:C564661 SNOMEDCT_US:398760006 MSH:D020434 SNOMEDCT_US:398925009

?def: Stenosis of a peripheral branch of the pulmonary artery.
Altered immune function characterized by lymphoid proliferation, immune activation, and excessive autoreactivity often leading to autoimmune/inflammatory complications.
A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance beween the vertebral endplates affecting the lumbar spine.
An anomaly of the pulse pressure, which is defined as the systolic pressured minus the diastolic pressure.
Western blot reveals reduced calpain-3 protein in the muscle biopsy tissue.
Decreased addition of fucose sugar units to N-linked glycans.
Disproportionately small hand.
Abnormal concentration of hexanoylglycine in the urine.

Height of the vermilion of the medial part of the lower lip more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently reduced height of the vermilion of the lower lip in the frontal view (subjective).
An increased susceptibility to infections involving both the paranasal sinuses and the lungs, as manifested by a history of recurrent sinopulmonary infections.
Partial duplication of the first metacarpal bone.
Disordered thermoregulation characterized by an impaired ability to maintain a balance between heat production and heat loss, with resulting instability of body temperature.
An abnormality of the texture of the hair.
An abnormality of a temporalis muscle.
A type of sideroblastic anemia that is alleviated by pyridoxine (vitamin B-6) treatment.

An abnormality of cortical sensation. Assuming the primary sensory modalities are intact and the patient is alert and cooperative, the presence of an abnormality of sensory function usually indicates a lesion of a parietal cortex or of the thalamocortical projections to the parietal cortex.
Severe mental retardation is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 20-34.
Evidence of chronic denervation on electromyography.

Digits that appear disproportionately short compared to the hand/foot. The word brachydactyly is used here to describe a series distinct patterns of shortened digits (brachydactyly types A-E). This is the sense used here.
Number of leukocytes per volume of blood beyond normal limits.
Reduced binding of annexin V to platelet membrane, which is mediated by exposed phosphatidylserine. This can be measured by flow cytometry.
An abnormality of the nervous system.
An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall of the leg.
Underdevelopment of the ulna on both sides.
A brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter.
High risk patients who were in Zone 1 (no Plus or stage 3) or Zone 2 with Plus or stage 3 but not both.

Subcortical heterotopia consisting of a bilateral and symmetric single continuous, undulating ribbon-like layer of gray matter located in the frontal, parietal and occipital lobes. It has no visible connection to the overlying cortex.
Decreased strength (ability to move) of the lateral rectus muscle.

The presence of central, fine, whitish granular lesions in the stroma of the cornea. This type of corneal dystrophy is usually asymptomatic and begins in childhood and shows a slow progression. Later in the course, the corneal epithelium and Bowman's layer may be affected. Histologically, the cornea shows a uniform deposition of hyaline material.
An abnormally decreased chloride concentration in the blood.
Flaring of distal femur.
An abnormal increase of density of the bones making up the calvaria.
Chronic pain in the limbs with no clear focal etiology.
Eosinophil infiltration of skeletal muscle.
A closed sac located in the spleen.

For children from birth to 4 years of age the palm width is more than 2 SD above the mean; for children from 4 to 16 years of age the palm width is above the 95th centile; or, the width of the palm appears disproportionately wide for the length.

A deviation from normal range of the erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), a test that measures the distance that erythrocytes have fallen after one hour in a vertical column of anticoagulated blood under the influence of gravity. The ESR is a nonspecific finding. An elevation may indicate inflammation or may be caused by any condition that elevates fibrinogen. A decreased ESR may be seen in polycythemia or in certain blood diseases in which red blood cells have an irregular or smaller shape that causes slower settling.
A structural anomaly of the first metacarpal.
An abnormality of the thalamus.
Slow or limited growth after birth.
Reduced movement of the lateral rectus muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.
A structural anomaly of the digestive system.
Small defect of the helical fold that lies at the junction of the superior and descending portions of the helix.
Underdevelopment of the biceps muscle.
An abnormally increased phosphate concentration in the blood.

Absence of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
An abnormally decreased amount of catalase activity.
An anomaly of a metacarpophalangeal joint.
A non-neoplastic cardiac tumor characterized by calcification and eosinophilic amorphous material in the background of dense collagenous fibrous tissue.
A region of the aortic media in which smooth muscle cell nuclei, involving multiple lamellae, are not clearly identifiable on an hematoxylin and eosin stain.
Congenital absence of the vermis of cerebellum.
Midline indentation or cleft of the scrotum.
A bacterial infection and inflammation of the skin und subcutaneous tissues.
?xrefs: MSH:D002481 SNOMEDCT_US:128936008 UMLS:C0007642 UMLS:C0162627 SNOMEDCT_US:385627004 MSH:D017192 SNOMEDCT_US:128045006

?def: A cartilage capped bony outgrowth of a long bone. Osteochondroma arises on the external surface of bone containing a marrow cavity that is continuous with that of the underlying bone.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the breast.
Premature synostosis of only the right lambdoid suture.

Osteopoikilosis is a benign, asymptomatic sclerotic dysplasia of the bones. It affects both male and female and may be seen at any age. Radiographically sclerotic circular or ovoid lesions are usually symmetrically distributed in a periarticular location. Lesions can increase or decrease in size and number in serial radiographs or even disappear and do not have increased bone radiotracer uptake.
Congenital atresia of the pylorus.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes one to three.
Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located on the skin of sole of foot.
Deposition of calcium salts in a tissue or location in which calcification does not normally occur.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one to four.

A lesion that is observed following light damage to the macula. Damage to the retinal by exposure to intense visible light, usually the sun. Intense light exposure such as staring at the sun causes fine structural anomalies in the outer segments of the photoreceptors and the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) cells of the macula. Symptoms usually develop within 1 to 4 h after exposure and include decreased vision, metamorphopsia, micropsia, and central or paracentral scotomas. Fundus examination typically shows a small yellow spot with a surrounding gray zone in the foveolar or parafoveolar area. Spontaneous evolution leads to the improvement of visual acuity.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the middle phalanx of the 4th finger is affected.
Terminal broadening of the fingers (distal phalanges of the fingers).
The inability to synthesize postvaccination antibodies against a hepatisis B antigen, as measured by antibody titer determination following vaccination.
Visible space between the dental arches in occlusion.
An insufficiency of the aortic valve, leading to regurgitation (backward flow) of blood from the aorta into the left ventricle.
A fissure in the gingiva (gums), i.e., the mucosal tissue that lies over the mandible and maxilla.
Penile length more than 2 SD above the mean for age.
Liver mast cell infiltration.
A disordered proliferation of mature tissues that are native to the kidneys.
A decreased rate of pyruvate carboxylase activity.
Muscular atrophy involving the muscles of the hand.

Paralysis of voluntary muscles means loss of contraction due to interruption of one or more motor pathways from the brain to the muscle fibers. Although the word paralysis is often used interchangeably to mean either complete or partial loss of muscle strength, it is preferable to use paralysis or plegia for complete or severe loss of muscle strength, and paresis for partial or slight loss. Motor paralysis results from deficits of the upper motor neurons (corticospinal, corticobulbar, or subcorticospinal). Motor paralysis is often accompanied by an impairment in the facility of movement.
Disproportionate shortening of the proximal segment of the arm (i.e. the humerus).
Any deviation from the normal range of a protein concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Absence of one or more interphalangeal creases (i.e., of the transverse lines in the skin between the phalanges of the fingers).
The presence of large spherical melanosomes (1 to 6 micrometer in diameter) in the cytoplasm of melanocytes.

A benign pituitary-region neoplasm that originates from Rathke's pouch. Craniopharyngiomas are benign slow growing tumours that are located within the sellar and para sellar region of the central nervous system.

Flesh-colored or yellowish papules, 2 mm or larger, that are responses to internal mechanical pressure and weakness in the connective tissue in the dermis, appear commonly over the medial aspect of the heel, but in some cases on the wrists. They are thought to represent herniations of adipose tissue through the plantar fascia retinaculum.

An acute phenomenon characterized by hypotension and anasarca due to the loss of plasma volume into peripheral tissues, with evidence of decreased plasma volume (hemoconcentration) and protein loss from the intravascular space (hypoalbuminemia) during acute episodes.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:87730004 UMLS:C0343084 UMLS:C1382398 SNOMEDCT_US:1608005 MSH:D019559 pmid:24808988 pmid:24467750

?def: Extension of the proximal transverse crease (five finger crease) to the ulnar edge of the palm.
A developmental anomaly wtih a small tubular or saccular midline stomach.
Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the humerus.
A congenital skeletal deformity characterized by the elevation of one scapula (thus, one scapula is located superior to the other).
Congenital absence of the normal opening of a structure of the urinary tract.
Excessively deep creases of the palm.
A partial dislocation of one or more intervertebral joints in the cervical vertebral column.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the foot.
Failure of the immune system to protect the body adequately from infection, due to the absence or insufficiency of some component process or substance.
The presence of more than the normal number of eyelids.
Any abnormality of the physiological function of the skin.
A type of double aortic arch in which the two branches are of equal size. In most cases of double aortic arch, the right aortic arch is larger and located higher than the left aortic arch.

A malignant cutaneous tumor of the elderly that is characterized by an aggressive course with regional nodal involvement, distant metastases and a high rate of recurrence. Most patients present with rapidly growing, painless, firm, non-tender, dome-shaped red, occasionally ulcerated skin nodules, which have a red or bluish color, measuring up to several centimeters, on predominantly sun-exposed areas of the body. The overlying skin is smooth and shiny, sometimes exhibiting ulcerative, acneiform or telangiectatic features.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against the La/Sjogrens syndrome antigen.
A history of repeated fungal infections located on the sole of the foot, usually manifested by scaling, maceration, and itching.

A finding of a focus of increased echogenicity upon prenatal ultrasound examination of the fetus. The foci may be present in one or both ventricles. Echogenic intracardiac focus (EICF) is defined as a focus of echogenicity comparable to bone, in the region of the papillary muscle in either or both ventricles of the fetal heart.
A coloboma of the iris.
An abnormality of the Dura mater.
All of the metacarpal bones of the hand have a pointed proximal appearance.
The presence of an altered number of the incisor teeth.
An increased amount of glutamate in the blood.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the distal phalanx of the 5th finger is affected.
Absence of the vestibular nerve
A skin nodule that is unusually hard (indurated).
Hair that is fine or thin to the touch.
Underdevelopment of the ilium ala.
Absence of the middle phalanx of the index (2nd) finger.
Thick, elongated, worm-like or corkscrew eosinophilic bundle that are found on H&E staining of the brain in the presence of long standing gliosis, occasional tumors, and some metabolic disorders.
Absence of the distal phalanx of the middle (3rd) finger.
An abnormality of the jejunum, i.e., of the middle section of the small intestine.
An abnormality affecting one or both 5th fingers.
Excretion in urine of proteins of a size smaller than albumin (molecular weight 69 kD).
A type of glomerulonephropathy characterized by thickening of the basement membrane and deposition of immune complexes in the subepithelial space.

Fibrofolliculoma is a clinically asymptomatic, 2-4 mm, skin-colored, dome-shaped smooth papule. It usually arises in the form of multiple lesions in adults in different areas such as the scalp, forehead, face, and neck. According to histology, the lesion is a fibrotic hamartoma characterized by infundibular epithelial proliferation and perifollicular fibrous proliferation.
The presence of a localized dilatation or ballooning of a cerebral artery.
Decreased activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain.
A congenital malformation with a cleft (gap or opening) in the midline of the face.
Lack of transparency of the corneal epithelium.
This term applies to all changes in bone mineral density of the tarsal bones, which (depending on severity) can be seen on x-rays as a change in density and or structure of the bone.
Developmental hypoplasia of the cochlea.
An abnormality of the placenta (the organ that connects the developing fetus to the uterine wall) or of the umbilical cord (the cord that connects the fetus to the placenta).
Abnormally short chordae tendineae of the tricuspid valve.
A lung infection by Mycobacterium tuberculosis a slightly curved non-motile, aerobic, non-capsulated and non-spore forming strains of mycobacteria.
The presence of erythrocyte in the aqueous humor of the anterior chamber of the eye.
An abnormality of skeletal development characterized by a disturbance of the metaphysis and its histological structure with relatively normal epiphyses and vertebrae.
Manifest deviation of the visual axes not controlled by fusion.
A reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood.
Congenital fusion (ankylosis) of the interphalangeal joint of the thumb.
Hypertrophy (increase in size) of muscle cells in a generalized (not localized) distribution.
Abnormal calcification in the cardiovascular system.
An increased concentration of proteins in the blood.
Ingrowth of new blood vessels into the cornea.
A reduced level of the complement component C4a in circulation.
Underdevelopment of the corpus callosum.
Reduced level of a protein that is normally present on the granulocyte surface as assessed by flow cytometry.
Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the second toe.
A patchwork of intermingled areas of increased and decreased attenuation visualized on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography.

Lipofuscin (age pigment) is a brown-yellow, electron-dense, autofluorescent material that accumulates progressively over time in lysosomes of postmitotic cells, such as neurons and cardiac myocytes. This term pertains if there is an increase in the accumulation of lipofuscin (also known as autofluorescent lipoprotein) more than expected for the age of the patient.
Deficiency of thyroid hormone.
EEG with abnormally slow frequencies.
A type of insomnia characterized by waking up (too) early in the morning.
An abnormality of the cerebral cortex with fewer gyri but with normal cortical thickness. This pattern is usually often associated with congenital microcephaly.
Abnormally reduced levels of aldosterone.
Increased size of the head of sperm.
Breakage (tear) of a tendon.
Agenesis of upper secondary incisor or of upper central primary incisor.
Absence of the sweat glands.
An abnormality of the placenta, the organ that connects the developing fetus to the uterine wall to enable nutrient uptake, waste elimination, and gas exchange.

Left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) obstruction can occur at the valvular, subvalvular, or supravalvular level. In general, there is an obstruction to forward flow which increases afterload, and if untreated, can result in hypertrophy, dilatation, and eventual failure of the left ventricle.
No identifiable superior and/or inferior lacrimal punctum.
Inflammation of a lymph node.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the middle phalanx of the 5th toe.
Convergent strabismus in which normal binocular single vision is alternating with large angle esotropia in rhythmic cycle.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a branched chain family amino acid in the blood circulation.
Detection of methadone or its metabolite 2-ethylidene-1,5-dimethyl-3,3- diphenylpyrrolidine (EDDP) in urine.
Abnormality of macular or foveal pigmentation.

Lipofuscin, a generic term applied to autofluorescent lipopigment, is a mixture of protein and lipid that accumulates in most aging cells, particularly those involved in high lipid turnover (e.g., the adrenal medulla) or phagocytosis of other cell types (e g., the retinal pigment epithelium or RPE; macrophage). This term pertains if there is an increase in the neuronal accumulation of lipofuscin (also known as autofluorescent lipoprotein) more than expected for the age of the patient.

An abnormality of conjugate lateral gaze in which the affected eye shows impairment of adduction. The pathognomonic clinical sign of internuclear ophthalmoplegia is an impaired adduction while testing horizontal saccades on the side of the lesion in the ipsilateral medial longitudinal fascicule.
A lack of strength of the proximal muscles.
Deviation from normal of the ratio of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) within platelets.
An abnormality of an atrioventricular valve.
Overshoot of downward saccadic eye movements.
A ventricular septal defect that involves the inlet of the right ventricular septum immediately inferior to the AV valve apparatus.
Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, occurring in the midline region of the face.
Anomaly of the contour of the proximal epiphysis of the tibia such that its normally smooth appearance is irregular.
EEG with an amplitude less than 30 microvolts without observable occipital alpha rhythm (8-13 Hz).
Convergent squint which follows loss or impairment of vision.
Presence of multiple hyperplastic polyps in the colon. Hyperplastic polyps are generally about 5 mm in size and show hyperplastic mucosal proliferation.
An abnormality of chloride homeostasis or concentration in the body.

Information about close relatives of an individual who is the proband of a study or who is being investigated with the goal of identifying a medical diagnosis. Usually, the family history includes information from three generations of relatives, including children, brothers and sisters, parents, aunts and uncles, nieces and nephews, grandparents, and cousins.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of calcium in the blood circulation.
Complete duplication of middle phalanx of fourth toe.
A distinct type of headache characterized by piercing, throbbing, or electric-shock-like chronic pain in the upper neck, back of the head, and behind the ears, usually on one side.
A neoplasm composed of neural epithelium, not necessarily a neoplasm located in the neural epithelium or neuroepithelium.
Partial dislocation of the head of the radius in the posterior direction.
The presence of a fifth metatarsal bone that has not undergone ossification at an age when ossification is usually visible.
An abnormal thickening of the Achilles tendon.
Abnormally increased cuvature (anterior concavity) of the lumbar or cervical spine.
Anterior schisis (cleft or cleavage) of vertebral bodies.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the elbow.
An abnormal communication between the terminus of a coronary artery, bypassing the myocardial capillary bed and entering any segment of the systemic or pulmonary circulation.
Repetitive pressing, poking, and/or rubbing in the eyes.
Underdevelopment of the latissimus dorsi muscle, which is involved in adduction, extension, internal rotation, and transverse extension of the shoulder and assists in movement of the scapula.
Excessive action of the lateral rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.

A short humerus length is defined as a length below the 2.5th percentile for gestational age or as a measurement less than 0.9 of that predicted by the measured biparietal diameter. The humerus should be measured with the bone perpendicular to the ultrasound beam and with epiphyseal cartilages visible but not included in the measurement (pmid:16100637).
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers three and four.
Absence of the crystalline lens of the eye as a result of a developmental defect.
Developmental dysplasia of dentin or both the primary dentition and the permanent dentition.
Abnormal elevation of the floor of the posterior fossa including occipital condyles and foramen magnum.

Abnormal small intestinal contractions, such as spasms and intestinal paralysis related to the loss of the ability of the gut to coordinate muscular activity because of endogenous or exogenous causes.
Hyperplastic submucosal and myenteric plexus containing an increased number of ganglion cells, glial cells and nerve fibers.

A vascular malformation located in the lip that is characterized by direct blood shunting from an artery to a vein due to the absence of a capillary bed. The artery and vein can be directly connected by a fistula or indirectly connected by an abnormal vessel channel termed a nidus.
Underdevelopment of the ischiopubic ramus, which is comprised of the inferior pubic ramus and the inferior ramus of the ischium.
A developmental anomaly characterized by the presence of two, instead of one, ureter connecting a kidney to the bladder.
A reduced sense of touch (tactile sensation). This is usually tested with a wisp of cotton or a fine camel's hair brush, by asking patients to say 'now' each time they feel the stimulus.
A secondary ossification center in the proximal phalanx of the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
Inflammation of retinal blood vessels as manifested by perivascular sheathing or cuffing, vascular leakage and/or occlusion.
Uneven increase in bone density within the 1st metacarpal.
A deviation from the normal concentration of serum bile acid concentration.
Abnormal response to ristocetin as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of ristocetin.

A structural anomaly of the chordae tendinae of the mitral valve, whose main function is to transmit the contraction and relaxation of the papillary muscles during the cardiac cycle, thus ensuring the closing of the leaflets of the mitral valve.
A severe delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
An involuntary abnormality of fixation in which there is an abnormal saccade away from fixation followed by a delayed corrective saccade.

A Malignant mesothelioma originating from cells of the peritoneum (the thin layer of mesothelium lining the abdomen). Peritoneal mesothelioma is the second most common form of mesothelioma after pleural mesothelioma.

Any abnormality in the activation of T cells, i.e. the change in morphology and behavior of a mature or immature T cell resulting from exposure to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific.
A secondary ossification center in the middle phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
Congenital failure to develop, and absence of, the nipple.
An altered ability of the kidneys to void urine and/or specific substances.
A developmental defect resulting in the presence of fewer than the normal number of digits.
A reduction from normal of the mean corpuscular volume, or mean cell volume (MCV) of red blood cells (usually defined as an MCV below 80 femtoliters).

An abnormality of the pectoral muscle, comprising the pectoralis major, a thick, fan-shaped muscle of the anterior chest and the pectoralis minor, a thin, triangular muscle situated underneath the pectoralis major.
A type of lagophthalmos that occurs in association with facial nerve palsy.
Underdevelopment of the distal portion of the humerus.
Ventral, lateral, or ventrolateral bowing of the shaft and glans penis of more than 30 degrees.
A developmental defect that occurs if the two halves of the patella fail to fuse in early childhood.
A seizure that occurs in the context of a brain insult (systemic, toxic, or metabolic) and may not recur when the underlying cause has been removed or the acute phase has elapsed.

A type of ataxia characterized by the impairment of the ability to perform rapidly alternating movements, such as pronating and supinating his or her hand on the dorsum of the other hand as rapidly as possible.
A type of blistering that affects the skin of the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet.
The circumflex coronary artery originates from the right aortic sinus of Valsalva.
The presence of megakaryocytes in the bone marrow whose nuclei are more lobulated than expected for the size of the nucleus.
A developmental abnormality characterized by the absence of the fifth metatarsal bone.
Underdevelopment of the interstitial (Leydig) cells of the testis. These cells produce testosterone.

An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones of the fingers. The synonymous term \symphalangism of the hand\" may be translated as fusions of bones of varying digree, that involve at least one phalangeal bone of the hand. If bony fusions are referred to as \"Symphalangism\" the fusion occurs in a proximo-distal axis. Fusions of bones of the fingers in a radio-ulnar axis are referred to as \"bony\" Syndactyly."
Inability to see well at night or in poor light.
An increased concentration of cystine in the urine.
Increased width of the middle phalanx of finger.
Bleeding within the vitreous compartment of the eye.

Fluffy white patch on the retina, representing localized areas of dense white swelling of the retinal nerve fibre layer. They often have a zigzag internal structure, a feathered edge but an otherwise well-delineated form and an approximately 1 mm dimension; they project slightly into the vitreous and sometimes deflect retinal vessels.
Short-lived and not permanent. This term applies to a phenotypic abnormality that is temporary and of short duration.
Increased number of neutrophils circulating in blood.
EEG with sharp slow waves in the parietal region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
Absence of the proximal phalanx of the little (5th) finger.
A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.
Involuntary contractions of the neck musculature resulting in an abnormal posture of or abnormal movements of the head.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0949445 UMLS:C0152116 UMLS:C0040485 SNOMEDCT_US:270476009 SNOMEDCT_US:70070008 SNOMEDCT_US:74333002 MSH:D014103

?def: Abnormal deposition of periosteal bone.
A deviation in any aspect of the alternative complement pathway.

The lysosomal-vacuolar pathway has a role in the controlled intracellular digestion of macromolecules such as protein complexes and organelles. This feature refers to the presence of an abnormally increased number of autophagic vacuoles in muscle tissue.
An abnormality of the abdominal situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the abdomen and its organs.
An abnormality of compact bone (also known as cortical bone), which forms the dense surface of bones.
An abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the intestine.
Decreased strength of the medial rectus muscle.
EEG with repetitive generalized sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.
Onset of signs or symptoms of disease between the age of 5 and 15 years.

A form of lissencephaly in which the cortex is thickened and has four more or less disorganized layers rather than six normal layers resulting from incomplete neuronal migration during brain development.
