An abnormally reduced degree of pneumatization (i.e., formation of air cells) in the mastoid process with respect to age-dependent norms.
Nodding movement of the head or body.
Presence of complement C3 in the dermoepidermal junction that are dsitributed in a linear pattern. This feature can be appreciated by immunofluorescence microscopy.
A form of sensorineural deafness with either congenital onset or infantile onset, i.e., before the acquisition of speech.
Hypoplastic (short) distal phalanx of the thumb.
An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in an artery that is located within the skull (intracranial).
Splitting of the retinal layers in the macula.
Involuntary flexion or extension of the arms and legs.
An abnormal hair whorl (that is, a patch of hair growing in the opposite direction of the rest of the hair).
A decreased amount of lamin A/C in muscle tissue. This feature can be shown by immunohistochemistry of Western blotting of muscle tissue.

A condition in which there is increased production of gastrin by a gastrin-secreting tumor (usually located in the pancreas, duodenum, or abdominal lymph nodes) that stimulates the gastric mucosa to maximal activity, with consequent gastrointestinal mucosal ulceration.
An abnormally low-pitched voice.
Hypopigmented hair that appears silver-gray.
Underdevelopment of the pubis, which together with the ilium and the ischium, is one of the three bones that make up the hip bone.
Abnormal secretion of the platelet dense-granule content adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
A type of atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) where the are the atrioventricular node is used for anterograde conduction and the accessory pathway for retrograde conduction.
Synostosis affecting only the left coronal suture.
Osteoporosis affecting predominantly the vertebrae.
Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of fourth toe.
Dislocation of the distal humerus out of the elbow joint, where the radius, ulna, and humerus meet.
Prominence of blood vessels of the superficial episcleral tissues.
Drainage of cerebrospinal fluid through the nose. This can occur when there is a fistula between the dura and the skull base and discharge of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) from the nose.
A deviation from the normal circulating concentration of B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP).
Intraocular pressure that is 2 standard deviations above the population mean.
An abnormality of any of the muscles of the pharynx.
Presence of an angular or V -shaped indentation on the ulnar side of the fifth metacarpal bone (i.e., on the sides towards the fifth finger).
A deviation from normal of the mean corpuscular volume, or mean cell volume (MCV) of red blood cells, usually taken to be 80 to 100 femtoliters.
Partial or complete duplication of the middle phalanx of index finger.
A neoplasm originating in the pharynx.
Underdevelopment of the ciliary body.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the vertebral column.
A unilateral or bilateral eyelid retraction due to midbrain lesions.
Multiple abnormal growths that arise from the lining of the large intestine (colon or rectum) and protrude into the intestinal lumen.
Curved appearance of the distal phalanx of the 5th (little) finger.
A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the toes 2, 3, and 4.
A capillary hemangioma surrounding the eyeball but within the orbit.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes two to five.
An decreased concentration of cholesterol in the blood.
Absence of the middle phalanx of the little (5th) finger.
Reduced size of the cerebellar cortex.
Underdevelopment of muscles of the neck.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.
An abnormal concentration of potassium(1+) in the urine.
An abnormal increase in the total number of T cells detected in the blood.
A type of keratitis characterized by inflammation in pinpoint areas of the corneal epithelium.
An abnormality of the intrinsic pathway (also known as the contact activation pathway) of the coagulation cascade.
A widening (ballooning) localized in the wall of the posterior communicating artery.
Tiny bumps of thickened skin (hyperkeratosis) on the palms of the hands.
A reduction below the normal concentration of the HDL3c subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL3c particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 7.20-7.79 nm.
Frontal hairline with bilateral arcs to a low point in the midline of the forehead.
Repeated episodes of pyelonephritis.
Abnormally increased levels of ethanolamine in circulation.
An abnormality of the glia cell.
Any deviation from the normal ocular alignment.
A thickened white patch on the oral mucosa that cannot be rubbed off.
?xrefs: MSH:D007971 MSH:D007972 SNOMEDCT_US:9187004 UMLS:C0023532 SNOMEDCT_US:414603003 UMLS:C1704317

?def: Widening of the femoral head and neck.

Centrally located corpus callosum hyperintensities said to resemble snowballs upon magnetic resonance imaging (with T2 or Sagittal fluid attenuated inversion recovery [FLAIR] sequences). The central location in the callosum makes them pathognomonic for Susac syndrome.
A lipoma localized to the tongue. May present as a nontender, soft, spherical mass of the tongue.
Hyperplasia of the islets of Langerhans that affects only certain regions of the pancreas and not others.
A functional anomaly of the lateral rectus muscle.
A failure to develop of the upper vagina.
Sudden breakage of an artery leading to leakage of blood from the circulation.
Phagocytosis by macrophages of erythrocytes, leukocytes, platelets, and their precursors in bone marrow and other tissues.
A small tear in the thin, moist tissue (mucosa) that lines the anus. It appears as a crack or slit in the mucous membrane of the anus.
A notch or cleft of the lower part of the retina.
The presence of developmental dysplasia of the femoral head.
A chronic autoimmune phenomenon characterized by fibrosis (or hardening) and vascular alterations of the skin.
Presence of a lipoma in the region of the sacrum.

With the pathergy test, a small, sterile needle is inserted into the skin of the forearm. The site of injectionis circuled and observed after one and two days. If a small red bump or pustule at the site of needle insertion occurs, the pathergy test is considered to have a positive (abnormal) result.
An anomaly of the dynein arms of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.
Increased numbers of mesangial cells per glomerulus, defined as four or more nuclei in a peripheral mesangial segment.
An abnormality of coagulation related to a decreased concentration of vitamin K-dependent protein S. Protein S is a cofactor of protein C.
Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers with respect to age-dependent norms.
Developmental hypoplasia of teeth.
The union of two separately developing tooth germs typically leading to one less tooth than normal in the affected dental arch.
Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, occurring in the face.

Brown or blue-gray discoloration of the skin tha can present on the axillary and inguinal areas, face, palms or soles. In addition, blue-black discoloration can be apparent on skin overlying cartilage in which the pigment is deposited, such as the ears. This is a characteristic manifestation of alkaptonuria, which is an autosomal recessively inherited deficiency of homogentisic acid oxidase that results in accumulation of homogentisic acid in collagenous structures. The sclerae are also typically involved.
Subjective impression of increased softness upon palpitation of the skin.
An abnormality of the thenar eminence, i.e., of the muscle on the palm of the human hand just beneath the thumb.
Complete obstruction of a carotid artery.
A structural abnormality of a diaphysis of the arm or leg.

An increased concentration of tropnin T in the blood, which is a cardiac regulatory protein that controls the calcium mediated interaction between actin and myosin. Raised cardiac troponin concentrations are now accepted as the standard biochemical marker for the diagnosis of myocardial infarction.
Development of the reproductive system is inconsistent with the chromosomal sex.
An abnormality of lymphocytes.
The presence of a supernumerary finger (not a thumb) involving the third or fourth metacarpal with associated osseous syndactyly.
Underdevelopment of the carotid canal, which normally is a circular aperture in the temporal bone of the skull through which the internal carotid artery and the carotid plexus of nerves traverse.
A small V-shaped indentation on the internal aspect of the femoral head. This feature is well illustrated in Figure 5 of PMID:11694546.
inflammation of the adenoid tissue.

A condition in which middle parts of the foot (toes and metatarsals) are missing giving a cleft appearance. The severity is very variable ranging from slightly hypoplastic 3rd toe over absent 2nd or 3rd toes as far as oligo- or monodactyl feet.
A benign or malignant neoplasm (tumour) originating in striated muscle, either skeletal muscle or cardiac muscle.
Relatively increased growth of the fibula compared to that of the tibia.
Abnormal formation of new bone on the surface of a bone of the hand.
A form of neutropenia with congenital onset.
An increase in the level of allantoin in the serum.
Excretion of urine with an acid pH.
A delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.
An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which both lungs have the morphology of a right lung.
A significant descent of the kidney as the patient moves from the supine to the erect position.
Chest wall pain in the area of the costochondral junctions.
The presence of telangiectases on the skin of palm of hand.
Visible increase in width of the non-hallux digit without an increase in the dorso-ventral dimension.

A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on chromosomes in which a trait can manifest in the heterozygotes and homozygotes, with differing phenotype severity present dependent on the number of alleles affected.
A defect of the atrioventricular septum of the heart.
?xrefs: Fyler:606 MSH:C562831 Fyler:1100 SNOMEDCT_US:15459006 MSH:D004694 UMLS:C1389016 Fyler:0606 UMLS:C0014116

?def: A cystic tumor of the ovary, containing thin, clear, yellow serous fluid and varying amounts of solid tissue.
Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of middle finger.
A viral infection that fails to be contained by the immune sytem and spreads throughout the body.
Any structural anomaly of a chromosome, which is a thread like molecule consisting of DNA and proteins (chromatin) that contains DNA sequences for genes and other genetic elements in linear order.
Agenesis of secondary molar tooth.
Reduced ability to move the eye in the direction of the nose.
A reduced level of the complement component Factor H in circulation.
Abnormally decreased size of the anterior fontanelle with respect to age-dependent norms.
Displacement of the thumb from its normal position.
An anomaly of vein.
A sudden attack of dyspnea that occurs while the affected person is at rest.
A subjective feeling of tiredness characterized by a lack of energy and motivation and that is induced by exertion or exercise.
Increased width of nail.

Deviation from normal in the amount of delta sarcoglycan in muscle. The alpha, beta, gamma, and delta sarcoglycans are components of the dystrophin-complex. They are all N-glycosylated transmembrane proteins with a short intra-cellular domain, a single transmembrane region and a large extra-cellular domain containing a cluster of conserved cysteines.
Any abnormality of the blood vessels of the conjunctiva.
The presence of bilateral coxa_valga.
A venous angioma of the frontal lobe of the brain.
An increased concentration of keratan sulfate in the urine.
The presence of an increased mass of red blood cells in the circulation.
Any structural abnormality of the cerebellum.

Accumulation of chyle (the whitish fluid taken up by the lacteals in the intestine, consisting of an emulsion of lymph and triglyceride fat thatpasses into the veins by the thoracic duct) in the pericardium. Chylopericardium is generally caused by obstruction of or trauma to the thoracic duct.
A reduction of bone mineral density, that is, of the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones.
A type of arrhythmia that originates above the ventricles, whereby the electrical impulse propagates down the normal His Purkinje system similar to normal sinus rhythm.
Sclerosis (hardening) of the arteries with increased thickness of the wall of arteries as well as increased stiffness and a loss of elasticity.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0003850 UMLS:C4280568 SNOMEDCT_US:72092001 MSH:D001161 SNOMEDCT_US:107671003 SNOMEDCT_US:28960008

?def: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a dicarboxylic acid in the blood circulation.

The presence of a piece lung tissue which is not attached to the pulmonary blood supply and does not communicate with the other lung tissue (not connected to the standard bronchial airways and not performing a function in respiration).
A facial appearance characterized by a permanently or nearly permanently opened mouth.
An area of fat accumulation at the back of the neck in the form of a hump.
Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in bile ducts.
An abnormality of the intestine. The closely related term enteropathy is used to refer to any disease of the intestine.
An EEG with constitutional variants contains waves that are rare or unusual but not generally pathologic.
An abnormal concentration of 5-methyltetrahydrofolate in the blood.
Triangular shaped phalanges of the 4th finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
An impairment of the ability to track objects with the ocular smooth pursuit system, a class of rather slow eye movements that minimizes retinal target motion.
An abnormality of an internal carotid artery.
Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the ovary.
An increased concentration of tyrosine in the blood.
Any abnormality of the foramen magnum.
Inflammatory or noninflammatory diseases affecting the glomeruli of the nephron.

An abnormality of the base of the skull, which forms the floor of the cranial cavity and separates the brain from other facial structures. The skull base is made up of five bones: the ethmoid, sphenoid, occipital, paired frontal, and paired parietal bones, and is subdivided into 3 regions: the anterior, middle, and posterior cranial fossae. The petro-occipital fissure subdivides the middle cranial fossa into 1 central component and 2 lateral components.
Aplasia (congenital absence) of the vas deferens.
Repeated episodes of sudden-onset and transient lethargy.
The presence of M2 nti-mitochondrial antibody (immunoglobulins) in the serum.
An increased concentration of glucose in the blood following a meal.
Multiple pointlike areas of high T2 signal observed upon magnetic resonance imaging of the periventricular cerebral white matter.
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of an atery, vein or the heart.
?xrefs: Fyler:2399 UMLS:C4020848 SNOMEDCT_US:85659009 UMLS:C0002940 SNOMEDCT_US:432119003 MSH:D000783

?def: A type of pigment gallstone that is brown, containing calcium fatty acids. These stones are softer than black pigment gallstones.
Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
A breast lump is any discrete mass in a breast noticed by the patient, significant other, or physician.
A defect in the motor ability that enables speech.
Excessive growth of the bones of the vertebral bodies.

Complete or partial duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx), a partially fused appearance of the two bones, or two separate bones appearing side to side.
Complete absence of the vestibule of the inner ear.
Absent thumb, i.e., the absence of both phalanges of a thumb and the associated soft tissues.
A cancer of the prostate.
An decreased concentration of tyrosine in the blood.
Underdevelopment of the helix, i.e., of the outer rim of the pinna.
A usually benign neoplasm originating in the chemoreceptor tissue of the cartodi body, glomus jugulare, glomus tympanicum, aortic bodies, or the female genital tract.
Tremor of the trunk in an anterior-posterior plane at 3-4 Hz.
Failure to form of portions of the abdominal musculature.

Onychodystrophy (nail dystrophy) refers to nail changes apart from changes of the color (nail dyschromia) and involves partial or complete disruption of the various keratinous layers of the nail plate.
A discontinuity of the skin exhibiting incomplete loss of the epidermis, a lesion that is moist, circumscribed, and usually depressed.
EEG with sharp slow waves in the frontal region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
A mild form of conductive hearing impairment.
A congenital anomaly with a narrowing or complete absence of the opening between the right ventricle and the pulmonary artery.
Anemia characterized by the presence of erythroblasts that are larger than normal (megaloblasts).
An increase in size of the third ventricle.
An abnormal lack of stability of the cervical spine.
A deficit in the ability to fixate eye movements in order to stabilize images on the retina
Stricture or narrowing of the larynx that may be associated with symptoms of respiratory difficulty depending on the degree of laryngeal narrowing.
Absence of the inner ear due to a developmental defect.
Increased size of the maxillary central secondary incisor tooth.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react to thyroglobulin.

Lack of visual responsiveness or decrease in visual capabilities suggesting a lack of visual responsiveness or decrease in visual capabilities in an infant or young child in which visual behavior fails to meet normal developmental milestones.
A decrease in the maximum amount of negative pressure a person can generate during an inhalation.
Reduced ability to use nonverbal behavior for communication, such as eye-to-eye gaze, facial expression, body posture, and gestures.

Birbeck granules (BG) are cytoplasmic organelles that are only found in Langerhans cells (LC). The function of BG is still not completely understood, although most studies point toward an active role in receptor-mediated endocytosis and participation in the antigen-processing/presenting function of LC. This feature refers to the absence of BG in LC, a feature that can be documented by means of electron microscopy.
The presence of an elevated amount of 5-hydroxylysine in the urine. This compound is a hydroxylated derivative of the amino acid lysine that is present in certain collagens.
A developmental defect leading to the union of two adjacent vertebrae.
Abnormality of the occipital bone of the skull.
A coronary artery begins (branches off from) the pulmonary artery rather than as normal from the root of the aorta.
Prolonged bleeding post dental extraction sufficient to require medical intervention.
Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as phenobarbital in the hair.
Numerous lymphocytes surrounding blood vessels in the deep part of the dermis.
An eyelash that emerges from the underside (conjunctiva) of the upper or lower eyelid.
Pili (from Latin pilus, hair) torti (from Latin tortus, twisted) refers to short and brittle hairs that appear flattened and twisted when viewed through a microscope.

The cleft lip is midway between the philtral ridge and the commissure of the mouth. The cleft is lateral to the normally shaped and placed nasal ala and passes onto the cheek. The cleft extends through the lower eyelid lateral to the punctum. The lacrimal system and inner canthus are normal. Microphthalmia may be present. The alveolar cleft passes between the lateral incisor and canine, as in the Number 3 cleft. The cleft passes around the pyriform aperture and continues through the portion of the maxillary sinus medial to the infraorbital foramen. The cleft terminates at the medial end of the inferior orbital rim. There is severe vertical soft tissue deficiency in a Number 4 cleft, with the medial margins of the cleft lip extending directly into the medially placed cleft of the lower eyelid. Within the medial segment of the right-sided cleft lip, muscle elements are apparently absent. Muscle bunching is noted in the ipsilateral lateral lip segment, as is seen in a typical unilateral cleft lip. The anatomically normal nasal ala is superiorly displaced in association with a severe deficiency in the overall nasal length. Marked dystopia of the right globe results in its inferior displacement into the medially deficient orbital floor and inferior rim. Both globes are otherwise normal. The complete palatal cleft passes through the maxilla medial to the infraorbital foramen and extends to the medial portion of the inferior orbital rim without evidence of an intact maxillary sinus. Bony septation persists medially, thereby separating the nasal cavity from the orbit, maxillary sinus, and mouth, which are contiguous. Marked midfacial hypoplasia is present. The cleft is manifest as asymmetry of the body of the sphenoid; it is smaller on the right, with asymmetric placement of the pterygoid plates relative to the midline. The orbital floor cleft has no communication with the inferior orbital fissure. The cleft does not extend to the skull base, but there is marked facial asymmetry associated with plagiocephaly.
Enlargement of the large blood vessels in the choroid.
An abnormality in the production or cellular release of a chemokine (a class of cytokines).

An abnormality of the ability (skills) to perform a precise movement of large muscles with the intent to perform a specific act. Gross motor skills are required to mediate movements of the arms, legs, and other large body parts.

A neurological condition related to lesions of the basal ganglia leading to typical abnormalities including akinesia (inability to initiate changes in activity and perform volitional movements rapidly and easily), muscular rigidity (continuous contraction of muscles with constant resistance to passive movement), chorea (widespread arrhythmic movements of a forcible, rapid, jerky, and restless nature), athetosis (inability to sustain the muscles of the fingers, toes, or other group of muscles in a fixed position), and akathisia (inability to remain motionless).
A failure to collect oocytes after an apparently normal controlled ovarian hyperstimulation cycle for in vitro fertilization.
Any anomaly of the vocalizing of an infant's crying, i.e.,the typically loud voice production that is accompanied by tears and agitation.
An increased resorption of bone matrix by osteoclasts leading to bony defects involving the tarsal bones.
An abnormal morphology of the firstmetatarsal bone, which is short and wide and tapers distally, and lacks the normal diaphyseal constriction.

Cone-shaped epiphyses (also known as coned epiphyses) are epiphyses that invaginate into cupped metaphyses. That is, the epiphysis has a cone-shaped distal extension resulting from increased growth of the central portion of the epiphysis relative to its periphery.
Congenital absence of the extraocular muscles.
Smaller than normal size according to sex and gestational age related norms, defined as a weight below the 10th percentile for the gestational age.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the parietal region.
An abnormal narrowing of the pylorus.
Elevated concentration of isobutyrylglycine in the urine.
Intrauterine growth retardation that is 4 or more standard deviations below average, corrected for sex and gestational age.
Atrophy of the temporal cortex.
Crackles that are heard during the inspiratory phase.
Short palm.
Loss of myelin from peripheral nerves in a pattern that differs between right and left.
Increased width of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.
The loss of gum tissue. The result is that gum tissue is recessed and its position on the tooth is lowered, exposing the roots of the teeth.
Absence or underdevelopment of the eyelid.
An abnormally small sella turcica.
An increased amount of 3-aminoisobutyric acid in the urine.
A reduction in the thickness of the outer shell (cortex) of foot bones.
Abnormality in the space in the meninges beneath the arachnoid membrane and above the pia mater that contains the cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormally elevated concentration or amount of 11-deoxycorticosterone in the urine.
Focal seizure with eyelid myoclonia, not eyelid myoclonias in the context of absence seizures.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the knee.
A benign tumour of meningothelial cells of the meninges that usually occurs in middle age. It is typically unilateral and there is an association with neurofibromatosis type 2.

Keratoacanthoma (KA) is a common benign epithelial tumour that originates from the pilosebaceous glands. In most cases, it is characterized by rapid evolution, followed by spontaneous resolution over 4 to 6 months. KA usually presents as a solitary flesh-coloured nodule with a central keratin plug on the sun-exposed skin of elderly individuals.
Any anomaly of the structure of the larynx.
Excretion of oligosaccharides conjugated to sialic acid in the urine.
Short (hypoplastic) middle phalanx of finger, affecting one or more fingers.
A two-part calcaneus, a finding that probably results from delayed coalescence of two primary calcaneal centers of ossification.
Abnormal concentration of 1-methylhistidine in the urine.
A type of rosette in which a spoke-wheel arrangement of cells with tapered cellular processes radiates around a wall of a centrally placed vessel.
Excessive, increased hair growth located in the elbow region.
The presence of free monoclonal kappa immunoglobulin light chains in the urine.
Areas of white discoloration visible on the surface of the teeth (enamel) in the form of streaks or specks.
A type of Macrodactyly affecting one or several fingers.
A functional motor deficit where individuals whose responses to the challenges of exercise fail to achieve levels considered normal for their age and gender.
The presence of mildly increased concentrations of albumin in the urine (in adults, 30-150 mg per day).
Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger with another bone.
A deviation from the normal circulating concentration of the normal gonadotropin-releasing hormone level secreted from the pituitary gland.
A nevus is a type of hamartoma that is a circumscribed stable malformation of the skin.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:400096001 SNOMEDCT_US:51697005 UMLS:C0027960 SNOMEDCT_US:21119008 MSH:D009506 UMLS:C0027962 MSH:D009508

?def: The presence of lymphangiectasis in the pancreas.
Muscular rigidity (continuous contraction of muscles with constant resistance to passive movement).
In the resting position, the tip of the thumb is on, or near, the palm, close to the base of the fourth or fifth finger.
Inflammation of fascia, the tissue under the skin and over the muscle.

A myxoma (tumor of primitive connective tissue) of the heart. Cardiac myxomas consist of stellate to plump, cytologically bland mesenchymal cells set in a myxoid stroma. Cardiac myxomas are of endocardial origina and general project from the endocardium into a cardiac chamber.
Selective deficiency of one or more, but not all, classes of immunoglobulins.
Incapability to ambulate.
Tremor classified by the affected body part.

In contrast to forms of polydactyly where the supernumerary digit (this can either be a rudimentary or a completely 'normal' digit) is either located postaxial (on the fibular side of the foot, next top the little toe), preaxial (on the tibial side of the foot, next to the big toe) or mesoaxial (somewhere central, between big and little toe), a supernumerary digit may also be placed ectopically, meaning anywhere else except post-,meso- or preaxial. In the literature this is sometimes referred to as Disorganisation-like Syndrome (OMIM223200).
An abnormal reduction in the amplitude of the miniature endplate potentials, i.e. the postsynaptic response to transmitter released from an individual vesicle at the neuromuscular junction.

An elevated proportion of T cells that express human leukocyte antigen (HLA)-DR. HLA-DR is an MHC class II cell surface receptor that presents antigens (peptides of at least 9 amino acids), thereby constituting a ligand for the T-cell receptor. HLA-DR can be upregulated in response to immune stimulation.
Golden brown or gray deposits with a clockwise, whorl-like distribution in the inferior interpalpebal portion of the cornea.

Poor anticoagulant response to activated protein C. A plasma is termed 'APC resistant' when the addition of exogenous APC fails to prolong its clotting time in an activated partial thromboplastin time assay.
Inflammation of the eye, parts of the eye or the periorbital region.
A decreased concentration of protein in the blood.
Abnormally large size of glomeruli.
Increased mobility of one ore more metacarpophalangeal joint.
Breadth of the incisura from the anterior to posterior border greater than that observed in the average population.
Seizures that occur while the affected individual is sleeping.
Partial duplication of the proximal phalanx of fifth toe.
Shoulder dislocation occurring repeated times.

A measured foot length that is more than 2 SD below the mean for a newborn of 27 - 41 weeks gestation, or foot that is less than the 3rd centile for individuals from birth to 16 years of age (objective). Alternatively, a foot that appears disproportionately short (subjective).
Naevus flammeus localised in the skin of the eyelid.
Chronic loss of joint motion of the metacarpophalangeal joint of the 2nd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

An inflammatory exfoliative dermatosis involving nearly all of the surface of the skin. Erythroderma develops suddenly. A patchy erythema may generalize and spread to affect most of the skin. Scaling may appear in 2-6 days and be accompanied by hot, red, dry skin, malaise, and fever.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:396350005 MSH:D003873 SNOMEDCT_US:400005007 SNOMEDCT_US:396349005 SNOMEDCT_US:399992009 SNOMEDCT_US:200948000 UMLS:C0011606

?def: A type of acute myeloid leukemia in which abnormal promyelocytes predominate.
Amelia of one or both upper limbs.

Applies to an abnormality whose localization corresponds to the lines of Blashko, which are thought to reflect the pathways of epidermal cell migration and proliferation during the development of the fetus.
An abnormal accumulation of excess fluid in the lower extremity resulting in swelling of the feet and extending upward to the lower leg.
Piebaldism is characterized by stable and persistent, well-circumscribed depigmented patches present at birth affecting the skin of the face, trunk, and extremities in a symmetrical distribution.
Dislocation of many joints.
Supernumerary ridge or crus of the ear arising from the antihelix.
Inflammation of the uterine cervix.
Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger.
Slowing at frequencies between 7.5 and 8.5 Hz.
The presence of unusually deep creases (ridges/wrinkles) on the skin of sole of foot.
A cystic lymphatic lesion of the neck.
?xrefs: NCIT:C8965 SNOMEDCT_US:423984004 UMLS:C0206620 SNOMEDCT_US:40225001 MSH:D018191 SNOMEDCT_US:399882002

?def: A type of monoclonal elevation of IgG in which the involved immunoglobulin has an abnormal structure with a lambda light chain but not a heavy chain.
Premature synostosis of only the left lambdoid suture.
An abnormality of a levator veli palatini.
A crease that connects the proximal and distal transverse palmar creases.
The presence of fibromata beneath finger or toenails.

Decreased activity of coagulation factor XII. Factor XII (fXII) is part of the intrinsic coagulation pathway and binds to exposed collagen at site of vessel wall injury, activated by high-MW kininogen and kallikrein, thereby initiating the coagulation cascade.
Lack (aplasia) of the ethmoidal sinus.

This sign is seen in pneumomediastinum in which air accumulates between the lower border of the heart and the superior part of the diaphragm, which results in complete visualization of the diaphragm in chest X-ray, hence named continuous diaphragm sign.
Overproduction of gonadotropins (FSH, LH) by the anterior pituitary gland.
Any structural abnormality of the pulmonary valve.
Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger.
Missing humerus bone associated with congenital failure of development.
An abnormal reduction in the ability to masticate (chew), i.e., in the ability to crush and ground food in preparation for swallowing.
An abnormal red-brown color of the urine.
A type of malocclusion in which there is a gap between the anterior teeth (incisors).
Lack of any response to stimulation upon electroretinography.
An infection of the small intestine (enteritis) by clostridium difficile.
Underdevelopment of the colon.
Absence (agenesis) or underdevelopment of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the 3rd toe.

A mode of inheritance that is observed for dominant traits related to a gene encoded on the X chromosome. In the context of medical genetics, X-linked dominant disorders tend to manifest very severely in affected males. The severity of manifestation in females may depend on the degree of skewed X inactivation.
An increased concentration of 4-hydroxy-L-proline the urine.
Abnormal concentration of urobilinogen present in the stool.
A row of beadlike prominences at the junction of a rib and its cartilage (i.e., enlarged costochondral joints), resembling a rosary.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the esophagus.
A discrete abnormal tissue mass that protrudes into the lumen of the small intestine and is attached to the intestinal wall either by a stalk, pedunculus, or a broad base.
Blockade of impulses at a focal site along the course of a motor axon.
Gradual, very slow onset of disease manifestations.
Abnormally wide (broad) distal phalanx of finger of all fingers.
An abnormality of the creases of the skin of palm of hand.
A kind of craniosynostosis affecting the sagittal suture.
Abnormal sensations with no apparent physical cause that are painful or unpleasant.
Abnormal growth ossification centers in children. Initially a degeneration/ necrosis followed by regeneration or recalcification.
The presence of a stenotic, i.e., constricted ureter.
A depression located at an oral commissure.

Small, dome-shaped nodules without a prominent central vessel located on the conjunctiva. The lymphoid follicles are located in the subendothelial region of the conjunctiva. They consist of a germinal center that contains immature, proliferating lymphocytes, as well as a corona that contains mature lymphocytes and plasma cells.
Repeated episodes of inflammation of a vein associated with venous thrombosis (blood clot formation within the vein).
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the respiratory system.
Pit in the midline of the philtral groove.
An elevated concentration of C-peptide in the circulation. Since C-peptide is secreted in equimolar amounts to insulin, this feature correlates with increased insulin secretion.
Edema affecting the region situated around the orbit of the eye.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:109245003 UMLS:C0424810 UMLS:C0149754 UMLS:C0151205 SNOMEDCT_US:267041004 SNOMEDCT_US:49563000

?def: An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can expel following maximal insipiration, with the test being performed after the administration of a bronchodilating medication.
Underdevelopment of muscles of the arm.
An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater in the region surrounding the cerebrum.
Increased concentration of cotinine in urine.

Cerebellar ataxia refers to ataxia due to dysfunction of the cerebellum. This causes a variety of elementary neurological deficits including asynergy (lack of coordination between muscles, limbs and joints), dysmetria (lack of ability to judge distances that can lead to under- oder overshoot in grasping movements), and dysdiadochokinesia (inability to perform rapid movements requiring antagonizing muscle groups to be switched on and off repeatedly).

Thickening of the peribronchovascular interstitium, a connective tissue sheath that surrounds the central bronchi and pulmonary arteries. The peribronchovascular interstitium extends from the level of the pulmonary hila into the peripheral lung. This feature may be ascertained on high-resolution computer tomography.
Mild reduction of the ability to see defined as visual acuity less than 6/12 (20/40 in US notation; 0.5 in decimal notation) but at least 6/18 (20/63 in US notation; 0.32 in decimal notation).

A deviation from the normal concentration in blood of an apolipoprotein, i.e., of a protein that binds lipids to form lipoprotein and is thereby responsible for the transport of lipids in the blood and lymph circulation.
A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs with onset in infancy.
Abnormality of the sella turcica, a saddle-shaped depression in the sphenoid bone at the base of the human skull.
Absence of nail of little finger.
A phenomenon whereby patients are not able to stand up without the use of the hands owing to weakness of the proximal muscles of the lower limbs.
Nonmidline alveolar cleft of the maxilla.
An abnormality of a medial pterygoid muscle.
A situation in which mutation carriers do not show clinically evident phenotypic abnormalities.
An anomaly of the second toe.
An abnormal dark-yellow color of the urine.
A chronic skin condition involving the inflammation of the apocrine sweat glands, forming pimple-like bumps known as abscesses.
Abnormal dilatation of the iris.
One or more brown punctate macules on the skin of the genitalia.
Inflammation of the meninges.
Congenital absence of the scrotum.
A broad appearance of the fourth toe.
A transient reduction in the number of erythroblasts in the circulation.

A subtype of retinitis pigmentosa in which, instead of the pathology starting in the mid-periphery like typical retinitis pigmentosa, the disease starts in the near periphery closer to the vascular arcades and tends to spare the far periphery.
An abnormally increased thickness of a leaflet of the aortic valve.
Any abnormality of the part of the nervous system that consists of the nerves and ganglia outside of the brain and spinal cord.
Peripheral arterial stenosis with onset before the age of 50 years.

No detectable response to the light-adapted 3.0 ERG (single-flash cone response). This type of ERG measures responses of the cone system; a-waves arise from cone photoreceptors and cone off-bipolar cells; the b-wave comes from On- and Off-cone bipolar cells.
An increased level of phosphoserine in the urine.
Reduced volume of the earlobe.

Inability to be weaned from intravenous (parenteral) nutrition, as judged by the hydration status (urine output, blood urea nitrogen, creatinine, urine sodium concentration), ability to maintain weight, stool output, and serum electrolyte status.
A kind of short stature in which different regions of the body are shortened to differing extents.
A type of eczema that occurs in the lips and perioral area.
Any deviation from the normal circulating creatine kinase concentration.
Underdevelopment of the breast.
Reduction in diameter of the ulna.
A deviation from the normal concentration of beta-C-terminal telopeptide of type I collagen in the blood circulation, a marker of the rate of bone turnover.
A growth pattern that displays an abnormal difference between the left and the right side.
A functional anomaly of the mouth (which is also known as the oral cavity).
Abnormally increased caliber of the left subclavian artery.
A lack or loss of appetite for food (as a medical condition).
A split or cleft in the uvula resulting from incomplete fusion of the palatine shelves.
Increased width of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger.
Absence of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.
ABO phenotype B, corresponding to the genotype BO or BB.
Atrophy (wasting) of the cerebellar cortex.
A generalized form of developmental hypoplasia of the dental enamel.
An abnormal anterior curvature of a long bone.
Chronic loss of joint motion of the distal interphalangeal joint of the 4th finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.
Replacement of normal lung tissues by fibroblasts and collagen.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the distal phalanx of the 5th toe.
Interalar distance more than two standard deviations above the mean for age, i.e., an apparently increased width of the nasal base and alae.
Atrophy of the optic nerve. Optic atrophy results from the death of the retinal ganglion cell axons that comprise the optic nerve and manifesting as a pale optic nerve on fundoscopy.
Reduction in the anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.

An abnormality of the premaxilla [UBERON_0002244], the most anterior part of the maxilla that usually bears the central and lateral incisors and includes the anterior nasal spine and inferior aspect of the piriform rim. The premaxilla contains the bone and teeth of the primary palate.
An arachnoid cyst located within the ventricular system.
A type of hearing loss resulting from a combination of conductive hearing impairment and sensorineural hearing impairment.
The distal interphalangeal joint of the 2nd toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.
A specific combination of heart defects with a primum atrial septal defect, cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet, and inlet ventricular defect. There is one valve annulus and two valve orifices.
This applies to an individual who needs help with dressing or needs to be completely dressed.
Partial or complete duplication of the fifth proximal phalanx of hand.

Symmetrical vermiform facial atrophy that affects mainly the forehead, the chin, the ear lobes and helices. Atrophodermia vermiculata is characterized by erythema and follicular plugs on the cheeks, developing into painless reticular impressions.
Reduced intensity of muscle tendon reflexes in jaw.
Proximal radial shortening owing to a congenital defect of development.
A rounded, bulging chest that resembles the shape of a barrel. That is, there is an increased anteroposterior diameter and usually some degree of kyphosis.
Supraventricular tachycardia with an accessory connection mediated pathway that is called concealed becasue it is not seen on the ECG during sinus rhythm.
A teratoma arising in the nasopharyngeal region.
A small/hypoplastic or absent/aplastic 3rd (middle) finger.
Coxa vara includes all forms of decrease of the femoral neck shaft angle (the angle between the neck and the shaft of the femur) to less than 120 degrees.

An anomaly of the mitochondrion, the membranous cytoplasmic organelle the interior of which is subdivided by cristae. The mitochondrion is a self replicating organelle that is the site of tissue respiration.

A lymphangioma (congenital malformation consisting of focal proliferations of well-differentiated lymphatic tissue in multi cystic or sponge like structures) located within the mediastinum, i.e., the central compartment of the thoracic cavity that is surrounded by loose connective tissue. Mediastinal lymphangioma is a slow growing mass with benign features, and accounts for 1% of all mediastinal tumors.
Cholangitis associated with evident ductal fibrosis that develops as a consequence of long-standing bile duct inflammatory, obstruction, or ischemic injury; it can be obliterative or nonobliterative.
A deviation of the normal proportion of marginal zone B cells (CD19+/CD27+/IgM+/IgD+) in circulation relative to the total number of B cells.
Waking up at night gasping for breath.

Talipes equinovarus (also called clubfoot) typically has four main components: inversion and adduction of the forefoot; inversion of the heel and hindfoot; equinus (limitation of extension) of the ankle and subtalar joint; and internal rotation of the leg.
?xrefs: MSH:D003025 SNOMEDCT_US:397932003 UMLS:C0009081 SNOMEDCT_US:249808002 Fyler:4171 MEDDRA:10043106

?def: A type of pallor that is secondary to the presence of anemia.

An anomaly of a reflex that is elicited as a motor response to scraping of the skin. They are generally graded as present or absent. They differ from tendon reflexes in that the sensory signal must ascend the spinal cord to reach the brain and then descend the spinal cord to reach the motor neurons.
The presence of atretic ureter.

An abnormality of adhesion of thrombocytes. Normally, platelets adhere to collagen in the vascular subendothelium within seconds of injury via a receptor made up of glycoprotein Ia and IIa and GPVI and to vWF via receptor GPIb/IX/V. The adherent platelets then release granules that lead to platelet activation and aggregation.
An encephalocele located between bregma and lambda.
An abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) pattern of calcifications in soft tissues within or surrounding bones (as observed on radiographs).
The presence of an abnormal connection between the urethra and another organ or the skin.
Separation of the placenta from the uterus wall before delivery.
Increased concentration of 3-methylhistidine in the urine.
The presence of a dysgerminoma, i.e., an undifferentiated germ cell tumor of the ovary.
A decrease below the normal concentration of glycerol in the blood.

Any deviation from the normal amount of time to coagulation in the prothrombin time test, which is a measure of the extrinsic pathway of coagulation. The results of the prothrombin time test are often expressed in terms of the International normalized ratio (INR), which is calculated as a ratio of the patient's prothrombin time (PT) to a control PT standardized for the potency of the thromboplastin reagent developed by the World Health Organization (WHO) using the formula: INR is equal to Patient PT divided by Control PT.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers two and three.
Radiolucent focal defect of a rib shaft.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by being dehydrated, i.e., by a deficit in total body water.
Defect or defects of the morphogenesis of the left heart identifiable at birth.

A conduction block of the right branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a prolongation of the QRS complex (greater than 0.12 s) with delayed activation of the right ventricle and terminal delay on the EKG.
Mirror image duplication of digits affecting the hands only.
The presence of a fistula between the bowel and the perineum.
The presence of calcium deposition affecting one or more structures of the basal ganglia.
Flaring (widening) of the epiphysis.
An abnormality of the dental root.

The presence of intraceullar inclusion bodies (aggregates of stainable substances, usually proteins) in neutrophils. Cytoplasmic neutrophil inclusions (oval, basophilic) are also known as Doehle bodies.
A difference in the amount of intraocular pressure in the right and left eye.
Paralysis of both the extrinsic and intrinsic ocular muscles.
An abnormality of a levator palpebrae superioris.
Increased amplitude of the pulse pressure (systolic blood pressure minus diastolic blood pressure).
Hemorrhage occurring within the skull.
Applies to an abnormality that is situated in the central part of the body, in the head and trunk as distinguished from the limbs.
A localized defect in the anterior eye wall with protrusion of uveal tissue due to alterations in scleral thickness and structure.
A chronic disorder of the liver in which liver tissue becomes scarred and is partially replaced by regenerative nodules and fibrotic tissue resulting in loss of liver function.
An abnormality of coagulation related to a decreased concentration of heparin co-factor II
A structural anomaly of the nephron.
A myxoma originating in the skin.
A kind of craniosynostosis affecting the lambdoidal suture.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the distal phalanx of the thumb.
An abnormality of facial morphology characterized by a small mouth opening and constant contraction of the lips as if the patient were whistling.
A reduction in aldehyde oxidase activity.
An abnormally flat form of the proximal epiphysis of the radius.
A generalized form of periodontitis.
An abnormality of the eyelashes.
An abnormally increased tendency towards muscle fatigue induced by physical exercise.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger is affected.

A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on one of the autosomes (i.e., the human chromosomes 1-22) in which a trait manifests in heterozygotes. In the context of medical genetics, an autosomal dominant disorder is caused when a single copy of the mutant allele is present. Males and females are affected equally, and can both transmit the disorder with a risk of 50% for each child of inheriting the mutant allele.
Abnormal calcification of the vasculature.
Digits that appear disproportionately long compared to the foot.
Absence of the semicircular canal.

An abnormality of the proximal phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of arginine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Destruction of an area of humerus bone due to a disease process, such as cancer.

An crumpled radiographic appearance of the long bones, as is the long bone had been crushed together producing irregularities. This feature is the result of multiple fractures and repeated rounds of ineffective healing, as can be seen for instance in severe forms of osteogenesis imperfecta.

Colitis refers to an inflammation of the colon and is often used to describe an inflammation of the large intestine (colon, cecum and rectum). Colitides may be acute and self-limited or chronic, and broadly fit into the category of digestive diseases.
Inability to ejaculate.
Underdevelopment of the vertebral artery on one side.
An elevated level of carnitine in the urine.
Enlargement of the thymus.
Inflammation of the myocardium.

An intermittent esotropia with binocular single vision present at distance fixation but esotropia on accommodation for near fixation. Usually associated with hypermetropia but patients can be emmetropic and rarely myopic. Associated with a high accommodative convergence/accommodation (AC/A) ratio.
An abnormality of the cochlea.
Abnormally curly or curved eyelashes.
An increase in the level of medium chain dicarboxylic acid in the urine.
The presence of a leiomyoma of the uterus.
?xrefs: NCIT:C3157 UMLS:C0042133 MSH:D007889 SNOMEDCT_US:44598004 SNOMEDCT_US:95315005 SNOMEDCT_US:146801000119103

?def: An abnormality of the zygomatic bone.
A type of sutural cataract in which the opacity follows the posterior Y suture.
Congenital abnormal dilation of the pupil on both sides.
An abnormally high amount of luteinizing hormone (LH) is released upon gonadotropin-releasing hormine stimulation test.
A developmental defect consisting in the duplication of part of the first metatarsal bone.
Inability to elicit tendon reflexes in the lower limbs.
Increase in thickness of the subpleural interstitium.

A supranuclear gaze palsy is an inability to look in a horizontal direction as a result of cerebral impairment. There is a loss of the voluntary aspect of eye movements, but, as the brainstem is still intact, all the reflex conjugate eye movements are normal.
Increased width of the humeral epiphyseal growth plate.
Slow, creeping onset, slow progress and long continuance of disease manifestations.
A diffuse form of amyloidosis.
The appearance of the urine having visible material in suspension, i.e., appearing cloudy.
Diplopia is a condition in which a single object is perceived as two images, it is also known as double vision.

Folds of membranous tissue (peritoneum, mesothelium) attached to the wall of the abdomen and enclosing viscera. Examples include the mesentery for the small intestine; the transverse mesocolon, which attaches the transverse portion of the colon to the back wall of the abdomen; and the mesosigmoid, which enfolds the sigmoid portion of the colon. Cells of the same embryologic origin also surround the other organs of the body such as the lungs (pleura) or the heart (pericardium).

Slipped capital femoral epiphysis is defined as a posterior and inferior slippage of the proximal epiphysis of the femur onto the metaphysis (femoral neck), occurring through the physeal plate during the early adolescent growth spurt.
Absence of the distal phalanx of the little (5th) finger.
A type of holoprosencephaly in which the left and right frontal and parietal lobes are fused and the interhemispheric fissure is only present posteriorly.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by breast feeding in an infant.
Underdevelopment of part or all of the male external reproductive organs (which include the penis, the scrotum and the urethra).
Excessive growth of a nail laterally into the nail fold.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the adrenal gland.
An abnormality of the concentration of pregnenolone in the blood.
Phalanges of the fingers becoming thinner toward the distal end.
A type of non-small cell lung carcinoma that is derived from stratified squamous epithelial cells.
Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against nut food products.
Muscular atrophy in the distribution of shoulder girdle and peroneal muscles.
A lesion of the skin that is located in a specific region rather than being generalized.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of homocarnosine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Reduction in the concentration of albumin in the blood.
An abnormality of the biliary system.
Any structural anomaly of the bladder.
An abnormal shortening of the femur.
Absence of the distal/terminal phalanx of the thumb.
An abnormality of blood circulation.
Abnormally reduced concentration of ferritin, a ubiquitous intracellular protein that stores iron, in the blood.

A type of headache that last hours with continuous pain of mild or moderate intensity, bilateral location, a pressing/tightening (non-pulsating) quality and that is not aggravated by routine physical activity such as walking or climbing stairs.
A type of second degree atrioventricular (AV) block characterized by sudden failure to conduct an impulse through the AV node without a preceding change in the PR interval.
A pale yellow discoloration of the temporal (lateral) portion of the optic disc.
A type of transposition of the great arteries (TGA) in which aorta is in front of and primarily to the right of the pulmonary artery. This is the most common kind of TGA.
Increased tendency of choiroidal blood vessels to allow fluids to leak characterized by multifocal choroidal hyperfluorescence on indocyanine green angiography (ICGA).
A reduction in diameter of the distal phalanx of finger towards the distal end such that the tip of the phalanx comes to a point (this feature can be observed on radiograms).
Schisis (cleft or cleavage) of vertebral bodies.
A congenital anomaly with complete lack of the pericardium on the lefthand side of the heart.
A nuclear cataract with a triangular form.
An increased concentration of an amino acid in the urine, due to a decreased kidney functionality .
Decreased retinal arteriolar diameters, which may decrease blood flow and slow oxygen delivery to regions of the retina.
A speech pattern characterized by abnormally reduced or lacking variability of the pitch of the voice.
An abnormal dilatation of the fourth cerebral ventricle.
Significant maternal hemorrhage/bleed in the second half of pregnancy and prior to the birth of the baby.
An abnormally low urinary specific gravity, i.e., reduced concentration of solutes in the urine.
Developmental aplasia of the distal phalanx of third toe.
An abnormality of the common carotid arteries, which provide the arterial supply to the head and neck and give rise to the internal carotid artery and the external carotid artery.
Metacarpal that becomes thinner toward the distal end.
Temporal and spatial heterogeneity in lungs based on presence of fibrosis and honeycombing.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a prostaglandin in the blood circulation.
An abnormality of an external jugular vein of the neck.
Structural abnormality of the thalamus related to defective development.

Y-shaped metatarsals are the result of a partial fusion of two metatarsal bones, with the two arms of the Y pointing in the distal direction. Y-shaped metatarsals may be seen in combination with polydactyly.
The presence of a gonadoblastoma of the testis.

An abnormal hand position characterized by hyperextension of the fourth and fifth fingers at the metacarpophalangeal joints and flexion of the interphalangeal joints of the same fingers such that they are curled towards the palm.
Upturned concavity of toenails.

A type of erythrocyte inclusion characterized by basophilic stippling of erythrocytes, that is, by numerous very small coarse or fine blue granules within the cytoplasm with the additional stipulation that the stippled particles are due to iron granules (demonstrable by the Prussian blue stain).
Increased concentration of ornithine in the blood.
Abnormal function of a sphincter of the urinary bladder.
A reduction in the concentration of bile acid in the blood.
A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more phalanges of the third toe.
Seizures of which initial semiology indicates, or is consistent with, initial activation of only part of one cerebral hemisphere.
The presence of a diverticulum of the esophagus.

A type of cutaneous melanoma localized to the palm, sole, or beneath the nail (subungual melanoma). Acral lentiginous melanoma starts as a slowly-enlarging flat patch of discoloured skin and usually displays a size above 6 mm and often several centimetres or more in diameter upon diagnosis and variable pigmentation with a mixutre of colors including brown, and blue-grey, black and red. The surface of the lesion is initially smooth but later in the course may become thicker and irregular, and may ulcerate or bleed.

Increased dimensions of the Virchow-Robin spaces (also known as perivascular spaces), which surround the walls of vessels as they course from the subarachnoid space through the brain parenchyma. Perivascular spaces are commonly microscopic, and not visible on conventional neuroimaging. This term refers to an increase of size of these spaces such that they are visible on neuroimaging (usually magnetic resonance imaging). The dilatations are regular cavities that always contain a patent artery.

Increased time to coagulation in the partial thromboplastin time (PTT) test, a measure of the intrinsic and common coagulation pathways. Phospholipid, and activator, and calcium are mixed into an anticoagulated plasma sample, and the time is measured until a thrombus forms.

A myelodysplastic/myeloproliferative neoplasm which is characterized by persistent monocytosis, absence of a Philadelphia chromosome and BCR/ABL fusion gene, fewer than 20 percent blasts in the bone marrow and blood, myelodysplasia, and absence of PDGFRA or PDGFRB rearrangement.

An accessory spleen is a round, iso-echogenic, homogenic and smooth structure and is seen as a normal variant mostly on the medial contour of the spleen, near the hilus or around the lower pole. This has no pathogenic relevance.
Reduction in density of metaphyseal bony tissue.
An increased concentration of the MB isoform of creatine kinase in the blood circulation.
A type of incomitant strabismus in which the angle of deviation varies as the patient's gaze shifts upwards and/or downwards.
Clonus is an involuntary tendon reflex that causes repeated flexion and extension of the foot. Ankle clonus is tested by rapidly flexing the foot upward.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the outer ear.

An abnormality of the maxillary sinus, one of the mucosa-lined, normally air-filled paranasal sinuses of the bones of the skull. The maxillary sinus is located within the skeleton of the midface, lateral to the nasal cavity.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the head and neck region with origin in the lip, oral cavity, nasal cavity, paranasal sinuses, pharynx, or larynx.
Poorly defined or shallow palmar creases.
Bleeding between the neurosensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) arising from the choroidal or retinal circulation.
A reduction below normal limits of estriol in the circulation.
Increased density/number and/or increased diameter of eyebrow hairs.
A pregnancy in which the fertilized egg inserts in a location outside of the main cavity of the uterus (usually in the Fallopian tube).
Absence of one half of the vertebral body in the lumbar spine.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger.

A deviation from the normal blood concentration of the insulin like growth factor binding protein acid labile subunit (IGFALS; Entrez Gene ID 3483). The acid-labile subunit (IGFALS) acts in the insulin-like growth (IGF) system by binding circulating IGF1 in a ternary complex with binding protein (IGFBP)-3 to prevent IGF1 from crossing the endothelial barrier.
Increased width of ribs
A form of hypermetropia with more than +2.00 diopters but not more than +5.00 diopters.
Facial diplegia (that is, bilateral facial palsy) with congenital onset.
Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the metacarpals, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
Type I lesions represent the very initial changes and are recognized as an increase in the number of intimal macrophages and the appearance of macrophages filled with lipid droplets (foam cells).
The presence of pigmented, oval and dome-shaped raised hamartomatous nevi of the iris..
Multiple punctate calcifications in the dental pulp.
An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement about a joint axis.
Abnormal concentration of biopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the little finger of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.
Shortening of the fourth and fifth metacarpals when the fist is clenched.
An abnormality related to a defect of vertebral separation during development.
Inflammation of the eyelids.
An increased susceptibility to respiratory infections as manifested by a history of recurrent respiratory infections.

Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of an icosanoid (also know as eicosanoids). These are signaling molecules derived from oxidation of 20-carbon fatty acids. Most are produced from arachidonic acid, a 20-carbon polyunsaturated fatty acid (5,8,11,14-eicosatetraenoic acid).
The presence of a moderate form of conductive hearing impairment.

A type of pleural effusion with a exudate (extravascular fluid that has exuded out of a tissue or its capillaries due to injury or inflammation). Pleural effusions can be classified as transudates or exudates based on Light's criteria, which classify an effusion as exudate if one or more of the following are present: (1) the ratio of pleural fluid protein to serum protein is greater than 0.5, (2) the ratio of pleural fluid lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) to serum LDH is greater than 0.6, or (3) the pleural fluid LDH level is greater than two thirds of the upper limit of normal for serum LDH.
Increased susceptibility to coronavirus 229e, as manifested by recurrent episodes of coronavirus 229e.

Nonprogressive restriction of movement of the external ocular muscles such that the eyes of affected individuals are partially or completely fixed in a strabismic position. Residual eye movements are significantly limited.
An abnormal deviation from normal levels of immunoglobulins in blood.
Fibrous dysplasia of the bones were lesions are localized in only one bone.
Decrease in the activity of pyruvate kinase (PK) within erythrocytes. PK catalyzes the reaction: ATP + pyruvate = ADP + phosphoenolpyruvate.

An elevation of the blood concentration of an androgen, that is, of a steroid hormone that controls development and maintenance of masculine characteristics. The androgens include testosterone and Dehydroepiandrosterone.
Excessive or pathological tendency to save and collect possessions.
An alteration of the color of the lip to take on a violet color. This term does not include cyanosis.

The examiner applies firm but persistent pressure over the liver for 10 seconds while observing the mean jugular venous pressure. Normally there is either no rise or only a transient (i.e., 2 to 3 sec) rise in mean jugular venous pressure. A sustained increase in the mean venous pressure until abdominal compression is released is abnormal and indicates impaired right heart function. This abnormal response is called hepatojugular reflux.
The presence of a gonadoblastoma, a neoplasm of a gonad that consists of aggregates of germ cells and sex cord elements.
A diminution of the peripheral visual field whereby at least 50 degrees of central field are preserved in all meridians.
Lack of urothione (the urinary metabolite of molybdenum cofactor) in the urine.
An anomaly in the process of intramembranous ossification by which flat bones (cranial bones of the skull, i.e., the frontal, parietal, occipital, and temporal bones, and the clavicles) are formed.
Fibrous connective tissue resulting from incomplete healing of a wound (i.e., a scar) located in the choroid and retina or the eye.
Abnormal increased size of the elbow joint.
Increased amount of autofluorescence in the retina as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.
Lack of development of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.

Abnormal position of urethral meatus on the ventral penile shaft (underside) characterized by displacement of the urethral meatus from the tip of the glans penis to the ventral surface of the penis, scrotum, or perineum.
The presence of an abnormally short lingual frenulum.
Conduction block in the anterior division of the left bundle branch of the bundle of His.
Lack of symmetry between the left and right mandible.
The presence of a malignant neoplasm of the genital system.
Increased susceptibility to viral infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of viral infection.
Increased protrusion of the superior crus relative to the prominence of a normal antihelix stem.
A unilateral vestibular Schwannoma (acoustic neurinoma).
A small break in the retina.

?def: An eccentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the abdominal aorta that involves only a portion of the circumference of the vessel wall.
A hypopigmented spot in the shape of a leaf from the mountain ash tree.
A mild delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.
Any abnormality of the eye, including location, spacing, and intraocular abnormalities.
?xrefs: MSH:D005124 UMLS:C0015397 UMLS:C0015393 SNOMEDCT_US:371409005 MSH:D005128 SNOMEDCT_US:371405004 SNOMEDCT_US:19416009

?def: A discontinuity of the vertebral arch, i.e., of the posterior part of a vertebra.
The presence of a fistula between the perineum and the rectum.
The presence of abnormal calcium deposition in the liver.
An exaggerated startle reaction in response to a sudden unexpected visual or acoustic stimulus, or a quick movement near the face.
A severe form of sensorineural hearing impairment.
Presence of xenobiotic in hair.
Underdevelopment of the semicircular canal.

Abnormal arrangement of the structures of the axoneme, which is the cytoskeletal structure that forms the inner core of the motile cilium and displays a canonical 9 + 2 microtubular pattern of motile cilia studded with dynein arms.

Trophic changes is a term used to describe abnormalities in the area of pain that include primarily wasting away of the skin, tissues, or muscle, thinning of the bones, and changes in how the hair or nails grow, including thickening or thinning of hair or brittle nails.
Abnormally anterior location of the papillary muscles of the left ventricle.
Generalized reduced transparency of the stroma of the cornea.
A lack of strength of the proximal muscles of the arms.
Absence of shoulder muscles.
Myokymia consists of involuntary, fine, continuous, undulating contractions that spread across the affected striated muscle.
Radiolucent focal defect of the posterior portion of a rib shaft. The 'gaps' may lead to flail chest.
An abnormal gyral pattern characterized by abnormalities of sulcal depth or orientation and a thickened cortex intermediate between pachygyria and polymicrogyria.
Features of tetralogy of Fallot with either rudimentary ridges or the complete absence of pulmonic valve tissue.

A functional anomaly of the inferior rectus muscle, which is innervated by the inferior division of oculomotor nerve and functions in the depression, adduction, and lateral rotation (extortion) of the eye.
A left-right reversal (or \mirror reflection\") of the anatomical location of the viscera of the abdomen."

Reduction in the activity of lysosomal acid lipase (LAL) in the blood. Lysosomal lipase activity is measured. LAL hydrolyzes cholesteryl esters derived from cell internalization of plasma lipoproteins.
Hemorrhage affecting the gastrointestinal tract.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of hepcidin in the blood circulation.
The presence of more than the normal number of metacarpal bones.
An abnormally slow velocity of horizontal saccadic eye movements.
Any structural abnormality of the caudate nucleus.
The presence of aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the ear.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger.
Reduced level of plasminogen activator inhibitor 1 antigen.
Blockage of the upper airway at the level of the larynx often accompanied by respiratory distress.
The presence of erythrocytes that are sphere-shaped.
Abnormally developed (dysplastic) distal epiphysis of the radius.
An anomaly of the nasal base, which can be conceived of as an imaginary line between the most lateral points of the external inferior attachments of the alae nasi to the face.
A form of atrioventricular (AV) dissociation (i.e., the atria and the ventricles are under the control of two separate pacemakers) with congenital onset.
A cyst occurring within the choroid plexus within a cerebral ventricle.
An increased concentration of ammonia in the blood not associated with symptoms such as encephalopathy.
Sleep apnea resulting from a transient abolition of the central drive to the ventilatory muscles.
A type of entropion (abnormal inversion of the eyelid towards the globe) that is related to a mass effect of a lesion (e.g., a tumor) that pulls the eyelid margin away from the globe.
Focal epileptiform discharges with spreading to contralateral hemisphere but without secondary generalization.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.
Seizures of with initial involvement of both cerebral hemispheres.
A reduced blood concentration of retinol-binding protein. This finding predicts vitamin A deficiency with high sensitivity and specificity.
The absence of a phalangeal segment of a thumb.
An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall of the femoral artery.
An accumulation of free radical groups in the body inadequately neutralized by antioxidants, which creates a potentially unstable and damaging cellular environment linked to tissue damage.
An abnormality of the concentration or function of circulating immune proteins.
Absence or underdevelopment of the first metatarsal bone.
In left atrial isomerism there is a bilateral small finger-shaped morphologically left atrial appendage joining the atrial chamber along a narrow front without an internal terminal crest.
Decreased quantity or activity of von Willebrand factor. Von Willebrand factor mediates the adhesion of platelets to the collagen exposed on endothelial cell surfaces.
An abnormality of nerve cell cluster or a group of nerve cell bodies located in the autonomic nervous system of the cranium.
An increased concentration of lactic acid in the urine.
Any structural abnormality or abnormal count of granulocytes.
Reduced level of CD59 on the fibroblast surface as assessed by flow cytometry.
A morphological abnormality of the vertebral arch, i.e., of the posterior part of a vertebra.
Lack or loss of the soft tissues between the zygomata and mandible.
A secondary ossification center in the middle phalanx of the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
Painful or difficult urination.
Abnormally small size of the epiphyses located at the distal end of the metacarpals in respect to age-dependent norms.

High frequency discharges in electromyography (EMG) that vary in amplitude and frequency, waxing and waning continuously with firing frequencies ranging from 150/second down to 20/second and producing a sound that has been referred to as a dive bomber sound.
Abnormal release of alpha granule contents from platelets.
The presence of reduced conduction velocity of motor nerves on electromyography.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against thyroid peroxidase.
One or both of the leaflets (cusps) of the mitral valve bulges back into the left atrium upon contraction of the left ventricle.
The presence of a bifid uterus.
A congenital anomaly of the urinary tract, in which the kidney is duplicated and is drained via two separate renal pelves and ureters.
High urine phosphate in the presence of hypophosphatemia.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger.
Muscle hypertrophy affecting the scapular muscles.
Single (solitary) abscess in the spleen.
A closed sac-like structure originating from the pleura that contains a liquid, gaseous, or semisolid substance.
Chornic neutropenia arising from an impaired proliferation and maturation of myeloid progenitor cells in the bone marrow.
An abnormal predominance of type I muscle fibers (in general, this feature can only be observed on muscle biopsy).
Increase in width (breadth) of the radial metaphysis.
Edema/fluid accumulating within the retinal layers.

A kind of ventriculomegaly occurring in the fetal period and usually diagnosed by prenatal ultrasound. Cerebral ventriculomegaly is defined by atrial measurements 10 mm or more. Mild ventriculomegaly (MVM) is defined as measurements between 10 and 15 mm. Measurements are obtained from an axial plane at the level of the thalamic nuclei just below the standard image to measure the BPD (pmid:16100637).

Eosinophilic hyaline ovoid bodies which are often found in the subepidermal papillary regions or sometimes in the epidermis. Civatte bodies (CBs) are seen as rounded, homogenous, eosinophilic masses on routine H and E staining lying in the deeper parts of epidermis/epithelium and more frequently in dermis/connective tissue. They are known as CBs (in epithelium/epidermis), colloid bodies, or hyaline bodies (in connective tissue). They are 10-25 micrometers in diameter and situated mostly within or above the inflammatory cell infiltrate. In lichen planus, the number of necrotic keratinocytes may be so large that they are seen lying in clusters in the uppermost dermis. These bodies show a positive periodic acid Schiff reaction and are diastase resistant
