?def: The mitochondrial matrix refers to the substance occupying the space enclosed by the inner membrane of a mitochondrion, which contains enzymes, DNA, granules, and inclusions of protein crystals, glycogen, and lipid. Mitochondrial swelling refers to an increase in size of the mitochondrial matrix. This phenomenon is thought to be related to a permeabilized inner membrane that originates a large swelling in the mitochondrial matrix. Mitochondrial swelling may distend the outer membrane until it ruptures.
An abnormal level of catalysis of the reaction: 2 superoxide + 2 H+ = O2 + hydrogen peroxide.
The congenital absence of the thyroid gland.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by vestibular stimulation, including head turning, cold calorics, postural changes, or rotating chair.
The presence of an asymmetric mouth.
Craniosynostosis of all calvarial sutures.
An elevated concentration of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL) in the blood.
The humerus is shortened and displays flaring (widening) of the metaphyses.
The presence of minimal changes visible by light microscopy but flattened and fused podocyte foot processes on electron microscopy in a person with nephrotic range proteinuria.
A myeloproliferative disorder characterized by increased proliferation of the granulocytic cell line without the loss of their capacity to differentiate.
An elevated concentration of proinsulin (the prohormone precursor to insulin) to mature insulin in the circulation.
The distention of the ureter with urine.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by a lack of sufficient sleep.
Medial deviation of the great toe owing to a deformity of the great toe joint causing the hallux to deviate medially.

A functional brain anomaly detectable by positron emission tomography (PET). PET scanning is a method for functional brain imaging, and its measurements reflect the amount of brain activity in the various regions of the brain.

Pachygyria is a malformation of cortical development with abnormally wide gyri with sulci 1,5-3 cm apart and abnormally thick cortex measuring more than 5 mm (radiological definition). See also neuropathological definitions for 2-, 3-, and 4-layered lissencephaly.
Immunohistochemistry shows complete lack of delta sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.
A tooth that has not erupted because of local impediments (overcrowding or fibrous gum overgrowth).

Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen, resulting from post-testicular obstruction or retrograde ejaculation. Can be differentiated from obstructive azoospermia on the basis of testicular biopsy.
A cutaneous eruption that consists of multiple (at least two) concentric erythematous rings.
An anomaly of the size of the testicle (the male gonad).
The presence of inclusion bodies within the nucleus of muscle cells. Inclusion bodies are aggregates (deposits) or stainable material, usually misfolded proteins.
A severe loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

Contrast material enhancement of the pia mater or enhancement that extends into the subarachnoid spaces of the sulci and cisterns is leptomeningeal enhancement. Leptomeningeal enhancement is usually associated with meningitis, which may be bacterial, viral, or fungal. The primary mechanism of this enhancement is breakdown of the blood-brain barrier without angiogenesis.
Muscle hypertrophy affecting the muscles of the neck.
An increase in the level of ketone bodies in the blood.
Curved appearance of the middle phalanx of the 4th (ring) finger.
Complete lack of mature B cells, that is, of B cells that have left the bone marrow.
A variability of phenotypic features.
A ratio of serum triiodothyronine (T3) to thyroxine (T4) in the blood that is higher than normal.
DIsruption and breaking up of the basement membrane of the tubules of the kidney.
A stable tendency to experience negative emotions, i.e., a disposition to experience aversive emotional states.
Anomaly of the contour of the Distal epiphysis of femur such that its normally smooth appearance is irregular.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of branched-chain amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.

Transient left ventricular apical ballooning syndrome or takotsubo cardiomyopathy is characterized by transient regional systolic dysfunction involving the left ventricular apex and/or mid-ventricle in the absence of obstructive coronary disease on coronary angiography. Patients present with an abrupt onset of angina-like chest pain, and have diffuse T-wave inversion, sometimes preceded by ST-segment elevation, and mild cardiac enzyme elevation.
Increased side-to-side width of the metacarpal epiphyses.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of transferrin in the blood circulation.
A type of cyclophoria (latent strabismus in which the occluded eye wheel-rotates on dissociation.) in which the upper poles of the globes are rotated inward (medially) to each other.
Cyst-like space not lined by epithelium and contained within the pancreas. Pancreatic pseudocysts are often associated with pancreatitis.
Hyperkeratosis affecting the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot in areas exposed to friction.
Curved appearance of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger.
Fingers appear swollen and plump owing to inflammation of the complete finger.

Benign tumors that are composed of fibrous or connective tissue. They can grow in all organs, arising from mesenchyme tissue. The term \fibroblastic\" or \"fibromatous\" is used to describe tumors of the fibrous connective tissue. When the term fibroma is used without modifier, it is usually considered benign, with the term fibrosarcoma reserved for malignant tumors."

Hypoplastic (short) proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
An anomaly of the outer shell (cortex) of a foot bone.
A cataract that affects the capsule of the lens.
Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles brought on by physical exertion.
Applies to a sign, symptom or manifestation that occurs multiple times separated by intervals in which the sign, symptom, or manifestation is not present.
Decreased diameter of eyebrow hairs.
An abnormality of binocular vision, that is of the ability to synthesize the visual inputs from both eyes to a single image with perception of depth.
An ameliorating factor is defined as an external factor that leads to a sign or symptom that is already present improving or becoming more bearable
An abnormal reduction in the Arden ratio, which is the ratio between the light peak and the dark trough of the smoothed (physiologic) EOG record.
The presence of calcium-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.
Developmental hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of fourth toe.
A wartlike (with multiple small elevated projections) papule.
A benign growth the projects outward from the bone surface of the pelvis. Exostoses are capped by cartilage, and arise from a bone that develops from cartilage.
Stomatitis is an inflammation of the mucous membranes of any of the structures in the mouth.
Passage of many stools containing blood and mucus.
Persistent vaginal dryness.
An abnormality of the pons.

Increased susceptibility to gastroenteritis, an infectious inflammationof the stomach and small intestines manifested by signs and symptoms such as diarheas and abdominal pain, as manifested by recurrent episodes of gastroenteritis.
An inflammation of the kidney involving the parenchyma of kidney, the renal pelvis and the kidney calices.
An abnormality of the function of the middle ear.
Anterior positioning of the nasal root in comparison to the usual positioning for age.
A sarcoma of the kidney.
Extra fold of tissue extending from the alveolar ridge to the inner surface of the upper or lower lip.
A type of maturation arrest in which only spermatogonia or spermatocytes are found.
A form of sensorineural hearing impairment with onset after the acquisition of speech.
Absent 4th finger.
A type of vulvar cancer that originates from melanocytes of the vulva.
Presence of myoglobin in the urine.
An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones of the upper limbs.

An abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the third finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
A disorder of the cardiac conduction system of the heart characterized by ventricular preexcitation due to the presence of an abnormal accessory atrioventricular electrical conduction pathway.
An abnormality of a zygomaticus major muscle.
Spontaneous flow of milk from the breast, unassociated with childbirth or nursing.
Muscle hypertrophy affecting the paraspinal muscles.
An abnormality of the mitochondria in muscle tissue.
An increased quantity of earwax.
Any functional defect of the mitral or tricuspid valve.
A reduction in diameter of the distal phalanx of finger towards the distal end.
An abnormal structure of the tip (end) of a finger.
An increased concentration of insulin combined with a decreased concentration of glucose in the blood.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses.
A functional anomaly of a vertical or horizontal rectus muscle.
Presence of pus (appears as a white fluid) producing a fluid level in the inferior part of the anterior chamber.
Pain in the lower back and hip radiating in the distribution of the sciatic nerve.
Swelling within the basal ganglia due to the accumulation of fluid.
A malignant epithelial tumor with a glandular organization that originates in the jejunum.
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance resembles that of measles, i.e., maculopapular lesions that are red and roughly 2 to 10 mm in diameter and may be partially confluent.
The presence of chronic diarrhea, which is usually taken to mean diarrhea that has persisted for over 4 weeks.
The presence of a neoplasm of the ureter.

?def: Abnormally increased levels of homocarnosine in cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormality of the male internal genitalia.
A reduction in the magnitude or amount of ossification of the skull.
A type of digital ulcer that manifests as an open sore on the surface of the skin at the tip of a finger or toe.
Inspiration of a foreign object into the airway.

A deviation from the normal activity of coagulation factor VIII. Factor VIII (fVIII) is a cofactor in the intrinsic clotting cascade that is activated to fVIIIa in the presence of minute quantities of thrombin. fVIIIa acts as a receptor, for factors IXa and X.
A cataract that affects the anterior part of the cortex of the lens.
Malignant tumor of melanocytes affecting the iris.
Asymmetry or size difference between the left and right nostril.
Abnormal anatomical location of the adrenal gland.
Compression of the spinal cord in the cervical region, generally manifested by paresthesias and numbness, weakness, difficulty walking, abnormalities of coordination, and neck pain or stiffness.
Mirror image arrangement of the mainstem bronchi with the right pulmonary artery posterior to the right upper lobe bronchus and the left pulmonary artery anterior to the left upper lobe bronchus.
Abnormally increased excretion of porphyrins in the urine.
A decreased amount of taurine in the blood.
A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex II, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

Abnormally increased intraepithelial lymphocyte count. This finding may be appreciated as large numbers of surface intraepithelial lymphocytes as seen (for instance) with hematoxylin and eosin staining of a colonic biopsy sample taken during colonoscopy.
Abnormal thickening of the cortex of long bones.
An abnormal increase in the Arden ratio, which is the ratio between the light peak and the dark trough of the smoothed (physiologic) EOG record.
Defects in the formation of pulmonary lobules.
A cataract which affects the layer of the lens surrounding the nucleus, i.e., the lens cortex. It is identified by its unique wedge or spoke appearance.
Abnormal narrowing of the urethra.

The presence of genetically distinct populations of somatic cells in a given organism caused by DNA mutations, epigenetic alterations of DNA, chromosomal abnormalities or the spontaneous reversion of inherited mutations.
Any abnormality of the proximal epiphysis of the tibia.
An increased concentration of alpha-fetoprotein.
A type of hypothyroidism with congenital onset.

Lactase is produced in the small intestine in humans, Lactase is a member of the beta-galactosidase family of enzymes, and hydrolyzes D-lactose to form D-galactose and D-glucose, which can be absorbed by the small intestine. There are many ways of assessing lactase activity. In one test, an endoscopic biopsy from the postbulbar duodenum is incubated with lactose on a test plate, and a color reaction develops within 20 min as a result of hydrolyzed lactose (a positive result) in patients with normolactasia, whereas no reaction (a negative result) develops in patients with severe hypolactasia. Other, less direct, tests include the hydrogen breath test, and blood tests following lactose challenges.
A deviation from the normal concentration in the circulation of sex hormone-binding globulin, a circulating glycoprotein that transports testosterone and other steroids in the blood.
Abnormality of the twelfth cranial nerve.
An abnormality of the cell cycle.
A structural anomaly of the olfactory lobe, the structure within the brain that receives neural input from the nasal cavity and thereby processes the sense of smell.
Swelling of the margin of the cornea overlapped by the sclera.

Absence of the normal opening of a coronary ostium. There are normally two coronary ostia, which are site of origin of the main left or right main coronary artery and are located in the ascending aorta just above the aortic valve.
Failure of the femur to develop.
A form of hemolytic anemia that is triggered by ingestion of certain drugs.
Reduced inferior to superior extent of the thorax.
Failure to complete ossification (maturation and calcification) of the palatine bone.

Dysplasia and dysgenesis of the corpus callosum are nonspecific descriptions that imply defective development of the corpus callosum. The term dysplasia is applied when the morphology of the corpus callosum is altered as a congenital trait. For instance, the corpus callosum may be hump-shaped, kinked, or a striped corpus callosum that lacks an anatomically distinct genu and splenium.
The upper eyelid margin is positioned 3 mm or more lower than usual and covers the superior portion of the iris (objective); or, the upper lid margin obscures at least part of the pupil (subjective).
An anomaly of the wave-like muscle contractions of the digestive tract.
The presence of one or more bullae on the skin of the genital region, defined as fluid-filled blisters more than 5 mm in diameter with thin walls.

A deviation of the normal proportion of memory B cells in circulation relative to total number of B cells. Memory B cells develop from naive B cells. Upon antigen rechallenge, memory B cells rapidly expand and differentiate into plasma cells under the cognate control of memory Th cells (Phase IV).
An abnormal appearance of the long bones with resemblance to a dumbbell, a short bar with a weight at each end. That is, the long bone is shortened and displays flaring (widening) of the metaphyses.
A reduction below the normal concentration of the HDL3b subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL3b particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 7.8-8.19 nm.
An acute form of hepatic steatosis.

Delay in cutaneous immune reaction to specific antigens mediated not by antibodies but by cells. The delayed hypersensitivity test is an immune function test measuring the presence of activated T cells that recognize a specific antigen and is performed by injecting a small amount of the antigen into the skin. The area of the injection is examined 48-72 hours thereafter.

The tree-in-bud pattern represents centrilobular branching structures that resemble a budding tree. The pattern reflects a spectrum of endo- and peribronchiolar disorders, including mucoid impaction, inflammation, and/or fibrosis (See Figure 70 of PMID:18195376).
Decreased time between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).
Abnormality of the corticospinal tract, which is the chief element of the pyramidal system (the principle motor tract) and is the only direct connection between the cerebrum and the spinal cord.
Presence of a xenobiotic in meconium.
The presence of axonal regeneration following a previous axonal lesion.
Increased level of IgE antibody against antigens from plants and products derived from plants, such as wood or pollen.
The presence of inflammation of the epididymis.
Reduced intensity (volume) of speech.
Bleeding at irregular intervals.

A type of focal seizure (i.e., affecting initially only one hemisphere of the brain) that is simple (not resulting in alteration of consciousness) that originates in the occipital lobe. Visual hallucinations are the hallmark of occipital seizures, but are not invariably present. Hallucinations typically commence in the visual field contralateral to the affected visual cortex and then spread to involve the entire visual field. Elementary visual seizures are characterized by fleeting visual manifestations which may be either positive (flashes, phosphenes) or, less commonly, negative (scotoma, hemianopia, amaurosis). Positive phenomena are usually flashes of colour or light, which are simple in shape and may be static or mobile.
Increased susceptibility to Giardia lamblia infection of the intestine, as manifested by a medical history of multiple episodes of Giardia lamblia intestinal infection.
Camptodactyly is a painless flexion contracture of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint that is usually gradually progressive. This term refers to camptodactyly of one or more toes.
Heterotopia or neuronal heterotopia are macroscopic clusters of misplaced neurons (gray matter), most often situated along the ventricular walls or within the subcortical white matter.
Generalized (diffuse, unlocalized) amyotrophy (muscle atrophy) affecting multiple muscles.
An increased susceptibility to pharyngitis as manifested by a history of recurrent pharyngitis.
Triplication of the spinal cord - extremely rare.
Abnormal increased size of the spleen.

An abnormal degree of flatness of the Ala of nose, which can be defined as a reduced nasal elevation index (lateral depth of the nose from the tip of the nose to the insertion of the nasal ala in the cheek x 100 divided by the side-to-side breadth of the nasal alae).
An abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Inflammation of the liver characterized by a mononuclear cell infiltrate whereby portal inflammatory cells extend through the limiting plate between the portal tract and liver parenchyma.
Fluid retention and edema in the intestine caused by a compromised lymphatic system.
A sudden involuntary contraction of the musculature surrounding the mouth.
An anomaly of the fifth metatarsal bone.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the distal phalanx of the 4th finger is affected.

Presence of lupus anticoagulant (LA) autoantibodies. LA represent a heterogeneous group of autoantibodies, IgG, IgM, or a mixture of both classes, that interfere with standard phospholipid-based coagulant tests (this is only an in vitro phenomenon, LA do not cause reduction of coagulation in vivo). The antibodies are directed against plasma proteins which also bind to phospholipid surfaces.
Thickening of the epidermal layer of the skin.
Any deviation from the normal activity of the enzyme phosphoribosyl pyrophosphatesynthetase, which catalyzes the synthesis of PP-ribose-P from ATP and ribose-5-phosphate.
A twisting of the Fallopian tube. Sudden onset with sharp, colicky pelvic pain associated with nausea, vomiting, bowel, and bladder symptoms is the usual presentation.
A type of cutaneous amyloidosis that is characterized clinically by waxy, purpuric plaques and nodules and histologically by amyloid deposits in the dermis and subcutaneous tissue.

A functional rather than mechanical obstruction of the intestines, associated with manifestations that resemble those caused by an intestinal obstruction, including distension, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, constipation or diarrhea, in an individual in whom a mechanical blockage has been excluded.

Increased concentration of 11-deoxycortisol in the circulation. 11-deoxycorticosterone, which is also known as simply deoxycorticosterone and 21-hydroxyprogesterone, is a steroid hormore that is produces in the adrenals and is a precursor to aldosterone.
Sudden loss of renal function, as manifested by decreased urine production, and a rise in serum creatinine or blood urea nitrogen concentration (azotemia).
An abnormally decreased level of immunoglobulin E (IgE) in blood.
With the hand relaxed and the thumb in the plane of the palm, the axis of the thumb forms an angle of at least 90 degrees with the long axis of the hand.
Hypertrophy of the clitoris.
The presence of a characteristic high-pitched cry that sounds similar to the meowing of a kitten.
Recurrent bleeding into the parenchyma of the brain.
A decreased amount of tryptophan in the blood.
Redness of the skin of the eyelids, caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.
A type of hyperparathyroidism caused by a primary abnormality of the parathyroid glands (e.g., adenoma, carcinoma, hyperplasia). Primary hyperparathyroidism is associated with hyercalcemia.
Short fourth metacarpal bone.
Fissure within the spinal cord of the neck.
An increased concentration of a branched chain amino acid in the blood.

A structural anomaly of the growth plates (epiphyseal plates), areas of cartilage located near the ends of long bones that are located between the metaphysis (widened part of the shaft of the bone) and the epiphysis (end of the bone) and in which growth occurs in the developing bone. After conclusion of bone growth, the growth plates ossify (harden into solid bone).
Increased breadth of the nasal bridge (and with it, the nasal root).
Increased length of the proximal phalanx of finger.
An intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material in a curved pattern.
A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the thalamus.
The presence of a coronal suture (the cranial suture that separates the frontal and parietal bones) that is not ossified but rather wide open at an age when it is normally closed.

Blockage at the level of the bladder and the ureter caused by stenosis of the ureteral valves or failure of a narrow juxtavesical ureteral segment to dilate due to segmented fibrosis or localized absence of muscle.
Any structural anomaly of a cell of the monocyte, granulocyte, mast cell, megakaryocyte, or erythroid lineage.
Unilateral paresis (weakness) with spasticity of the affected muscles and increased tendon reflexes.
A unilateral form of atrophy of the kidney.
Abnormal functionality of the gastrointestinal tract.
Developmental defect resulting in congenital absence of the middle portion of the clavicle.
Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of second toe.
The occurence of fever in a mother during the first trimester of pregnancy.
An abnormality of the third metatarsal bone.
Abnormal narrowing of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture).
Displacement of the 2nd (index) finger towards the ulnar side.
A deviation from normal of the waist to hip ratio, defined as the waist measurement divided by hip measurement.
A anomaly in the rate of apoptosis in lymphocytes.
A scotoma (area of diminished vision within the visual field) located between the central point of fixation and the blind spot with a roughly horizontal oval shape.
Defective ossification in an irregular pattern of the seven bones of the foot comprising the calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, and the cuneiform bones.
Small hands and feet.

Malignant tumor of melanocytes of the choroid. The classic appearance of choroidal melanoma is a pigmented dome-shaped or collar button-shaped tumor with an associated exudative retinal detachment. Choroidal melanoma is usually pigmented, but can be variably pigmented and even amelanotic (non-pigmented).
Muscular atrophy affecting the muscles of the pelvis.
An elevation of the eyelid above the normal level in the primary position.
An abnormal narrowing of the orifice of the mitral valve.
?xrefs: EPCC:06.02.92 Fyler:1511 UMLS:C0026269 MSH:D008946 SNOMEDCT_US:79619009 ICD-10:Q23.2

?def: Hard-palate submucous clefts are characterized by bony defects in the midline of the bony palate that are covered by the mucous membrane of the roof of the mouth. It may be possible to detect a submucous cleft hard palate upon palpation as a notch in the bony palate.
Wasting or decrease in size of all or part of the duodenum.
A kind of short stature in which different regions of the body are shortened to a comparable extent.
An abnormal generalized reduction in amplitude of the cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
Reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids.
The distal and proximal transverse palmar creases are merged into a single transverse palmar crease on both hands.
Bending or curvature of a fifth toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).
Atrophy affecting the pons and the cerebellum.
Absence of the fourth long bone of the hand.
Anaphylaxis after physical activity.
Inability to react to a delayed hypersensitivity skin test.

Optic disc drusen are acellular, calcified deposits within the optic nerve head. Optic disc drusen are congenital and developmental anomalies of the optic nerve head, representing hyaline-containing bodies that, over time, appear as elevated, lumpy irregularities on the anterior portion of the optic nerve.
An abnormality of one or more of the vertebrae.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:205043005 UMLS:C0158775 Fyler:4108 UMLS:C4020839 SNOMEDCT_US:74877002 UMLS:C4020840

?def: An abnormally elevated concentration or amount of 11-deoxytetrahydrocorticosterone the urine.
A reduction from the normal concentration of beta-C-terminal telopeptide of type I collagen in the blood circulation.
Any anomaly of the structure of the humerus.
A decreased concentration of sex-hormone binding protein in the circulation.
An abnormally low level of blood oxygen.

An abnormality of the auditory evoked potentials, which are used to trace the signal generated by a sound, from the cochlear nerve, through the lateral lemniscus, to the medial geniculate nucleus, and to the cortex.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by smoking.
A marked tapering of the lower face to the chin.
Failure to form (agenesis) of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux.
Any structural anomaly of the connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of bone tissue that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity.
An increased concentration of glycerol in the urine.
Any anomaly of the function of the bronchi.
A form of lactic acidemia that occurs in relation to stress or infection.
An anomaly of the process of rib bone formation.

The feeling of frustration can be defined as an emotional reaction that occurs if a desired goal is not achieved. Frustration intolerance is defined as an age-inappropriate response to frustration characterized by crying or temper tantrums (in children) or aggressive or other undesirable behaviors.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the middle phalanx of the 4th finger.
Ectopic respiratory epithelium presenting as a superficial lesion in the skin usually localised unilateral in the skin of the forearm and associated with ipsilateral hand malformations.
Absence of one or more of the phalanges of the hand.
Underdevelopment of the nasal bone.
Underdevelopment of the pulmonary artery.
A deviation from the normal number of vertebrae in the spinal column.
Elevated thickness of the myelin sheath of peripheral nerves, in a regular and concentric fashion.
Accumulation of air in the pleural cavity leading to a partially or completely collapsed lung.
Any abnormality of the parietal bone of the skull.
An abnormally low concentration of urea nitrogen in the blood.
Abnormality of the wrist, the structure connecting the hand and the forearm.
Toes that are disproportionately narrow (reduced girth) for the hand/foot size or build of the individual.
An abnormal communication between coronary artery and a cardiac chamber.
The upper incisors deviate from the normal angle of being roughly parallel to the surface of the face and instead slant outwards.
A form of leukemia characterized by overproduction of an early myeloid cell.
Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the thumb. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
Abnormally decreased levels of leucine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
A type of vasculitis (inflammation of blood vessel walls) that affects blood vessels that are smaller than arteries, i.e., arterioles, venules, and capilllaries.
Repeated episodes of the formation of a blot clot in a deep vein.
The presence of inflammation of the prostate.

Injury to the median nerve caused by its entrapment at the wrist as it traverses through the carpal tunnel. Clinically, constrictive median neuropathy is characterized by pain, paresthesia, and weakness in the median nerve distribution of the hand.
Peripheral visual field constriction with <10 degrees central field preserved.
Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of the carotid arteries.
A condition characterized by resistance to the action of parathyroid hormone, in which there is hypocalcemia, hyperphosphatemia, and (appropriately) high levels of parathyroid hormone.
An abnormally increased number of mitochondria in the cytoplasma adjacent to the sarcolemma (muscle cell membrane), whereby the mitochondria also possess an abnormal morphology.
An abnormality of the lacrimal bone.

An atrial arrhythmia characterized by disorganized atrial activity without discrete P waves on the surface EKG, but instead by an undulating baseline or more sharply circumscribed atrial deflections of varying amplitude an frequency ranging from 350 to 600 per minute.
An abnormal reduction in mitochondrial DNA content of cells.
The presence of small depressions in the dental enamel.
Reduced diameter of the distal phalanx of finger.
Absence (agenesis) or underdevelopment of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the 2nd toe.
Increased susceptibility to Serratia marcescens infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Serratia marcescens infection.
An abnormally increased overall level of immunoglobulin E in blood.

A skin condition in which there is an increase in sebum secretion by the pilosebaceous apparatus associated with open comedones (blackheads), closed comedones (whiteheads), and pustular nodules (papules, pustules, and cysts).
Displacement of the 2nd finger towards the radial side.
A malignant neoplasm originating from the surface ovarian epithelium.
An abnormality of divalent inorganic cation homeostasis.

An infection that is caused by a bacterium that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such bacteria take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.
Reduced motility through the sphincter of Oddi, resulting in impedance of bile and pancreatic juice flow from the common bile duct into the duodenum.
Individuals with anomalous trichromacy possess three types of cones, but one of the three types of cones has an abnormal spectral sensitivity compared to normal cones.
Increased width of the humeral diaphysis.
Developmental aplasia of the middle phalanx of third toe.
Retinopathy which extends centrifugally from the edge of zone I to the nasal ora serrata.
Any deviation from the activity of coagulation factor V.
An abnormality in the process of focusing of light by the eye in order to produce a sharp image on the retina.
A type of epicanthus in which a primarily upper lid fold is present.

Incomplete partition I is also known as cystic cochleovestibular malformation, where the cochlea has no bony modiolus, resulting in an empty cystic cochlea. This is accompanied by a dilated cystic vestibule with developmental arrest at the fifth week of gestation.
Premature closure of the coronal suture of skull.
Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized at the insertion of the ductus arteriosus, i.e., to the juxtaductal region of aortic arch.

A congenital cardiac malformation comprising pulmonary stenosis, overriding aorta, ventricular septum defect, and right ventricular hypertrophy. The diagnosis of TOF is made if at least three of the four above mentioned features are present.
A nonparallel arrangement of cardiac myocytes.
Undergrowth of the limbs that affects only one side.

Alveolar cleft is a tornado-shaped bone defect in the maxillary arch. Alveolar cleft occurs in response to divergence from normal development during frontonasal prominence growth, contact, and fusion. The most common alveolar portion of the cleft is located between the lateral incisor and the canine.
An abnormal high-pitched noisy sound, occurring during inhalation or exhalation caused by the incomplete obstruction in the throat.
Absence of the proximal phalanx of the ring (4th) finger.
Short and wide proximal phalanges that taper distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
A cough that produces phlegm or mucus.
Any neoplasm composed of fibrous tissue.
An abnormal enlargement of the renal calices, the system of ducts of the kidney that collect urine.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries.
Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the middle phalanges of the hand.
An abnormally increased number of plasma cells in tissues, exudates, or blood
Curved appearance of the middle phalanx of the 3rd (middle) finger.
Hemidystonia refers to dystonia which involves the ipsilateral face, arm, and leg.

The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
Displacement of the heart outside the thoracic cavity and into the abdomen.
Being related to a mutation that gamete that participates in fertilization. All cells of the emerging organism will be affected and the variant canl be passed on to the next generation.

Continuous involuntary sustained muscle contraction. When an affected muscle is passively stretched, the degree of resistance remains constant regardless of the rate at which the muscle is stretched. This feature helps to distinguish rigidity from muscle spasticity.
An abnormal resistance to glucose, i.e., a reduction in the ability to maintain glucose levels in the blood stream within normal limits following oral or intravenous administration of glucose.
Dilation and elongation of the penile urethra associated with absence or hypoplasia of the corpora spongiosa and cavernosa.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against drugs.
An increased concentration of ammonia in the blood with sudden onset.
Cystic collection (sac-like, fluid containing pocket of membranous tissue) located in the interhemispheric fissure, with or without communication with the ventricular system.
The presence of crystals in the urine.
EEG discharges recorded in particular areas of the A localized (focal) abnormality in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
Severe asthma unresponsive to repeated courses of beta-agonist therapy such as inhaled albuterol, levalbuterol, or subcutaneous epinephrine.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger.
Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength.
Hypoplastic (short) thumb phalanx.

A type of bicuspid aortic valve (BAV) characterized by two equal-sized cusps, with no raphe and only two commissures. There is a lateral arrangement of the free edge of the cusps. Note that this differs from some other forms of BAV in which there are three commissures and two of the three cusps are joined by a raphe forming two functional leaflets. This type of BAV often is associated with aortic stenosis.
Any structural anomaly of a lingual nerve.
Abnormal increased in length of the chordae tendinae of the mitral valve.
Blindness with onset at birth.

A type of proximal renal tubulopathy characterized by resorption defects leading to glycosuria, aminoaciduria, tubular proteinuria, renal hypophosphatemia, and urate tubular hyporeabsorption with bicarbonate loss and resulting acidosis.

Telangiectasias refer to small dilated blood vessels located near the surface of the skin or mucous membranes, measuring between 0.5 and 1 millimeter in diameter. Telangiectasia are located especially on the tongue, lips, palate, fingers, face, conjunctiva, trunk, nail beds, and fingertips.
Reduced amount of the thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), which is produced by the anterior pituitary gland and stimulates the function of the thyroid gland.
Anterior cervical hypertrichosis (ACH) or 'hairy throat' refers to the presence of a tuft of terminal hair on the anterior neck, just above the laryngeal prominence.
An abnormality of the appearance of the face caused by constant contraction of the lips leading to a puckered or pursed appearance.
An increase in width of one ore more proximal toe phalanges.
An abnormality in which the cardiac ventricles depolarize too early as a result of an abnormality of cardiac conduction pathways such as an accessory pathway.
Any abnormality in the proportion natural killer subsets relative to the total number of natural killer cells.
A kind of bronchopulmonary sequestration that is completely discrete from the normal lung and is surrounded by separate pleura.
An abnormal regulation of the sweat glands by the sympathetic nervous system associated with abnormal perspiration.
The presence of an increased number of mast cells and CD34+ mast cell precursors in the body.

A solid, low grade, spindle cell, glial neoplasm of adults that originates in the neurohypophysis or infundibulum. Clinical signs and symptoms include visual disturbance, headache and features of hypopituitarism. Pituicytomas are well-circumscribed, solid masses that can measure up to several centimeters. Histologically, they show a compact architecture consisting of elongate, bipolar spindle cells arranged in interlacing fascicles or assuming a storiform pattern.
An increased concentration of proline in the urine.
A kind of breech presentation in which one or both hips are extended and one or both of the fetus' feet are pointing down and entering the birth canal.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the intracranial portion of the internal carotid artery wall.
A tendency or compulsion to examine objects by mouth.

A developmental disorder characterized by the progressive loss of primordial germ cells in the developing ovaries of an embryo, leading to hypoplastic ovaries composed of wavy connective tissue with occasional clumps of granulosa cells, and frequently mesonephric or hilar cells.
A vascular malformation located in the lip that is related to abnormal vascular morphogenesis.
A benign exophytic neoplasm that arises from the oropharynx. It is characterized by the presence of a connective tissue core covered by stratified squamous epithelium [NCI thesaurus].

A type of rest posture in an infant that indicated a generalized reduction in muscle tone. The hips are flexed and the legs are abducted to an extent that causes the lateral thigh to rest upon the supporting surface. This posture is said to resemble the legs of a frog.

Mallet finger refers to a condition in which the end joint of a finger bends but will not straighten by itself. In this situation, the joint can be pushed straight but will not hold that position on its own.
Lack of eyelashes on the lower lid.
An increased amount of glycogen in muscle tissue.
The presence of multiple granulomata (small nodular inflammatory lesions containing grouped mononuclear phagocytes) in the myocardium.

The aortic arch crosses the right mainstem bronchus and not the left mainstem bronchus, but does not result in the creation of a vascular ring. The first branch is the left brachiocephalic artery which divides into the left carotid artery and left subclavian artery, the second branch is the right carotid artery, the third branch is the right subclavian artery.
A thrusting or bulging out of the abdomen.
Aplasia or Hypoplasia affecting the 4th metacarpal.

A form of focal dystonia affecting the face and especially the jaw that is induced by the act of speaking. It is an involuntary contraction of the masticatory muscles, resulting in dysarthria or dysphagia.
An abnormality of the calf, i.e. of the posterior part of the lower leg.

A conenital abnormality of the aortic arch in which the two embryonic aortc arches form a vascular ring that surrounds the trachea or esophagus and then join to form the descending aorta. Double aortic arch can cause symptoms because of compression of the esophagus (dysphagia, cyanosis while eating) or trachea (stridor).
A cancer of the blood and bone marrow characterized by an abnormal proliferation of leukocytes.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:269475001 UMLS:C0376545 SNOMEDCT_US:129154003 MSH:D019337 UMLS:C0023418 MSH:D007938 SNOMEDCT_US:87163000 SNOMEDCT_US:93143009

?def: Decreased density/number and/or decreased diameter of lateral eyebrow hairs.
Increased size of the placenta.
The presence of whitish spots in a ring-like arrangement at the periphery of the iris.
A type of dystonia (abnormally increased muscular tone causing fixed abnormal postures) that affects muscles of the limbs.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating large quantities of food, for instance, by a heavy meal.
Accumulation of pus in the pleural cavity.
Loss of hair from the head or body.
An increased concentration of dicarboxylic acid in the urine.
A separation of the rectus abdominis muscle into right and left halves (which are normally joined at the midline at the linea alba).
Shoulder dystocia occurs when the fetal anterior shoulder impacts against the maternal symphysis following delivery of the vertex.
Lightening or darkening of the lips from their usual coloring.
Astigmatism in which the refractive power of the vertical meridian is the greatest.
Habitual repetitive movement of the body.
Partial or complete duplication of distal phalanx of third toe.
Abnormality of the basal ganglia.
Absence of specific immunoglobulins directed against a specific antigen or microorganism.
A lack of bone mineralization of one or more body of thoracic vertebra.
An abnormality of the Common bile duct, a tube-like anatomic structure in the human gastrointestinal tract, formed by the union of the Common hepatic duct and the Cystic duct from the gall bladder.
Aplasia of the malleus.
Limitation of the ability to bend the toes.
An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the big toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
The presence of an infectious agent in the blood circulation.
An increase in voltage of the PR segment below baseline.
A short discontinuity of the margin of the upper eyelid.
Increased level of methionine in urine.
An epithelial neoplasm originating in the appendix and often associated with cystic dilation of the appendix due to accumulation of gelatinous material, morphologically referred to as mucoceles.
An abnormality of an inferior alveolar nerve.
Crossing of the inflow streams of the two ventricles, due to an apparent twisting of the heart about its long axis.

A pituitary tumor with subarachnoid, brain, or systemic metastasis. The diagnosis of a pituitary carcinoma requires evidence of metastatic disease, either outside the central nervous system (CNS) or as separate noncontiguous foci within the CNS.
A congenital disorder where the hymen (a membrane that surrounds or partially covers the external vaginal opening) does not have an opening and completely obstructs the vagina.
An abnormality in a cellular process.
A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hypointensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.
A decrease in the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Any structural abnormality of the fundus of the eye.

A plaque representing a connective-tissue nevus. Connective tissue naevi are uncommon skin lesions that occur when the deeper layers of the skin do not develop correctly or the components of these layers occur in the wrong proportion. Shagreen patches are oval-shaped and nevoid, skin-colored or occasionally pigmented, smooth or crinkled, The word shagreen refers to a type of roughened untanned leather.
A diminished volume of the central part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis.
A hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, located in the upper part of the larynx (voice box) including the epiglottis; the area above the vocal cords.
A type of mesenchymal tissue cell tumor that exhibits epithelial differentiation, which most frequently arises in the extremities.
Regional increase in the width (height) of the lateral eyebrow.

A degenerative disease of the brain characterized by the insidious onset of dementia. Impairment of memory, judgment, attention span, and problem solving skills are followed by severe apraxia and a global loss of cognitive abilities. The condition primarily occurs after age 60, and is marked pathologically by severe cortical atrophy and the triad of senile plaques, neurofibrillary tangles, and neuropil threads.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:230267005 MSH:C536595 UMLS:C0002395 UMLS:C1863051 SNOMEDCT_US:26929004 MSH:D000544

?def: Lack of intermediate von Willebrand Factor multimers on gel electrophoresis.
Diffuse unlocalised atrophy affecting the cerebellum.
Reduced uptake of [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) in the parietal cortex as measured by positron emission tomography (PET) brain scan.
An increased amount of tryptophan in the blood.
An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the fifth toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the neck.
Increased susceptibility to aspiration pneumonia, defined as pneumonia due to breathing in foreign material, as manifested by a medical history of repeated episodes of aspiration pneumonia.
An anomaly of the first metatarsal bone.
Movement-based tics affecting discrete muscle groups.
Epiphysis of the thumb having multiple bony fragments.
Underdevelopment of the toenail.
Any anomaly of the time interval between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).
Accumulation of serous fluid (pale yellow and transparent fluid) in the pericardial sac.
Partial or complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of fifth toe.
A tumor originating in the jaw (mandible or maxilla).
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance resembles that of the grouped umbilicated vesicles seen in herpes simplex and herpes zoster infections.

A skin condition characterized by excessive development of keratin in hair follicles, resulting in rough, cone-shaped, elevated papules resulting from closure of hair follicles with a white plug of sebum.
Anterior chamber cells with more than 50 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.
A type of anterior polar cataract which projects as a conical opacity into the anterior chamber.
A structural abnormality of retinal vasculature.
Degeneration of retinal ganglion cells and their axons.
A chronic loss of ankle joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevent normal movement of the joints of the ankle.
Splitting of the retina in the macular region.
A carcinoma that arises in a sebaseous gland (an exocrine gland of the skin that secretes sebum, a waxy substance.
Absence or underdevelopment of the tongue.
An increased level of xanthine in the blood circulation.
Death during adolescence, the period between childhood and adulthood (roughly between the ages of 10 and 19 years).
A decreased concentration of glucose in the blood associated with a reduced concentration of ketone bodies.
Gliosis is the focal proliferation of glial cells in the central nervous system.
Having a medium degree of severity. For quantitative traits, a deviation of between three and four standard deviations from the appropriate population mean.
A deviation from the normal straight form of the middle phalanx of the fourth toe.
A bending or abnormal curvature of the fibula.
A malignant plasma cell tumor growing within soft tissue or within the skeleton.
?xrefs: MSH:D010954 SNOMEDCT_US:415112005 UMLS:C0032131 SNOMEDCT_US:10639003 SNOMEDCT_US:55921005 MSH:D009101 UMLS:C0026764 SNOMEDCT_US:109989006

?def: Abnormal shortening of all middle phalanges of toes.
An abnormality of the female external genitalia.
An abnormality of the process of ossification of the skull.

A vascular lesion defined histologically as one or more dilated blood vessels lying directly subepidermal and showing an epidermal proliferative reaction. Clinically, angiokeratoma presents as a small, raised, dark-red spot.
A type of xanthoma characterized by a nodular form. Tuberous xanthomas are firm subcutaneous nodules,whereby the overlying skin can have red or red-yellow color changes.
EEG with abnormal amplitude.
Rhythmic, involuntary oscillations of one or both eyes related to abnormality in fixation, conjugate gaze, or vestibular mechanisms.

Formation of new blood vessels on the iris. The new vessels do not display the typical radially symmertic growth pattern of normal iris blood vessels, but rather appear disorganized. Rubeosis usually starts from the pupillary border with tiny tufts of dilated capillaries or red spots that can only be appreciated with high magnification.
A limitation of the ability to direct one's gaze below the horizontal meridian.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of a gonad.
A moderate form of myopia with refractive error of between -3.00 and -6.00 diopters.
Replacement of bone marrow by fibrous tissue.
Abnormally decreased levels of glutamic acid in cerebrospinal fluid.
Any abnormality of the mandible, the bone of the lower jaw.
Abnormally increased prominence of the fat pad underneath the heal. This feature can be appreciated in figure 1 of PMID:26769062.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the toe.
A decreased proliferative response of lymphocytes in vitro or in vivo, when stimulated with mitogens, such as phytohemagglutinin (PHA).
A type of uniparental disomy in which the two identical chromosomes (or chromosome segments) of the same parent are transmitted.
An abnormality of size or shape of the long bones.
Opposing or not responding to instructions or external stimuli.
Pathological protein aggregates formed by hyperphosphorylation of a microtubule-associated protein known as tau, causing it to aggregate in an insoluble form.
Pectus carinatum affecting primarily the superior part of the sternum.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the lip.
Obstruction of the intestine due to abnormally thick meconium.
?xrefs: UMLS:C2939175 SNOMEDCT_US:86092005 UMLS:C3553397 SNOMEDCT_US:206523001 UMLS:C0398349 SNOMEDCT_US:233662009

?def: Small, hard cyst-like nodules, freely moveable in the subcutis over the bony prominences of the legs and arms, which have an outer calcified layer with a translucent core on x-ray.
A fontanelle that is small for age.

A deviation from normal in the amount of dystrophin in muscle fiber tissue. Dystrophin is located at the muscle sarcolemma in a membrane-spanning protein complex that connects the cytoskeleton to the basal lamina.
The presence of spontaneous bursts of rapidly firing potentials that recur at regular intervals of 2-10 per second and are unaffected by voluntary effort. This is an electromyographic (EMG) finding.
Abnormality of the nasal cavity (the cavity includes and starts at the nares and reaches all the way through to the and includes the choanae, the posterior nasal apertures).
Reduced ability to control the movement of the eye associated with damage to the third cranial nerve (the oculomotor nerve).
A bending or abnormal curvature of the radius.
Chorioretinal atrophy along the retinal veins.
An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in the thoracic aorta.
Inflammation of the periodontium.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:2556008 SNOMEDCT_US:41565005 UMLS:C0031090 MSH:D010510 MSH:D005882 SNOMEDCT_US:18718003 UMLS:C0031099 UMLS:C0017563 MSH:D010518

?def: The presence of calcium deposition in the cerebral white matter surrounding the cerebral ventricles.
An abnormality of the axial skeleton, which comprises the skull, the vertebral column, the ribs and the sternum.
Developmental hypoplasia of one or more phalanx of fourth toe.

A congenital skin lesion characterized by irregular hypopigmented macules that coalesce to form plaques and occur particularly on the chest. It is generally present at birth or develops in the first days of life. It is more common in females. Diagnosis is confirmed by applying gentle friction to the lesion and the surrounding skin and checking that the erythema produced in the healthy skin does not appear in the hypopigmented lesion. This pale macule becomes more conspicuous when the lesion and its surroundings are rubbed. The margin of the naevus is ill-defined and consists of an archipelago of small anaemic spots/

A type of weakness of a skeletal muscle in the neck that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.
Marked decrease in the number of granulocytes.
Nystagmus dating from or present at birth.
Developmental hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of fourth toe.
Sharply demarcated, congenital hyperpigmentation of thr retinal pigment epithelium.
A increased concentration of alpha-aminoadipic acid in the urine.
An abnormality of the conjunctiva.
Abnormality of the oral cavity, i.e., the opening or hollow part of the mouth.
An abnormality of the thyroid gland owing to the presence of a fibrous cyst resulting from the persistence of the thyroglossal duct.
Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the bones of the hand.
Atrophy of the kidney.
A lack of differentiation between renal cortex and medulla on diagnostic imaging.
Opacity of the entire lens nucleus.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking fructose.
Failure to close of the chest and abdominal wall likely caused by the failure of the ventral wall to close during week 4 of development.
A circumscribed, fluid-containing, epidermal elevation generally considered less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point.
Absence or underdevelopment of the ulna.
Accumulation of cell free, noninflammatony fluid within the wall of the intestinal tract producing uniform thickening of the mucosal folds.
An abnormality of the region around the nails of the fingers or toes.
A structural anomaly of the muscle layer of the heart wall.
A descriptive term that is applied to computer tomography imaging and that refers to a hazy area of increased attenuation in the lung with preserved bronchial and vascular markings.
Longitudinal grooves in the surface of the esophagus arranged in a longitudinal fashion (from top to bottom of the esophagus).
First period after the age of 15 years.
An above normal level of saturation of serum transferrin with iron.
An abnormality of a central retinal artery.
An abnormally decreased size of the pituitary gland.

A tumor arising from glia in the central nervous system with macroscopic regions of necrosis and hemorrhage. Microscopically, glioblastoma multiforme is characterized by regions of pseudopalisading necrosis, pleomorphic nuclei and cells, and microvascular proliferation.
Absence or underdevelopment of the cochlea, a spiral shaped cavity in the inner ear, owing to a developmental defect.
Developmental hypoplasia of the phalanx of third toe.
Ultra-low vision with complete lack of light and form perception.
Ambiguous genitalia in an individual with XY genetic gender.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of aspartate-family amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.
An increased concentration of asparagine in the urine.

An incessant orthodromic tachycardia with anterograde conduction over the atrioventricular node and by retrograde conduction via an accessory pathway usually located in the posteroseptal region with slow and decremental conduction.
The presence of wide, concave anterior rib ends.
A structural abnormality of B cells.
An abnormal concentration of sodium in the urine.
An abnormality of the function of the electrical signals with which nerve cells communicate with each other or with muscles as measured by electrophysiological investigations.

Congenital mesoblastic nephroma is a type of kidney tumor that is usually found before birth by ultrasound or within the first 3 months of life. It contains fibroblastic cells (connective tissue cells), and may spread to the other kidney or to nearby tissue.
A congenital malformation of the tricuspid valve characterized by leaflet deformation.
A lack of mobility of ejaculated sperm.

Change in the color of the fundus from red in the dark-adapted state to golden immediately or shortly after the onset of the light. The color of the fundus reflex in the light adapted state has also been described as golden-yellow, gray-white, and yellow-white. This reflex can appear either homogeneous or in streaks in the fundus. The retinal vessels appear to be protruding in contrast to the radiant background. Dark adaptation leads to disappearance of the unusual fundus coloration [Digital Journal of Ophthalmology 2008; Volume 14, Number 14].
A congenital malformation of the anterior segment characterized by iridicorneal malformation, glaucoma, iris stroma hypoplasia, posterior embryotoxon, and corneal opacities.
Inflammation of the cartilage of the external ear.
The inability to close the eyelids during sleep.
An enlargement of the thyroid gland with congenital onset.
Passage of many stools containing blood.
A reduced level of the complement component C8 in circulation.
A cyst of the ovary that exhibits deposition of calcium salts.
A reduced ability of a T cell population to expand by cell division following T cell activation.
Decreased concentration of adenosylcobalamin. Adenosylcobalamin is one of the active forms of vitamin B12.
The presence of abnormal muscle fiber size such that type 1 fibers are smaller than type 2 fibers.
Abnormal results of exercise on heart function.
A sensation of itching in the vagina.
An abnormal increased in the concentration of corticotropin, also known as adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), in the blood.
Bleeding occurring within the fovea.
Abnormality in the process of thought including the ability to process information.
Any abnormality of the scapula, also known as the shoulder blade.
High urine potassium in the presence of hypokalemia.
Failure to develop of the tricuspid valve and thus lack of the normal connection between the right atrium and the right ventricle.
?xrefs: ICD-10:Q22.4 SNOMEDCT_US:253455004 MSH:D018785 SNOMEDCT_US:63042009 UMLS:C0243002 Fyler:400 EPCC:06.01.01 Fyler:0400

?def: The presence of aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of all or part of the external ear.
The presence of an adenoma of the pancreas with origin in a pancreatic B cell.
Intermittent episodes of increased resistance to the passage of air in the upper airway.
Abnormal positioning in which the elbows are turned out.

Type V lesions are defined as lesions in which prominent new fibrous connective tissue has formed. When the new tissue is part of a lesion with a lipid core (type IV), this type of morphology may be referred to as fibroatheroma or type Va lesion. A type V lesion in which the lipid core and other parts of the lesion are calcified may be referred to as type Vb. A type V lesion in which a lipid core is absent and lipid in general is minimal may be referred to as type Vc. With these lesions, arteries are variously narrowed, generally more than with type IV. Importantly, as with type IV lesions, type V lesions may develop fissures, hematoma, and/or thrombus (type VI lesion), and for this reason too they are clinically relevant.
Persistence of the stapedial artery, which normally regresses during embryonic life.
A tendency to tilt the head towards the right shoulder to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.

An apical cap is a caplike lesion at the lung apex, usually caused by intrapulmonary and pleural fibrosis pulling down extrapleural fat or possibly by chronic ischemia resulting in hyaline plaque formation on the visceral pleura. The prevalence increases with age. It can also be seen in hematoma resulting from aortic rupture or in other fluid collection associated with infection or tumor, either outside the parietal pleura or loculated within the pleural space.
Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the medial rectus muscle.
Any anomaly of the P wave of the EKG, which results from atrial depolarization. The P wave occurs when the sinoatrial node creates an action potential that depolarizes the atria.
Cutis gyrata of palms and soles.
Absence or underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the middle phalanx of the fifth finger.
The appearance of the liver in sonographic images is normally uniform. This term applies when there is an irregular or non-uniform appearance of the liver parenchyma in liver sonography.
A type of retinal reticular pigmentation that forms a polygonal, netlike arrangement of hyperpigmented lines forming geometric patterns in the fundus.

Large subcortical heterotopia of variable morphology wiht streaks and swirls. These always connect to the overlying cortex in at least one, but usually in multiple, locations. Spaces with the signal intensity of CSF are usually seen within the heterotopia.
A delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more long bones.
A broad appearance of the second toe.
Abnormally increased volume of the first heart sound.
Abnormality of the patella (knee cap).
An elevation over the normal range of the average amount of hemoglobin per red blood cell (27 to 31 picograms/cell).
An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the third toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Agenesis, that is, failure of the kidney to develop during embryogenesis and development.

Avascular necrosis of the proximal epiphysis of the femur occurring in growing children and caused by an interruption of the blood supply to the head of the femur close to the hip joint. The necrosis is characteristically associated with flattening of the femoral head, for which reason the term coxa plana has been used to refer to this feature in the medical literature.
A decreased rate of skeletal maturation. Delayed skeletal maturation can be diagnosed on the basis of an estimation of the bone age from radiographs of specific bones in the human body.
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by ingestion of aspirin.
Congenital absence of the colon

On prenatal ultrasound, the nasal bone is a thin echogenic line within the bridge of the fetal nose. The fetus is imaged facing the transducer with the fetal face strictly in the midline. The angle of insonation is 90 degrees, with the longitudinal axis of the nasal bone as the reference line. Calibres are placed at each end of the nasal bone. Absence of the nasal bone or measurements below 2.5th percentile are considered significant (pmid:16100637).
Failure to develop of the small intestine.

A precancerous condition characterized by dysplasia of the cervical epithelium. Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia (CIN) 1, 2 and 3 based on its relationship with the prognosis. CIN 1 is mild dysplasia, which is mostly observed because it disappears as part of its natural course. CIN 3 includes severe dysplasia and carcinoma in situ, and management involves treatment because it is highly likely to develop into invasive cancer.
The presence of misshapen or partially destroyed nail plates, often with accumulation of soft, yellow keratin between the dystrophic nail plate and nail bed, resulting in elevation of the nail plate.
Partial or complete duplication of proximal phalanx of third toe.

Cautious gait refers to an excessive degree of age-related changes in walking and fear of falling. The walking difficulties seem out of proportion when considering the patient's actual sensory or motor deficits. The gait appears slow, with a wider base than normal, reduced arm swing bilaterally and a slightly stooped posture. This type of gait change often occurs after the first time a patient has fallen.
Abnormality of the phalanges of the 5th (little) finger.
A type of ectopia cordis with the heart partially in the cervical region and without a defect of the sternum.
Increased convexity of the occiput (posterior part of the skull).
An altered ability of any enzyme to act as catalysts within erythrocytes. This term includes changes due to altered levels of an enzyme.
Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the 1st metacarpal with respect to age-dependent norms.
Auras with sensation of tingling, numbness, electric shock sensations, pain, sense of movement, or desire to move.
An abnormality of the skull, the bony framework of the head which is comprised of eight cranial and fourteen facial bones.
Somewhat rapid onset and change of disease manifestations.
Anterior tongue-like protrusions of the vertebral bodies of the lumbar spine.

The ilia is round and hypoplastic with a very flat acetabular roof and a very unusual medial projection of bone that is said to resemble the head of a snail. Figure 4 of PMID:3799723 illustrates this feature.
Absence of ceruloplasmin in the blood.
Any anomaly of the structure of the breast.
Uneven rhythm of breathing.

The presence of aneurysmal polypoidal lesions in the choroidal vasculature. The aneurysmal dilatations, also known as polyps, may be found at subfoveal, juxtafoveal, extrafoveal, peripapillary or even peripheral regions. These polypoidal dilatations may be visible as reddish-orange subretinal nodules during ophthalmoscopic examination. The polypoidal lesions are best detected on indocyanine green angiography (ICGA) and might be associated with a branching vascular network (BVN) of neovascularization.
Hemorrhage into the parenchyma of the brain.
?xrefs: MSH:D020300 SNOMEDCT_US:274100004 SNOMEDCT_US:230706003 UMLS:C2937358 MSH:D002543 UMLS:C0553692

?def: Underdevelopment of the trapezoid.

A Hoffman test is performed by flicking the fingernail of the long finger, from dorsal to volar, on each hand while the hand was supported by the examiner's hand. The test was done with the neck in the neutral position and then with the neck maximally forward flexed. Any flexion of the ipsilateral thumb and/or index finger was interpreted as a positive test.
An abnormal osseous union (fusion) between the ulna and the humerus.

In the NBT test, neutrophils change the colorless compound NBT into a compound with a deep blue color. If this test is negative (i.e., no blue color is produced), then this indicates a defect in superoxide-generating NADPH oxidase activity with inability to efficiently kill phagocytized bacteria.
Abnormal accumulation of fluid in the brain.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.
Decreased cell membrane concentration of P2Y12 receptor.
A form of polydactyly in which the extra digit or digits are localized on the side of the thumb or great toe.

The rotator cuff comprises four muscles (supraspinatus, infraspinatus, teres minor, and subscapularis) which attach close to the humeral head via tendons and are critically involved in stability and function of the shoulder. A rotator cuff tear is when one or more of these tendons tears or detaches from the humerus.
The gradual reduction in girth of the finger from proximal to distal.
Abnormal persistent patency of the ductus arteriosus when birth was at less than 37 weeks completed gestation.
A pterygium (or pterygia) in the intercrural (groin) region.
The presence of microscopic crystalline calcium precipitates in the form of oxalate and/or phosphate in the renal parenchyma.
Left ventricular noncompaction (LVNC) is defined by 3 markers: prominent left ventricular (LV) trabeculae, deep intertrabecular recesses, and the thin compacted layer.
An abnormality of emotional behaviour.
Cleft lip and cleft palate affecting both sides of the face.
A congenital malformation characterized by an abnormal connection (fistula) between the rectum and the vulval vestibule, at the lower aspect of the vaginal opening.
Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in large bile ducts outside the liver.
The total absence of the hand, with no bony elements distal to the radius or ulna.
A structural anomaly of lysosomes, membrane-enclosed organelles that contain an array of enzymes capable of catabolizing proteins, nucleic acids, carbohydrates, and lipids.
A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the lumen of the rectum. That is, there is an abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the rectum.
A deviation from the normal discoid platelet shape.
A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in the thyroid gland.

An increase in adipose tissue mass by hyperplastic growth (increase in the number of adipocytes) or by hypertrophic growth (increase in the size of adipocytes occurring primarily by lipid accumulation within the cell).
Any anomaly of the function of a coronary artery.
Episodes of atrial fibrillation that typically last for several hours up to one day and terminate spontaneously.
A reduced circulating concentration of folic acid, which is also known as vitamin B9.
The interphalangeal joint of the big toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.
Osteoarthritis of the metatarsophalangeal joint of the first toe.
A type of dystonia (abnormally increased muscular tone causing fixed abnormal postures) that affects muscles of the legs.
A reduction in the amount of galactose residues of N-glycans.

Narrowing of peripheral arteries with reduction of blood flow to the limbs. This feature may be quantified as an ankle-brachial index of less than 0.9, and may be manifested clinically as claudication.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:399957001 SNOMEDCT_US:400047006 MSH:D058729 MSH:D016491 UMLS:C0085096 UMLS:C1704436

?def: Noticeably unpleasant odors exhaled in breathing.
Complete duplication of middle phalanx of second toe.
Two-sided or bilateral weakness of the muscles of facial expression and eye closure.
A tan, regularly bordered patch with darker macules within the lesion.
A congenital underdevelopment (aplasia or hypoplasia) of the pancreas.
The abnormal accumulation of fluid in two or more fetal compartments, including ascites, pleural effusion, pericardial effusion, and skin edema.

An abnormality of the sternum that presents at birth as a ventral sternal non-union defect, due to an abnormality of the fusion of the layers of the skin. It presents as a scar-like line that extends upward from the umbilicus (belly button).
Mulberry molars are irregular teeth generally affecting the first molars and are characterized by a grossly deformed crown imitating, as the name implies, the surface of a mulberry.
Any deviation from the normal cell count per volume of granulocytes in the blood circulation.
A type of sacrococcygeal teratoma that is predominantly intrapelvic with a small external, buttock mass.
Absence or underdevelopment of the urinary bladder.

Cerebral cysts, usually located in the wall of the caudate nucleus or in the caudothalamic groove. They are found in up to 5.2% of all neonates, using transfontanellar ultrasound in the first days of life.
Abnormal protrusion of the scapula away from the surface of the back.
Anterior chamber cells with 26-50 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.
An abnormality of nerve cell cluster or a group of nerve cell bodies located in the peripheral autonomic nervous system.
An abnormal decrease in the average size of low-density lipoprotein particle size in the blood circulation.
Episodes of reduced body termperature.
Inflammation of the blood vessels within the brain.
Folds or ridges within the concha that are distinct from the crus helix.
A type of urethral stricture affecting the bulbar urethra, which is the part of the urethra that traverses the root of the penis.
An abnormally increased concentration of N-Acetylaspartic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
Abnormally increased density of metaphyseal bone.
An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in red blood cells.
The presence of a bicuspid pulmonary valve.
An anomaly in the magnitude of the action potential along a peripheral nerve, that is, of the rapid rise and fall of the electrical membrane potential of the nerve.

A type of myoclonus in which the myoclonias shift from body region to another in a random and asynchronous fashion. Erratic myoclonus can affect the face or limbs, are brief, single or repetitive, very frequent and nearly continuous.
Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the thumb.
Enlargement or increased size of the heart left ventricle.
Increased susceptibility to Haemophilus influenzae infections as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection by Haemophilus influenzae.
A congenital anomaly characterized by a joining (fusion) of two or more lumbar vertebral bodies with one another.
Development of gray hair at a younger than normal age.
Thickened fingernails.
Very brief, involuntary random muscular contractions occurring at rest, in response to sensory stimuli, or accompanying voluntary movements.
Abnormally increased hair growth referring to a male pattern of body hair (androgenic hair).
Single umbilical artery (SUA) is the absence of one of the two umbilical arteries surrounding the fetal bladder and in the fetal umbilical cord.
A deviation from the normal concentration of hyaluronic acid in the blood.
Abnormal reduction in ossification of the calvaria (roof of the skull consisting of the frontal bone, parietal bones, temporal bones, and occipital bone).

Brain damage related to a lowering of blood glucose below a critical level (around 30 mg/dl), which may lead to confusion, lethargy and delirium followed by seizures and coma. Prolonged hypoglycemia may lead to irreversible brain damage.
Any anomaly of the conduction of motor nerve impulses in the central nervous system.
Forward protrusion of the glabella.
A staphyloma is a localized defect in the eye wall with protrusion of uveal tissue due to alterations in scleral thickness and structure.
Impaired ability to eat related to problems gathering food and getting ready to suck, chew, or swallow it.
A increased concentration of arginine in the urine.
Applies to an abnormality that is located farther from the median plane or midline of the body or of the referenced structure.

The passage of blackish, tarry feces associated with gastrointestinal hemorrhage. Melena occurs if the blood remains in the colon long enough for it to be broken down by colonic bacteria. One degradation product, hematin, imbues the stool with a blackish color. Thus, melena generally occurs with bleeding from the upper gastrointestinal tract (e.g., stomach ulcers or duodenal ulcers), since the blood usually remains in the gut for a longer period of time than with lower gastrointestinal bleeding.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:249627005 UMLS:C0025222 SNOMEDCT_US:267055007 SNOMEDCT_US:2901004 SNOMEDCT_US:269899009 UMLS:C0474585 MSH:D008551 SNOMEDCT_US:35064005

?def: Absence of a lobe of the thyroid gland related to a failure of its embryologic development.

A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the pulmonary origin. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
Abnormal inversion (turning inward) of the eyelid towards the globe associated with scarring that vertically shortens the posterior lamella of the eyelid.
Ventral hernia refers to a condition in which abdominal contents protrude through a weakened portion of the abdominal wall.
Absence of facial hair.
Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized to the region of the descending trunk of arch of aorta.

Abnormal accumulation of surfactant-like, periodic acid-schiff-positive lipoproteinaceous material in macrophages within the alveolar spaces and distal bronchioles. This results in gas exchange impairment leading to dyspnea and alveolar infiltrates.

A deviation in the normal proportion of transitional B cells (CD19+/CD38high/IgMhigh) in circulation relative to the total number of B cells. B cells originate from precursors in the bone marrow, and the first cells which migrate to the peripheral blood have been classified as transitional B cells.
An abnormality of glycolysis.
Abnormality of eyesight (visual perception).
Proximal spinal muscular atrophy, i.e., muscular weakness and atrophy related to loss of the motor neurons of the spinal cord and brainstem.
Any structural abnormality of the coronary arteries.
Hypoplasia (underdevelopment) of the pectoralis minor on only one side of the chest.
