An increased concentration of histidine in the urine.
EEG dominated by diffuse alpha-waves (8-13Hz).
Overproduction of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), which generally leads secondarily to overproduction of cortisol by the adrenal cortex.
A form of hydrocephalus in which there is no visible obstruction to the flow of the cerebrospinal fluid between the ventricles and subarachnoid space.
Abnormal concentration of isobutyrylglycine in the urine.
Focal spikes occurring for several seconds.
Nasal tip positioned to one side of the midline.
Reduced number of beta cells in the pancreatic islets of Langerhans.
An abnormality of the hepatic vasculature.
A reduction in the degree of glycosylation of alpha-dystroglycan in muscle tissue.
Increased width of the phalanges of the hand.
Decreased amount of leucine in the blood.
Increased lacrimation owing to overproduction of tears.

A type of spinal dysraphism presenting as a subcutaneous fatty mass, that is, a spinal defect associated with lipomatous tissue, and covered by skin. The most usual location for lipomyelomeningocele is at the gluteal cleft.@en
Localized thickening and tightness of the skin of the fingers or toes.
A deviation from the normal concentration of biopterin in the blood circulation.
Early closure (ossification) of the anterior fontanelle, which generally undergoes closure around the 18th month of life.
Anomaly of the folded ridges (wrinkles) of skin of the scrotum.
Diffuse sclerosis of the mesangium, as manifestated by diffuse mesangial matrix expansion.

An impairment in the rate and degree to which platelets aggregate after the addition of an agonist that stimulates platelet clumping. Platelet aggregation is measured using aggregometer to measure the optical density of platelet-rich plasma, whereby platelet aggregation causes the plasma to become more transparent.
Abnormal consumption of fluids with excessive or insufficient consumption of fluid or any other abnormal pattern of fluid consumption.
An electromyographic finding associated with erratic or absent neuromuscular transmission with erratic, moment-to-moment changes in the shape of the motor unit potential (MUP).
Decreased strength of the inferior oblique muscle.
A clogged cutaneous sebaceous follicle, which is a cutaneous gland that secretes sebum (usually into a hair follicle).

Penile width more than 2 standard deviations (SD) below the mean for age. Alternatively circumference of the flaccid penis more than 2 SD below the mean for age. Alternatively, apparently decreased penile width for age.
Any abnormality in the proportion of CD3-positive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers with respect to age-dependent norms.
An abnormally decreased level of immunoglobulin in blood.
A sensation of itching in the vulvar region.
Inability to develop or maintain an erection of the penis.
A reduction in the amount of very-low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

An elevation above the normal concentration of thyroxine in the blood. Thyroxine (also known as T4) is the main hormone secreted by the thyroid gland into the blood. It can be converted into the active form triiodothyronine (also known as T3).
Diffuse thickening of the ventricular endocardium and by associated myocardial dysfunction
An abnormality of the morphology of the tooth.

A type of bicuspid aortic valvue (BAV) characterized by the presence of two raphes that each extend from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps. This type of BAV has developmental anlagen of three cusps, commissures, and sinuses, but two commissures are more or less malformed and obliterated, giving rise to a raphe, a fibrous ridge, which extends from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps. This type of BAV is typically associated with a high degree of aortic stenosis.

A Number 0 Tessier cleft is a true median cleft lip with a broad columella and bifid nasal tip. The alveolar cleft is between the central incisors. The nasal septum may be thickened, duplicated, or absent. The nasal bridge is usually broad with associated orbital hypertelorism. The midline soft tissue anomaly may range from a mild broadening of the philtrum or there may be a true median cleft lip. The columella and nasal tip are typically bifid and broadened with a midline depression. The alae nasi are intact but laterally displaced. The nose appears shortened in the vertical dimension.
Recurring episodes of myoglobinuria, i.e., of the presence of myoglobin in the urine. This is usually a consequence of rhabdomyolysis, i.e., of the destruction of muscle tissue.
Abnormality of the homeostasis (concentration) of a monoatomic ion.
A solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter and that has a yellow color.

Galectin-3 is a member of the family of beta-galactoside-binding endogenous lectins. It is a multifunctional factor that binds to distinct ligands and tiggers production of matrix metalloproteinases, and thereby plays a role in cardiac fibrosis and remodelling.
An abnormality of the philtrum.
Abnormal (retrograde) movement of urine from the bladder into ureters or kidneys related to inadequacy of the valvular mechanism at the ureterovesicular junction or other causes.
Mottled (spotted or blotched with different shades) pigmentary abnormality of the macula lutea.
A state of shock characterized by decreased circulating blood volume in relation to total vascular capacity. This type of shock is characterized by a reduction of diastolic filling pressures.
Absence or underdevelopment of the anterior segment of the eye.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of one or more phalanges of the thumb.
Loss of all scalp hair.
An abnormality of the thoracic vertebral column.
An involuntary abnormality of fixation in which there is an abnormal saccade away from fixation followed by an immediate corrective saccade.
A congenital malformation with a cleft (gap or opening) in the face.
The presence of multiple xanthomas (xanthomata) in the skin distributed in the creases of the palm of the hand. Xanthomas are yellowish, firm, lipid-laden nodules in the skin.
Reduced length of the middle phalanx of second toe as a result of developmental hypoplasia.
Abnormal twisting of a portion of intestine around itself or around a stalk of mesentery tissue.

A type of weakness of a skeletal muscle of proximal part of a limb that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.
Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the fifth finger, also known as the little finger.
An impairment in the ability to produce voice sounds.
Any abnormality of the morphology of the major calices or minor calices of the kidney.
Wasting of the tongue.
An abnormality of the lower arm.
Any abnormality of the lumbosacral nerve plexus.
Increased pigmentation of the fundus

?xrefs: UMLS:C0235025 MSH:D009443 SNOMEDCT_US:95663000 MSH:D011115 SNOMEDCT_US:85423005 UMLS:C0271683

?def: A functional abnormality of neutrophils.
Disproportionate shortening of the proximal segment of limbs (i.e. the femur and humerus).
Abnormality in single fiber EMG recording, a technique that allows identification of action potentials (APs) from individual muscle fibers.
An abnormality of the abducens nerve.

An anomaly in the blood concentration of an androgen, that is, of a steroid hormone that controls development and maintenance of masculine characteristics. The androgens include testosterone and Dehydroepiandrosterone.
Recurrent episodes of oral herpes, typically characterized by blisters or ulcers on the gums, lips and/or tongue caused by herpes virus.
Abnormally flat shape of the heads of the metacarpal bones.
Formation of one or more fibrous bands within the temporomandibular joint (TMJ) with resulting limitation of movement of the TMJ. Adhesions may be seen in degenerative processes that involve the TMJ.
A fold of skin starting at or just below the medial aspect of the lower lid and arching upward to cover, extend in front of and lateral to the medial canthus.
Underdevelopment of the philtrum.
Underdevelopment of the frontal bone.
An abnormality of a procerus.
Inflammation of the episclera, a thin layer of tissue covering the white part (sclera) of the eye.

A type of ventricular septal defect communicating directly between the left ventricle and right atrium. This is anatomically possible because the normal tricuspid valve is more apically displaced than the mitral valve.
Bleeding from vessels of the various tissues of the eye.
An abnormal loss of anagen (growth phase) hairs.
Moderate osteoporosis.
Inflammation surrounding hair follicles.
Telangiectasia (that is, the presence of small dilated superficial blood vessels) of the oral mucosa.
Severe degree of osteoporosis.
Increased size of the incisor tooth.
An abnormal increase in catecholamine concentration in the blood.
Congenital malformation of the ventral wall with partial or total evisceration of the heart outside the thoracic cavity and through the defect in the ventral wall.
Hyperplasia of the islets of Langerhans, i.e., of the regions of the pancreas that contain its endocrine cells.
Areas of radio-opaque sclerotic bands alternating with those of normal lucency give rise to stripes akin to a zebra.
Funnel detachment from the retina with generally traction in all four quadrants.
A mild delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in one or more epiphyses.
An anomaly of the complex formed by the Q, R, and S waves, which occur in rapid succession on the electrocardiogram.
Excess skin around the neck, often lying in horizontal folds.

Hemiballismus is a rare movement disorder that is caused primarily by damage to various areas in the basal ganglia. Hemiballismus is usually characterized by involuntary flinging motions of the extremities. The movements are often violent and have wide amplitudes of motion. They are continuous and random and can involve proximal and/or distal muscles on one side of the body, while some cases even include the facial muscles. The more a patient is active, the more the movements increase. With relaxation comes a decrease in movements.
The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the cerebral white matter.
An elevated concentration of a gonadotropin hormone (stimulating hormone or luteinizing hormone) in the urine, consistent with the diagnosis of primary hypogonadism.
An abnormal high amount of bleeding following the procedure of taking a blood sample.
Generalized epileptiform discharges of different shapes and frequencies.
Fusion of two or more bones of the 4th finger.
Eversion of the endocervix with protrusion of the central (endocervical) columnar epithelium through the external os of the cervis into the vaginal milieu.
Decreased count of erythroid precursor cells, that is, erythroid lineage cells in the bone marrow.
An abnormality of the shape of the thoracic vertebra T12 such that it is wedge-shaped (narrow towards the front).
An abnormality of a cartilage of external ear.
A type of tremors that is triggered by holding an arm in a fixed position.
An uneven increase in bone density of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.
An abnormality of the frontal bone.
Exaggerated convexity of the cervical vertebral column, causing the cervical spine to bow outwards and take on a rounded appearance.

Perifoveal vitreous separation with remaining vitreomacular attachment and unperturbed foveal morphologic features. It is an OCT finding that is almost always the result of normal vitreous aging, which may lead to pathologic conditions.

Presence of an abnormal type of hemoglobin characterized by the subsitution of a glutamic acid residue at position 7 following the initial methionine residue by a lysine (6GAG>6AAG). The presence of HbC can be determined by hemoglobin electrophoresis.
An abnormality of the skin that is not localized to any one particular region.
Low platelet count following administration of unfractionated or (less commonly) low-molecular weight heparin.
The presence of more than the normal number of carpal bones.
A ratio of serum triiodothyronine (T3) to thyroxine (T4) in the blood that is lower than normal.

An abnormality of the pupillary light reaction characterized by a marked slowing of the light reaction of usually just one pupil. The pupil tends to be relatively dilated, and there is reduced accommodation.
Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the distal phalanx of the third finger.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of an artery.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:26845001 SNOMEDCT_US:9406001 SNOMEDCT_US:710864009 UMLS:C0002949 MSH:D000784 SNOMEDCT_US:233992003

?def: The presence of two distinct odontoid processes. The odontoid process, also known as the dens of the axis, is a protuberance of the C2 vertebral body around which the first vertebra rotates.

Abnormally increased size of the costochondral junctions, which are located between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum.
Proliferative changes of the bile ducts.
An elevated concentration of phosphohydroxylysine in the urine.

Altered level of the enzyme that catalyzes conversion of hypoxanthine to inosine monophosphate and guanine to guanosine monophosphate via transfer of the 5-phosphoribosyl group from 5-phosphoribosyl 1-pyrophosphate.
An abnormality of the partial pressure of oxygen in the arterial blood.

Increased susceptibility to opportunistic infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection by opportunistic agents, i.e., by microorganisms that do not usually cause disease in a healthy host, but are able to infect a host with a compromised immune system.
An abnormality of a geniohyoid muscle.

The prothrombin consumption test measures the formation of intrinsic thromboplastin by determining the residual serum prothrombin after blood clotting is complete. If there is a defect in the process, less prothrombin will be converted to thrombin than normal (less prothrombin is consumed). This test may be abnormal with conditions including deficiency of factors VIII or IX, with circulating anticoagulants, thrombocytopenia.
A conspicuously unhappy disposition characterized by negative assumptions, self-defeating talk, fear of failure, and negative ruminations about past events.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger.
Recurrent infections by bacteria of the genus Neisseria, including N. meningitidis (one of the most common causes of bacterial meningitis).
A form of lissencephaly characterized by an uneven cortical surface with a so called 'cobblestone' appearace. There are no distinguishable cortical layers.

Tumor-like growths that consist of replacement of the medullary bone with fibrous tissue, causing the expansion and weakening of the areas of bone involved. Especially when involving the skull or facial bones, the lesions can cause externally visible deformities. The skull is often, but not necessarily, affected, and any other bone or bones may be involved. Fibrous dysplasia can either effect isolated bones (Monostotic fibrous dysplasia) or also generalized all bones of the body (Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia).

No consensus exists on what a stroke-like episode is, but these episodes can be functionally defined as a new neurological deficit, occurring with or without the context of seizures, which last longer than 24 hours.

An adverse response (dislike) to sound no matter what volume the sound is, characterized by a strong negative reaction to soft sounds that can sometimes be further triggered by seeing the source of the offending sound.
Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of little toe.
Inherited progressive cone degeneration.
A localized outpouching of ventricular cavity that is generally associated with dyskinesia and paradoxical expansion during systole.
An abnormality of the dental pulp.
Recurrent infection of the gastrointestinal tract.
Reduced concentration of beta-2-microglobulin in the blood.
A hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, that is located in the intrathoracic or chest region.
A breach of the capsule of the spleen.
An elevated concentration of progesterone in the blood.
Decreased density/number and/or decreased diameter of eyebrow hairs.
Persistent or frequent angry feelings; anger or irritability in response to minor slights and insults.
A type of anterior uveitis, in which there is Inflammation of the iris and the ciliary body.

The presence of multiple granulomas in the liver as based on pathological examination. Granulomas are small 0.5 to 2 mm collections of modified macrophages called epithelioid cells usually surrounded by lymphocytes.
An anomaly of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.
Hyposegmented (hypolobulated) or bilobed neutrophil nuclei.
Any abnormality of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.
Absence of a localized portion of the ear that cannot be described by a more precise term (e.g., absent ear lobe).
Calcium deposition affecting the Meninges.
The ability of the knee joint to extend beyond its normal range of motion (the lower leg is moved beyond a straight position with respect to the thigh).
A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position occuring at distal joints.
Absence of one half of the vertebral body in the cervical spine.
Episodic fever that recurs at irregular intervals.
An abnormal amount of oxygen passes into the blood from the lungs and/or an abnormal amount of carbon dioxide passes from the blood into the lungs.
An incomplete absence of the foot, with no bony elements distal to the tarsals, but with preservation of some or all of the tarsals.

A medium reduction in the fraction of blood pumped from the left ventricle with each cardiac cycle. The normal range in adults is at least 55 percent, and a moderate reduction is defined as 30-44 percent.
Involuntary and irregular twitches of the chin.
Delivery of a fetus through surgical incisions made through the abdominal wall (laparotomy) and the uterine wall (hysterotomy).
The presence of degenerative changes of intervertebral disk.
A cone-shaped deformity of the cornea characterized by the presence of corneal distortion secondary to thinning of the apex.
Abnormal development of the choroid and retina.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of adipose tissue.

?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:278040002 SNOMEDCT_US:56317004 MSH:D000505 UMLS:C0002170 SNOMEDCT_US:298000004 UMLS:C1850535 UMLS:C0574769

?def: Absence of the proximal radial epiphysis.

Accessory pathway-related atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) involves an abnormal electrical conduction of the accessory pathway. The accessory pathway connecting impulses between the atrium and the ventricle can be seen at any site in the AV groove.
A type of tetralogy of Fallot with pulmonary atresia in which all pulmonary blood flow is derived from major aortopulmonary collateral arteries (MAPCA).

Third-degree atrioventricular (AV) block (also referred to as complete heart block) is the complete dissociation of the atria and the ventricles. Third-degree AV block exists when more P waves than QRS complexes exist and no relationship (no conduction) exists between them.

Ichthyosis follicularis is characterized by widespread non inflammatory thorn-like follicular projections. Dyskeratotic papules are most pronounced over the extensor extremities and scalp and are symmetrically distributed.
Any structural abnormality of erythrocytes (red-blood cells).
Urticaria characterized by spontaneously recurring hives for 6 weeks or longer.

The Duffy blood group system is based on the presence of a glycoprotein termed Fy that is on the surface of erythrocytes and some other cells. There are two Duffy antigens named Fya and Fyb, and thus there are four Duffy phenotypes: a+b+, a+b-, a-b+,a-b-.
A malformation of the laryngeal cartilage.
A form of torticollis in which the head is drawn back, either due to a permanent contractures of neck extensor muscles, or to a spasmodic contracture.
An abnormally increased length of the metacarpal bones.
Uneven increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the 5th finger.
An increased proportion of mast cells are positive for the cell surface marker CD25 (also called interleukin-2 receptor alpha chain).

Leukoplakia is a precancerous dermatosis of mucous membranes analogous Leukoplakia is basically a chronic inflammatory hypertrophy in which anaplasia and malignant dyskeratosis may develop and subsequently advance to an invasive squamous cell cancer. The clinical diagnosis of primary anal leukoplakia is indicated by single or multiple slightly raised,irregular, marginated, grayish-white keratinized' patches in the anal canal. Tissue biopsy is necessary for confirmation.
Spontaneous detachment of a foot from the body.
A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the little finger of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.
A congenital anomaly characterized by the presence of two separate pancreatic ducts.
Partial duplication of the third proximal phalanx of hand, seen on x-rays as a broad and/or bifid phalanx.
Decreased amount of autofluorescence in the retina as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.

A type of low sperm count where ejaculated semen contains less than 100,000 spermatozoa per ml. With cryptozoospermia, the sperm count may fluctuate and a zero sperm count in the ejaculate may be initially measured. If sperm are observed in a second semen sample following centrifugation, the diagnosis of cryptozoospermia can be made (and azoospermia can be ruled out).
A chronic inflammatory disease of the large intestine (colon, cecum and rectum).
A compensatory head posture occurs when the head is deviated out of the normal primary straight head position in order to compensate for an ocular problem.
A sectoral indentation of the crystalline lens, usually due to zonular weakness or absence.
An anomaly of the expressive patterns of speech that involve intonation, stress pattern, loudness variations, pausing, articulatory force, and rhythm.
Hypoplastic/small or absent thumb.
An abnormality of the anterior segment of the eyeball (which comprises the structures in front of the vitreous humour: the cornea, iris, ciliary body, and lens).

Multiple cream-yellow colored hypopigmented choroidal anomalies whose size is approximately one quarter to one half of that of the optic disc, and whose location tends to cluster around the optic nerve radiating towards the periphery. The pattern of the lesions is said to be similar to gunshot spatter from birdshot.
Wide, concave rib end.
A slower than normal heart rate (in adults, slower than 60 beats per minute).
The presence of an abnormally increased amount of connective tissue.
Longstanding metabolic acidosis.
A sensation of tightness in the wrist joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.
The presence of inflammation affecting the kidney.
EEG dominated by diffuse beta-waves (>13 Hz).
An abnormality of the pigmentation of the mucosa of the mouth.
Thrombosis of the portal vein and/or its tributaries, which include the splenic vein and the sup-erior and inferior mesenteric veins.
An abnormality of one or more of the five muscles of the soft palate.
A non-malignant neoplasm of the genitourinary system.
Developmental hypoplasia of one or more phalanx of little toe.
A benign epithelial tumor derived from intrinsic cells of the adenohypophysis.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0032000 ICD-O:M8272/0 SNOMEDCT_US:128664001 MSH:D010911 SNOMEDCT_US:254956000 NCIT:C2855

?def: An anomaly of the muscular contractions that propel food though the gastrointestinal tract.
Abnormal growth of endometrial cells (which are normally limited to the uterus) within the cervix.
A form of sensorineural hearing impairment that affects primarily the lower frequencies.

Abnormally diminished motor activity. In contrast to paralysis, hypokinesia is not characterized by a lack of motor strength, but rather by a poverty of movement. The typical habitual movements (e.g., folding the arms, crossing the legs) are reduced in frequency.
Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the middle phalanx of the third finger.
The occurrence of the full-thickness tear (perforation) of the wall of the esophagus.
One or more bent (flexed) joints of the third toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.
Presence of telangiectases in the oral cavity.
A small angle heterotropia (usually of 10 diopters or less) in which a form of binocular single vision occurs.

Abnormally decreased level of the enzyme that catalyzes conversion of hypoxanthine to inosine monophosphate and guanine to guanosine monophosphate via transfer of the 5-phosphoribosyl group from 5-phosphoribosyl 1-pyrophosphate.
A deviation from the normal straight form of the middle phalanx of the fifth toe.
An abnormal appearance of the liver or any of its components on sonography (ultrasound).
A reduction in the thickness of Descemet's membrane.
A type of facial cleftlocated near to but not directly on the midline of the face.
A slowly growing malignant neoplasm derived from cartilage cells.
Osteosclerosis (increased density related to increased bone mass) of the ulna.

Abnormality of the nasal bridge, which is the saddle-shaped area that includes the nasal root and the lateral aspects of the nose. It lies between the glabella and the inferior boundary of the nasal bone, and extends laterally to the inner canthi.
Malalignement of carpal bone angles either with respect to each other, to the corresponding metacarpals or with respect to the wrist (radius and ulna).

Acromegaly is a condition resulting from overproduction of growth hormone by the pituitary gland in persons with closed epiphyses, and consists chiefly in the enlargement of the distal parts of the body. The circumference of the skull increases, the nose becomes broad, the tongue becomes enlarged, the facial features become coarsened, the mandible grows excessively, and the teeth become separated. The fingers and toes grow chiefly in thickness.
Mild fever that does not exceed 38.5 degree centrigrade.
An abnormal enlargement (i.e. increase in measured voltage) of somatosensory evoked potentials.
Any structural anomaly of the kidney.
An abnormal reduction in the quantity of three-dimensional space taken up by the pineal gland.
Auras which reflect ictal dysmnesia such as: feelings as familiarity (deja-vu) and unfamiliarity (jamais-vu).
Any deviation from the normal concentration of alpha-aminobutyrate in the cerebrospinal fluid.

A reduction in the normal proportion of class-switched memory B cells (CD19+/CD27+/IgM+/IgD+) relative to the total number of B cells. Marginal zone B cells undergo limited somatic hypermutation and produce high-affinity IgM and some IgG, whereas class-switched memory B cells synthetize IgG, IgM, and IgA.
The presence of one or more embedded tooth germs which have failed to erupt.
Increase in periorbital soft tissue.

A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on one of the autosomes (i.e., the human chromosomes 1-22) in which a trait manifests in homozygotes in a sex-specific manner (i.e. only in males or only in females).
Hypertrophy or overdevelopment of the interstitial (Leydig) cells of the testis. These cells produce testosterone.
A condition in which the helix is folded over to a greater degree than normal. That is, excessive curling of the helix edge, whereby the free edge is parallel to the plane of the ear.
An abnormality of the sphenoid sinus, one of the mucosa-lined, normally air-filled paranasal sinuses of the bones of the skull. The sphenoid sinus is located within the sphenoid bone.
An excess of eosinophilic cells in colonic tissue, i.e., eosinophilic infiltration in the colon.
A profound (essentially complete) form of hearing impairment.
Reduced number or density of pubic hair.

An increase in the normal proportion of class-switched memory B cells (CD19+/CD27+/IgM+/IgD+) relative to the total number of B cells. Marginal zone B cells undergo limited somatic hypermutation and produce high-affinity IgM and some IgG, whereas class-switched memory B cells synthetize IgG, IgM, and IgA.
An abnormality of the lip.
Abnormal bleeding related to a procedure or trauma which does not start at the time of the initial insult, but after delay by at least 24 hours.
A functional abnormality of the adrenal glands.

Juvenile myelomonocytic leukemia (JMML) is a lethal myeloproliferative disease of young childhood characterized clinically by overproduction of myelomonocytic cells and by the in vitro phenotype of hematopoietic progenitor hypersensitivity to granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor.
Abnormal increase in retinal thickness in the macular area observed on fundoscopy or fundus imaging.
Partial or complete duplication of the third proximal phalanx of hand.
A tumor made up of nerve cells and nerve fibers.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0027858 MSH:D009463 SNOMEDCT_US:84116009 UMLS:C0273482 SNOMEDCT_US:25169009 SNOMEDCT_US:443892003 SNOMEDCT_US:274089002

?def: Underdevelopment of the external ear.
A bilateral form of fetal pyelectasis.
A glial tumor of the retinal nerve fiber layer arising from a retinal astrocyte.

Infection of the lungs with Histoplasma capsulatum. Symptoms may include fever, headache, weakness, chest pain and dry cough. When imaging is done, chest radiographs may show patchy pneumonia involving one or more lobes with adenopathy of the mediastinum or hilum.
Presence of the Duffy Fyb antigen.
Absence of one half of the vertebral body in the thoracic spine.

Amenorrhea due to loss of ovarian function before the age of 40. Primary ovarian inssuficiency (POI) is a state of female hypergonadotropic hypogonadism. It can manifest as primary amenorrhea with onset before menarche or secondary amenorrhea.
Inferior malposition of the lower eyelid margin without eyelid eversion.
An abnormality of the function of the pulmonary veins.
Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger with the 4th metacarpal.

An ocular motility abnormality characterized by an overacting superior oblique muscle resulting to vertical incomitance of the eyes in lateral gaze. On examination, this is commonly seen as a downshoot of the adducting eye occuring when gaze is directed into the field of action of the inferior oblique muscle, producing a greater downward excursion of the adducted eye than of the abducted eye.
Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the metaphysis of the radius.
Reduced transparency of the central posterior portion of the corneal stroma.
Displacement of the big toe from its normal position.

A type of primitive reflex that is elicited by repetitive tapping on the forehead. Normal subjects usually blink in response to the first several taps, but if blinking persists, the response is abnormal and considered to be a sign of frontal release. Persistent blinking is also known as Myerson's sign.
Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of lymphocytes, which results in the expansion of a cell population.
A type of chronic kidney disease with severely reduced glomerular filtration rate (GFR 15-29 mL/min/1.73 m2).
An abnormality of the tragus.
Lack of skin pigmentation (coloring) of the chest.
Death of tissue in the outer part of the kidney.

Chronic loss of joint motion in the 2nd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The term camptodactyly of the 2nd finger is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.

Coxa valga is a deformity of the hip in which the angle between the femoral shaft and the femoral neck is increased compared to age-adjusted values (about 150 degrees in newborns gradually reducing to 120-130 degrees in adults).
Decreased functionality of the female gonads, i.e., of the ovary.
Increased susceptibility to respiratory infections in early life, as manifested by recurrent episodes of respiratory infections.
Decreased or impaired upregulation of CD25 on T cells after activation via the T cell receptor (TCR).
Any abnormality of the proximal epiphysis of the fibula.
Developmental hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of fifth toe.
Hyponasal speech is when there is an abnormally reduced nasal airflow during speech often in a setting of nasal obstruction or congestion.
Absence of the cochlea, a spiral shaped cavity in the inner ear, owing to a developmental defect.
An abnormal morphology of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

An abnormality of the middle phalanx of the second finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
Right atrial isomerism is characterized by bilateral triangular, morphologically right atrial, appendages, both joining the atrial chamber along a broad front with internal terminal crest.
Abnormally reduced ability of T cells to perform their functions in cell-mediated immunity.
An increase of the pressure inside the cranium (skull) and thereby in the brain tissue and cerebrospinal fluid.

Deviated fingers is a term that should be used if one or more fingers of the hand are deviated from their normal position, either to the radial or ulnar side. A deviation of a finger can be caused by an abnormal form of one or more of the phalanges of the affected finger, or by a deviation or displacement of one or more phalanges.
Chronic loss of joint motion in the tarsometatarsal joint of the hallux due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The tarsometatarsal joints of the feet are also called Lisfranc's joints.
Zonular cataracts are defined to be cataracts that affect specific regions of the lens.
Abnormality of one or all of the epiphyses of the proximal, middle, and distal phalanges of the 4th finger.
An abnormality of the Maxilla (upper jaw bone).
Cleft in the anterior mitral valve leaflet not associated with an atrioventricular canal defect.
A increased concentration of serotonin in the blood.
Decreased concentration of methylcobalamin. Methylcobalamin is a form of vitamin B12.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger is affected.
Type 3 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
Osteosclerosis of ribs (increased density related to increased bone mass).
Any abnormality of the size of the skeletal muscle cell.
An abnormal increase in pressure in the pulmonary veins, usually as a result of left atrial hypertension.

An anomaly of the lymphatic system, a network of lymphatic vessels that carry a clear fluid called lymph unidirectionally towards either the right lymphatic duct or the thoracic duct, which in turn drain into the right and left subclavian veins respectively.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0024228 SNOMEDCT_US:111590001 SNOMEDCT_US:234087005 SNOMEDCT_US:362971004 UMLS:C4021976 MSH:D008206 SNOMEDCT_US:3305006

?def: A form of telangiectasis characterized by a central elevated red dot the size of a pinhead, representing an arteriole, with numerous small blood vessels that radiate out thereby resembling the legs of a spider. Characteristically, compression of the central arteriole causes the entire lesion to blanch, and the lesion quickly refills once the compression is released.
Head circumference below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender.
An immunodeficiency defined by the absent or suboptimal functioning of one of the complement system proteins.
Neurofibromas present in a smaller number than usually seen in neurofibromatosis type 1.
A pituitary prolactin cell adenoma of less than 10 mm diameter.
Elevated binding of annexin V to platelet membrane, which is mediated by exposed phosphatidylserine. This can be measured by flow cytometry.
Increased level of IgE antibody against an feathers, which could be indicative of an allergy against feathers themselves, or mite allergens present in feathers.
The engulfing of lymphocytes by hepatocytes, which typically occurs in the interface hepatitis area.
A deviation from the normal range of manganese in the blood circulation.

An abdominal wall defected related to a developmental anomaly of the allantois, which is an embryonic structure that develops as a diverticulum off the yolk sac at about 16 days post fertilization. During further development, the allantois becomes incorporated into the body of the embryo, connecting the ventral aspect of the urogenital sinus (which will develop into the upper pole of the urinary bladder) to the external portion of the umbilicus. Upon further development, the lumen of the allantois becomes obliterated and forms a thick fibrous cord called the urachus, which connects the apex of the bladder to the umbilicus. In adults, the urachus is known as the median umbilical ligament. Failure of the allantoic cavity to obliterate can result of one of four conditions: 1) congenital patent urachus (a completely open connection between bladder and umbilicus); 2) vesicourachal diverticulum (a diverticulum off the bladder but not communicating with the umbilicus); umbilical cyst and sinus (not communicating with the bladder); and 4) alternating urachal sinus. An abdominal wall defect can be associated with a urachal cyst.
Epiphyses of the 4th toe are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.
An abnormality of the metacarpal bones.
Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the 2nd finger.
Reduced strength of the frontalis muscle (which is located on the forehead).
A form of hemolytic anemia that can be triggered by cold temperatures.
An abnormality of the glabella.
Otitis media characterized by thick or sticky fluid behind the tympanic membrane.
Partial dislocation of the ulna in the dorsal direction.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of alanine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Head movements associated with nystagmus, that may represent an attempt to compensate for the involuntary eye movements and to improve vision.
Any deviation from the normal overall count of natural killer (NK) cells in the circulation or a deviation from the normal distribution of NK cell subtypes.

A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
An abnormality of the concentration of glucose in the urine.
Presence of a chemical substance found within an individual that is not naturally produced or expected to be present in human tissues or bodily fluids.
Abnormally increased lacrimation, that is, excessive tearing (watering eye).
Occurence of excessive sweating during sleep.
An increased concentration of cholesterol in the blood.
Hyperplasia of the thyroid gland.
The presence of one or more cysts of the ovary.
An abnormally reduced amount of creatinine in the blood.
Congenital absence of the lumen of the larynx.

Dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM) is defined by the presence of left ventricular dilatation and left ventricular systolic dysfunction in the absence of abnormal loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) or coronary artery disease sufficient to cause global systolic impairment. Right ventricular dilation and dysfunction may be present but are not necessary for the diagnosis.

Fusion involving two or more metacarpal bones (A synostosis of the first metacarpal and the proximal phalanx of the thumb can also be observed, note that the first metacarpal bone corresponds to a proximal phalanx).
Any deviation from the normal circulating concentration of mast cell beta-tryptase concentration.
A herniation of meninges through a congenital bone defect in the skull in the occipital region.
Lack of prominence of the nose resulting from a posteriorly-placed nasal ridge.
A type of supraventricular tachycardia in which the atria are the principal site of electrophysiologic disturbance.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a glutamine family amino acid in the blood circulation.
Abnormally increased hair growth with a localized distribution.

Celiac disease (CD) is an autoimmune condition affecting the small intestine, triggered by the ingestion of gluten, the protein fraction of wheat, barley, and rye. Clinical manifestations of CD are highly variable and include both gastrointestinal and non-gastrointestinal features. The hallmark of CD is an immune-mediated enteropathy. This term is included because the occurence of CD is seen as a feature of a number of other diseases.
Increased levels of protein in the urine.

A recurrent pattern of behavior that is characeterized by the failure to resist an impulse, drive, or temptation to perform an act that is harmful to the person or to others. The repetitive engagement in these behaviors ultimately interferes with functioning in other domains.
The presence in serum of antibodies against smooth muscle.
Abnormal increased size of the viscera of the abdomen.
The presence of complexes of slow spikes and slow waves (<2.5 Hz) in electroencephalography (EEG).

Reduced ability of the right ventricle to perform its function (to receive blood from the right atrium and to eject blood into the pulmonary artery), often leading top pitting peripheral edema, ascites, and hepatomegaly.
An increase in uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase activity in plasma. Uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase catalyzes the reaction: UDP-glucose = UDP-galactose.
Occurrence of epileptiform discharges in occipital regions during photic stimulation.
Encephalopathy is a term that means brain disease, damage, or malfunction. In general, encephalopathy is manifested by an altered mental state.
Pain that is localized to the region of the upper abdomen immediately below the ribs.
A sudden eruption (rash) of the surface of a mucous membrane of the mouth or pharynx.
A deviation from the normal concentration of a carbohydrate in the blood circulation.
Abnormally increased size of the knee joint.
A form of hydrocephalus in which the flow of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) within the cerebral ventricular system or in the outlets of the CSF to the arachnoid space is obstructed.

A type of non-small cell lung carcinoma that is derived from undifferentiated malignant neoplasms originating from transformed epithelial cells in the lung, and which is differentiate from small-cell lung carcinoma by the larger size of the anaplastic cells, a higher cytoplasmic-to-nuclear size ratio, and a lack of salt-and-pepper appearance of the chromatin.
A congenital absence of the convolutions of the cerebral cortex and a poorly formed sylvian fissure that affects a particular part of the cortex.
An abnormally small and flat configuration of the posterior cranial fossa.
Absent eyelids.
Elongated curved (S-shaped) fibulae.
Nails whose growth is quicker than normal.
An anomaly in the system of mucociliary transport, which functions to transport the mucous layer lining the respiratory epithelium by ciliary \nbeating.
A chronic, relapsing, pustular eruption that is localized to the palms and soles.
A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in thyroid-stimulating hormone secretion.
Triangular shaped middle phalanx of the 2nd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
The presence of blood in the pleural space.
One sided hypoplasia of the kidney.
Reduced size of the placenta.

A type of weakness of the muscles involved in speech that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.
Linear heterotopia spanning from the cerebral mantle from the pia to the ependyma.
Agenesis of the midbrain.
Sudden-onset episode of abnormal, involuntary eye movements.
Abnormality/dysplasia of a single myeloid cell (erythroid, granulocytic, or megakaryocytic).
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against mitochondria.
Bowing (bulging out) of the membranous part of the interventricular septum of more than 10-15 mm into the cavity of an adjacent ventricle (usually into the right ventricle).
The congenital absence of all teeth.
A type of sideroblastic anemia that is not responsive to treatment.
Decreased cell membrane concentration of alpha-2A adrenergic receptor that is stimulated by epinephrine.
A decreased amount of lysine in the blood.
Detachment of the nail from the nail bed.
Enlargement of the chamber of the right ventricle.

A type of ataxia characterized by the impairment of the ability to coordinate the movements required for normal walking. Gait ataxia is characteirzed by a wide-based staggering gait with a tendency to fall.
An abnormality of the parathyroid gland.
An anomaly of the sternum, also known as the breastbone.
Epileptiform discharges identified at multiple locations temporarily in both hemispheres and temporarily in one hemisphere.
A compact, organized collection of mature mononuclear phagocytes, which may be but is not necessarily accompanied by accessory features such as necrosis.
An abnormal morphology of the middle phalanx of the fourth toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
An increase in the level of long-chain dicarboxylic acid in the urine.
Decreased width of the diaphysis of long bones.
Yellowish discoloration of the nails.
An abnormality of the pulmonary artery.
Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

Bigonial distance (lower facial width) more than 2 standard deviations below the mean (objective); or an apparently decreased width of the lower jaw (mandible) when viewed from the front (subjective).
Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of arteries affecting most or all arteries.
Short second metacarpal bone because of developmental hypoplasia.
Diagonal earlobe creases run from the lower pole of the external meatus, diagonally backwards to the edge of the lobe at approximately 45 degrees.
Underdevelopment of the malar prominence of the jugal bone (zygomatic bone in mammals), appreciated in profile, frontal view, and/or by palpation.
A decreased amount of alpha sarcoglycan in muscle. Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced alpha sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.
Acute otitis media is a short and generally painful infection of the middle ear.
Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in infancy.
A belief that is pathological and is held despite evidence to the contrary.
A morphological abnormality of epiphyses whereby they are abnormally outwardly curving (protuberant).
An increased concentration of hydroxyproline in the blood.

In contrast to forms of polydactyly where the supernumerary digit (this can either be a rudimentary or a completely 'normal' digit) is either located postaxial (on the ulnar side of the hand, next to the little finger), preaxial (on the radial side of the hand, next to the thumb) or mesoaxial (somewhere central, between thumb and little finger), a supernumerary digit may also be placed ectopically, meaning anywhere else except post-,meso- or preaxial. In the literature this is sometimes referred to as Disorganisation-like Syndrome (OMIM223200).
A type of epicanthus in which a medial vertical fold is present between upper and lower lids.

Vitreomacular traction is characterized by anomalous posterior vitreous detachment accompanied by anatomic distortion of the fovea, which may include pseudocysts, macular schisis, cystoid macular edema, and subretinal fluid. Vitreomacular traction can be subclassified by the diameter of vitreous attachment to the macular surface as measured by OCT, with attachment of 1500 micrometers or less defined as focal and attachment of more than 1500 micrometers as broad.
An abnormal narrowing of the urethral opening (meatus) of the penis.
A type of adenocarcinoma originating in the cervix and characterized by large cells with moderate to abundant clear cytoplasm.
The presence of clear, sharply defined vacuoles in the lymphocyte cytoplasm.
Deposition of calcium salts in gonadal tissue.
The speed at which disease manifestations appear and develop.
Conjunctival papillae with a diameter greater than 1 millimeter. They characteristically have flattened tops which sometimes demonstrate staining with fluorescein.
Oral aphthous ulcers typically present as painful, sharply circumscribed fibrin-covered mucosal defects with a hyperemic border.
Congenital absence of the toenail.
An intermittent (discontinuous) form of lactic acidemia.
A pinguecula is a yellowish to brown protruding lesion in the conjunctiva that is easily seen on the nasal and temporal sides of the cornea.
The occurrence of an immune reaction against the organism's own cells or tissues.
Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the cervical vertebral column.

A granulomatous inflammation leading to multiple granuloma formation, which is a specific type of inflammation. A granuloma is a focal compact collection of inflammatory cells, mononuclear cells predominating, usually as a result of the persistence of a non-degradable product and of active cell mediated hypersensitivity.

A deformity of the sella turcica whereby the sella extends further anterior than normal such that the anterior clinoid process appears to overhang it, giving the appearance of the letter J on imaging of the skull.
A general term for inflammation of the muscles without respect to the underlying cause.
An increased concentration of interleukin-6 in the circulation.

An elevation in the proportion of memory B cells (CD19+/CD27+) in circulation relative to the total number of B cells. Memory B cells develop from naive B cells. Upon antigen rechallenge, memory B cells rapidly expand and differentiate into plasma cells under the cognate control of memory Th cells (Phase IV).
A congenital defect characterized by absence of the Maxilla.

In this case the right ventricle is more muscular than normal, causing a characteristic boot-shaped (coeur-en-sabot) appearance as seen on anterior- posterior chest x-rays. Right ventricular hypertrophy is commonly associated with any form of right ventricular outflow obstruction or pulmonary hypertension, which may in turn owe its origin to left-sided disease. The echocardiographic signs are thickening of the anterior right ventricular wall and the septum. Cavity size is usually normal, or slightly enlarged. In many cases there is associated volume overload present due to tricuspid regurgitation, in the absence of this, septal motion is normal.
A severely increased count of eosinophils in the blood defined as a blood eosinophil count of 1.5  10e9/L or greater (one and a half billion cells per liter).
Reduced ability to detect any qualitative olfactory sensation.
Clefting affecting the humerus.
A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 4th finger of the hand.

A type of ataxia characterized by the inability to carry out movements with the correct range and motion across the plane of more than one joint related to incorrect estimation of the distances required for targeted movements.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against dairy.
A decreased concentration of free (unbound) carnitine in the blood.
Underdevelopment of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.
Significant reduction in both length and girth of the toe compared to the contralateral toe, or alternatively, compared to a typical toe size for an age-matched individual.
The presence of xanthomata in the skin of the eyelid.
?xrefs: UMLS:C4280601 UMLS:C0302314 SNOMEDCT_US:6400008 MSH:D014973 SNOMEDCT_US:75594004 UMLS:C0155210 SNOMEDCT_US:63103006 UMLS:C4280602

?def: In the orthopedic and radiological literature, sagittally cleft vertebra is generally known as a butterfly vertebra.
A type of hemolytic anemia in which the Coombs test is positive.
Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) affecting the musculature of the trunk.
Abnormally increased concentration of cortisol in the urine.
Lack of the cartilage of the nasal septum.
An anomaly in the amount or timing of melatonin secretion by the pineal gland. Note that melatonin is also synthesized by multiple tissues outside of the pineal gland.
Respiratory difficulty as newborn.
Congenital anomaly characterized by closure or failure to develop an opening in the urethra in males.
A foot deformity resulting due to an abnormality affecting the muscle and soft tissue. In contrast if the bones of the foot are affected the term structural foot deformity applies.
Persistence of the primary teeth beyond the age by which they normally are shed and replaced by the permanent teeth.
Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
Any functional anomaly of Langerhans cells, which are dendritic cells in the epidermis and some other locations. Langerhans cells play roles iin immune surveillance and homeostasis.

An anomaly of the suspensory ligament of lens, also known as the ciliary zonule. These ligaments represent a series of fibers connecting the ciliary body and lens of the eye, holding the lens in place.
Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disc is 0.9 (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).
An abnormality of the fifth finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
Lack of breathing with no movement of the respiratory muscles and no exchange of air in the lungs. This term refers to a disposition to have recurrent episodes of apnea rather than to a single event.
A ratio of serum triiodothyronine (T3) to thyroxine (T4) in the blood that deviates from normal.
The presence of a hernia in which the upper part of the stomach, i.e., mainly the gastric cardia protrudes through the diaphragmatic esophageal hiatus.
Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the middle phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.
Episodes of intense fear, screaming and flailing although affected individuals are still asleep.
Any deviation from the normal circulation of leucine in the blood circulation.
Hair growth from a single point on the scalp in any location other than lateral to the midline and close to the vertex of the skull.
An abnormality of the nasal tip.
Structural abnormality of the hippocampus related to defective development.

An abnormality of head shape characterized by the presence of a short, wide head as well as a pointy or conical form of the top of the head owing to premature closure of the coronal and lambdoid sutures.
An abnormality of the Diencephalon, which together with the cerebrum (telencephalon) makes up the forebrain.
Bleeding that persists longer than the normal time following a surgical procedure.
A type of brachydactyly characterized by brachymesophalangy affecting mainly the 2nd and 5th digits.
Cellular infiltrate confirmed by a cellular infiltrate comprised of mainly eosinophils in the gallbladder wall on histological examination.
Generalized degenerative changes of the fat tissue.
Atrophy of the cerebellum affecting primarily the Purkinje cell layer.
A type of microtropia with no manifest movement on cover test, the eccentric fixation point coinciding with the angle of ARC.
Abnormal concentration of 3-methylhistidine in the urine.
A type of monoclonal elevation of IgG in which the involved immunoglobulin has a normal structure with a light and heavy chain.
Prominence of a triangular soft tissue area of the philtrum with the apex to the columella.
A type of melanoma that starts as a raised area that is usually dark blackish-blue or bluish-red but may not have any color.
A sudden sensation of feeling cold.
An abnormality of a buccal fat pad.
Unprovoked explosive pathological sneezing.
Structural abnormality of the hypothalamus related to defective development.
Decreased concentration of neopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
A primitive neuroectodermal neoplasm that occurs in the central nervous system.
An accessory (not normally present) muscle bundle in the right ventricle which obstructs the right ventricular outflow tract.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by menstruation in a female.
Congenital defect characterized by underdevelopment of the tricuspid valve.
Decreased activity of coagulation factor IX. Factor IX, which itself is activated by factor Xa or factor VIIa to form factor IXa, activates factor X into factor Xa.
A fungal infection of the toenails or fingernails that tends to cause the nails to thicken, discolor, disfigure, and split.
An abnormally increased degree of bleeding following a superfical injury to the surface of the skin.

An abnormality of swallowing characterized by reduced tongue coordination to form bolus after chewing. Food material spreads over the oral cavity instead of being concentrated into a bolus that is easily swallowed.
Abnormally increased formation of dense trabecular bone tissue. Despite the increased density of bone tissue, osteopetrotic bones tend to be more fracture-prone than normal.
Abnormal calcification of the mitral valve.
An elevation in bone density in one or more carpal bones of the hand.
A form of triphalangeal thumb that can be placed opposite the fingers of the same hand.
An increased amount of arginine levels in the blood.

A localized dilation of microvasculature formed due to disruption of the internal elastic lamina of a retinal capillary blood vessel. The lesions present as small circular, red dots having distinct margins and are no larger than a blood vessel width at the disk margin. This expansion disturbs the normal flow pattern, changing shear force and pressure along the vessel. Shear force plays a key role in promoting the differentiation and proliferation of endothelial cells.
Any abnormality affecting the cortex of the humerus.
An abnormality of morphology of the incisor tooth.
An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in a cerebral artery.
The presence of an excessive amount of fluid in the pleural cavity.
An incomitant tendency for an occluded eye to elevate and extort which resolves on uncovering.

Any noninflammatory disease of the retina. This nonspecific term is retained here because of its wide use in the literature, but if possible new annotations should indicate the precise type of retinal abnormality.
The presence of normal overall immunoglobulin levels with deficiency of specific immunoglobulins directed against a specific antigen or microorganism.
An abnormal susceptibility to bleeding, often referred to as a bleeding diathesis. A bleeding diathesis may be related to vascular, platelet and coagulation defects.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the gastrointestinal tract.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.
Lack of sharpness of vision resulting in the inability to see fine detail.
Decreased occipito-frontal (head) circumference (OFC). For the microcephaly OFC must be between -3 SD and -2 SD compared to appropriate, age matched, normal standards (i.e. -3 SD <= OFC < -2 SD).

Junctional ectopic tachycardia (JET) is a unique type of supraventricular arrhythmia defined by narrow QRS complex and atrioventricular (AV) dissociation or retrograde atrial conduction in a 1:1 pattern.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the pelvis.
A congenital defect with failure to open of the mitral valve orifice.

?def: The distal interphalangeal joint of the 3rd toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.
An abnormal build up of iron (Fe) in brain tissue.
Gallstones composed primarily of cholesterol, usually about 2-3 cm in length with an oval form and a yellow or green/brown color.
An anomalous amount of protein present in or on the surface of muscle fibers. This feature may be appreciate upon immunohistochemical investigation of muscle biopsy tissue.
Bony swelling of the proximal interphalangeal joint (PIP) associated with the formation of osteophytes (calcific spurs) of the articular (joint) cartilage that are visible radiographically.
A subtype of ductal pancreatic carcinoma that is thought to originate from squamous metaplasia of pancreatic ductal epithelium.
Inflammation and fibrosis of the bronchioles leading to partial or complete obstruction of these airways.

A type of acelluar casts that have a surface composed of granules, which can vary in size. The granules can be rather heterogeneous, ranging from fine (finely granular cast) up to coarse (coarsely granular cast), dark, clear, and pigmented.
Leg shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the lower extremity.
Increased cytoplasmic staining of fibroblasts with toluidine blue.
An decrease in the level of triglycerides in the blood.
A type of anemia characterized by increased size of erythrocytes with increased mean corpuscular volume (MCV) and increased mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH).
Decreased activity of complex II Of the mitochondrion in the liver.
The contour of the foot in lateral profile has a convex shape.
Bony defects situated along the cranial suture lines or at the junction of the bone plates of the skull.
Irregular surface of the normally relatively smooth border between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum.
A rare subtype of acute myeloid leukemia evolving from primitive megakaryoblasts.
An abnormally increased activity of the renin-angiotensin system, causing hypertension by a combination of volume excess and vasoconstrictor mechanisms.
The presence of non-malignant hyperplasia of the prostate.

Cholangitis characterized by the accumulation of granulomas. Granulomas are aggregates of modified macrophages (epithelioid cells) and other inflammatory cells that accumulate after chronic exposure to antigens. The underlying trigger may be exposure to noxious agents that cannot be biochemically degraded or to immune dysfunction. The ultimate result is a release of a variety cytokines that stimulate mononuclear cells that fuse to form multinucleated giant cells with a surrounding rim of lymphocytes and fibroblasts.
A structural abnormality of the thyroid gland.
Decrease of these levels result in increased inhibition of fibrinolysis and reduced inhibition of coagulation
Esotropia in a patient who has previously had exotropia or exophoria; may be constant or intermittent. and usually follows surgical overcorrection.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger.

The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against P450 2D6, a cytochrome P450 mono-oxygenase. Anti-LKM-1 antibodies are considered to be a diagnostic marker of autoimmune hepatitis type 2 (AIH2).
The presence of renal tubules with thick redundant basement membranes, or a reduction of greater than 50% in tubular diameter compared to surrounding non-atrophic tubules.
Branching of the umbilical cord before its insertion into the placenta.

Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at each end of a long bone, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.
A type of sacrococcygeal teratoma that is predominantly external but has a large intrapelvic component.
Persistence of the embryonic dorsal or sciatic vein system that normally should have involuted around the tenth to twelfth week of intrauterine life.
Proximal femoral focal deficiency is a deformity manifested by hypoplasia of a variable portion of the femur with shortening of the entire limb.
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger.
A form of ventricular preexcitation due to the presence of multiple accessory pathways for cardiac conduction.
An abnormality of the styloglossus muscle.
Any structural anomaly of the tongue.
An uncontrolled autonomous cell-proliferation originating in a hair follicle, which is an epidermal adnexal structures responsible for hair growth.
An abnormal shape of the frontal part of the head.
Non-continuity of the arch of aorta with an atretic point or absent segment.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by a sudden movement.
Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the 2nd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
Qualitatively abnormal fibrinogen.
A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the Y chromosome.
An increased amount of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) in the subarachnoid space.
Recurrent or persistent superficial Candida infections of the skin, mucous membranes, and nails.
An abnormality detectable by sonography of the heart (echocardiography).
Protrusion of the rectal mucous membrane through the anus.
High urine magnesium in the presence of hypomagnesemia.
A group of abnormalities characterized by hyperglycemia and glucose intolerance.
An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which the morphology of both left and right lungs is the same.
A severe form of gait ataxia such that an affected person cannot walk at all.
Downward movement of the trachea during inspiration due to downward traction on the tracheobronchial tree.
An abnormal morphology (form) of the midface or its components, the cheeks, maxilla, zygomatic bone, malar region, and infraorbital rims.
An abnormal increase in the amount of intramuscular fat tissue.
Hypoglycermia following a meal (or more generally, after intake of glucose).

An epiphysis that curves around from its transverse orientation to a longitudinal one from proximal to distal along one side of the phalanx, thus resembling the letter 'C' and forming a bracket around the diaphysis. This results in a so called delta phalanx characterized by a triangular or trapezoidal shaped bone with a C-shaped epiphyseal plate.
An abnormally decreased proportion of CD4-negative, CD8-negative (double negative or DN) alpha-beta regulatory T cells (Tregs) as compared to total number of T cells.
Increased length of the ulna.
The intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent storage material.
The presence of a neoplasm of the urinary bladder.
Underdevelopment of the dilatator pupillae.
Any abnormality of the primary tooth.
A gestational or non-gestational neoplasm composed of neoplastic trophoblastic cells [NCIT:C3422].
A tendency to tilt the head towards the left shoulder to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.
Developmental dysplasia of the hair.
Abnormal shape of one or more phalanges of the thumb such that affected phalanges resemble a triangle.
A reduction below normal limits of the ratio of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) albumin concentration to serum albumin concentration.

Polypoidal masses arising mainly from the mucous membranes of the nose and paranasal sinuses. They are freely movable and nontender overgrowths of the mucosa that frequently accompany allergic rhinitis.
An abnormality of phosphate homeostasis or concentration in the body.
A larger than normal amount or percentage of hematopoietic cells relative to marrow fat.
The presence of a paralyzed diaphragm.
An abnormality of the renal tubules.
A loss of consciousness followed by stiffening and brief clonic movements affecting some or all limbs, often misinterpreted as an epileptic seizure.
A type of retinal neovascularization that affects the posterior pole of the retina.
Any structural anomaly of the muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the left ventricle of the heart (cardiac trabeculae, trabeculae carneae).
An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin, or in one or more cavities of the body because of decreased osmotic pressure of plasma (hypoproteinemia).
Absence or underdevelopment of the anterior pituitary gland, also known as the adenohypophysis.
White discoloration of the nails.
An increased concentration of valine in the blood.
A tendency to hold the chin depressed (lowered) to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.

A demarcated, largely intraventricular tumor in the region of the foramen of Monro composed of spindle to large plump or ganglion-like cells with eosinophilic to amphophilic cytoplasm and somewhat pleomorphic nuclei with occasional prominent nucleoli. These tumors are almost always associated with tuberous sclerosis.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the jejunum.
A form of watery eye associated with obstruction of the nasolacrimal system. This may arise at the level of the punctum, the canaliculi, the sac or the nasolacrimal duct.
Abnormality of the vestibulocochlear nerve, the eighth cranial nerve, which is involved in transmitting sound and equilibrium information from the inner ear to the brain.
A dilatation (balooning or bulging out of the vessel wall) of a carotid artery.
Spasticity of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve.

Eosinophilic infiltration of one or more gastrointestinal organs. Gastrointestinal eosinophilia is a broad term for abnormal eosinophil accumulation in the GI tract, involving many different disease identities. These diseases include primary eosinophil associated gastrointestinal diseases, gastrointestinal eosinophilia in HES and all gastrointestinal eosinophilic states associated with known causes. Each of these diseases has its unique features but there is no absolute boundary between them.
An abnormality of Sharpey's fibers (bone fibers, or perforating fibers), which are a matrix of connective tissue consisting of bundles of strong collagenous fibres connecting periosteum to bone.
An increase in the level of galactitol in the plasma.
Increased width of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
An increase in the amount of intravascular fluid, particularly in the volume of the circulating blood.
A lack of intestinal ganglion cells (i.e., an aganglionic section of bowel) affecting the duodenum.
Bilateral clubfoot deformity (see HP:0001762).
Increased size of the parotid gland.

An abnormally increased rate of skeletal maturation. Accelerated skeletal maturation can be diagnosed on the basis of an estimation of the bone age from radiographs of specific bones in the human body.

Longstanding impairment in ventilation such that the partial pressure of carbon dioxide (PaCO2) is elevated above the upper limit of the reference range (more than 45 mm Hg), with a normal or near-normal pH secondary to renal compensation and an elevated serum bicarbonate levels (more than30 mEq/L).

Subcortical heterotopia extending along the mesial aspect of the lateral ventricles, with direct connection to mesial polymicrogyria-like cortex at the anterior and posterior limits of the heterotopia.

An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate with a low signal on T1-weighted sequences and high signal on T2-weighted sequences. Modic type I changes are thought to represent bone marrow edema and inflammation.
A neoplasm affecting the spinal cord.
A bending or abnormal curvature of the tibia.
An abnormality of the External acoustic tube (also known as the auditory canal).
A small reduction in the fraction of blood pumped from the left ventricle with each cardiac cycle. The normal range in adults is at least 55 percent, and a mild reduction is defined as 45-54 percent.
Uneven radiographic opacity of the one or more epiphyses of the thumb.
A muscular ventricular septal defect located at the apex of the heart.
Obesity with a body mass index of 30 to 34.9 kg per square meter.

A type of T-cell lymphoma that is characterized by so-called hallmark cells with a pleomorphic appearance that express the CD30 antigen, are lobulated, and have indented nuclei. These so-called hallmark cells have lobulated and indented nuclei.

A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.
A type of congenital cataract in which the opacity follows the anterior or posterior Y suture.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of citrulline in the blood circulation.
Sharply demarcated hyperpigmentation which is congenital.
A decreased amount of enamel mineralization.
A nodular pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography that has an apparently random pattern.
An abnormal structure or form of the joints, i.e., one or more of the articulations where two bones join.
A state of respiratory distress that requires a life saving intervention in the form of gaining airway access and instituting positive pressure ventilation.
Excessive vomiting in early pregnancy, leading to the loss of 5% or more of body weight.
This term applies if one or more of the phalanges of the hand are either partially duplicated, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance of the phalanges, or completely duplicated.
Decreased height of the intervertebral disk.
A loss of the ability to move the vocal fold on one side.
A vascular malformation located in the lip that is characterized by\nectatic papillary dermal capillaries and postcapillary venules in the upper reticular dermis.
An abnormal motion of a segment of the left ventricle during the cardiac cycle.
An abnormality of the hair.

A swan neck deformity describes a finger with a hyperextended PIP joint and a flexed DIP joint. The most common cause for a swan neck-like deformity is a disruption of the end of the extensor tendon. Conditions that loosen the PIP joint and allow it to hyperextend, for example conditions that weaken the volar plate, can produce a swan neck deformity of the finger. One example is rheumatoid arthritis. Another cause are conditions that tighten up the small (intrinsic) muscles of the hand and fingers, for example hand trauma or nerve disorders, such as cerebral palsy, Parkinson's disease, or stroke.
Hair that is disorderly, stands out from the scalp, and cannot be combed flat.
Abnormal acid accumulation or depletion of base.
Defective development of the vermis of cerebellum.
The absence of all phalanges of all the digits of a limb and the associated soft tissues.
An abnormality of the concentration of hydrogencarbonate in the urine.
An abnormality of morphology of the incisor tooth in which the tooth is shaped like a screwdriver blade, i.e., having a rhomboid shape.
Paroxysmal chest pain that occurs with exertion or stress and is related to myocardial ischemia.
An obstruction in the veins of the liver caused by a blood clot (thrombosis).
A type of chromosomal aberration characterised by reduced resistance of chromosomes to change or deterioration.
An abnormally increased concentration of transferrin in the blood circulation.
An abnormality of the function of the inner ear.
Reduced ability of the cornea to respond to stimulation.
Anterior vaginal wall prolapse with bulging of the bladder into the vagina.
A reduction below the normal proportion of plasmablasts in circulation relative to total number of B cells.
An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the aortic root.
Accumulation of blood located beneath the neurosensory retina in the space between the neurosensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.
Muscular dystrophy affecting the muscles of the limb girdle (the hips and shoulders).
An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in a dried blood spot.

Complete lack of memory B cells, that is, of mature B cell type that is long-lived, readily activated upon re-encounter of its antigenic determinant, and has been selected for expression of higher affinity immunoglobulin.
The enteric villi are atrophic or absent.

?def: Any abnormality of the clavicles (collar bones).
A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration in the legs.
Abnormally prominent ear helix.
Cleft palate is a developmental defect of the palate resulting from a failure of fusion of the palatine processes and manifesting as a separation of the roof of the mouth (soft and hard palate).
