An increased count of granulocytes in the peripheral blood circulation.
Increased length of the big toe.
An abnormal conical form of the teeth, that is, a tooth whose sides converge or taper together incisally.
Absence of the Premaxilla, which is the embryonic structure that forms the anterior part of the maxilla.
The presence of xanthine-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

Chorea (Greek for 'dance') refers to widespread arrhythmic involuntary movements of a forcible, jerky and restless fashion. It is a random-appearing sequence of one or more discrete involuntary movements or movement fragments. Movements appear random because of variability in timing, duration or location. Each movement may have a distinct start and end. However, movements may be strung together and thus may appear to flow randomly from one muscle group to another. Chorea can involve the trunk, neck, face, tongue, and extremities.
Scrotum in a position other than the usual position inferior to the base of the penis.
Osteomyelitis caused by infection with the bacteria, salmonella.
Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.
Any abnormality of the thorax (the region of the body formed by the sternum, the thoracic vertebrae and the ribs).

Increased width of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.
Premature synostosis of only one lambdoid suture.
Any abnormality of the masticatory muscle.
A type of gait ataxia displaying progression of clinical severity.
Retinopathy which extends from the center of the optic disc to twice the distance from the center of the optic disc to the center of the macula.
An abnormality of an anterior ethmoidal artery.
An anomaly of the calf bone (fibula), one of the two bones of the calf.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the face.
An abnormality of the Ala of nose.

Malignant mesothelioma is a form of cancer that originates from the cells of the mesothelium, a thin tissue layer surrounding the body's internal organs. Malignant mesothelioma is almost exclusively caused by asbestos exposure, pleural mesothelioma beeing the most common form, affecting the lining of the lungs called the pleura. Other forms such as perioneal-, percardial- or testicular- mesothelioma are much rarer.
An abnormal reduction of the anterioposterior diameter of the vertebral body.
Affecting all regions without specificity of distribution.
An abnormality characterized by disruption of the normal functioning of peripheral axons.
An elevated concentration of glucagon in the blood circulation.
Slowed relaxation of muscles in the leg.
Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the 5th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
A reduction of skin color related to a decrease in melanin production and deposition.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:18655006 MSH:D017496 UMLS:C0162835 SNOMEDCT_US:23006000 SNOMEDCT_US:89031001 SNOMEDCT_US:201284005

?def: The ability of the interphalangeal joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the stomach.
Absence of a fingernail.
Absence or underdevelopment of the eyebrow.
A tumor formed from the endocrine (argentaffin) cells of the mucosal lining of a variety of organs including the stomach and intestine. These cells are from neuroectodermal origin.
Esotropia in which either eye may be used for fixation.
Occipitofrontal (head) circumference greater than 97th centile compared to appropriate, age matched, sex-matched normal standards. Alternatively, a apparently increased size of the cranium.
Bleeding in the anterior chamber of the eye.
Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the proximal phalanx of the second finger.

A systemic disease which can present with cutaneous lesions with or without internal involvement. Tumors are caused by Human herpesvirus 8 (HHV8), also known as Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus (KSHV).
A higher than normal levels of the fatty acids which can occur in plasma as a result of lipolysis in adipose tissue or when plasma triacyglycerols are taken into tissues.
An increased amount of desmosine measure in the skin. Desmosine is a cross-linking amino acid formed from lysyl residues in elastin.
The presence of an embryonal neoplasm of the kidney that primarily affects children.
An abnormal connection between the gut and another hollow organ, such as the bladder, urethra, vagina, or other regions of the gastrointestinal tract.
Bursts of large-amplitude multidirectional saccades without intersaccadic interval
Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms.
Lack of skin pigmentation (coloring) of the anterior chest.
Abnormal increase in density of the tissue at the costochondral junctions.
Abnormally increased variability of the size of the vertebral bodies.
An increase in the number of spontaneous sister chromatid exchanges observed in cell culture of lymphocytes or other cells.
Any deviation from the normal quantity of secretion of nasal mucus, a thick viscous liquid produced by the mucous membranes of the nose.
A partial failure of the development of the corpus callosum.
Pain in and around the anus or rectum (perianal region).
A type of hydrops fetalis in which there is no identifiable circulating antibody to red blood cell antigens .
A lack of restraint manifested in several ways, including disregard for social conventions, impulsivity, and poor risk assessment.
An abnormality of the humoral immune system, which comprises antibodies produced by B cells as well as the complement system.
An abnormality of a levator anguli oris.
An abnormality of the appendicular skeletal system, consisting of the of the limbs, shoulder and pelvic girdles.
A renal tumor originating from an oncocyte, which is an epithelial cell characterized by an excessive amount of mitochondria, resulting in an abundant acidophilic, granular cytoplasm.

A developmental disorder of the lacrimal drainage system that most often affects the lacrimal ostium and resulting in non-opening of the nasolacrimal duct. It usually results from a non-canalization of the nasolacrimal duct.
A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the X chromosome.
Chronic loss of joint motion of the interphalangeal joint of the thumb due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. This joint is also called Articulatio interphalangealis pollicis.
Accumulation of abnormal amounts of pigment within the trabecular meshwork.
An abnormality of the hematopoietic system.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:34093004 SNOMEDCT_US:191124002 UMLS:C4020864 UMLS:C0018939 UMLS:C0850715 MSH:D006402

?def: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of the retinal arterioles.
Abnormal concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Shortening of the middle parts of the leg in relation to the upper and terminal segments.
The presence of a carcinoma in the renal pelvis.
Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located near the surface of the skin in a butterfly midface distribution.
The presence of many cysts in the medulla of the kidney.
Absence or underdevelopment of the nasal bone.
Tractional retinal detachment at the periphery of the retina.
Abnormal blood test results measuring creatine kinase (CK), CK-MB, troponin (TROPI), myoglobin, and/or cardiac enzymes.
Wasting (atrophy) of the vermis of cerebellum.
A deviation from the normal count of alpha granules per thrombocyte.
Abnormally decreased levels of tyrosine in cerebrospinal fluid.
A forehead with abnormal flatness.
The presence of an antibody in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that is directed against the organism's own cells or tissues.
An increased concentration of magnesium the urine.
Abnormal concentration of urate in the urine.
Increased top to bottom height of vertebral bodies.
An abnormal purple color of the urine.
An abnormal conformation of the femur that becomes gradually enlarged towards the proximal end. This feature affects the proximal femoral metaphysis and epiphysis.
A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more toe phalanges.
A developmental abnormality characterized by the absence (aplasia) of a metatarsal bone.
Absent 2nd (index) finger.
A type of undifferentiated germ cell tumor that may be benign or malignant.
Increased concentration of uracil in the urine.
A type of choroidal neovascularization in which the nearest edge of the area of neovascularization is located 200 to 1500 micrometers from the center of the fovea.
Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the vagina.
The presence of fewer than normal sweat glands.
Increased degradation of fibrin, associated with clot instability and bleeding
Constipation of sudden onset and lasting for less than three months.

Progressive PR interval prolongation with the subsequent occurrence of a single nonconducted P wave that results in a pause. The pause that follows the nonconducted impulse is less than fully compensatory (less than the sum of two normal sinus intervals).
Atrophy of the extensor digitorum longus muscles, which mediate extension of the toes.
Any abnormality of the shoulder muscles.
A form of lactic acidemia that occurs following exercise or exertion.
Severe loss of visual acuity within hours or days. This is characteristic of Leber hereditary optic neuropathy.
A hamartoma (disordered proliferation of mature tissues) of the conjunctiva.
Multiple pupils.
Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.
A bifid rib refers to cleavage of the sternal end of a rib, usually unilateral. Bifid ribs are usually asymptomatic, and are often discovered incidentally by chest x-ray.
Decreased cell membrane concentration of glycoprotein IIb-IIIa.
Partial duplication of middle phalanx of third toe.
A structural anomaly of the mucous lining of the small intestine.
Reduced length of the clavicles.
An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on the back of the hands.
An increased concentration of dopamine in the urine.
An abnormality of a genioglossus muscle.

This term applies if one or more of the phalanges of the 2nd finger are either partially duplicated, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance of the phalanges, or completely duplicated.
Absence of the clavicles as a developmental defect.
Any abnormality of the large intestine.

Ring fibers are formed by a bundle of peripheral myofibrils which are circumferentially oriented such that they encircle the internal portion of the sarcoplasm which is normal in structure and orientation.
Abnormal decrease in diastolic blood pressure.
Bilateral temporal scarlike defects, which are said to resemble forceps marks.
An increased concentration of glutaric acid in the urine.

The condition in which both atria are joined to the left ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. Usually there is a hypoplastic right ventricle, which may be on the opposite side of the heart as usual.
Pterygium affecting the elbow. This is a cutaneous web that can lead to severe flexion contracture of the elbow joint. Antecubital pterygium can be unilateral, bilateral, symmetric, or asysmmetric.
Absence of the epiglottis.

This term applies if one or more of the proximal phalanges of the hand are either partially duplicated, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance of the phalanges, or completely duplicated.
A form of vitreoretinopathy characterized by thinning (erosion) of the retinal pigment epithelium that permits increased visualization of the choroidal vessels.
An increase in circulating IgA characterized by one predominant band in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase in circulating immunoglobulins.
Abnormality of left ventricular contraction, often defined operationally as an ejection fraction of less than 40 percent.
A form of inflammation of the kidney affecting the interstitium of the kidneys surrounding the tubules.
Any abnormality of the distal epiphysis of the radius.
Motor hyperactivity with excessive movement of muscles of the body as a whole.
?xrefs: MSH:D006948 SNOMEDCT_US:45352006 SNOMEDCT_US:44548000 UMLS:C0037763 UMLS:C0424295 MSH:D013035

?def: Underdevelopment of the femoral head.
Delayed myelination in the central nervous system.

A congenital anomaly with partitioning of the right atrium to form a triatrial heart caused by persistence of the right valve of the sinus venosus. Typically, the right atrial partition is due to exaggerated fetal eustachian and thebesian valves, which together form an incomplete septum across the lower part of the atrium. This septum may range from a reticulum to a substantial sheet of tissue.
Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 4th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
An abnormality of glycoprotein metabolism related to a decreased rate of alpha-1,6-mannosylglycoprotein 2-beta-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase activity.
Partial or complete wasting (loss) of the pituitary gland.

Short distance from the end of the finger to the most distal interphalangeal crease or the distal interphalangeal joint flexion point. That is, hypoplasia of one or more of the distal phalanx of finger.
Distance between medial and lateral canthi is more than two standard deviations above the mean for age (objective); or, apparently increased length of the palpebral fissures.
Increased time between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).

Exotropia (intermittent or constant) worse for distance fixation in which the near angle of deviation increases (or near exophoria becomes exotropia) with: (1) prolonged disruption of fusion and/or (2) elimination of accommodation.
Amniotic constriction rings affecting the legs.
Blockage of the lacrimal duct.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:231841004 SNOMEDCT_US:314022009 SNOMEDCT_US:416920000 UMLS:C0022906 UMLS:C1281931 SNOMEDCT_US:246865000 MSH:D007767

?def: A type of tubercular infection located outside of the lung, which is the most common location of tuberculosis. There are two types of clinical manifestation of tuberculosis (TB) are pulmonary TB (PTB) and extrapulmonary TB (EPTB). The former is most common. EPTB refers to TB involving organs other than the lungs (e.g., pleura, lymph nodes, abdomen, genitourinary tract, skin, joints and bones, or meninges). A patient with both pulmonary and EPTB is classified as a case of PTB.
A form of acute leukemia characterized by excess lympoblasts.
Increased thickness (diameter) of ribs.
A form of chronic pancreatitis that is characterized by calcification.
Abnormal rhythm of the heart.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.
Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) affecting the musculature of the trunk and with onset in infancy.

Normally, the aortic valve closure (A2) is followed by the pulmonic valve closure (P2) but the A2-P2 interval increases with inspiration and decreases with expiration. With paradoxical splitting, there is a delay in the closure of the aortic valve, so that A2 can follow P2; the individual components can be appreciated at the end of expiration and the interval narrows with inspiration (which is the oposite of the normal pattern).
Reduction of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction.
Increased susceptibility to upper and lower respiratory tract infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of upper and lower respiratory tract infections.
Abnormally increased levels of arginine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Overgrowth of the outer labia.
Increased concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.

The kneecap normally is located within the groove termed trochlea on the distal femur and can slide up and down in it. Patellar subluxation refers to an unstable kneecap that does not slide centrally within its groove, i.e., a partial dislocation of the patella.
Underdevelopment of the nasopharyngeal adenoids.
An abnormality of the intestine in which part of the intestine invaginates (telescopes) into another part of the intestine.
An increased concentration of lysine in the urine.
An abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the fifth toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
A discrete abnormal tissue mass that protrudes into the lumen of the intestine and is attached to the intestinal wall either by a stalk, pedunculus, or a broad base.
A sensation of breathlessness in the recumbent position, relieved by sitting or standing.
An abnormality of the pia mater.
Ossification affecting the external ear cartilage.
Underdevelopment of the optic nerve and absence of the septum pellucidum.
Tumor of the lung.
The middle phalanx of finger resembles a thimble, a small metal cap to protect the finger while sewing that has a broad (proximal) base and narrower top, whereby both base and top are flat.
A form of anterior segment dysgenesis in which abnormal cleavage of the anterior chamber occurs. Peters anomaly is characterized by central, paracentral, or complete corneal opacity.
A chronic form of gastritis.

Oral melanoacanthoma usually presents as an asymptomatic, ill-defined, rapidly enlarging, macular pigmentation. Although most lesions are heavily pigmented, the coloration may or may not be uniform. Any mucosal site may be affected, but buccal mucosal involvement is most common. Although typically solitary, rare patients may present with multifocal lesions.
The presence of stenosis of the renal artery.
A subjective feeling that an experience which is occurring for the first time has been experienced before.
Ab abnormal appearance of hair under polarizing microscopy (using crossed polarizers), whereby hair shafts show striking alternating bright and dark bands, often referred to as tiger tail banding.
Diffuse unlocalised atrophy affecting the cerebrum.

Atherosclerosis which occurs in a person with certain risk factors (e.g., SLE, diabetes, smoking, hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, family history of early heart disease) at an earlier age than would occur in another person without those risk factors.
A chronic form of pancreatitis.
Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of bones of the axial skeleton.
Loss of previously present mental and motor abilities.
The presence of excessive redundant myelin in the peripheral nerve sheath.

An abnormal concentration of an HDL subfraction, which can be determined by methods such as electrophoresis followed by densitometric determination of the areas under the peaks. Large HDL subfractions are defined as HDL1 (greater than 12 nm), HDL2b (9.7-12 nm), and HDL2a (8.8-9.69 nm). Small HDL subfractions are defined as HDL3a (8.2-8.79 nm), HDL3b (7.8-8.19 nm), and HDL3c (7.20-7.79 nm).
A neoplasm arising in the neuroectoderm, the portion of the ectoderm of the early embryo that gives rise to the central and peripheral nervous systems, including some glial cells.
Prolonged or protracted bleeding following an invasive procedure or intervention.
Erythematous, poikilodermatous macules distributed in a V-shaped distribution over the anterior neck and chest.
An abnormal level of an analyte measured in the blood.

An abnormal echotexture visible in liver ultrasound manifesting as a diffuse hyperechoic liver echotexture with multiple, small hypoechoic lesions. The appearance is said to resemble a starry sky (multiple white spots on a dark background).
An abnormally increased level of immunoglobulin M in blood.
Abnormal (non-physiological) constriction of the pupil of congenital onset.
A type of tremors that is triggered by holding a limb in a fixed position.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.

Pulmonary vasodilator testing is performed during right-heart catheterization and involves a short-acting vasoactive agent such as adenosine, epoprostenol, or inhaled nitric oxide. The current definition of a normal (positive) response is a drop in mean pulmonary artery pressure of at least 10 mm Hg (or 20 percent) to below 40 mm Hg.
An abnormal connection (fistula) between the esophagus and the trachea.
Complete duplication of the distal phalanx of little toe.

A form of watery eye associated with abnormal lid tone and/or lid position. The former is due to lid laxity (common involutional change in the elderly) or a weak orbicularis muscle (e.g. due to VII cranial nerve palsy). The latter is typically associated with ectropion causing punctal eversion.
An abnormally elevated proportion of memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood.

A malignant lymphocytic neoplasm of B-cell or T-cell lineage involving primarily the bone marrow and the peripheral blood. This category includes precursor or acute lymphoblastic leukemias and chronic leukemias.
A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short limbs but an average-sized trunk.
Formation of excess connective tissue in the testicle.
Inflammation of blood vessel.
Reduced strength of the musculature of the hand.
A form of macular degeneration characterized by the presence of multiple cysts in the macula.
Triangular shaped middle phalanx of the 3rd (middle) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.
An abnormality of an ethmoid sinus.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against parasites.
An abnormal increase in the volume of cardiac myocytes.
An increased concentration of glycolate in the urine.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the rectum.

Reduced activity of coagulation factor VIII. Factor VIII (fVIII) is a cofactor in the intrinsic clotting cascade that is activated to fVIIIa in the presence of minute quantities of thrombin. fVIIIa acts as a receptor, for factors IXa and X.
A bony projection (spur, osteophyte) originating from the tibia.
Thin (atrophic) and wide scars.
Partial duplication of middle phalanx of fourth toe.
The presence of an increased degree of wrinkling (irregular folds and indentations) of the skin as compared with age-related norms.

In contrast to the metacarpals 2-5, the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5 (whereas the proximal phalanx of the thumb is equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits). The epiphysis of the first metacarpal is localized at the proximal end (as seen in the proximal phalanges of the other digits), whereas the epiphyses of the other metacarpal bones are located at the distal end. This term applies if the epiphysis of the 1st metacarpal is in any way abnormal, referring to age and gender depending norms, as seen on x-rays.
Breast carcinoma that is bilateral or otherwise multifocal.

A reduction compared to the predicted value of the forced expiratory flow over the middle one-half of the FVC; the average flow from the point at which 25% of the FVC has been exhaled to the point at which 75% of the FVC has been exhaled. Here, the test is performed before the administration of a bronchodilating medication.

Exposure of pregnant women to toxins from any source, such as environmental toxins or chemicals, that may potentially cause problems such as miscarriage, preterm delivery, low birth weight, and, in some cases, developmental delays in infants.
Absence of hair in the anterior midline and/or parietal areas.
Over curvature of the lumbar region.
Defective structure and function of myelin sheaths. Dysmyelination is distinguished from demyleination where there is destruction or damage of previously normal myelination.
Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements, in which the movement in one direction is faster than in the other.
An abnormally increased extension of the knee joint, so that the knee can bend backwards.
Nail that appears thick when viewed on end.
The presence of a supernumerary, i.e., extra, maxillary incisor, either the primary maxillary incisor or the permanent maxillary incisor.
Slowed relaxation of muscles in the arm.
Overconstriction, or narrowness of the diaphysis and metaphysis of long bones.

Cholesteatoma is a benign but potentially destructive growth consisting of keratinizing epithelium located in the middle ear and/or mastoid process. In cholesteatoma, a skin cyst grows into the middle ear and mastoid. The cyst is not cancerous but can erode tissue and cause destruction of the ear.
An abnormal increase in the length of the tibia.
A delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more vertebrae.

An increased concentration of circulating alpha polypeptide of glycoprotein hormones (Entrez Gene 1081). This alpha subunit is common to luteinizing hormone (LH) , follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) , thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) and human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG), which are glycoprotein hormones composed of an identical alpha subunit together with a beta subunit that confers biological specificity. The alpha subunit is used as a marker for tumors that produce these hormones.
An abnormal morphology of one or more distal phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
Rotated position of the glans, with or without the penile shaft, of 30 degrees or more.

A papule (circumscribed, solid elevation of skin with no visible fluid, varying in size from a pinhead to less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point) that exhibits increased pigmentation (is darker) compared to the surrounding skin.
Increased width (breadth) of metaphyses of the arms.
Telangiectases in the area of the nails.
Abnormally increased density of craniofacial bone tissue.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the jaw.
Increased focal pigmentation of the vermilion of the lips.
Increased width of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers two to five.

A short femur length is defined as either a measurement below the 2.5th percentile for gestational age or a measurement that is less than 0.9 of that predicted by the measured biparietal diameter. The femur should be measured with the bone perpendicular to the ultrasound beam and with epiphyseal cartilages visible but not included in the measurement (pmid:16100637).
Excess facial hair.
Pain during menstruation that interferes with daily activities.
The presence of small, white vitreous opacities consisting of calcium phosphate and complex, layered lipid deposits.
Multifocal atrial tachycardia is a rare supraventricular arrhythmia in neonates and young infants that is characterized by multiple P waves with varying P wave morphology and is usually asymptomatic.

Polyp-like protrusions which are histologically hamartomas. These can occur throughout the gastrointestinal tract. Hamartomatous polyps are composed of the normal cellular elements of the gastrointestinal tract, but have a markedly distorted architecture.
A periodic beat-to-beat variation in the amplitude or shape of the T wave in an EKG.
Decreased catalysis of the reaction: 2 superoxide + 2 H+ = O2 + hydrogen peroxide.
Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.
Lack of detectible CD8-positive T cells
A malignant epithelial tumor with a glandular organization that originates in the large intestine.

A loss of global cognitive ability of sufficient amount to interfere with normal social or occupational function. Dementia represents a loss of previously present cognitive abilities, generally in adults, and can affect memory, thinking, language, judgment, and behavior.
Presence of struvite (magnesium ammonium phosphate) containing calculi (kidney stones).
An abnormality of myeloid leukocytes.
A deviation from the normal straight form of the proximal phalanx of the fifth toe.
Immunohistochemistry shows complete lack of beta sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.
The presence of remnants of a fetal membrane that persist as strands of tissue crossing the pupil.
An anomaly of the structure of mitochondria within cardiomyocytes.

The essence of the lesion is the combination of discordant atrioventricular and ventriculo-arterial connections. Thus, the morphologically right atrium is connected to a morphologically left ventricle across the mitral valve, with the left ventricle then connected to the pulmonary trunk. The morphologically left atrium is connected to the morphologically right ventricle across the tricuspid valve, with the morphologically right ventricle connected to the aorta.
?xrefs: ICD-10:Q20.5 UMLS:C0344616 MSH:C535426 SNOMEDCT_US:83799000 UMLS:C0232301 SNOMEDCT_US:56743000 EPCC:01.01.03

?def: Peritonitis caused by intrauterine intestinal rupture and spillage of fetal meconium into the fetal peritoneal cavity. Intra-peritoneal meconium usually calcifies, sometimes within 24 hours. Ultrasound findings may include intraabdominal calcifications.
An abnormality resulting from a lesion of the sympathetic nervous system characterized by a combination of unilateral ptosis, miosis, and often ipsilateral hypohidrosis and conjunctival injection.
The presence of a neoplasm (tumour) in the neurohypophysis, which is also known as the posterior lobe of the hypophysis.
A smooth, extratesticular, spherical cyst in the head of the epididymis.
An abnormally increased number of immature neutrophils in the peripheral blood circulation.
A mode of inheritance in which the severity of a disorder increases or the age of onset decreases as the disorder is passed from one generation to the next.
A reduced ability to synthesize postvaccination antibodies against a Haemophilus H type B antigen, as measured by antibody titer determination following vaccination.
The birth of a baby of less than 37 weeks of gestational age.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0151526 UMLS:C0233315 MSH:D047928 SNOMEDCT_US:49550006 SNOMEDCT_US:367494004 SNOMEDCT_US:282020008

?def: An abnormality of a homocysteine metabolic process.
The absence of all phalanges of a digit and the associated metacarpal /metatarsal.
Any decreased amount from normal of valine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormality of the mitral valve characterized by insufficiency or incompetence of the mitral valve resulting in retrograde leaking of blood through the mitral valve upon ventricular contraction.

Impaired response of CD8 T cells to pathogens. CD8 T cells direct the killing of a target cell through the release of granules containing cytotoxic mediators or through the engagement of death receptors.
The presence of multiple polyps in the intestine.
Collapse of part of a lung associated with absence of inflation (air) of that part.
Congenital lack of the skin of prepuce of penis, that is, of the double-layered fold of skin and mucous membrane that covers the glans penis.
Increased level of IgE antibody against proteins found in foods, such as milk, egg, soy, wheat, peanut, treenut, fish, and shellfish.
A tachycardia originating in the ventricles characterized by rapid heart rate (over 100 beats per minute) and broad QRS complexes (over 120 ms).
An ulcer, that is, an erosion of an area of the gastric mucous membrane.
Presence of multiple dilatations (sac-like outpouchings) in the blood vessels of the conjunctiva.
The presence of an abnormally large skull with onset at birth.
Bony fusion of the mandibular condyle to the base of the skull, resulting in limitation of jaw opening.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:91866004 UMLS:C0685924 SNOMEDCT_US:298231004 SNOMEDCT_US:50603008 UMLS:C2931375 MSH:C536957 UMLS:C0575010

?def: An increase in circulating IgE characterized by two or more bands in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase in circulating immunoglobulins.
An abnormality of the epididymis.
Increased height of the central portion of the eyebrow, forming a crescent, semicircular, or inverted U shape.
Feeding problem necessitating gastrostomy tube feeding.
A reduced level of the complement component C4 in the circulation.
Applied to pain that is tender, i.e., elicited by touching the affected body part.
Abnormally decreased rate of beta-galactosidase activity. Beta-galactosidase activity can be measured in leukocyte, fibroblast, or plasma.
Underdevelopment of the areola, the circular area of pigmented skin surrounding the nipple.
Demyelination of peripheral sensory nerves.
A functional anomaly of the inferior or superior oblique muscle.
Increased width of the phalanges of the 5th finger.

The middle finger is more than 2 SD above the mean for newborns 27 to 41 weeks EGA or above the 97th centile for children from birth to 16 years of age AND the five digits retain their normal length proportions relative to each other (i.e., it is not the case that the middle finger is the only lengthened digit), or, Fingers that appear disproportionately long compared to the palm of the hand.
A benign or malignant neoplasm that occurs within the intracranial cavity above the tentorium cerebelli.
?xrefs: UMLS:C0031941 MSH:D015173 NCIT:C3328 MSH:D010871 SNOMEDCT_US:47598005 UMLS:C0038874 SNOMEDCT_US:127026004 SNOMEDCT_US:359619007

?def: A ventircular escape rhythm occurs whenever higher-lever pacemakers in AV junction or sinus node fail to control ventricular activation. Escape rate is usually 20-40 bpm, often associated with broad QRS complexes are broad (at least 120 ms).
Atrophy of the choroid and retinal layers of the fundus.
Facial contours, as viewed from the front, show a broad upper face/cranium and lower face/mandible, creating a square appearance.

Any abnormal result of flow cytometry, a method that suspends cells in a stream of fluid and passes them through an electronic detection apparatus in order to assess cell count or measure biomarkers or surface molecules.
An anomaly of one or more epiphyses of one or both legs.

Ultra-low vision but with retained ability to perceive the difference between light and dark. Also when light is projected in each of the four quadrants of the visual field, the individual is able to correctly identify the origin of the light stimulus.
A visual defect characterized by the inability to see as clearly in bright light as in dim light. The word hemeralopia literally means day blindness.
Underdevelopment of the ilium.
Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the fifth toe.
Complete and diffuse scarring of glomerulus.
An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in the basilar artery.
Underdeveloped, small right heart atrium.
FEV1 (forced expiratory volume in 1 second) and FVC (forced vital capacity) less than 80 per cent.
Abnormal prominence of the chin related to increased length of the mandible.
?xrefs: UMLS:C4280645 UMLS:C4280644 SNOMEDCT_US:22810007 UMLS:C0399526 SNOMEDCT_US:109504005 UMLS:C0302501 UMLS:C2227134 MSH:D008313

?def: A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the ring finger of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.
Bowing (abnormal curvature) of the vocal folds.
A congenital anomaly, in which the transverse process of the last lumbar vertebra (L5) fuses to the sacrum on one side or both, or to ilium, or both.
An anomaly of one or more metaphyses of the arms.

Cervical dysplasia is the precursor to cervical cancer. It is caused by the persistent infection of the human papillomavirus (HPV) into the cervical tissue. Affected cells develop morphologic features with immature basaloid- type squamous cells and mitotic figures in the upper half of the cervical epithelium.
A degree of language development that is significantly below the norm for a child of a specified age.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:162294008 UMLS:C0233715 SNOMEDCT_US:29164008 SNOMEDCT_US:62415009 MSH:D007805 UMLS:C0023012 UMLS:C0241210 UMLS:C0454644 SNOMEDCT_US:229721007

?def: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by a strong spontaneously arising mental state, reaction or feeling (emotion).
Acidosis resulting from accumulation of ketone bodies.

Euryblepharon is a congenital eyelid anomaly characterized by horizontal enlargement of the palpebral fissure. The eyelid is shortened vertically compared with the horizontal dimension, with associated lateral canthal malpositioning and lateral ectropion abnormally wide lid opening.
Aplasia (absence) of the distal phalanges.
An entwining of a segment of umbilical cord, usually without obstructing fetal circulation and commonly result from fetal slippage through a loop of the cord.
Being present on only the left or only the right side of the body.

Maternal diabetes can either be a gestational, mostly type 2 diabetes, or a type 1 diabetes. Essential is the resulting maternal hyperglycemia as a non-specific teratogen, imposing the same risk of congenital malformations to pregnant women with both type 1 and type2 diabetes.
Ambiguous genitalia in an individual with XX genetic gender.

Delivery by means of therapeutic termination of pregnancy. Therapeutic abortion may be done to end a pregnancy if the mother's life is in danger or if the baby has abnormalities involving the major organ systems and is not expected to survive after birth or by choice.
Intermittent clonic or tonic contraction of muscles supplied by facial nerve. Muscles are relaxed in between contractions.

Decreased fetal activity associated with multiple joint contractures, facial anomalies and pulmonary hypoplasia. Ultrasound examination may reveal polyhydramnios, ankylosis, scalp edema, and decreased chest movements (reflecting pulmonary hypoplasia).

A circumscribed, solid elevation of skin with no visible fluid, varying in size from a pinhead to less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point that is composed of localized hyperkeratosis (the latter may be demonstrated histopathologically).
A hamartoma (disordered proliferation of mature tissues) which can originate from any tissue of the orbital region.
A very common condition in which the extreme end of the nasolacrimal duct underneath the inferior turbinate fails to complete its canalization in the newborn period.
An abnormally elevated or decreased level of a maternal serum marker analytes used in screening for aneuploidy.
Abnormal persistent patency of the ductus arteriosus in postnatal life when birth was at 37 completed weeks of gestation or greater.
Increased level of IgE antibody against eggs, including egg whites, egg yolks, and egg proteins such as ovoalbumin and ovomucoid.
Presence of persistent islands of renal blastema in the postnatal kidney, anywhere within a renal lobe (a portion of a kidney consisting of a renal pyramid and the renal cortex above it).

An elevation in the proportion above normal of immature B cells (CD19+/ CD21low) in circulation relative to total number of B cells. Immature B cells (IgM+) are still in final stages of development within the bone marrow. Naive B cells are those which have left the bone marrow, before they bind to the antigen for which they're specific (IgM+/IgD+).

This term applies to all changes in bone mineral density which (depending on severity) can be seen on x-rays as a change in density and or structure of the bone. Changes may affect all bones of the organism, just certain bones or only parts of bones and include decreased mineralisation as may be seen in osteoporosis or increased mineralisation and or ossification as in osteopetrosis, exostoses or any kind of atopic calicfications of different origin and distribution. The overall amount of mineralization of the bone-organ can be measured as the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones, usually measured by densitometry of the lumbar spine or hip. The measurements are usually reported as g/cm3 or as a Z-score (the number of standard deviations above or below the mean for the patient's age and sex). Note that measurement with this method does not reflect local changes in other bones, and as such might not be correct with regard the hole bone-organ.
Seizures with sustained increase in muscle contraction in parts of the body lasting a few seconds to minutes.
A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia.

Being related to a de novo variant that occurs in a single cell in developing somatic tissue. The cell is the progenitor of a population of identical mutant cells, all of which have descended from the cell that mutated. Clinical manifestations depend on the identity and proportion of affected cells in the body.
Bracket epiphysis refers to an abnormality in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.
Refers to the loss of the outer layer of the epidermis in large, scale-like flakes.
Reddish, brown opalescent discoloration of teeth in normal light.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the male external genitalia.

Webbing or fusion of the fingers, involving soft parts only or including bone structure. Bony fusions are referred to as \bony\" Syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a radio-ulnar axis. Fusions of bones of the fingers in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as \"Symphalangism\"."
Peripheral visual field constriction with 20-49 degrees binocular visual field preserved.
Partial or complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of fourth toe.
Splitting of the neuroretinal layers of the retina.
An acute and self-limited inflammatory disease of the large intestine (colon, cecum and rectum).
A close blood relative had cancer.
Absence or underdevelopment of the biceps muscle.
A congenital anomaly with an abnormal connection between the aorta and the main pulmonary artery resulting in an aortopulmonary shunt.
A type of generalized tonic-clonic seizure that occurs in and rapidly engages bilaterally distributed networks.
Enlargement of the thyroid gland related to one or more nodules in the thyroid gland.
Abnormal smallness of the lens.
A cyst located along the allantois canal.
Excessive bending, twisting, and winding of a cerebral artery.
Applied to pain that is described as sharp, i.e., sudden and severe.
An anomolous earwax color. Earwax (cerumen) is usually light to dark brown or orange in color.
An anatomical anomaly that results from an abnormal rotation of the gut as it returns to the abdominal cavity during embryogenesis.
A history of repeated acute infections of the upper or lower respiratory tract.

A congenital defect of the vasculature such that there is a shunt (by-pass) of blood directly from the portal vein to the vena cava (i.e., the blood from the portal vein is not filtered through the liver).
A heterogeneous increase in IgM immunoglobulins characterized by a diffuse band on serum electrophoresis.
Absence of both testes from the scrotum owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the testis.
Impaired binding of factor VIII to von Willebrand Factor. This is determined using a modified ELISA assay.
Any abnormality of the atlas and the axis.
The presence of steatosis in the liver.
Any structural anomaly of the leaflets (also known as cusps) of the mitral valve.
Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the proximal phalanx of big toe.
Presence of abnormal additional layers of the basement membrane of the glomerulus.
Dilatation of the blood vessels of the conjunctiva leading to a red appearance of the sclera.
An increased concentration of phosphoethanolamine in the urine.
An increase in the level of galactonate in the red blood cells.
A form of myopia related to an axial length above the norm and too long for the refractive power of the whole optical system of the eye.
Increased blood pressure during a pregnancy.
Abnormally decreased levels of serine in cerebrospinal fluid.
The presence of six or more cafe-au-lait spots.
Increase in bone density of the vertebral body.
Abnormally increased levels of leucine in cerebrospinal fluid.

?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:80098002 UMLS:C0085200 MSH:D020961 UMLS:C0752347 MSH:D016631 SNOMEDCT_US:312991009 SNOMEDCT_US:43127003

?def: Two penile structures, separated from the tip to the base of the shaft.
A reddish appearance over the white part (sclera) of the eye ranging from a few enlarged blood vessels appearing as wiggly lines over the sclera to a bright red color completely covering to sclera.

A rapidly growing embryonic tumor arising in the posterior part of the cerebellar vermis and neuroepithelial roof of the fourth ventricle in children. More rarely, medulloblastoma arises in the cerebellum in adults.
The presence of leuucine crystals in the urine.
A heterogeneous increase in IgA mmunoglobulins characterized by a diffuse band on serum electrophoresis.

An increased degree of femoral version, which is defined as the angular difference between axis of femoral neck and transcondylar axis of the knee. Thus, femoral anteversion is an inward twisting of the femur that causes the knees and feet to turn inward.
An abnormality of the lingual frenulum, that is of the small fold of mucous membrane that attaches the tongue to the floor of the mouth, or the presence of accessory frenula in the oral cavity.

An ichthyosiform abnormality of the skin that presents at birth or shortly thereafter with generalized, erythema, blistering, erosions, and peeling. In the subsequent months, erythema and blistering improves but patients go on to develop hyperkeratotic scaling that is especially prominent along the joint flexures, neck, hands and feet.
An abnormality of carbon dioxide (CO2) in the arterial blood.
A sensation of tightness in the ankle joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.
Increased bone density affecting the bones of the spine (vertebral column).
Flatness of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.
Abnormality of glucose homeostasis.
A form of esotropia in which the angle of deviation is not affected by accommodative effort.

A chronic condition in which the pancreas produces little or no insulin. Type I diabetes mellitus is manifested by the sudden onset of severe hyperglycemia with rapid progression to diabetic ketoacidosis unless treated with insulin.
An abnormal growth of parafollicular (C-cells) cells.
Congenital protrusion of the abdominal or thoracic viscera, usually with a defect of the sternum and ribs as well as of the abdominal walls.
A severe delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.

Os odontoideum is classified into two anatomic types (orthotopic and dystopic). Os odontoideum is defined as an ossicle that consists of smooth and separate caudal portions of the odontoid process.With dystopic os odontoideum, the ossicle is located near the basion or is fused with the clivus.
Failure of the tricuspid valve to close sufficiently upon contraction of the right ventricle, causing blood to regurgitate (flow backward) into the right atrium.
Bleeding from the vessels of the cord with extravasation of blood into the Wharton jelly surrounding the umbilical cord vessels.
An abnormality of the region situated around the orbit of the eye.
Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.
A carcinoma derived from a squamous epithelial cell of the tongue.
An area of depressed vision located at the point of fixation and that interferes with central vision.
Epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.
An chronic form of hemolytic anemia.
A reduction in goal-directed behavior, that is, motivation, the determinant of behavior and adaptation that allows individuals to get started, be energized to perform a sustained and directed action.

A type of anemia resulting from suppression of erythropoiesis with little or no abnormality of leukocyte or platelet production. Erythroblasts are virtually absent in bone marrow; however, leukocyte and platelet production show little or no reduction.
Underdevelopment of the breast on one side only.
Hypoplasia of all of the distal phalanx of finger.
A triangular depigmented region of white hairs located in the anterior midline of the scalp.
Hypertrophy of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).
Facial diplegia refers to bilateral facial palsy (bilateral facial palsy is much rarer than unilateral facial palsy).
An abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the big toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
An abnormality in the range and ease of motion of joints across their normal range.
An abnormality of the process of DNA repair, that is, of the process of restoring DNA after damage.
Complete duplication of the middle phalanx of index finger.
A type of pigment gallstone that is hard and black, containing calcium carbonate and calcium phosphates.
A structural abnormality of the sperm head.
Atrophy of the eyeball with blindness and decreased intraocular pressure due to end-stage intraocular disease.
Epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb having multiple bony fragments.
Recurrent infections by Neisseria meningitidis (one of the most common causes of bacterial meningitis), which is also known as meningococcus.
A fold of skin starting above the medial aspect of the upper eyelid and arching downward to cover, pass in front of and lateral to the medial canthus.
An abnormality of filling of a ventricle with blood during diastole.
Anterior tongue-like protrusions of the lower thoracic vertebral bodies.
Progressive bone resorption in the distal part of the clavicle.
Reduced depth of the orbits associated with prominent-appearing ocular globes.
An acute hypersensitivity reaction due to exposure to a previously encountered antigen.
Hyperplasia of lining epithelia of the septal and large bile ducts manifesting as micropapillary projections or as a stratification of the epithelium with or without dilatation of the duct lumen.
Increased level of cryoglobulins in the blood. Cryoglobulins are abnormal immunoglobulins, especially IGG or IGM, that precipitate spontaneously when serum is cooled below 37 degrees Celsius.
Any structural anomaly of the pulmonary valve leaflets.
Pain in muscle.
A midline anterior incomplete closure of the abdominal wall in which there is herniation of the abdominal viscera into the base of the abdominal cord.
An abnormality in the placement of the ocular globe (eyeball).

A testis that is located at the upper scrotum or lower inguinal canal and that can be made to descend completely into the scrotum without resistance by manual reduction but returns to its original position by the cremasteric reflex.
An abnormal irregularity of the cortical surface of the diaphysis (shaft) of the humerus.
An abnormally decreased level of immunoglobulin M (IgM) in blood.
Increased concentration of albumin in the urine.
An atrioventricular valve that empties into both ventricles. The valve overrides the interventricular septum above a ventricular septum defect.
An abnormal hand posture in which the hands are clenched to fists. All digits held completely flexed at the metacarpophalangeal and interphalangeal joints.

Hyperplasia of the gingiva (that is, a thickening of the soft tissue overlying the alveolar ridge. The degree of thickening ranges from involvement of the interdental papillae alone to gingival overgrowth covering the entire tooth crown.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:54711002 UMLS:C0017567 SNOMEDCT_US:441787004 UMLS:C0376480 SNOMEDCT_US:441798003 MSH:D005885 MSH:D019214 MSH:D005886 UMLS:C0017566

?def: Adhesions or scar tissue that form inside the cavity of the uterus.

Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is characterized by reduced function of the gonads (testes in males or ovaries in females) and results from the absence of the gonadal stimulating pituitary hormones: follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).
A repeated, painful urge to defecate without excreting stool.
Cystic, urine-containing intrarenal cavities lined with transitional cell epithelium that communicate through a narrow channel with the collecting system.
Any abnormality of the brachial nerve plexus.

Resistnace of the extensor muscles of the neck to being bent forwards (i.e., impaired neck flexion) as a result of muscle spasm of the extensor muscles of the neck. Nuchal rigidity is not a fixed rigidity. Nuchal rigidity has been used as a bedside test for meningism, although its sensitivity for this purpose has been debated.
A type of perisylvian polymicrogyria that largely affects one side of the brain.
Unicoronal synostosis affecting only the right coronal suture.
A type of persistance of the hyaloid vascular system associated with a retrolental mass that may lead to fetal cataract.
The distal interphalangeal joint of the 4th toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.
Absence of the anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.
An exaggeration of the normal arched form of the acetabular roof such that it takes on a steep appearance.
Any abnormality of the distal epiphysis of the femur.

An anomaly of the patella characterized by two layers visible on lateral knee X-ray such that one layer is in front of the other in the sagittal orientation (See Figure 2A and 3B of PMID:12966518). This finding persists into adulthood.

Any structural anomaly of cardiomyocytes, which are terminally differentiated muscle cells in the heart that are interconnected end to end by gap junctions, which allows coordinated contraction of heart tissue.
A decreased concentration of carnitine in the blood.
Muscle hypertrophy primarily affecting the legs.
A dislocation of the head of the radius from its socket in the elbow joint in an anterior direction.
Absence of proximal phalanx of third toe, owing to a congenital defect of development.
Contractures of one ore more joints of the hands meaning chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.
A type of anemia characterized by an abnormally low concentration of hemoglobin in the erythrocytes.

Anomalous staining of Connexin43 in cardiomyocytes. Connexin43 (Cx43) is the primary gap junction protein in the working myocardium. Cx43 exhibits increased localization at the lateral membranes of cardiomyocytes in a variety of heart diseases.
Abnormal thickening of the cortex of the diaphyseal region of long bones.
A rounded, puffy face with fat deposits in the temporal fossa and cheeks, a double chin.

Subcutaneous bleeding with a diamter greater than 1 cm (ecchymosis). The bleeding does not extend into the tarsal plate (the comparatively thick, elongated plates of dense connective tissue within the eyelid) due to an anatomic structure called the orbital septum, which limits extravasation of blood beyond the tarsal plate.
Constipation for longer than three months with fewer than 3 bowel movements per week, straining, lumpy or hard stools, and a sensation of anorectal obstruction or incomplete defecation.
Mild intellectual disability is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 50-69.

Hermaphroditism refers to a discrepancy between the morphology of the gonads and that of the external genitalia. In male pseudohermaphroditism, the genotype is male (XY) and the external genitalia are imcompletely virilized, ambiguous, or complete female. If gonads are present, they are testes.
A focal lesion of a single peripheral nerve. Damage to a sensory nerve is accompanied by sensory impairment of all modalities in the affected anatomic distribution.
Thrombocytopenia with congenital onset.
A developmental defect of the pericardium with congenital onset.
A sensation of unease in the stomach together with an urge to vomit.
A type of poikilocytosis characterized by the presence in the blood of erythrocytes of varying sizes and abnormal shapes.

Hyperkeratosis is thickening of the outer layer of the skin, the stratum corneum, which is composed of large, polyhedral, plate-like envelopes filled with keratin which are the dead cells that have migrated up from the stratum granulosum.
Intermittent episodes of ketoacidosis.
The presence of free monoclonal immunoglobulin light chains in the urine.

Spastic hemiparesis is characterized by a dominance of the tonus in the upper limb flexor muscles: the arm is held in an adducted posture and is bent and rotated inwards, the forearm is pronated and the hand and the fingers are flexed. The leg is slightly bent at the hip, the knee cannot be extended fully at the end of the stance phase and the foot is inverted and in a plantar flexed position. Gait is slow, with a wide base and asymmetrical with a shortened weight-bearing phase on the paretic side. During the swing phase, the paretic leg performs a lateral movement (circumduction) which is characteristic of this gait disorder, also termed Wernicke-Mann gait. Spastic gait problems typically worsen on attempts to walk faster.
An anomaly of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
An increased concentration of heparan sulfates in the urine.
Temper tantrums that occur more frequently than usual.
Periodically occurring generalized periodic complexes.
Limitation in the ability to open the mouth.
?xrefs: MSH:D014313 UMLS:C0041105 SNOMEDCT_US:87866006 UMLS:C4228933 UMLS:C4280672 UMLS:C1848474

?def: A delay in the process of formation and maturation of the humeral epiphysis.
An elevation in bone density in one or more middle phalanges of the toes. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.
Increased vertical distance from the vermillion border of the lower lip to the inferior-most point of the chin.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger.
An area of the retina that is buckled so that a sector-shaped sheet of retina lies in front of the normal retina. This feature is of congenital onset.
The presence of an abscess of the liver.
Increased width of the skull.
Increased numbers of platelets in the peripheral blood.
Lack of CD4+CD25+ T regulatory cells.
An abnormality in the of lipid metabolism.
A movement disorder which consists of effects including diminished voluntary movements and the presence of involuntary movements.

Bilateral impairment of the function of the cranial nerves 9-12, which control musculature involved in eating, swallowing, and speech. Pseudobulbar paralysis is characterized clinically by dysarthria, dysphonia, and dysphagia with bifacial paralysis, and may be accompanied by Pseudobulbar behavioral symptoms such as enforced crying and laughing.
A persecutory delusion of supposed hostility of others.
An anomaly of one or more epiphyses of a limb.
An increased concentration of homocystine in the blood.
A structural anomaly of the liver located predominantly in the hepatocytes as opposed to stromal cells.
Significant luminal narrowing of a long segment of or the entire ascending aorta.
Fusion of the terminal/distal and middle phalanges of the 5th finger.
Underdevelopment of the glenoid fossa, which is the cavity in the lateral part of the scapula which articulates with the head of the humerus.
An abnormally flat sella turcica.
Deposits accumulating between the retinal pigment epithelium and Bruch's membrane and that are distributed in a single focus.
Degeneration (wear and tear) of the articular cartilage of the neck joints.
The presence of arthrosis, i.e., of degenerative joint disease, affecting the cervical vertebral column.
A funnel-shaped symmetrical enlargement of the origin of the posterior communicating artery at its junction with the internal carotid artery.

A deviation from the normal contents of the platelet alpha granules, which normally contain hemostatic proteins such as fibrinogen, von Willebrand factor, and growth factors such as platelet-derived growth factor.

In a medical encounter, the physician generally will interview the patient about his or her current problem, and may perform additional testing. The past medical history (PMH) in contrast records information about the patient's medical, personal and family history that might be relevant to the presenting illness or to provide optimal clinical management. The PMH generally includes (if relevant) other major illnesses, hospitalizations, surgeries, injuries, allergies, gynecologic and obstetric history, family history, personal history including occupational history, alcohol and drug use, etc.
An abnormal reduction in the number of mitochondria in hepatocytes.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of an aspartate family amino acid in the blood circulation.
Curved appearance of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger.
The presence of a teratoma.
A reduced ability to secrete adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), a hormone that stimulates the adrenal cortex to secrete of glucocorticoids such as cortisol.
Uneven increase in bone density of the distal phalanx of the fourth toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.
Auras with creation of composite perceptions without corresponding external stimuli involving visual, auditory, somatosensory, olfactory and/or gustatory phenomena.
The tendency to repeat vocalizations made by another person.
Abnormal result of a test designed to test an individual's central and peripheral vision by determining the ability of the individual to perceive objects at differing locations of the visual field.
Increased excretion of oxalates in the urine.
Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger.
An abnormality of an artery of lower lip.
An anomaly of the metaphysis of the proximal femur (close to the hip).
Absence of the distal interphalangeal flexion creases of the fingers.
Partial or complete duplication of the second proximal phalanx of hand.
An alteration of the normally relatively smooth margins of the kneecap in radiographic images leading to an irregular contour.
Absence of gastric intrinsic factor, which is normally produced by the parietal cells of the stomach, and is required for the absorption of vitamin B12.
Increased level of IgE antibody against dust mites, such as house dust mites.

In primary position, the eyes drift slowly downward and then spontaneously beat upward. Upward gaze accentuates the nystagmus. The associated oscillopsias are often very irritating, but the symptoms are usually transient.
A progressive form of decreased height of the intervertebral disk.

Abnormality of the cytokine levels in the blood, i.e., an abnormality of any of the non-antibody proteins made by inflammatory leukocytes and some non-leukocytic cells that affect the behavior of other cells.
An abnormality of the function of the skeletal system.
A reduction of the distance between the lower thoracic vertebral pedicles.
A reduction below the normal concentration of a subclass of immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood.
Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of index finger, seen on x-rays as a broad and/or bifid phalanx.
An anomolous response to stimulation by adminstration of the adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH). ACTH stimulation normally stimulates the adrenal glands to release cortisol and adrenaline.
Later than normal development of the breasts.
Partial or complete duplication of a phalanx of second toe.
Breakdown of muscle fibers that leads to the release of muscle fiber contents (myoglobin) into the bloodstream.

An abnormality in the function of the chemical reactions related to processes including conversion of food to enter, synthesis of proteins, lipids, nucleic acids, and carbohydrates, or the elimination of waste products.
Abnormal reduction in length of all metacarpal bones.
A decrease in biotinidase activity, an enzyme that releases biotin from biocytin, the product of biotin-dependent carboxylases degradation.
A type of fungal meningitis caused by dissemination of coccidioides to to basilar meninges.
Posterior curving of the antihelix from its origin at the antitragus, traveling initially almost perpendicular to the descending helix and obscuring some of the concha.
The deposition of calcium salts in the parenchyma of the renal cortex (the outer portion of the kidney between the renal capsule and the renal medulla).
Episodes of ventricular tachycardia that have a sudden onset and ending.
The outer labia are sealed together.
Transmural inflammation of the bladder predominantly with eosinophils, associated with fibrosis with or without muscle necrosis.
An increased concentration of xanthine in the urine.

A type of reduced stature with normal proportions related to dysfunction of the pituitary gland related to either an isolated defect in the secretion of growth hormone or to panhypopituitarism, i.e., a deficit of all the anterior pituitary hormones.
A malformation of the uterus in which the uterus is present as a paired organ as a result of the failure of fusion of the mullerian ducts during embryogenesis.
A pseudoepiphysis (which is a secondary ossification center distinct from the normal epiphysis) of the distal phalanx of the thumb.
Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger.
Excessive formation of fibrous bands of scar tissue in between muscle fibers.
Formation of abnormal bony tissue within tendon tissue.
Redness surrounding the hair follicles.

To avoid pain weight is put on the affected leg for as short a time as possible, resulting in a limp. The patients appear to be walking as if there were a thorn in the sole of the foot. To reduce the load on the affected leg the patients lift and lower their foot in a fixed ankle position.

Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger is affected.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes three and four.

Usually, three large arteries arise from the arch of the aorta: the brachiocephalic trunk (divided into the right common carotid artery and the right subclavian artery), the left common carotid artery, and the left subclavian artery. However, when aberrant right subclavian artery variant is present, the brachiocephalic trunk is absent and four large arteries arise from the arch of the aorta: the right common carotid artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery, and the final one with the most distal left sided origin, the right subclavian artery, also called the arteria lusoria.
Involuntary movements characterized by both athetosis (inability to sustain muscles in a fixed position) and chorea (widespread jerky arrhythmic movements).
Cardiac arrest that would have led to rapid and unexpected death had an intervention not taken place to prevent it.

Occult macular dystrophy is a, typically hereditary, abnormality of the macula associated with progressive foveal cone dysfunction and no apparent fundoscopic, full-field electoretinogram (ERG), or fluorescein angiogram abnormalities.
Deposition of calcium salts in the pituitary gland.
A closed fluid filled sac originating from the mesentary.
Presence of an additional phalanx-like bone, producing an extra, wedge-shaped bone at the base of the proximal phalanx of the third finger.

A congenital malformation of the outflow tract of the heart. Conotruncal defects are thought to result from a disturbance of the outflow tract of the embryonic heart, and comprise truncus arteriosus, tetralogy of Fallot, interrupted aortic arch, transposition of the great arteries, and double outlet right ventricle.

An anomaly of the anterior commissure, a bundle of nerve fibers that connect the two cerebral hemispheres across the midline. The anterior commissure plays a role in pain sensation and contains decussating fibers from the olfactory tracts.
Regurgitation of milk through the nose.
A congenital stenotic mitral valvular anomaly with a ring of tissue above the mitral valve.
Reduced time for the PR interval (beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex). In adults, normal values are 120 to 200 ms long.
Complete loss of ability to move facial muscles innervated by the facial nerve (i.e., the seventh cranial nerve).
Absence of the normal opening of the coronary ostium from which the right main coronary artery originates.
Increased width of the proximal phalanges of the finger.
Elevations of the levels of SGOT (serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase) and SGPT (serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase) that occur during infections.
Detection of abnormal ultra-large von Willebrand factor multimers.
Cleft between the helix and the lobe.

Irregular lines in the deep retina that are typically configured in a radiating fashion and emanate from the optic disc. Angioid streaks are crack-like dehiscences in abnormally thickened and calcified Bruch's membrane, resulting in atrophy of the overlying retinal pigment epithelium. They may be associated with a number of endocrine, metabolic, and connective tissue abnormalities but are frequently idiopathic.
A hernia which occurs just below the inguinal ligament, where abdominal contents pass through a naturally occurring weakness called the femoral canal.

Hemoglobin A (HbA) contains two globin alpha chains and two globin beta chains. HbA is normally the main adult hemoglobin, representing about 96-98 percent of all hemoglobin. This term represents a decreased in the proportion of HbA below this limit, and can be seen in various forms of thalassemia.
The narrowing or partial blockage of a portion of the duodenum.

A form of partial status epilepticus with simple motor manifestations that are maintained for over one hour, with clonic activity restricted to one body part and recurring at fairly regular intervals.
Underdevelopment of the vertebral artery.
Diminished length of one or more metacarpal bones in relation to the others of the same hand or to the contralateral metacarpal.

Significant increase in the length and girth of most or all of a digit compared to its contralateral digit (if unaffected) or compared to what would be expected for age/body build. The increased girth is accompanied by an increase in the dorso-ventral dimension AND the lateral dimension of the digit.
An eyebrow that extends straight across the brow, without curve.

Chilblains, also called perniosis, are an inflammatory skin condition related to an abnormal vascular response to the cold. We are unaware of a reliable estimate of incidence. It typically presents as tender, pruritic red or bluish lesions located symmetrically on the dorsal aspect of the fingers, toes, ears and nose. Less commonly, reports describe involvement of the thighs and buttocks. The lesions present hours after exposure to cold and usually resolve spontaneously in one to three weeks.
An abnormal connection between a carotid artery and the cavernous sinus.
A reduced number of hematopoietic cells present in the bone marrow relative to marrow fat.

Thin (2-3mm) membranes of normal esophageal tissue consisting of mucosa and submucosa that can be congenital or acquired. Congenital webs commonly appear in the middle and inferior third of the esophagus, and they are more likely to be circumferential with a central or eccentric orifice. Acquired webs are much more common than congenital webs and typically appear in the cervical area (postcricoid). Clinical symptoms of this condition are selective (solid more than liquids) dysphagia, thoracic pain, nasopharyngeal reflux, aspiration, perforation and food impaction (the last two are very rare).
An abnormality of the choroid plexus, which is the area in the cerebral ventricles in which cerebrospinal fluid is produced by modified ependymal cells.
Flaring (increase of width with a splayed appearance) of the humeral metaphysis.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the female external genital tract (vulva).
Episodic bouts of involuntary movements with dystonic, choreic, ballistic movements, or a combination thereof. There is no loss of consciousness during the attacks.
AF that cannot be successfully terminated by cardioversion, and longstanding (more than 1 year) AF, where cardioversion is not indicated or has not been attempted, is termed permanent.
A decreased proportion of circulating CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells relative to total number of T cells.
Elevated concentration of gamma-aminobutyric acid in the urine.

A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 2nd finger. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.
Pale often indistinct lesions of the macula.
An abnormality of an odontoid tissue.
A condition where one or both of the two principal meridians focus in the front of the retina when the eye is at rest.
An abnormality of the skin characterized the presence of excessive amounts of dry surface scales on the skin resulting from an abnormality of keratinization.

An intermittent atrioventricular block with failure of some atrial impulses to conduct to the ventricles, i.e., some but not all atrial impulses are conducted through the atrioventricular node and trigger ventricular contraction.
A form of hyperaldosteronism caused by a defect within the adrenal gland.
Spontaneous, repetitive electrical activity demonstrated by electromyography (EMG).
A decreased rate of urine production.
A form of hypermetropia with not more that +2.00 diopters.
Irregular distribution of the teeth along the dental arch, i.e., and irregular spatial pattern of teeth.
An abnormality of an inferior rectus extraocular muscle.

The heart is located in the right hand sided hemithorax. That is, there is a left-right reversal (or \mirror reflection\") of the anatomical location of the heart in which the heart is locate on the right side instead of the left."
?xrefs: EPCC:02.01.02 MSH:D003914 Fyler:0110 UMLS:C0011813 Fyler:110 ICD-10:Q24.0 SNOMEDCT_US:27637000

?def: Any abnormality in the total number of lymphocytes in the blood.
Anomaly of primary or secondary sexual development or characteristics.
Muscular atrophy affecting the lower limb.
An increase in uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase activity in red blood cells. Uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase catalyzes the reaction: UDP-glucose = UDP-galactose.
Abnormal results of investigations using electromyography (EMG).
A severe reduction in the ability to perceive visual contrast characterized by 1.00 log unit or more contrast sensitivity loss.

A hazy, grayish-white ring about 2 mm in width located close to but separated from the limbus (the corneoscleral junction). Corneal arcus generally occurs bilaterally, and is related to lipid deposition in the cornea. Corneal arcus can occur in elderly persons as a part of the aging process but may be associated with hypercholesterolemia in people under the age of 50 years.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:111522004 SNOMEDCT_US:231925004 MSH:D001112 UMLS:C0339268 UMLS:C0003742 SNOMEDCT_US:231924000

?def: Abnormally lax eyelid associated with tissue relaxation; it can be demonstrated by the eyelid distraction test and/or the eyelid snap test.
An accumulation of blood located between the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) and Bruch's membrane.

A reduced ability to participate in the back and forth flow of social interaction, which is normally characterized by an influence of the behavior of one person on the behavior of another person who is in conversation with the first.
An injury of the wrist with displacement of any of the eight carpal bones.
An anomaly of one or more epiphyses of one or more vertebrae.
A lesser degree of hair pigmentation than would otherwise be expected.
A functional anomaly of that portion of the cardiosvascular system that carries deoxygenated blood from the heart to the lungs and returns oxygenated blood back to the heart.
A melanoma that originates in the anal margin.
A severe virus infection of the central nervous system by the herpes simplex virus (HSV).
An ocular movement abnormality characterised by simultaneous weakness of the inferior rectus muscle and superior oblique muscle of the same eye.
An abnormal concentration of copper.
Anemia characterized by abnormal intracellular inclusions, composed of denatured hemoglobin, found on the membrane of red blood cells.
An abnormally reduced circulating concentration of mast cell beta-tryptase concentration.
Reduced strength of the orbicularis oculi, the circumorbital muscle in the face that closes the eyelid.
Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of index finger.
An abnormality resulting from an anomaly of neuronal migration, i.e., of the process by which neurons travel from their origin to their final position in the brain.

Red blood cell distribution width (RDW) is a simple parameter of the standard full blood count and a measure of heterogeneity in the size of circulating erythrocytes. It is provided by automated hematology analyzers and it reflects the range of the red cell size. It is calculated by dividing the standard deviation of erythrocyte volume by the mean corpuscular volume (MCV) and multiplied by 100 to convert to a percentage.
Weakness of the muscles of the pelvic girdle (also known as the hip girdle), that is, lack of strength of the muscles around the pelvis.
The deposition of calcium salts in the parenchyma of the renal medulla (innermost part of the kidney).

Platelets are replete with secretory granules, which are critical to normal platelet function. Among the three types of platelet secretory granules - alpha-granules, dense granules, and lysosomes - the alpha-granule is the most abundant. Granule contents must be released from their intracellular repository in order to achieve their physiologic function, and this term refers to a functional defect in granule secretion.
Increased length of the radius.
Any anomaly of a reflex, i.e., of an automatic response mediated by the nervous system (a reflex does not need the intervention of conscious thought to occur).
Combined syndactyly and polydactyly of the great toe.
Abnormal migration of corneal endothelium.

Paralysis of all four limbs, and trunk of the body below the level of an associated injury to the spinal cord. The etiology of quadriplegia is similar to that of paraplegia except that the lesion is in the cervical spinal cord rather than in the thoracic or lumbar segments of the spinal cord.
A structural anomaly of the internal part of the ear.

Abnormality of one or all of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand. Note that this includes the epiphysis of the 1st metacarpal.
