?def: Ovarian mucinous neoplasms consist of borderline tumors (tumors of low malignant potential, or LMP tumors), intraepithelial (non-invasive) carcinoma, and invasive carcinoma.
A deviation from the normal proportion of plasmablasts in circulation relative to total number of B cells. Plasmablasts are antibody-secreting cells that originate after infection or vaccination.
Abnormal excessive perspiration (sweating) despite the lack of appropriate stimuli like hot and humid weather.
?xrefs: MEDDRA:10020642 SNOMEDCT_US:364538006 SNOMEDCT_US:52613005 SNOMEDCT_US:415691001 UMLS:C0700590 SNOMEDCT_US:312230002 MSH:D006945 UMLS:C0038990 UMLS:C0020458 MSH:D013546 SNOMEDCT_US:161857006 SNOMEDCT_US:415690000

?def: A developmental defect consisting in the duplication of the first metatarsal bone.
Inflammation of the urethra.
An abnormality of a lacrimal sac.
Angiectasia of lymph vessels (i.e., dilatation of lymphatic vessels) in the intestines.
A type of pineal parenchymal cell neoplasm that is a mature well-differentiated tumour (WHO grade I).
A connective tissue neoplasm formed by proliferation of mesodermal cells. Bone and soft tissue sarcomas are the main types of sarcoma. Sarcoma is usually highly malignant.
?xrefs: SNOMEDCT_US:269469005 UMLS:C1261473 SNOMEDCT_US:2424003 SNOMEDCT_US:424413001 SNOMEDCT_US:424952003 MSH:D012509 NCIT:C9118

?def: Abnormal response to thrombin or thrombin mimetics as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of thrombin (or thrombin mimetics).
Normally, the female reproductive canal is connected to the internal genitalia. \Blind vagina\" denotes cases, where this canal ends in a sac."
The presence of sensorineural deafness with late onset.
Reduced depth of the anterior chamber, i.e., the anteroposterior distance between the cornea and the iris is decreased.
An abnormality of the outline, configuration, or contour of the mouth.
An increase in biotinidase activity, an enzyme that releases biotin from biocytin, the product of biotin-dependent carboxylases degradation.
The presence of a basal cell carcinoma of the skin.
?xrefs: UMLS:C1862314 SNOMEDCT_US:275265005 SNOMEDCT_US:1338007 SNOMEDCT_US:254701007 UMLS:C0007117 MSH:D002280 NCIT:C2921

?def: Increased level of IgE antibody against galactose-alpha-1, 3 galactose (alpha-gal), a carbohydrate found in mammalian meat.
A fleshy, tube-like structure usually located in the midline of the face or just to one side of the midline.
Abnormal response to collagen or collagen-mimetics as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition collagen or collagen-mimetics.
Duplication of all or part of the first ray.
Any abnormality of dentin.
A form of hepatic steatosis characterized by the presence of small, lipid-laden vesicles in the affected hepatocytes.
An open funnel detachment of the retina with generally traction in all four quadrants.
A degree of wrinkling of the facial skin that is more than expected for the age of the individual, leading to a prematurely aged appearance.
A developmental defect characterized by agenesis of one or more vertebral bodies of the cervical spine.
Congenital absence of the myelin sheath on a nerve.
Complete loss of hearing related to a sensorineural defect.
The presence of a moderate form of sensorineural hearing impairment.
Abnormal number of platelets per volume of blood. In a healthy adult, a normal platelet count is between 150,000 and 450,000 per microliter of blood.
A lack of coordination of leg movement manifested by undershoot or overshoot of the intended position of the leg.
The presence of a carcinoma of the breast.
Abnormally bright T2 signal from the striatum on brain magnetic resonance imaging.
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the superior mesenteric artery .
Extensive interstitial fibrosis with alveolar disruption and bronchiolectasis.
A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the anal canal or anal margin.
Pattern of blood flow in the heart that deviates from the normal circuit of the circulatory system from the right side of the heart to the left.
A secondary ossification center in the proximal phalanx of the fourth finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.
An unusually severe Epstein Barr virus (EBV) infection.
Progressive bending or abnormal curvature of a long bone.
An anomaly of venous function.

The presence of one or more dendritic corneal epithelial ulcers characterized by a treelike branching linear pattern with feathery edges and terminal bulbs. Herpetiform corneal ulcers can be identified by fluorescein staining.
A hamartoma (tissue malformation consisting of an abnormal mixture of constitutive components) originating in the skin.
Abnormal ossification (bone tissue formation) affecting the pubic bone, also known as the pubis.
In a heliotrope rash, the color of the skin turns to violet, which is the color of the heliotrope flower.
Hemorrhage into the parenchyma of the cerebellum.

The bones of the skeleton undergo a series of characteristic changes in size, shape, and calcification from fetal life until puberty. An abnormality of this process can include delayed or accelerated skeletal maturation, or deviation of some, but not all bones from the expected patterns of maturation.
An inability to digest lactose.

Leukodystrophy refers to deterioration of white matter of the brain resulting from degeneration of myelin sheaths in the CNS. Their basic defect is directly related to the synthesis and maintenance of myelin membranes.
An increase in the level of 3-hydroxydicarboxylic acid in the urine.
More than one fracture of the ribs.
An uneven increase in bone density of the distal phalanx of the thumb.
The presence of a leiomyosarcoma of the uterus.
An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater.
A developmental dysplasia of the dental enamel.

Multiple painful, dome-shaped, translucent pink to skin-colored papules on oral mucosa. Histologically, the lesions may demonstrate dermal proliferation of well-demarcated nerve bundles associated with abundant mucin and surrounded by a distinct perineural sheath.
Absence or underdevelopment of the triceps muscle.
Any of the middle phalanges with short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.
When viewed on end (with the tip of the toe pointing toward the examiner's eye) the curve of the toenail forms a tighter curve of convexity.
Abnormal response to ristocetin as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of ristocetin to platelet-poor plasma.
Complete duplication of the fifth middle phalanx of hand.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 3rd toe.
A type of adult onset with onset of symptoms at the age of 40 to 60 years.
Increased length of the hairs of the eyebrows.
Developmental abnormality in which the lens and cornea are not separated.
Cafe-au-lait spots are hyperpigmented lesions that can vary in color from light brown to dark brown with smooth borders and having a size of 1.5 cm or more in adults and 0.5 cm or more in children.
Increased time to coagulation in the Russell's viper venom assay
An abnormality related to a defect of vertebral separation of cervical vertebrae during development.
The presence of more than 12 rib pairs.
Abnormal pigmentation of the iris.
An anomalous finding in the examination of the urine for cells.
A groove of the skin immediately in front of the ear.
The presence of an abnormal curvature of the cervical vertebral column.
Failure of the ureter to undergo development.
Increased pigmentation, either focal or generalized, of the skin surrounding the vermilion of the lips.
Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles.
Dryness of the mouth due to salivary gland dysfunction.
Reduced visual acuity that is uncorrectable by lenses in the absence of detectable anatomic defects in the eye or visual pathways.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of valine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
